<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOUSTON-COWBOYS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   McNair, Jones want Cowboys in Houston for 2002 opener
</P>
<P>
   By JOHN McCLAIN
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   WICHITA FALLS _ Jerry Jones will join Bob McNair in an attempt
to convince the NFL to have Houston's expansion team play the first
game in franchise history against the Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   Jones and McNair are going to lobby the NFL to schedule the 2002
regular-season opener in prime time.
</P>
<P>
   ``In our first game, I'd like to play the Cowboys in our new
stadium on Monday Night Football and reintroduce to the nation a
great Texas rivalry _ Dallas vs. Houston,'' McNair said this week
from Saratoga Springs, N.Y. ``I really believe that would be
fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones strongly believes the more the Dallas vs. Houston rivalry
is promoted around the country, the better it will be for football
in the state of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm ready to join Bob whenever he wants me to,'' Jones said at
the Cowboys' training camp. ``I'd love to play the first game in
Houston's new stadium.''
</P>
<P>
   The NFL will be realigned into eight divisions of four teams
each when Houston makes its debut.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing Houston in their first game would be great for the
state, but it would be bigger than the state,'' Jones said. ``Not
only would it create a lot of interest in our natural rivalry, but
it would heighten awareness around the country of Houston's return
to the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be good for the NFL. It would be an attractive game
for television. It would get high ratings. The more I think about
it, the more sense it makes. It would accentuate the competition
and the rivalry.''
</P>
<P>
   Because McNair paid $700 million for his franchise, a record for
any professional sports team in the United States, the NFL is
expected to let him select his first opponent.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, when the new Cleveland Browns played their first game
as an expansion team, owner Al Lerner wanted to host the Pittsburgh
Steelers in their regular-season opener. Before the old Browns
moved to Baltimore, Pittsburgh was Cleveland's most bitter rival.
</P>
<P>
   Jones and McNair are hoping the new scheduling format, which
will be determined after realignment is settled, will allow their
teams to play a home-and-home series each season. They have already
scheduled a home-and-home series in preseason, and they plan to
scrimmage and practice against each other during training camp.
</P>
<P>
   After the Oilers moved to Tennessee, Jones played a significant
role in helping Houston beat out Los Angeles for the 32nd
franchise. He lobbied behind the scenes for Houston because he
thought the league would be better off if the Oakland Raiders
return to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Dallas Cowboys and the state of Texas haven't been better
off without a team in Houston,'' Jones said. ``I believe the more
competition you have, the more interest you create. That's good for
both teams and the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of interest in the Cowboys in Houston. Playing
the first game in their new stadium would set a tone by generating
right off the bat a very competitive atmosphere. Houston could make
a statement: The Cowboys are popular, but we've got our own team
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones also is hoping the NFL will allow Dallas and Houston to
play another preseason game in Mexico City in an attempt to break
the league's all-time attendance record. In August 1994, the
Cowboys and Oilers played a preseason game before 112,376 at Azteca
Stadium. It is still the largest crowd to witness an NFL game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to go back there for the very same reasons _ the
matchup, proximity and Hispanic interest in the two franchises,''
Jones said. ``Houston and Dallas have huge Hispanic populations.
Houston's going to be like Dallas in that Hispanics will be a major
part of their fan base.
</P>
<P>
   ``Playing Houston in Mexico City again would be an opportunity
to generate more interest. When you go south of the border, you
also generate interest among Hispanic fans who aren't south of the
border. It's a double whammy.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys and Oilers set preseason attendance records at
Mexico City, Tokyo and El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd consider playing in any of the American Bowls, but
playing the Cowboys in Mexico City makes all the sense in the
world,'' McNair said. ``It would benefit fans in two countries,
including the state of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jerry's been very aggressive in marketing the Cowboys and the
NFL. I respect what he's doing. We're very receptive to his ideas
because we believe as he does _ that we have to do everything
possible to keep the NFL on top.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
