<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KICKER PUTS FUTURE IN AIR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The powerful feet of freshman Chris Kluwe and
sophomore Nate Fikse notwithstanding, Chris Griffith has a leg up
on the Bruins' place-kicking job. Now if he can only get his kicks
up, too.
</P>
<P>
   Griffith, a red-shirt sophomore, earned a scholarship last
season after making 13 of 18 field-goal attempts and all 25 of his
extra-point attempts. The only problem was the misses: all five
were blocked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every fifth or sixth kick last year was low,'' Griffith said.
``I went home (Reno, Nev.) and worked with my kicking coaches and
we got it taken care of. I was turning my shoulders too far toward
the ball. I think I'm getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   If Griffith can improve his trajectory and maintain his
accuracy, the Bruins could have a kicker who is just about
automatic from 40 yards in. When the Bruins have had one in the
past - John Lee, Bjorn Merten and Chris Sailer - it's allowed the
offense to be more conservative, something the Bruins would like
with a sophomore quarterback, Cory Paus or Ryan McCann.
</P>
<P>
   ``The offense is not going to score a touchdown every time down
the field,'' said Bob Field, the defensive coordinator and kicking
coach. ``If a drive stalls and you miss a field goal, it can be
really disheartening.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your kicking game is inconsistent, it can change the
philosophy of the offense once you get the ball to the 25-yard
line. When you can pretty much count on getting three points, it's
a huge advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   Special-teams lowdown: Long snapper Jeff Grau returns, but there
will be a new holder this season: either receiver Drew Bennett or
quarterback Cory Paus. Fikse, who averaged 42.0 yards per punt last
year, will handle kickoffs but he could lose the punting battle to
Kluwe. Coach Bob Toledo said that decision won't be made until the
week before the season-opener.
</P>
<P>
   Diversity rules: Field considers it an advantage to have a
different player handling field goals, kickoffs and punts. In 1997
and 1998, Sailer handled all three. The first season he was a
first-team All-American. The second he was plagued by injuries.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to do all three,'' Field said. ``His leg broke down
on him.''
</P>
<P>
   Injury report: Defensive tackle Ken Kocher (knee) and guard
Micah Webb (shoulder) did not practice Friday. Webb's injury is
more serious and more significant.
</P>
<P>
   Webb, a fifth-year senior, could provide valuable experience on
a young line by filling in for injured right guard Oscar Cabrera
against Alabama. If Webb is out, the Bruins could start redshirt
freshman Shane Lehman with true freshman Eyoseph Efsaeff behind
him.
</P>
<P>
   Bye gone: As early as next week, UCLA expects to fill next
year's open date (Sept. 8) with a game at Kansas. The Bruins were
stuck earlier this summer when Missouri - and former USC coach
Larry Smith - backed out of a home-and-home series with the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   UCLA considered suing Missouri for the $500,000 it believes the
game would have brought in TV and ticket revenue, but the contract
doesn't state how much one school must pay to escape the contract.
The schools are still negotiating a settlement.
</P>
<P>
   However, UCLA may make Missouri pay another way. The Wooden
Classic was considering matching the two schools in 2001, but it's
a matchup the Bruins won't play now.
</P>
<P>
   Practice schedule: The Bruins' afternoon practice today at Drake
Stadium is open to donors by invitation only and Sunday evening's
special- teams practice is closed.
</P>
</TEXT>
