<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-USCNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOP PREP QUARTERBACK CLOSE TO DECISION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ It's not unusual that a big, tall quarterback
is drawing attention at a USC practice, but usually it's starter
Carson Palmer.
</P>
<P>
   But Palmer had a little competition, at least from an attention
standpoint, when Mater Dei High quarterback Matt Leinart decided to
attend Friday's practice at UC Irvine. Leinart is considered a
preseason All-American by most of the recruiting services, and has
narrowed his school choices to USC and Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're both right there. I just don't know. It's 50-50,''
Leinart said, but added, ``It does help (USC) a little because then
my family can come to the games.''
</P>
<P>
   Leinart said he expects to make his decision in early September,
probably the week of Mater Dei's season opener.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to say I would wait until the end of the season, but
now I want to get it over with,'' Leinart said.
</P>
<P>
   Leinart said he was not concerned that USC has already received
a commitment from quarterback Billy Hart of Mission Viejo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anywhere I go, there's going to be competition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Depth chart: Although a depth chart will probably not come until
Monday, several positions already seem decided, based on practice.
Ife Ohalete is the starter at free safety, Faasea Mailo has claimed
the right tackle spot, David Newbury should be the kicker and
Darrell Rideaux appears to have edged out Chris Cash at right
cornerback.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sultan McCullough seems ahead at the tailback position,
USC coach Paul Hackett said Friday he will probably name McCullough
and Malaefou MacKenzie as co-starters. MacKenzie returned to
practice, wearing a bandage on his left hand, which he cut in
Wednesday's scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   Another legitimate battle is at No. 2 tight end, where sophomore
Doyal Butler and freshman Alex Holmes of Harvard-Westlake are the
candidates. Freshman Gregg Guenther of Taft will also play, but has
been out most of the week with a sore back. He will return Monday.
</P>
<P>
   About face: Kansas State coach Bill Snyder has reversed himself,
and agreed to play USC in a home-and-home series that begins with a
game at the Coliseum on Sept. 8, 2001. The second game will be
played in either 2002 or 2003 in either Manhattan, Kan., or
Arrowhead Stadium in Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   USC tried to make the deal in February, but Snyder killed it.
USC officials believe a public backlash by Kansas State fans
rekindled the deal, and Hackett and Snyder also spoke about the
series before the contract was signed.
</P>
<P>
   Harris vows to play: Although Hackett is worried that a pulled
calf muscle might limit tight end Antoine Harris to 20-25 plays,
Harris said he expects to play the entire Penn State game.
</P>
<P>
   ``My calf muscle felt a little tweaked, but I'll be all right,''
Harris said. ``If game day comes and I have to play hurt, I'll play
hurt. But I'll be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   And at left guard ...: With Trevor Roberts out with a strained
foot, freshman Lenny Vandermade has worked all week with the first
unit. Hackett said it depends how Roberts recovers this weekend
before he makes a decision on a starter.
</P>
<P>
   Change of heart: Hackett was upset with Friday's morning
practice, which also happened to be the first one in which he began
to prepare for Penn State.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were sloppy,'' he said. ``We've got to pick it up.''
</P>
<P>
   But following the afternoon session, he had changed his tune.
</P>
<P>
   ``As upset as I was this morning, I couldn't be happier,''
Hackett said. ``We have set a standard at this camp that is higher
than ever before. And this afternoon, they were excellent.''
</P>
</TEXT>
