<HEADER>
A6411 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-DRUGDEBT-VICTIM-LADN     08-19 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUGDEBT-VICTIM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY BURIES TEEN DRUG-DEBT VICTIM
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ORITH GOLDBERG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MISSION HILLS, Calif. _ More than 400 mourners gathered Friday
for the memorial service of 15-year-old Nicholas Samuel Markowitz,
stunned that a teen who was ``always there'' when friends needed
him was killed - allegedly over drug money owed by his
half-brother.
</P>
<P>
   During the hourlong memorial service, friends of Nicholas spoke
haltingly through their tears to the mourners crowded inside the
Eden Memorial Park chapel in Mission Hills and those listening
outside to an intercom.
</P>
<P>
   His friends said they loved him and he would always be in their
hearts.
</P>
<P>
   A fellow peer counselor of Nick's cried as she explained how
good he was to her and how they became friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the light of the dark side of me,'' she said, weeping.
``He was always there when I needed him.''
</P>
<P>
   Zach Winters, 16, said his friend Nick always helped his
friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were always a call away when I needed you,'' Zach said.
``Things aren't going to be the same without you. All I can say is,
I love you, man. We'll always be friends for life.''
</P>
<P>
   The memorial was followed by a graveside service where friends
and relatives gathered around a makeshift tent.
</P>
<P>
   Susan and Jeffrey Markowitz watched somberly as Nick's casket
was lowered into the ground. Meanwhile, seven of Nick's closest
friends stood along the side weeping for their friend.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Santa Barbara County Sheriff's officials said Nick
was an innocent victim kidnapped because his half-brother,
22-year-old Benjamin Markowitz, owed money for a past drug deal.
</P>
<P>
   Four suspects in the case have been arrested. They are William
Skidmore, 20, of Simi Valley; Jesse Taylor Rugge, 20, of Santa
Barbara; Graham Pressley, 17, of Santa Barbara County; and Ryan
James Hoyt, 21, of West Hills. They were arrested Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Charges of kidnapping, criminal conspiracy and murder were filed
against each of the suspects by the Santa Barbara County District
Attorney's Office on Friday. Pressley was charged as an adult, said
sheriff's Lt. Mike Burridge.
</P>
<P>
   A fifth suspect, 20-year-old Jesse James Hollywood, remains at
large. He was last known to be in the West Valley area, Burridge
said.
</P>
<P>
   Police said Hollywood was looking for Benjamin - and kidnapped
Nick - because the older Markowitz owed him $36,000.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Benjamin said the debt was old and considerably less.
</P>
<P>
   ``For $1,200, it's just sickening to me that these kids that I
grew up with, that I played baseball with, that I went to high
school with, could take my little brother, take him to a hotel and
murder him and shoot him multiple times in the head and in the
stomach,'' said Benjamin, who admitted that he at one time sold
illegal drugs.
</P>
<P>
   Out of respect for his stepmother Susan Markowitz, Benjamin said
he did not attend the funeral.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any peace of mind I can give to her, I want to give to her,''
he said. ``I want to stay out of her face. She does not deserve me
being in her face.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Susan Markowitz said the family would seek
counseling to help them through this ordeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Benjamin knew that (the funeral) is as important to me as
giving birth to Nicholas,'' Susan Markowitz said.
</P>
<P>
   Nick was last seen walking in his neighborhood Aug. 6 by his
cousin and uncle. On that day, according to police, Hollywood,
Rugge and Skidmore, driving in a rented van, kidnapped Nick when
they couldn't find Benjamin. They took him to Rugge's home in the
700 block of Casiano Drive in Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   For two days, Nick remained at the home. His kidnappers provided
him with Valium and marijuana, probably to keep him passive while
he was at the home, police said.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 8, the same day Susan and Jeffrey Markowitz filed a
missing persons report at the LAPD's West Valley Division, Rugge
and Pressley took Nick to the Lemon Tree Inn in Santa Barbara,
where they were joined by Hoyt, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Rugge and Graham left the hotel and drove to an area in the Los
Padres National Forest known as Lizard's Mouth, a popular hiking
site, officials said. There, they dug a grave, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   When they returned to the hotel, the threesome took Nick to
Lizard's Mouth, where Rugge and Hoyt placed duct tape over his
mouth and taped his hands behind his back, officials said. Nick was
then placed in the grave and shot by Hoyt with a semiautomatic
handgun nine times, authorities said. Four days later, hikers found
the grave with pieces of Nick's clothing sticking out and contacted
the authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Detectives pieced together what apparently happened with the
help of Benjamin, who said Friday that he was never contacted by
Hollywood for the money owed. Instead, he received a call from
Skidmore, who said, ``Don't make me and my boys come down there,''
Benjamin said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, a neighbor of Hoyt's said the 21-year-old lived at
the West Hills home with his grandparents. Sometimes his mother,
who was divorced, would stay there as well, said Danny Goodman, 17.
</P>
<P>
   Goodman said he has known Hoyt for 10 years and played baseball
with his younger brother.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, as Goodman returned from a trip to Yosemite, he saw
Hoyt in front of his grandparents' home speaking with a girl.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just said, `What's up Danny? I haven't seen you in a
while.'''
</P>
<P>
   Goodman said he was stunned to learn that Hoyt could be involved
in the murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like something out of a movie almost,'' he said.
``Ryan was a good person to me. He'd give me rides to places.''
</P>
<P>
   Benjamin Markowitz also expressed disbelief about what happened,
adding that he holds himself responsible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to kill myself for what's going on,'' he said. ``I wish
it was me. I wish that I was the one that was gone.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
