<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW CALL-UPS TASTE BIG APPLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was just a little before 6 p.m. Friday when
pitcher Brian Cooper and catcher Shawn Wooten, both looking a
little tired, strolled into the visiting clubhouse at Yankee
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Both were in Edmonton on Thursday night when they were told they
were to catch an early flight Friday morning to New York to join
the Anaheim Angels. For Wooten, a graduate of South Hills High, it
was his first day in a major-league uniform.
</P>
<P>
   For Cooper, a graduate of Glendora High, it was a return to the
big leagues. However, he is not exactly feeling comfortable these
days. He was sent back to the minors last week to correct some
problems and was called up to start today's game because the Angels
don't have anyone else for the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need him to command the fastball,'' pitching coach Buddy
Black said. ``That sets everything else up.''
</P>
<P>
   Realizing his problem is one thing, but correcting it has been
another matter. In Cooper's start for Triple-A Edmonton last
Monday, he gave up six runs and seven hits in five innings. Today,
he's facing the defending champion Yankees, not the Sacramento
Rivercats.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a process, it doesn't happen overnight for a young
pitcher,'' Black said. ``There are adjustments that have to be made
when transgressing from the minor leagues to the major leagues, and
Brian is in the process of doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Wooten, called up because reserve catcher Matt Walbeck was
placed on the disabled list with tendinitis in his right knee, was
all smiles upon entering the clubhouse. He was hitting a
team-leading .353 for Edmonton with 11 homers and 42 RBI since
being called up from Double-A Erie. Entering Yankee Stadium for the
first time was quite an experience, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I found out last night, I was thinking, `Couldn't I have
started in Milwaukee?' '' Wooten joked. ``If you can play here, you
can play anywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Wooten, 28, was a teammate of Jason Giambi's at South Hills and
also attended Mt. SAC. He was drafted by the Tigers, but rarely
caught until joining the Angels organization.
</P>
<P>
   Walbeck update: Walbeck hurt his knee last Friday in Anaheim
when he backed up a play at first base, then retreated to cover
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was bothering me to do everything - catch, run, throw,''
Walbeck said. ``It gets to the point where it affects my calling a
game because my mind is here (knee). It's better to sit out two
weeks now and come back in September than play the rest of the year
at 50 percent.''
</P>
<P>
   Short hops: Bench coach Joe Maddon has returned to Southern
California, where is he undergoing tests to determine the cause of
his light-headedness and shortness of breath. Maddon had similar
symptoms in April, but tests revealed no problems with his heart.
... In order to make room on the roster for Cooper and reliever Al
Levine (activated from the DL), the Angels sent reliever Eric
Weaver and infielder back to Edmonton.
</P>
</TEXT>
