<SLUG> BC-CATHOLIC-INSURANCE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CATHOLIC CHURCH FIGHTS LAW ON BIRTH-CONTROL COVERAGE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By DON LATTIN 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  Catholic Church leaders in California have started a major
legal battle against a new state law that requires health insurance
companies to offer birth-control pills in employee health plans
that include coverage for other prescription drugs.
<P>
   What really upsets the state's Roman Catholic bishops is that
the new law, called the Women's Contraceptive Equity Act, requires
them to offer the pill to employees of Catholic Charities and other
church agencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand that a majority of Catholics, let alone the
general public, do not adhere to our teachings on birth control.
But that's not the point,'' said Rick Mockler, executive director
of Catholic Charities of California. ``What's at stake is our
ability to control our doctrine.'`
</P>
<P>
   Church leaders quietly filed their lawsuit last month in
Sacramento County Superior Court, on behalf of Catholic Charities
of Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, prepared by the California Catholic Conference, the
lobbying arm of the state's bishops, charges that the law, which
went into effect in January of this year, does not allow adequate
exemptions for church agencies that oppose contraception on moral
grounds.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic Charities, like many other welfare agencies affiliated
with religious organizations, is composed of semi-independent
nonprofit corporations, allowing the individual charities easier
access to government funds.
</P>
<P>
   But this structure, designed to create a buffer between the
worshipping community and the social service provider, has now
backfired on the Roman Catholic Church.
</P>
<P>
   The new law on contraception, co-sponsored by state Sen. Jackie
Speier, D-Hillsborough, and Assemblyman Robert Hertzberg, D-Sherman
Oaks, does contain a ``conscience clause'' for ``religious
employers'' seeking an exemption.
</P>
<P>
   To qualify as ``religious,'' however, the employer must hire
only people who share its beliefs and primarily serve like-minded
clients. It must also exist primarily to promote its religious
beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic Charities employs many non-Catholics, does not
emphasize proselytizing and serves a general population. Thus, it
is considered as a ``secular'' employer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a fig-leaf conscience clause. It doesn't cover enough,''
said Carol Hogan, spokeswoman for the California Catholic
Conference. ``It's gerrymandered to exclude a large portion of the
Catholic Church.''
</P>
<P>
   Katherine Kneer, the chief executive officer of Planned
Parenthood in California, said the issue is ``equal rights and
equal protection'' in the workplace. ``They want to take this
religious exemption and apply it to entities whose primary purpose
is not to inculcate religious beliefs,'' she said. ``Our concern is
for their employees who may not share those beliefs. They have a
right to contraception. Their rights should not be infringed.''
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Unpopular Teaching
</P>
<P>
   Since 1968, when Pope Paul VI issued ``Humanae Vitae,'' his
controversial condemnation of the birth control pill, public
opinion polls have shown that teaching to be one of the most
unpopular _ and widely ignored _ statements in the history of the
papacy.
</P>
<P>
   Writing in the archdiocesan weekly Catholic San Francisco, the
Rev. Gerald Coleman, president of St. Patrick's Seminary in Menlo
Park, concedes that ``the public nature of this lawsuit by Catholic
Charities will likely raise conflicts and moral questions in the
conscience of individuals.''
</P>
<P>
   But he argues the church should not be required to ``offer
benefits or insurance coverage to their employees when the object
of that benefit or coverage is in direct contradiction to Catholic
moral teachings.''
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the two state agencies named as defendants in the
lawsuit, the Department of Managed Health Care and Department of
Insurance, referred calls to the state Attorney General's office,
which is handling the case. A spokesman there declined to comment
on the merits of the case until the state had prepared its formal
response.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will defend this law, which has been enacted by the
Legislature and signed by the governor,'' said spokeswoman Sandra
Michioku.
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the contraceptive equity law argued that only 19
percent of heath care plans covered oral contraceptives. Three
earlier bills were vetoed by California's former governor, Pete
Wilson, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the church filed 4,000 pages of court
documents to support its argument that the new law violates the
``liberty of conscience'' protections of the California
Constitution and the U.S. Constitution's guarantee for the free
exercise of religion.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Hearing Set for Sept. 25
</P>
<P>
   A hearing on the church's motion for a preliminary injunction
against the new law has been set for September 25 before Sacramento
Superior Court Judge Joe Gray.
</P>
<P>
   Catholic Charities spends about $80 million a year on social
service programs in California, about 60 percent of it from
taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit could presage future church/state battles. Both of
the nation's major political parties favor private, tax-supported
``faith-based organizations'' to offer welfare services once
provided by government agencies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
