<SLUG> BC-FBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WARD HOPES TO STEP PAST `THE TRADE'
</HEADLINE>
 (ADDS grafs 10,11; EDITS 12th graf to conform)  
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ There was a day last week at New York
Jets camp when Dedric Ward, the Jets' fourth-year wide receiver,
was in a quiet, but upbeat, mood. Al Groh, the Jets' first-year
head coach, had officially named Ward as the Jets' starting wide
receiver alongside Wayne Chrebet.
</P>
<P>
   This was big news. Anything about the Jets' wide receivers is
big news ever since the organization sent Keyshawn Johnson to Tampa
Bay in the most controversial trade in franchise history.
</P>
<P>
   All sorts of names had been floated around as candidates to fill
the void created by the Johnson trade. First, Carl Pickens was
coming from Cincinnati, then Sean Dawkins from Seattle. Then talk
turned to the armada of Jets rookie receivers.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets stuck with Ward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trading Keyshawn, then not bringing in another receiver,
showed a lot of faith in me,'' Ward said.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets maintained that they were satisfied. Yes, the
5-foot-10-inch Chrebet and the 5-9 Ward were the shortest receiving
tandem in the league. But height was just a number.
</P>
<P>
   ``With receivers and running backs, they're not big or little;
they're effective,'' Groh said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, lo and behold, with the season bearing down on them, the
Jets acquired wide receiver Vincent Brisby after he was cut by New
England. Brisby's key selling point was _ guess what? _ his size.
While nobody mentioned the K-word, as in Keyshawn, Brisby, at 6-3,
gave the Jets the big target they were looking for, at least on
paper. That, anyway, is what the front office is selling to fans as
they attempt to justify the fact that they may have cut off their
noses to spite their face.
</P>
<P>
   With each practice, with each game, the Jets seem to be more
fully realizing that trading Johnson may well be one of those moves
that haunts the franchise for decades to come. It is Boston trading
Babe Ruth, the Nets trading Dr. J.
</P>
<P>
   But for one night, everything was all right for the Jets, who
defeated the Giants, 27-24, in their final exhibition game. Chrebet
caught three passes for 79 yards, scoring on a 52 yard
flea-flicker. Ward had a quiet game, with four receptions for 49
yards, while Brisby caught two passes for 30 yards.
</P>
<P>
   But the most significant statistics belonged to quarterback Ray
Lucas, who was 19-of-26 passing for 286 yards and three touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Ward could make everything right for himself and the Jets with a
breakthrough season. And if he does, the Jets' front office will no
doubt take credit for having the foresight and faith to have a
soft-spoken third-round draft pick replace the outspoken Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Ward got a vote of confidence from the man whose shoes
the Jets are desperately trying to fill.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all honesty I've always liked Dedric Ward,'' Johnson said
from Tampa. ``To me, I've always thought he was a much better
player than the other guy,'' he added in a reference to Chrebet,
the receiver Johnson has often criticized as overrated and once
even described as a mascot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always thought he should have been the opposite receiver
from me, for a lot of different reasons,'' Johnson said of Ward.
``He fits the role of a vertical guy.''
</P>
<P>
   When Chrebet broke a bone in his foot in the 1999 preseason,
Ward became the No. 2 receiver for the first five games of the
regular season. He ended up with 15 receptions for 143 yards and
two touchdowns. And this was with an overwhelmed Rick Mirer at
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   For the season, Ward caught 22 passes for 325 yards. Johnson had
89 receptions, and Chrebet 48. It wasn't Ward's best season; that
came in 1998, his second year, when he averaged 19.1 yards a catch
and established himself as a legitimate deep threat. Still, Ward
said he viewed his five starts a year ago as a ``steppingstone for
bigger and better things to come.''
</P>
<P>
   For Jets fans, for Bucs fans, this 2000 season has become an
intriguing drama: eyes on Groh, eyes on Johnson, eyes on Chrebet,
eyes on Ward. Perhaps, Chrebet in particular. Is he overrated, as
Johnson suggests? Can he carry the Jets' offense the way Johnson
did at times or the way Curtis Martin has done? Can he shut
Johnson's mouth?
</P>
<P>
   The defining scene of last season was a tough, but catchable,
pass bouncing off Chrebet's hands in the end zone against
Indianapolis, a pass that would have tied the score in the final
seconds of the game. This season, Chrebet will face the best
corners week in and week out. At the same time, the 25-year-old
Ward will be trying to break through to another level.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he'll do a good job,'' Johnson said of Ward. ``But the
other guy _ I don't think he's good enough to take the heat off of
Dedric. I took the heat off of him; I don't think he's good enough
to take the heat off of Ward.''
</P>
<P>
   Who will catch those 9-to-14-yard passes in heavy traffic in
clutch situations for the Jets? Chrebet? Ward? Brisby?
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, naturally, has his opinion: ``I don't know if they have
a receiver who can do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on what we had last year, we really only had one guy who
could do that,'' Johnson said. ``And he's in Tampa now.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
