<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-TRAIL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CANDIDATES PLUNGE INTO CENTRAL U.S.  &HT;     By MARC SANDALOW 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Al Gore was gone before the sun rose.
</P>
<P>
   Mindful that no presidential candidate who trailed in the polls
on Labor Day has ever won the election, the vice president and his
running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, rushed from California Friday
to board a riverboat that will float them down the Mississippi
River through several battleground states that could decide the
election.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're for you. We need you to help us,'' a raspy-voiced Gore
said to supporters in La Crosse, Wis., barely 12 hours after
accepting his party's nomination for president 2,000 miles away.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, his rival, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, was in Gore's
home state trying to portray the vice president's support as weak.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that the conventions are over, the battle lines are
clearly drawn. The voters have a clear choice,'' Bush told an
enthusiastic crowd in a suburb of Memphis, Tenn. Polls show that
Bush has a good chance of winning Gore's home state.
</P>
<P>
   The candidates' 81-day sprint toward election day took on a new
focus as crews tore apart the Staples Center podium and party-weary
Democrats began to leave this convention city.
</P>
<P>
   Although delegates were thrilled by their candidate's speech and
almost surprised by the orderliness of their convention, they were
anything but certain about their prospects of victory in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be a close election,'' said former President Jimmy
Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Carter said he does not accept Bush's claim to be a ``benevolent
conservative, or whatever it is,'' but he expressed concern that
Republicans might convince independent swing voters that they are
the party of the political center.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they do, they will win. If they don't, they won't,'' Carter
said.
</P>
<P>
   A look at the electoral map shows why both candidates will be
spending a great deal of time in the so-called Big 10 states, where
blue-collar union workers who voted for Ronald Reagan in the 1980s
and President Clinton in the 1990s may hold the key to the 2000
election.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic ticket is most solid in California and the
Northeast. Bush's strengths are come from  &LR; Texas, the South and the
Mountain West.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves a string of central states _ Wisconsin, Illinois,
Michigan, Missouri, Iowa, Ohio, Pennsylvania and New Jersey _ with
128 electoral votes that are in play.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, nothing is for certain, and each side is only now
beginning to map out the strategy that will take them to the
November election. Polls have swung wildly in recent weeks,
suggesting that voters have not yet decided.
</P>
<P>
   Bush held a lead for the past several months that swelled to
double digits after his party's convention two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Surveys taken immediately after the Democratic convention showed
that Gore is enjoying the traditional ``bounce.'' A
Voter.com-Battleground poll of 1,000 likely voters found that
Bush's 11 point lead at the beginning of the week had been cut to
just 5 points immediately after Gore's speech Thursday night.
Another poll showed the race a statistical dead heat.
</P>
<P>
   Strategists agree that it is too early for such fluid  &LR; polls to
be taken too seriously. It is the patterns that emerge over the
next several weeks that will be critical.
</P>
<P>
   But a state-by-state look at who is ahead shows Bush with the
electoral advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans lead in at least 16 states where they have won in
each of the past three presidential elections. Together, those
states hold 135 of the 270 electoral votes Bush needs to win.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Bush is ahead in Georgia, Colorado and Montana _
states Bush's father won in 1988 and Bob Dole won in 1996 _ which
have a total of 24 electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   There are 10 states, plus the District of Columbia, that have
voted for the Democratic ticket in each of the past three
elections. They total 107 electoral votes. But some of those
states, including Oregon and Washington, are not so solidly for
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has made much noise about competing in California. He has
spent a considerable amount of time in the state, and his aides
note that he is popular with some leaders of the high-tech
community, and does quite well, for a Republican, among Latino
voters. A poll released between the conventions showed Bush and
Gore neck-and-neck in the state.
</P>
<P>
   But Gore has some enormous advantages in California, including
the help of Gov. Gray Davis, who has shown how a centrist Democrat
can use issues like gun control, abortion and the environment to
defeat Republican opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's forays into California may have more to do with trying to
lure Gore into spending more time and money in the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you spend money in California, it's money you can't spend
nationwide,'' said Democratic pollster Celinda Lake, who said she
is confident Gore would win California.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will run an aggressive operation,'' said Gore's California
campaign director, Jay Ziegler, ``to make sure that Bush
understands this is a state he will have difficult time being
competitive.''
</P>
<P>
   The politics are flipped in Florida, a Republican-leaning state,
where polls show a Bush victory is likely but not certain.
</P>
<P>
   Strategists believe Gore will pay enough attention to Florida
and Bush to California to make them look competitive but will spend
the bulk of their time in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates start with $67.6 million in federal money for
their campaign, but that is only a part of the money that will be
spent. Each party will raise millions _ Republicans are trying for
$100 million _ to spend on television commercials and
get-out-the-vote drives.
</P>
<P>
   The ads will have to pierce the public's indifference to the
campaign. Before the conventions, the overwhelming majority of
voters said they were paying little attention to the candidates.
Next month, the summer Olympics may further drown out Bush and
Gore's efforts to get out their messages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
