<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tiger's paw firmly on PGA
</P>
<P>
   By EDDIE SEFKO
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ One of the players still within radar range of
Tiger Woods knows a good way to keep the PGA Championship relevant
on the weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``After all the rain we had, the water's real high in that creek
on No. 6,'' Fred Funk said Friday evening. ``If Tiger slips on that
little bridge and the current gets him, maybe we'll have a
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the good Lord's willing and the creek doesn't rise, the
PGA Championship could look awfully familiar by the time today's
play is over.
</P>
<P>
   While Funk, Davis Love III, Scott Dunlap and a few others are
trying their darnedest to stay in touch with Woods, he's making it
tough to do so. Woods fired a mechanical 5-under-par 67 on Friday
to get to 11-under 133 at the midpoint of the PGA.
</P>
<P>
   He owns just a 1-shot lead over Dunlap, who had a second-round
68. Love, Funk and J.P. Hayes are tied for third at 7-under 137.
But with Valhalla Golf Club softened by more than three inches of
rain early Friday morning, the likelihood of Woods going in reverse
seems remote.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's better than I thought he was,'' said Jack
Nicklaus after playing alongside Woods in the first two rounds.
``If this was a passing of the baton _ and I think it was passed a
long time ago _ I couldn't pass it to a nicer young man, who
obviously is the cream of the crop by a mile. At this point, he's a
little better player than I was at his age.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 37, Dunlap has been around long enough to remember
Nicklaus when he was in his prime. And Dunlap recalls what he
thought as a youngster any time the Golden Bear was on the prowl at
a major _ that the rest of the field was toast.
</P>
<P>
   ``Done and dusted, for sure,'' Dunlap said. ``And it usually
was, wasn't it? The thing with majors is they are so much more
important, and the better players relish those moments. It's not
that their games are that much better. It's that they are so much
better in that situation. And that's why Tiger is so extremely
difficult to beat, because this is what he lives for. He actually
gets better at that time and that moment, much like Jack did.''
</P>
<P>
   That Dunlap will have to play with Woods today in the third
round won't make it any easier for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's won more majors than I have made cuts (in majors),''
Dunlap said. ``It'll be old hat for him and a new experience for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   After what happened Friday, it doesn't seem like one theory _
that because of Valhalla's birdie-friendly atmosphere, Woods is
unlikely to run away from the field _ holds much water.
</P>
<P>
   With only one player within three shots of him _ and just six
within six strokes _ the stage is set for another dominating
performance if Woods continues his sizzling play.
</P>
<P>
   Heavy rain in the wee hours Friday morning pushed play back one
hour. The course was primped after all the precipitation had
rearranged sand in the bunkers and caused standing water in
low-lying areas.
</P>
<P>
   But nothing was going to keep Woods from his appointed round.
</P>
<P>
   He birdied four of the first eight holes and didn't have to make
any putts outside of 12 feet to do so. He tacked on another birdie
at No. 15, then suffered his only bogey on a three-putt at the
17th, botching the three-footer for par.
</P>
<P>
   But he came back to hole a 15-footer at the end after blasting
out of a buried lie in the greenside bunker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was perturbed to the 10th power,'' he said of his demeanor
after the three-putt. ``Then, to see my ball buried in the bunker,
I wasn't too happy. I thought I had hit a perfect 3-wood, and it
buried. But I hit the sand shot, and Steve (Williams, his caddie)
told me I was going to make the putt and get out with birdie. I
did, and I told him he was right.''
</P>
<P>
   So once again there's a field of chasers who have to prove they
can handle Woods and aren't running with their tails between their
legs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it's soft like this, any guy can get it going,'' said
Ernie Els, who had a second-round 68 and is 2-under for the
tournament. ``The guys who have the hot putter are going to score.
A guy like Tiger, this is right up his alley. He can really pull
away from the field and play his normal game. I have to go really
low over the weekend (to have a chance).''
</P>
<P>
   Woods mentioned he hasn't had a huge halfway lead at either of
the majors he's won this year. He was 6-up midway through the U.S.
Open, which he won by 15, and three ahead at the British Open,
winning by eight.
</P>
<P>
   ``There you go,'' he said. ``I'm going downhill _ six, three,
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are playing a major championship, you're going to
have to play well, and I've been able to do that so far this week.
And Scott has done the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods said his shot-making has ruled over his putting. But
pretty much all facets are clicking. And everybody else knows it,
too.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he's playing that well, he can go as low as he wants,''
said Thomas Bjorn, who is 4-under. ``He can shoot 60 on a golf
course like this if everything goes his way. But you never know. He
can shoot 74, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, perhaps. If he has to play 20 holes instead of
18.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, Woods seems to be on cruise control and is going 20
mph faster than anybody else.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately, everybody could have used some of that extra
speed on Friday. Play again was slow, and 11 players were left on
the course when darkness set in. One of them who finished in the
gathering gloom was Love, who could have been a lot closer than he
was but finished with back-to-back bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   Considering that the 18th was playing as one of the easiest
holes on the course, Love knew he let an opportunity slip away.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a very good way to finish,'' he said. ``I had a
pretty good round going up until then.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the late slip-ups, Love's challenge today will be
much harder.
</P>
<P>
   As it will be for everybody trying to run down Woods.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
