<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BREWERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Miller, Astros on a roll
</P>
<P>
   By JOSEPH DUARTE
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ With every out that passed, Wade Miller tried not to
think about the one word no pitcher wants to hear: No-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It crossed my mind,'' the rookie righthander said after his
no-hit bid lasted six innings Friday night as the Astros extended
their winning streak to five games with a 5-4 victory over the
Milwaukee Brewers.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros matched their season-high winning streak and won for
the seventh time in 10 games. They are three games over .500
(19-16) since the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   For the second time in five days, an Astros starting pitcher
took a no-hitter into the seventh inning. The Astros built a 5-0
lead before Miller had his no-hit bid snapped on Geoff Jenkins'
leadoff home run to right field in the seventh inning.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Holt pitched six no-hit innings Monday in a 16-2 rout of
Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``About the fifth inning, that's when I began to think I had
four innings to go,'' said Miller, who allowed three hits in
six-plus innings. ``I felt good as the game went on. I wasn't
trying to blow anybody away.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, who began the season at Class AAA New Orleans, retired
11 straight batters between the second and fifth innings. He
allowed only three Brewers to reach base _ two via walks and
another on a first-inning error by Julio Lugo _ and one ball to
leave the infield through six innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a no-hitter going, but he didn't really look like a
pitcher pitching a no-hitter in the sense he was scattering the
ball around a little and wasn't ahead in the count as you might
expect,'' Astros manager Larry Dierker said. ``But he had good
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Keeping with the Enron Field slogan ``Come early, stay late,''
the Brewers made things interesting by scoring four runs over the
seventh and eighth innings. But Astros closer Octavio Dotel retired
all six batters he faced for his eighth save.
</P>
<P>
   After relying on home runs during most of their winning streak,
the Astros generated runs the old-fashion way Friday: one by one,
hit by hit.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Cedeno had three hits, scored three runs and stole two
bases in his first game back since suffering a fractured left hand
May 25. Jeff Bagwell drove in a pair of runs. Richard Hidalgo,
Moises Alou and Bill Spiers each added two hits.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros broke a scoreless tie in the third when Cedeno
singled off Brewers righthander Jimmy Haynes (10-11), stole second
base and scored on a single up the middle by Bagwell, who extended
his hitting streak to 16 games.
</P>
<P>
   In the fifth, Cedeno led off with a single to center field,
advanced to second on a single by Lugo and moved to third on an
error by Jenkins. Bagwell followed with a sacrifice fly for his
97th RBI of the season. Mitch Meluskey, playing in his first game
since being activated off the disabled list, added a run-scoring
single.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros added two more runs in the sixth inning. Spiers
doubled over the head of center fielder Marquis Grissom and scored
on Cedeno's single up the middle off reliever Everett Stull. After
an intentional walk to Bagwell, Hidalgo hit an RBI double down the
left-field line to put the Astros ahead 5-0.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Miller worked out of two minor predicaments to keep
the Brewers hitless _ and scoreless. In the second, he issued a
one-out walk
</P>
<P>
   before retiring the final two batters. In the sixth, pinch
hitter James Mouton led off with a walk, but Ron Belliard hit a
line drive to Bagwell, who touched first for the double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was a big play there,'' Miller said of the sixth-inning
twin killing. ``I thought that could be the play that gets me the
win, the no-hitter or the shutout.''
</P>
<P>
   One out of three isn't bad. Miller allowed two runs and three
hits over six-plus innings for his first victory since July 22.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers rallied for two runs off Miller in the seventh.
Jenkins sent a 2-2 slider off the right-field foul pole to open the
inning. Richie Sexson followed with a single to left field, Jeromy
Burnitz walked, and Charlie Hayes singled up the middle to pull the
Brewers within 5-2.
</P>
<P>
   As Miller walked off the field while being replaced by Marc
Valdes, he was greeted to a standing ovation from the Enron Field
crowd of 36,781.
</P>
<P>
   Dierker said it was evident Miller had reached his limit after
115 pitches. Or maybe it was the extra 15 to 20 minutes of throwing
in the bullpen before his start that cost the 23-year-old
righthander the chance to work deeper into the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was talking to (pitching coach Burt Hooton) before the game,
and he said Miller threw more pitches warming up for a game than
any pitcher he's ever seen,'' Dierker said.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
