</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ONEILL-UMP </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'NEILL AT ODDS WITH UMPIRE
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Paul O'Neill, the New York Yankees' right fielder, sharply
criticized the home plate umpire Gary Cederstrom after Friday
night's game against Anaheim, saying that Cederstrom had retaliated
to some of O'Neill's actions by calling him out on strikes.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the most intentional thing I've ever seen in my
life,'' said O'Neill, who griped about a strike call in the fourth
inning, and was called out on a pitch that appeared to be outside
the strike zone. O'Neill turned and confronted Cederstrom, before
being pushed away by Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager. Cederstrom
did not eject O'Neill, but the rest of the game, he and O'Neill
traded words and glares, even as the umpire left the field after
the game.
</P>
<P>
   Torre called the situation disturbing. ``I didn't hear any of
the conversations,'' Torre said. ``It certainly looked like Gary
was bothered by something and pranced around a little bit.''
Cederstrom declined to comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
