<HEADLINE>
WHITE SITS WITH SORE SHOULDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The shoulder that caused Devon White to miss
nearly three months flared up again and forced the center fielder
out of the starting lineup Friday against the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   White said his left shoulder was sore, but he said he thought
the injury was only going to keep him out day-to-day. White missed
much of the season after suffering a partially torn left rotator
cuff diving for a ball May 2 against Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``He can't swing right-handed,'' Los Angeles Dodgers manager
Davey Johnson said. ``All I know is he can swing left, but he can't
swing right. I had him in the lineup when he came in and said he
couldn't swing right-handed.''
</P>
<P>
   With Mets lefty Al Leiter starting, that became a huge issue.
Dodgers trainer Matt Wilson said the soreness White is experiencing
is likely related to the previous injury. White was available to
pinch hit from the left side.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just sore, a little sore,'' said White, hitting .315 against
left-handers and .235 against right-handers. ``Most definitely
(day-to-day). It's not from the rotator cuff. It's in the back of
the shoulder. I'm available. I'm always available.''
</P>
<P>
   Proving it's an all-out platoon in center field, Johnson opted
to start switch-hitting F.P. Santangelo in center field and bat him
leadoff rather than go with lefty-hitting Tom Goodwin, acquired in
a trading deadline deal from Colorado for Todd Hollandsworth and a
pair of minor-leaguers.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the deal, Dodgers officials said the acquisition
of Goodwin solved the leadoff problem. General manager Kevin Malone
and Johnson each said Goodwin also brought speed
</P>
<P>
   which was sorely lacking to the top of the Dodgers' lineup.
</P>
<P>
   But Goodwin has stolen just three bases in five attempts for the
Dodgers. He's batting .274 with a .373 on-base percentage, but
Goodwin has had just six at-bats (two hits) against left-handed
pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   Power outage in middle: The Dodgers entered the series against
the Mets with a 6-9 mark in August, during which they've produced
few runs. And the middle of the lineup, which produced a bundle of
runs through July, hasn't done much lately.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield is batting .218 with three homers and five RBI,
Eric Karros is batting .200 with four RBI and Shawn Green is
batting .220 with five homers and 12 RBI. The No. 3, 4 and 5
hitters are batting a combined .213.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very rarely are all three of us hitting .200 for an extended
period,'' said Karros, whose last homer came July 25 at Colorado.
``At least Green is driving in some runs. There's not a good time,
but right now, with the way things are going, this is not the most
opportune time of the year. There's no explanation for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers averaged 4.64 runs in their first 15 games of
August, but they've scored three runs or less eight times.
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Right-hander Antonio Osuna had his ailing right
shoulder checked out and was fine. He was available to pitch. ...
Catcher Todd Hundley started for the first time in three games. He
was bothered by a sore right knee and will get today off because
Park is starting. ... With Leiter pitching, right-handed hitting
Kevin Elster started at shortstop over lefty-hitting Alex Cora. It
hurt defensively in the second inning when Elster committed his
13th error, which allowed the game's first run to score. Also,
Elster is hitting .247 (19 for 77) against left-handers and Cora is
batting .304 (7 for 23).
</P>
</TEXT>
