<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-YANKEES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERSTAD PROVIDES LATE-NIGHT THRILLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Forget Al Gore. Forget George W. Bush. In Anaheim,
it's Darin Erstad for president.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad made one of the best catches of the year to save the game
in the bottom of the 10th, then homered in the top of the 11th to
propel the Anaheim Angels to an improbable 9-8 victory over the New
York Yankees before 37,503 at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad's feats were made possible by a five-run ninth inning,
when the Angels rallied from an 8-3 deficit to tie the game at 8.
The final three runs of the inning came home on Mo Vaughn's
two-out, three-run homer off Yankees closer Mariano Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   But the big rally would have been meaningless if not for
Erstad's incredible catch.
</P>
<P>
   With runners on second and third and two outs in the 10th, Jorge
Posada hit a liner toward the gap in left field that appeared
headed to the wall. But Erstad made a spectacular diving catch with
his back to homeplate, keeping the game tied and the Angels' hopes
alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I moved in and over with two strikes, because the last thing I
wanted was for him to fight off a tough pitch and drop in a blooper
to beat us,'' Erstad said. ``If he was going to beat us, he was
going to have to hit it over my head.''
</P>
<P>
   Posada nearly did.
</P>
<P>
   ``You tell yourself before the pitch to react and trust your
ability,'' Erstad said. ``As I was running I wasn't 100 percent
sure I could get to it, but when I started to jump I had a good
bead on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Yankees starter Roger Clemens, who stifled the Angels for eight
innings before tiring in the ninth, called it one of the best
catches he has ever seen. Yankees manager Joe Torre wasn't sure at
first if Erstad made the catch, but ``we knew when the crowd went
silent it was bad for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Then with one out in the top of the 11th, Erstad hit a 1-0 pitch
from Mike Stanton (2-2) into the right-field seats for his 21st
homer of the year and a 9-8 lead. Erstad, though, had to fight off
pitcher Shigetoshi Hasegawa (8-2) to get to the on-deck circle at
the start of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Hasegawa, who threw three scoreless innings to get the victory,
gave up the liner by Posada and tried to give Erstad a hug in the
dugout after the inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, 'Stop it! I've got to hit,''' Erstad said.
</P>
<P>
   Even after Erstad's homer gave the Angels a lead, the Yankees
were due to send up Paul O'Neill, Bernie Williams and David Justice
in the bottom of the 11th. Had the game been tied, Angels manager
Mike Scioscia would have brought in lefty Mike Holtz to face the
three left-handed hitters. But with a chance to close it out, he
left Hasegawa in for a third inning.
</P>
<P>
   Hasegawa retired the side in order for the Angels' second
victory in four games on the current trip.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels appeared listless through eight innings against
Clemens, who finally tired in the ninth. Torre watched Clemens give
up back-to-back singles to Troy Glaus and Bengie Molina to start
the ninth, and went to his bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Nelson entered the game and got the first out on a fly ball
by Adam Kennedy, but walked Kevin Stocker to load the bases. Torre
went to his bullpen again, summoning Rivera, who has 26 saves.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad hit a sharp grounder to third, where Luis Sojo fielded
the ball and stepped on third for the force out. But his throw to
first was too late to get Erstad, allowing the first run of the
inning to score.
</P>
<P>
   With two out, Rivera got ahead of Orlando Palmeiro in the count,
0-2, but Palmeiro hit one down the right-field line for an RBI
double, cutting the Yankees lead to 8-5. That brought up Vaughn,
who launched a 0-1 pitch into the right-field seats for a
game-tying three-run homer.
</P>
<P>
   It marked the fifth blown save of the season for Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I haven't been around that long, but to me, that was
the biggest comeback we've ever had,'' Erstad said. ``Until the
game is over, you keep battling. How many times do you get to go
against one of the best pitchers in the history of baseball, and
the best closer? Opportunities like that are few and far between.
That's why you go to the last out.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia reiterated his vote for MVP of the American League is
Erstad, even if he's a little biased.
</P>
<P>
   ``People who see him play every day see the intensity he plays
with, and the different ways he can beat a ballclub,'' Scioscia
said. ``All I can say is incredible. Incredible.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
