<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWINDALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINSTON WEST SERIES OLDIES STILL GOODIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEITH LAIR  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. _ Take a close look at the NASCAR Winston West
cars when they take to Irwindale Speedway for the Home Depot 250
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Do they look exactly like Winston Cup cars? They should.
</P>
<P>
   Scratch off the paint on Steve Portegna's car and Derrick Cope's
paint scheme would appear. The cars driven by John Borneman and
Eric Norris once were raced by Ricky Rudd. Austin Cameron's car was
driven by Darrell Waltrip and the car of Brandon Ash was raced by
Rusty Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every Winston West team has purchased an old Winston Cup
car. The two division's weight, wheelbase and engine displacement
are the same. The only difference is in the 350 cubic V-8s'
compression ratio. Winston Cup cars are allowed a 12-to-1 ratio and
Winston West cars have a 9.5-to-1 ratio.
</P>
<P>
   ``What happens is that all the research and development has been
put into that race car,'' said Food4Less/Glendora Autotech team
owner Joe Nava, a Glendora resident. ``We don't have the time and
money to do that. You know you are getting great quality, and you
know what you've got going in.''
</P>
<P>
   Nava said there is an additional benefit.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we need a part, we can call (the former car owner, Jack)
Roush, tell them it came off Johnny's car, give them the part
serial number and they'll mail it,'' he said. ``We don't have to
try to make the part ourselves. That saves a lot of time.''
</P>
<P>
   This, and the fact the cars are so similar, is the reason many
teams purchase year-old or two-year-old Winston Cup models.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't take as long to break down cars,'' said Norris,
whose team bought the superspeedway car of Rudd. ``You know the car
has a good background, and you can get an excellent car a little
cheaper.''
</P>
<P>
   One team that was able to get into the Winston West Series
quickly and effectively was Ramona's Borneman, who raced in
Irwindale's Super Late Model class last year. Borneman bought the
car, parts and various equipment from Rudd, who disbanded his team
after the 1999 season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to get everything for 10 cents on the dollar,''
he said. ``We really got the whole shop. It's a real good car ...
it won a race at Michigan (Speedway). It was too good of an offer
to pass up.''
</P>
<P>
   But some drivers do not think having the cars is an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it has helped us win,'' said Bobby Dotter, who
won on 2-year-old Sterling Marlin equipment in the first Home Depot
250 at Irwindale on June 24. ``You can win if you have confidence
in your equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   Points leader Brendan Gaughan does not use any recycled Winston
Cup equipment. His car is built in a state-of-the-art facility
recently constructed just outside of Las Vegas, his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Small's team builds its own equipment, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people think the Winston Cup cars help, but I don't think
so,'' he said. ``Technical equipment doesn't make you go fast.
That's why we like to work on our own equipment.''
</P>
<P>
   But whether or not the old Winston Cup cars help Winston West
drivers win, they're a big part of the series. And it looks like it
will stay that way for the foreseeable future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-00 0203EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
