<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-RANGERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX KILL SUSPENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB HOHLER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   For a Red Sox team growing dangerously reliant on last-gasp
heroics, there was something sweet Friday night about dousing the
Texas Rangers, 6-4, in musty old Fenway in a contest almost free of
suspense.
</P>
<P>
   And something even sweeter about the triumph coming on the eve
of Pedro Martinez's start Saturday, which puts the Sox in good
position to win five of the first six games of their 10-game
homestand.
</P>
<P>
   The win lifted the Sox to within one game of Oakland in the
wild-card race and within three of the East-leading Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   And once again, the hero was a latecomer to the team, Tomo Ohka,
the pride of Siesio High School in Kyoto, Japan. His sturdy,
seven-inning outing helped give the Sox a 6-1 lead and allowed most
of the rain-soaked 33,009 in the ballyard to head for the exits
without the fear of missing any walk-off dramatics.
</P>
<P>
   The ever-modest Ohka, 24, fresh from the best performance of his
major league career, deemed his effort ``so-so.'' After all, only
80 days have passed since he threw a perfect game for Pawtucket.
</P>
<P>
   But the significance of the outcome was not lost on the
promising righthander. ``I am very happy,'' he said through a
translator, ``to contribute to my team's win more than anything,
especially (being) one game behind Oakland (in the wild-card
race.)''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, to their relief and Ohka's benefit, reversed their
recent trend of waiting until beer sales have been cut off before
they stage their biggest rallies.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox have come from behind to win three games this week,
including two spectacular rallies with two outs in the ninth
inning.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the third inning, Ohka was protecting the 6-1
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was big for us to score early,'' said catcher Jason
Varitek. ``On top of that, it was important to have somebody hold
the lead, which is not easy to do. But Tomo did a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohka (2-2) retired the side in order in five of his seven
innings. In the second, he pitched out of his most perilous jam.
Singles by Gabe Kapler and Ricky Ledee and a walk to Bill Haselman
loaded the bases with two outs. But Ohka escaped by inducing Royce
Clayton to ground into a force play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a lot more confidence,'' pitching coach Joe Kerrigan
said. ``He gets a couple of runners on and he doesn't waver. He
didn't much before, but I think this year he knows he can stay away
from the big inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohka's teammates said they have seen his confidence soar since
he posted his first major league win as a starter last Sunday in
Texas. And the early run support enhanced his comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever I saw him in Triple A, he was dominating, but he was
a completely different pitcher up here,'' said third baseman Lou
Merloni, who had two hits, extending his hitting streak to five
games since he rejoined the team Monday. ``Tonight, you could see
he had that confidence again. We just gave some runs and he took
the ball and held them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohka scattered four hits and one walk over seven innings, and
mowed down the final 14 batters he faced.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the reeling Rangers, mired in last place in the AL
West, showed every sign of spinning deeper into baseball's
netherworld. With one episode of ineptitude after another, the
Rangers helped the Sox turn five singles and a triple into six runs
by the third inning.
</P>
<P>
   Texas lefthander Kenny Rogers (11-11) was sliced apart mostly by
tweaky hits and a porous defense. One of the few solid Sox hits was
Troy O'Leary's two-run triple in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers officially committed three errors, but they
misplayed a number of other balls into hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an ugly day for us,'' said Rogers. ``I think I reached
the end of my rope after about the ninth crappy hit.''
</P>
<P>
   The way Sox manager Jimy Williams saw it, the game was a matter
of Boston making a lot out of a little.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had pretty good aim tonight,'' Williams said. ``Maybe we
didn't hit some balls real hard, but we hit them in the right
spots.''
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett found more holes than anyone, knocking out four
hits on a couple of bloopers to right, a grounder up the middle,
and an infield hit.
</P>
<P>
   But Boston's offense, other than O'Leary's triple and the
Rangers' miscues, was largely a patchwork effort. Designated hitter
Bernard Gilkey had a key hit during a three-run spurt in the third,
keeping alive a two-out rally by singling home Nomar Garciaparra.
It was Gilkey's first RBI since July 29.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers made a run in the ninth, with Boston leading, 6-1.
Back-to-back, one-out singles by Rafael Palmeiro and Kapler off
reliever Rheal Cormier, who started the ninth after Rod Beck held
Texas scoreless in the eighth, put them in position to reverse
Thursday's finale. Ledee followed with a double to right, scoring
Palmeiro, and moving Kapler to third.
</P>
<P>
   Closer Derek Lowe came in, only to have Mike Lamb double off the
center-field wall, cutting Boston's lead to 6-4. But Lowe struck
out Haselman and Clayton to end the game and earn his 28th save.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
