<SLUG> BC-OLY-WOMENS'GYM-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLASS OF '96 DETAINED? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The end grows closer, but the results no clearer.
</P>
<P>
   America's top female gymnasts hit the FleetCenter floor Friday
night for the preliminary round of the Olympic trials, but little
changed in the pyramid of power.
</P>
<P>
   With just Sunday night's final round to go, Elise Ray and
Kristen Maloney rank 1-2 on the scoresheet, but no one truly knows
who ranks higher in the eyes of Bela Karolyi and officials of USA
Gymnastics.
</P>
<P>
   However, just less than an hour after the end of Friday night's
competition, held before a crowd of 15,035, Karolyi revealed it is
highly unlikely _ his word: unlikeable _ that all three veterans
remaining from the '96 Games (Amy Chow, Dominique Dawes, and
Shannon Miller) will be asked to board the bus again for Olympus.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we could have my ultimate dream,'' said Karolyi, whose
personal wish list had three veterans and three of the new kids
making it to Sydney. ``But I don't think it's (likely). The new
generation is extremely strong.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the three remaining Golden Girls turned up the heat
Friday night on the likes of Jamie Dantzscher, Vanessa Atler, and
Alyssa Beckerman, who were ranked 3-5, respectively, when the
nationals ended last month in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   By the time the floor was cleared, Chow had rocketed from sixth
to third, Dantzscher was in fourth, and Morgan White had moved from
seventh to fifth.
</P>
<P>
   Dawes, ninth overall in St. Louis, finished the night ranked
seventh, just behind Atler, who had the night's worst breakdown,
crashing on her back as she botched her dismount from the balance
beam. Beckerman, with three of her scores under 9.0, plummeted to
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   There was also the continuing story of Miller, the most
decorated gymnast in US history, who only last December decided to
come out of retirement.
</P>
<P>
   It was her first time competing in four events and she opened
with a sparkling 9.712 on the uneven bars. Her low point was her
fall on her opening vault, leading to an 8.893 and a seventh-place
finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could I do that?'' said Miller, explaining her frame of
mind when she went derriere-down on her opening vault. ``That's not
a vault that I ever miss. I've done it so many times, maybe I just
wasn't thinking about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray, just out of high school and headed to the University of
Michigan, ranked No. 1 on the night, maintained her slim hold on
first overall over Maloney (54.081-53.376). It is almost impossible
to imagine a USA team without either of these talented tumblers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm pretty confident (about making the team),'' said Maloney.
``Nothing is for sure, but . . .''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the men's squad, which guarantees the top four finishers
trips Down Under, the women's team is chosen strictly by the
subjective slide rule of Karolyi and Co. But the scores have to
count, simply because scores, as well as style, drive the sport.
</P>
<P>
   Based on Karolyi's ruminations regarding the '96 holdovers, it's
likely four new faces will be seen in Sydney, probably Ray,
Maloney, Dantzscher, and White. Then it would come down to Chow
(second overall Friday night) and Karolyi's pick: Dawes or Miller.
</P>
<P>
   If Miller can improve on her numbers Sunday night, and convince
Karolyi that four more weeks of hard work will make her a valuable
contributor, she likely would go ahead of Dawes. With so many
youngsters on the team, it's a squad that could use Miller's
guiding hand.
</P>
<P>
   White's performance, fourth best, was encouraging. Her game
didn't fall apart in St. Louis, but it didn't meet expectations. In
the days leading up to the event in the Hub, Karolyi consistently
mentioned her as a potential key ingredient. For four events under
pressure, she lived up to the heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had two big mistakes on beam tonight, and I can definitely
clean those up,'' said White, who finished with a 9.312 on the
beam. ``But I moved up two spots, and I'm thrilled about that. It
was extremely important to move up, after being seventh in the
nationals, and I'm absolutely thrilled.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
