<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DODGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIAZZA AND ALFONZO SHARE   TOP BILLING IN METS' VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Sports Illustrated christened Mike Piazza as ``The
Man'' on its cover this week, but the Mets catcher does not feel
pressure to carry his team. He is thrilled with his supporting
cast, and he needs it to produce if he is going to reach the World
Series for the first time in his career. ``You're only as good as
the guys around you,'' Piazza said.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza and the Mets began a three-game series Friday night at
Dodger Stadium, where Piazza began his career eight years ago and
where he seemed destined to end it. But Piazza never led the
Dodgers to a playoff victory, and they traded him to the the
Florida Marlins in May 1998. Now Piazza looks poised to lead the
Mets deep into the postseason. Games like Friday night's make that
seem possible.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza slugged a two-run homer off Dodgers ace Kevin Brown in
the third inning, but the Dodgers tied the score. It was Edgardo
Alfonzo, Piazza's co-star, who drove in the winning run in a 5-3
Mets victory.
</P>
<P>
   After Joe McEwing singled and advanced to third on a wild
pickoff throw by reliever Terry Adams, Alfonzo stroked his third
single of the night to break a tie in the eighth inning. John
Franco and Armando Benitez preserved the lead, ensuring the victory
for Rick White, who worked 1 2/3 overpowering innings in relief of
Al Leiter.
</P>
<P>
   Alfonzo added his fourth hit, a double, in the ninth inning, and
Piazza singled him home for his 100th run batted in. This is the
fifth season in a row that Piazza has reached that RBI plateau.
</P>
<P>
   Leiter fell apart in a three-run Dodgers sixth that erased the
3-0 lead the Mets built on Piazza's homer. Gary Sheffield, the best
player of the five the Dodgers received from the Marlins in the
Piazza trade, homered for the Dodgers' first run. Sheffield's
popularity in Los Angeles will grow the more he produces, but he
has said he does not feel embraced by the fans, many of whom still
revere Piazza. Their statistics since the trade are similar, with
Piazza holding an edge in batting average and runs batted in,
Sheffield in on-base percentage and runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   The biggest difference is in the fortunes of the teams. The Mets
are 65 games above .500 since they acquired Piazza from the
Marlins. The Dodgers are only one game above .500 since they sent
Piazza away.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fans haven't gotten over it because of what Mike Piazza
meant to the Dodgers, and I understand that,'' Dodgers chairman Bob
Daly said recently. ``That thing got messed up, and everyone knows
about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield is the only player from the trade who is still with
the Dodgers. Seven months after trading Piazza, they signed Brown
to a seven-year, $105 million contract. Last winter, they signed
outfielder Shawn Green to a six-year, $84 million deal. Both
players have a higher average annual salary than the Dodgers
offered Piazza.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodger Stadium crowd, so relaxed so often, has a strong
reaction whenever Piazza comes to bat; he is booed or cheered with
passion. He lined out in his first at-bat, then came up in the
third with one out, after Edgardo Alfonzo lashed a single off the
second baseman's glove.
</P>
<P>
   Brown's 1-1 fastball tailed inside on Piazza, but it did not
sink. Piazza hit it squarely, and the ball carried into the
left-center-field bleachers to give the Mets a 3-0 lead and Piazza
his 32nd home run. He also drove in a run for the first time in a
week. Piazza has not exactly slumped, but the two-run homer
followed his only five-start stretch this year in which he did not
drive in a run.
</P>
<P>
   The home run was an emphatic way to score off Brown, whose
pitches, some hitters think, have more movement than any other
pitcher's. Darren Dreifort, the right-hander who faces the Mets on
Sunday, challenges Brown for that distinction.
</P>
<P>
   In the second, the Mets got their first run on two infield hits
and an error by shortstop Kevin Elster, who could not glove
Leiter's grounder. Piazza's homer brought in the only earned runs
Brown allowed in an abbreviated outing. He was removed for a
pinch-hitter in the sixth, an inning that started with a home run
by Sheffield, his 38th.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros then singled and Green doubled to the warning track
in center. A single by Adrian Beltre cut the Mets' lead to 3-2, and
Green scored the game-tying run on a sacrifice fly, with Jay
Payton's throw bouncing off his leg before it reached the plate.
Leiter would get no more outs, walking the next two hitters _
including Jim Leyritz, batting for Brown _ and yielding to White.
</P>
<P>
   White fanned F.P. Santangelo with a hard splitter, but Mark
Grudzielanek grounded sharply down the right-field line. First
baseman Todd Zeile, the other player the Dodgers traded when they
dealt Piazza, dove to his left and speared it, flipping to White
for the inning-ending out. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
