<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-METS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS CONTINUE TO FLOUNDER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Like Kevin Brown has said for the past five days,
his side appeared fine.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers' season, however, is not even close to
that. It's in dire, desperate despair, and that may be an
optimistic account.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are a season-high eight games out of first place
after a 5-3 loss to the Mets on Friday at Dodger Stadium, and at a
time when teams are tightening their play the Dodgers have come
apart.
</P>
<P>
   They committed three errors, failed miserably to score runs from
third base with less than two outs, and no longer is talk about
making the playoffs the topic in the clubhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't even look at the standings anymore,'' Dodgers left
fielder Gary Sheffield said. ``All it will do is depress me, and
depress people. We just have to go out there and play with some
pride. We have to play for respect.''
</P>
<P>
   That's how far the Dodgers have tumbled. Less than two weeks ago
they were 2 games out of first place. But they've lost nine of 12,
and while the future of manager Davey Johnson remains solid for the
remainder of the season, it's looking more and more bleak his
tenure will last much longer than October.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always talk about this being a big month, August, and we're
eight games out,'' said shortstop Alex Cora, who had a pinch-hit
single in the eighth. ``We need to start making a run.''
</P>
<P>
   Mets catcher Mike Piazza continued to torture his old team with
a two-run homer in the third inning and three RBI. Piazza's
ninth-inning single extended the Mets' lead to 5-3 and gave him 100
RBI. It's the fifth straight season Piazza's reached that mark.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always great to come back here,'' Piazza said. ``I still
have a lot of friends. The weather is great, and it's great to get
out of the humidity in New York. But I don't look at it as
vindication. My thing is to always keep it simple, and to just try
and stay relaxed.''
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield, who went 4 for 25 during the recently completed
six-game road trip, had three hits, including his 38th homer. His
home run to lead off the sixth inning leaves him one shy of
Chicago's Sammy Sosa, who leads the major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers continue to make mistakes, and squander chances.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, who allowed three runs (two earned) in six innings, fell
victim to Kevin Elster booting a ball with two outs in the second
inning that allowed a run to score and give the Mets a 1-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   And before Piazza, one of the leading MVP candidates, crushed
Brown's 1-1 pitch into the left-field bleachers in the third
inning, Edgardo Alfonzo singled to right on a line drive that
appeared second baseman Mark Grudzielanek could have caught.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the Dodgers scored three times in the sixth inning to
tie it, they wasted a chance to break the game open. With the bases
loaded and one out, Mets reliever Rick White struck out F.P.
Santangelo and got Mark Grudzielanek to ground to first baseman
Todd Zeile, who made a diving stop.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers also had first and third with one out and trailed
4-3 in the eighth inning, but again Santangelo struck out. It was
the fourth time in five plate appearances Santangelo whiffed, and
the third time looking. Grudzielanek ended the inning by grounding
out to third.
</P>
<P>
   ``The series that stick out in my mind are the ones against the
Brewers, the Phillies, the Cubs and Milwaukee,'' said Dodgers
catcher Todd Hundley, who was ejected in the eighth inning for
arguing a strike. ``Those are the series that have to be won, and
we're paying the consequences of those now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
