<HEADLINE>
AROUND THE WORLD, WHAT IT TAKES TO BE A MILLIONAIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Blame the British. The simple game show they started in
September 1998 has replicated like bacteria in warm agar. ``Who
Wants to Be a Millionaire'' has turned into a global subculture,
with 27 licensed versions being broadcast in 29 countries.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens more countries have already bought franchise rights from
the show's British creator, Celador Productions, and there are, of
course, at least a few unlicensed knockoffs. So far, the format
remains the same, with contestants facing questions worth
escalating amounts of money.
</P>
<P>
   At least half the fun for the show's American fans is kvetching
about how easy the questions are, and how, if they were on the
show, they'd win that million dollars, easy. That scornful
pleasure, too, is spreading around the globe. But just how common
is common knowledge? Here's your chance to see whether you, too,
could be a crorepati, a multi-miljonair, a miljonaariksi, a
milliardario . . .
</P>
<P>
   _ By Andrea Kannapell
</P>
<P>
   Britain
</P>
<P>
   TITLE: Who Wants to Be a Millionaire
</P>
<P>
   TOP PRIZE: 1 million pounds ($1.5 million)  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOST: Chris Tarrant, radio personality
</P>
<P>
   1. Starting with the earliest, put these four Archbishops of
Canterbury in order.
</P>
<P>
   A. George Carey
</P>
