<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Aug. 20:
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-OBASANJO (Abuja, Nigeria) _ Special Report: When
President Clinton crisscrossed Africa in 1998, his plane overflew
Nigeria in a pointed snub at the generals leading it. On his second
trip to Africa next weekend, Clinton's main destination will be
Nigeria, a country that under the elected civilian government of
Olusegun Obasanjo has undergone one of Africa's most stunning and
convulsive political transformations. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUBMARINE (Moscow) _ The Russian navy said Saturday that
all 118 members of the crew of the wrecked nuclear submarine Kursk
are now likely dead, or will be before a British rescue submarine
arrives with a team of Norwegian divers to make a final desperate
effort to open a rear hatch and look for survivors. By Patrick E.
Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   POLAND-POLITICS (Warsaw, Poland) _ A special Polish court last
week cleared the popular president, Aleksander Kwasniewski, and a
former president, Lech Walesa, of charges that they spied for the
Communist secret police. But behind that bizarre and embarrassing
drama, Poles believe, are the desperate straits of Solidarity's
current leader, the ambitious Marian Krzaklewski, whose own
candidacy for the presidency is floundering badly. By Steven
Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-GAS (Caracas, Venezuela) _ Like motorists everywhere,
Venezuelans love to complain about the price of gasoline, and they
have been doing a lot of that lately. But one thing sets them apart
from almost everyone else in the world: At less than 40 cents a
gallon, gas is cheaper than bottled water here. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   CIA-LATIN-AMERICA (Washington) _ Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright and CIA Director George Tenet are at odds over the extent
to which the United States should release documentation of its
involvement with repressive Latin American regimes in decades past.
By Christopher Marquis.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-ARMY-SHOOTING (Bogota, Colombia) _ In a test of its
commitment to improving its human rights record, the Colombian
government has promised a full-scale investigation into the
killings by army troops of six elementary school children last
week. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   PHILIPPINES-ESTRADA (Manila, Philippines) _ Halfway into
President Joseph Estrada's six-year term, the economy is faltering,
corruption and cronyism seem to be ascendant and Muslim separatists
and kidnappers are getting out of hand in the southern Philippines.
The public is desperate for him to start getting things done. By
Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-IMMIGRATION (Rome) _ With national elections looming next
year, immigration is emerging as the issue that may define the
battle between the ruling center-left coalition and its
center-right opposition. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-REFORM (United Nations) _ Vice President Al Gore would give
more unqualified support to the United Nations and be more willing
to sign international treaties than his Republican opponent, George
W. Bush, says an independent U.N. watchdog organization that
surveyed both candidates. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``s'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   OLY-WOMEN (Undated) _ When the modern Olympics began in 1896,
women were not allowed to participate. Times have changed,
grudgingly but significantly, in the past century. At the 2000
Summer Games in Sydney, Australia, more women will compete in more
sports, and in more events, than ever. And for the first time,
women will compete in the same number of team sports as men. By
Jere Longman.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   BILINGUAL-EDUC (Oceanside, Calif.) _ Two years after
Californians voted to end bilingual education and force a million
Spanish-speaking students to immerse themselves in English as if it
were a cold bath, those students are improving in reading and other
subjects at often striking rates, according to standardized test
scores released last week. By Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO-RIVER (Chicago) _ Long reviled as a virtual open sewer
that flowed through the heart of the city, the Chicago River has
been reborn. Now, city planners, especially Mayor Richard Daley,
are hoping to capitalize on the river _ the city's economic
lifeline for more than 100 years _ only this time with tourism
rather than heavy industry. By Ellen Almer.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``w'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-PRIVACY (Washington) _ After nine months of blistering
criticism from doctors, patients and consumer groups, the Clinton
administration has decided to beef up protections for the privacy
of medical records, beyond what it proposed last year. By Robert
Pear.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-2000 (Los Angeles) _ Moving quickly on several fronts
to capitalize on the afterglow from their conventions, the
presidential contenders plan this week to open the biggest
television advertising blitzes of their campaigns. Gov. George W.
Bush will emphasize education and Vice President Al Gore will
trumpet himself as a champion of working families. By Richard L.
Berke.
</P>
<P>
   DEM-CVN-LOCAL (Los Angeles) _ Just as the Republican convention
was really all about George W. Bush _ to the point that congressmen
and governors were consigned to tertiary roles _ the Democrats made
their convention all about ``providing content'' to local stations
so that LOCAL candidates could get their moment in the sun. By
Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH (Dallas) _ At rallies here and across the border in New
Mexico, Gov. George W. Bush planned to unveil a new campaign pledge
Saturday, a call to spend more than $800 million to repair
crumbling schools on the country's Indian reservations. By Michael
Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   GORE (Dateline to come) _ Developments from the campaign trail.
By Katharine Q. Seelye. Eds: Expected by late afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON (Lake Placid, N.Y.) _ As if to prove that he is fully
capable of ceding the spotlight to his vice president, President
Clinton has literally headed for the hills for a few days of
vacation in the Adirondacks. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   COLUMNS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``k'' news file)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Los Angeles) _ ``Liberties'' by Maureen Dowd: The
man we elect to occupy the Oval Office must have steady nerves in
case he faces a ``Fail Safe'' moment _ not a thermonuclear crisis
but a thong crisis.
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ ``Reckonings'' by Paul Krugman: Al
Gore is accusing the Republicans of offering tax cuts that benefit
only the rich. Is he telling the truth? In a word: yes.
</P>
