<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 11:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A5479 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-INDONESIA-JOKES-REVIE     08-19 0473
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-JOKES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDONESIA'S PRESIDENT IS A BARREL OF LAUGHS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 
 (EDS: Please note that the final joke may be offensive to some
readers.) 
  
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ There is no such thing as a political
movement based on jokes, President Abdurrahman Wahid once wrote.
But Wahid himself may be the evidence to the contrary. He jokes to
relieve tension, to instruct, to make a point. In fact, his address
to Parliament last week sounded a bit like a nightclub act.
</P>
<P>
   One joke, suggesting the need for cross-cultural understanding,
involved a non-Muslim bus driver who was knocked unconscious in an
accident. As he lay dying, a Muslim urged him to save his soul by
calling out the name of Allah.
</P>
<P>
   ``Say the name! Say the name!'' the man insisted.
</P>
<P>
   The bus driver opened his eyes briefly and murmured, ``Grogol,''
the name of the next stop on the line.
</P>
<P>
   Here are a few more.
</P>
<P>
   _ Why in the tough times of former President Suharto did so many
Indonesians go to Singapore for dental work? Were dentists in
Indonesia so inferior?
</P>
<P>
   No, it was not that. It was just that nobody in Indonesia was
allowed to open his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   _ One day Suharto was caught in a flood and rescued by a farmer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know who I am?'' he said. ``I'm the president of
Indonesia. As thanks, I'll give you anything you want.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want one thing,'' said the farmer. ``Please don't tell
anybody I rescued you.''
</P>
<P>
   _ When Wahid, who is virtually blind, was elected last October
he named his taciturn rival, Megawati Sukarnoputri, as vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an ideal team,'' he said. ``The president can't see
and the vice president can't talk.''
</P>
<P>
   _ An undertaker was unable to fold the hands of a corpse. The
body was stiff and one arm remained outstretched.
</P>
<P>
   ``What can I do?'' he asked the local religious leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was the man's profession?''
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a policeman.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In that case,'' said the religious leader, ``just put 10,000
rupiah in his other hand and he'll bring his arm down.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Wahid was reported to have told this anecdote to President
Clinton:
</P>
<P>
   Winston Churchill was taking a walk with Clement Atlee,
Britain's Labor prime minister at the end of World War II.
Churchill said he needed to relieve himself and asked for some
privacy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why?'' Atlee asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because,'' said Churchill, ``whenever you see something big
you want to nationalize it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
