<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 11:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6488 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-VEEPS-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      08-19 1084
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VEEPS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHOOSING A RUNNING MATE MATTERS. OR, MATTERED. 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Vice presidential candidates, like the Perseid
meteor shower, briefly light up midsummer skies. Usually, that's as
long as they matter because people vote for presidents, not vice
presidents.
</P>
<P>
   With the election only some 11 weeks away, Dick Cheney, a former
congressman and defense secretary, and Sen. Joseph Lieberman of
Connecticut have already done just about everything running mates
can do for their tickets, from reflecting well on the presidential
candidates who chose them to providing a lift for their national
conventions.
</P>
<P>
   But those contributions have been significant. Cheney and
Lieberman were serious choices, men voters can imagine as
president, and displayed Gov. George W. Bush of Texas and Vice
President Al Gore in a ``presidential'' manner, making a critical
big decision in a serious way.
</P>
<P>
   Neither man was a crassly political choice, someone selected
simply to carry a big state, as Gov. Tom Ridge of Pennsylvania
would have been for Bush, or Sen. Dick Durbin of Illinois for Gore.
Wyoming's three electoral votes were safe for Bush before he picked
its former congressman; Connecticut's eight were almost as solidly
secure for Gore before he chose its junior senator.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's choice of his father's defense secretary for a running
mate was ``safe and responsible,'' said professor Stephen Wayne, a
Georgetown University political scientist. ``It basically gave us
an indication that if George W. Bush is elected, he will be a
president who uses advisers in making decisions.'' Or, as a more
caustic academic student of presidential elections, professor
Nelson W. Polsby of the University of California at Berkeley, put
it, ``Cheney was picked to indemnify Bush against the charge that
he was ignorant.''
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Lieberman, the first Jew on a national ticket,
was more dramatic. As Wayne put it, ``the choice was unexpected and
courageous'' _ words not usually associated with Gore. Bob Shrum, a
key Gore strategist, said, ``People began taking a fresh look at Al
Gore through his choice of Joe Lieberman.'' And he brought
something else through his aura of incorruptibility and moral
outrage against President Clinton's dalliance with a White House
intern. As Polsby observed, ``Lieberman was picked to indemnify
Gore against the charge that he was sleazy.''
</P>
<P>
   And each fulfilled the other main duty of a vice presidential
choice. Each dominated public attention for several days, keeping
the other side out of the news and presumably out of voter's minds.
</P>
<P>
   That was especially important for Gore, whose staff leaked the
Lieberman choice on the Monday after the Republican convention _
stopping Bush's momentum cold. ``The Gore campaign had been in the
doldrums,'' Wayne said. ``If Gore wins the election, we'll say this
was the beginning, the jump start.''
</P>
<P>
   The publicity for Cheney was overwhelmingly positive, but
included some negative recollections of his voting record,
including his votes against banning ``cop killer'' bullets that
penetrate policemen's Kevlar vests. Cheney also voted against a
resolution urging freedom for Nelson Mandela, who was then
imprisoned.
</P>
<P>
   The attention focused on Lieberman was even more upbeat. No one
attacked him _ perhaps for fear of sounding anti-Semitic _ except
for a few blacks who were largely silenced by reminders from Rep.
John Lewis and the Rev. Jesse Jackson that Lieberman had marched
with the Rev. Martin Luther King Jr. Some of his more conservative
votes, like experiments with school vouchers, were instantly and
publicly forgiven on the assurance that Gore, not Lieberman, would
make policy.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it is not a certainty that Cheney or Lieberman will
have no continuing influence on this election. But take the most
obvious possibility _ Lieberman's religion. Jews already vote
heavily, and heavily Democratic. So Lieberman is not likely to
change their direct impact on the vote the way John F. Kennedy
brought Catholics back to their Democratic roots. He might cost his
ticket votes because of his religion or gain votes from people who
concluded that opposition to him was unworthy.
</P>
<P>
   But neither effect is likely to be large.
</P>
<P>
   That was not always true. Geographic balance meant more when the
country's regions were more distinct, and plainly Lyndon B. Johnson
carried Texas for Kennedy in 1960. Shrum thinks Bill Clinton's
choice of Gore in 1992 had a lasting effect, helping eke out some
narrow victories in Southern states and reinforcing a message of
youth and change.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes vice presidential nominations were necessary
investments just to get a nomination. Franklin D. Roosevelt won
over Texas delegates in 1932 with a promise to make John Nance
Garner his vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas E. Dewey's aides promised Rep. Charles E. Halleck of
Indiana the No. 2 spot in 1948 in exchange for Indiana's delegates.
(Dewey reneged and picked Gov. Earl Warren of California. He lost
California anyway.)
</P>
<P>
   And sometimes vice presidential candidates hurt a ticket by
creating a distraction or embarrassment. It is hard to imagine this
year's buttoned-down, dare-to-be-cautious vice presidential duo
committing a gaffe like Henry Cabot Lodge's 1960 promise that as
president, Richard M. Nixon would appoint a black to the Cabinet,
an offer that could have cost votes in the South.
</P>
<P>
   More often the distractions have developed from a disclosure of
hitherto unexamined parts of the candidate's past, like the secret
sources of Nixon's finances in 1952, Thomas Eagleton's electroshock
therapy in 1972, Geraldine Ferraro's husband's murky business ties
in 1984 and Dan Quayle's avoidance of the draft in 1988. And none
of those embarrassments were decisive in those elections.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in most elections, vice presidential nominees embody the
enduring truth of the following observation by Thomas Marshall,
Woodrow Wilson's vice president: ``Once there were two brothers:
One ran away to sea, the other was elected vice president _ and
nothing was ever heard from either of them again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-00 1114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000819.0046 </DOCNO>
