<SLUG> BC-FRONTPAGE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Page 1, Sunday, Aug. 20.
</P>
<P>
   TOP
</P>
<P>
   Lead story:
</P>
<P>
   BILINGUAL-EDUC (Oceanside, Calif.) _ Two years after
Californians voted to end bilingual education and force a million
Spanish-speaking students to immerse themselves in English as if it
were a cold bath, those students are improving in reading and other
subjects at often striking rates, according to standardized test
scores released last week. By Jacques Steinberg.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by noon in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Top center story:
</P>
<P>
   OLY-WOMEN (Undated) _ When the modern Olympics began in 1896,
women were not allowed to participate. Times have changed,
grudgingly but significantly, in the past century. At the 2000
Summer Games in Sydney, Australia, more women will compete in more
sports, and in more events, than ever. And for the first time,
women will compete in the same number of team sports as men. By
Jere Longman.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 1 p.m. ET in ``s'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Off-lead story:
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-2000 (Los Angeles) _ Moving quickly on several fronts
to capitalize on the afterglow from their conventions, the
presidential contenders plan this week to open the biggest
television advertising blitzes of their campaigns. Gov. George W.
Bush will emphasize education and Vice President Al Gore will
trumpet himself as a champion of working families. By Richard L.
Berke.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 1 p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ABOVE FOLD:
</P>
<P>
   DEM-CVN-LOCAL (Los Angeles) _ Just as the Republican convention
was really all about George W. Bush _ to the point that congressmen
and governors were consigned to tertiary roles _ the Democrats made
their convention all about ``providing content'' to local stations
so that LOCAL candidates could get their moment in the sun. By
Peter Marks.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 1:15 p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Reefer to:
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON (Lake Placid, N.Y.) _ As if to prove that he is fully
capable of ceding the spotlight to his vice president, President
Clinton has literally headed for the hills for a few days of
vacation in the Adirondacks. By Marc Lacey.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 2 p.m. ET in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BOTTOM
</P>
<P>
   NIGERIA-OBASANJO (Abuja, Nigeria) _ Special Report: When
President Clinton crisscrossed Africa in 1998, his plane overflew
Nigeria in a pointed snub at the generals leading it. On his second
trip to Africa next weekend, Clinton's main destination will be
Nigeria, a country that under the elected civilian government of
Olusegun Obasanjo has undergone one of Africa's most stunning and
convulsive political transformations. By Norimitsu Onishi.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 1 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   Reefer to:
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUBMARINE (Moscow) _ The Russian navy said Saturday that
all 118 members of the crew of the wrecked nuclear submarine Kursk
are now likely dead, or will be before a British rescue submarine
arrives with a team of Norwegian divers to make a final desperate
effort to open a rear hatch and look for survivors. By Patrick E.
Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   (We plan to move the story by 1:30 p.m. ET in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INSIDE STORIES PROMOTED ON PAGE 1:
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-ARMY-SHOOTING (Bogota, Colombia) _ In a test of its
commitment to improving its human rights record, the Colombian
government has promised a full-scale investigation into the
killings by army troops of six elementary school children last
week. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-PRIVACY (Washington) _ After nine months of blistering
criticism from doctors, patients and consumer groups, the Clinton
administration has decided to beef up protections for the privacy
of medical records, beyond what it proposed last year. By Robert
Pear.
</P>
<P>
   NYPD-CHIEF (New York) _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani named Correction
Commissioner Bernard B. Kerik as the city's next police
commissioner on Saturday, turning to a former undercover narcotics
detective and familiar member of his administration to command the
nation's largest police department. By William K. Rashbaum.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
