</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN REVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Run on Meat, and Not by Humans &QL;
</P>
<P>
   From hemisphere to hemisphere and around the globe comes news
about meat, and it's enough to put you off your feed.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for instance, the report from Britain, where thousands of
pigs have been slaughtered because of an outbreak of swine fever.
``People are at their wits' end,'' lamented James Black, vice
chairman of the National Pig Association.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the United States joined several European countries
in banning imports of live pigs, pig semen and related products
from Britain, which is still struggling with huge economic losses
from an outbreak of bovine spongiform encephalopathy, commonly
known as mad cow disease, that began several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Swine fever, like mad cow disease, is usually controlled only by
the destruction of infected animals. Outbreaks decimated herds in
the Netherlands and Germany in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike mad cow disease, swine fever is not thought to be a
threat to humans. About 50 people in Britain have died from
Creutzfeldt-Jacob disease, which has been linked to mad cow
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, a federal judge ordered two flocks of sheep
belonging to a Vermont couple to be destroyed out of concern that
they had a version of mad cow disease.
</P>
<P>
   In Malaysia, about 100 people died last year and a million pigs
were slaughtered because of the spread of the newly discovered
Nipah virus, which is in the same class of viruses as ebola and
AIDS. Researchers recently confirmed a chain of infection from
fruit bats to pigs and then to humans.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, an outbreak of hoof-and-mouth disease in Argentina
prompted the announcement last week of a temporary halt in beef
exports to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Bon appetit.
</P>
<P>
   Because the Hut Was There &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Forest Service drew some derision last year when it
told the Appalachian Mountain Club to make sure a hut the group was
rebuilding in New Hampshire's White Mountains was wheelchair
accessible according to federal rules. The Galehead hut is perched
2,000 feet up a boulder-strewn trail, doubters pointed out; a
wheelchair would never make it.
</P>
<P>
   Never say never.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, three hikers in wheelchairs engineered for rough
terrain and two hikers on crutches made it up the 4.6-mile trail in
about 12 hours, under their own steam but with plenty of help from
friends, family members and volunteers. They conquered the
mountain, they said, to show that their determination should not be
underestimated _ and for a fun hike in the woods.
</P>
<P>
   Their Galehead trek and the hubbub over the hut highlight a
tricky question: Just how accessible must the naturally
not-very-accessible wilderness become?
</P>
<P>
   Forest Service officials say they have no plans to pave trails,
but when it comes to new buildings, however remote, the answer is:
very accessible.
</P>
<P>
   Trial for Kennedy Nephew In 1975 Killing in Connecticut
</P>
<P>
   A Connecticut juvenile court judge ruled that Michael Skakel, a
nephew of Ethel Kennedy, should stand trial for the 1975 killing of
Martha Moxley, who was his 15-year-old next-door neighbor in
Greenwich's gated Belle Haven enclave. The judge has yet to decide
whether Skakel, who is now 39, should be tried as a juvenile or as
an adult. Conviction by a judge in juvenile court could mean a
sentence of less than four years; conviction by a jury in Superior
Court could bring a life term.
</P>
<P>
   Rising Tire-Related Toll
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has figured out yet why Firestone tires have been failing
on Ford Explorers, but the government has raised to 62 its tally of
deaths attributed to the tires in consumer complaints filed with
regulators. Most occurred when the tires failed at high speed and
the Explorers rolled over. State Farm, the nation's largest auto
insurer, said that it began billing Firestone for tire incidents in
1997, and mentioned the problem to regulators in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   A Threat to California's Oaks
</P>
<P>
   Up and down the California coast, thousands of oak trees are
dying of a fast-spreading new disease called sudden oak death
syndrome. In just five years, it has spread from one to three
species of oak and across 350 miles of coastline. Scientists fear
it may move outside the state and afflict other species of trees,
and the Agriculture Department says it will discuss its options in
fighting the disease next week. It appears to be caused by a
species of funguslike organism closely related to the pest that
caused Irish potato blight.
</P>
<P>
   The Concorde Is Grounded
</P>
<P>
   Following last month's fatal crash near Paris, Britain and
France formally grounded the Concorde after investigators
determined that a problem with its tires made the world's only
commercial supersonic airliner unsafe. Investigators found that the
crash, which killed 113, originated in a tire blowout that caused
chunks of rubber to rupture a fuel tank. The Concorde will fly
again only when its manufacturers devise safeguards against a
repetition, aviation authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   When the Nominee Knew
</P>
<P>
   More than two and a half years after an independent counsel
began investigating President Clinton's relationship with a White
House intern, a new grand jury has been impaneled to review the
case again, government officials said. The independent counsel,
Robert Ray, convened the panel last month after saying he would
consider whether Clinton could be charged with wrongdoing in the
Monica Lewinsky matter once he leaves office. Democrats and
Republicans piled criticism on the anonymous leak about the grand
jury, disclosed just hours before Vice President Al Gore accepted
the Democratic Presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   It's Melting
</P>
<P>
   An ice-free patch of ocean about a mile wide has opened at the
very top of the world, a sight that has presumably never before
been seen by human beings and is more evidence that global warming
may be real. The last time that scientists can be certain the pole
was awash in water was more than 50 million years ago. ``It was
totally unexpected,'' Dr. James J. McCarthy, an oceanographer and
director of the Museum of Comparative Zoology at Harvard
University, said after lecturing aboard a tourist cruise on a
Russian icebreaker earlier this month. He said that six years ago,
the ice near the North Pole was 6 to 9 feet thick.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
