<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 11:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6499 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s BC-OLYMPICS-WOMEN-900(2T     08-19 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLYMPICS-WOMEN-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN RAISE THE BAR TO HIGHEST LEVEL FOR SYDNEY OLYMPICS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Stacy Dragila was always a bit of a daredevil. She competed on
the high school rodeo circuit in Northern California and, entering
junior college in 1992, became intrigued by the risk and the
airborne gymnastics of the pole vault. It was a relatively new
event for women, however, and the first male pole-vaulter she
consulted suggested she could not clear the gender bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him if I could try it one day at practice,'' Dragila
said. ``He just looked at me and said: `Women can't do that. They
just don't have the upper-body strength. They are not made to do
it.' I took it to heart that, OK, this is one of those things that
women just don't do.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the urging of her coach, Dragila reconsidered in 1993 at
Idaho State University. Seven years later, the women's pole vault
is among track and field's most engaging events, and Dragila is the
world record-holder at 15 feet 2 and a quarter inches. She is a
gold-medal favorite at the 2000 Summer Games, which begin Sept. 15
in Sydney, Australia, where her event will make its Olympic debut
for women.
</P>
<P>
   When the modern Olympics began in 1896, women were not allowed
to participate. Times have changed, grudgingly but significantly,
in the 20th century. In Sydney, more women will compete in more
sports, and in more events, than ever. About 4,400 women, or 42
percent of the 10,500 competing athletes, will participate, up from
3,626 at the 1996 Atlanta Games. And for the first time, women will
compete in the same number of team sports as men.
</P>
<P>
   The gains go beyond numbers, however, as women continue to
penetrate the boundaries of previously male-only events that
require great strength and endurance. The sports added for women
this year are weight lifting, triathlon, tae kwon do and modern
pentathlon, and new competitions in multidiscipline sports include
water polo in the aquatics category and the hammer throw and pole
vault in track and field.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, Sydney will offer a grand stage for a generation of
women who have reaped the benefits of Title IX, followed the lead
of individual stars and team champions and carved out an even
larger presence for women in the Olympic movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're worthy of being a medal event at the Olympics,''
Dragila said. ``We've shown we can take it to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   She added: ``Girls are starting to come up to me. They are
encouraged because they know I came to this so late in my career.
They know anything is possible if they put their heart to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Not only will athletes like Dragila increase the profile of
women in the Sydney Games, but the overriding athletic story there
will also be a woman's story _ the attempt by Marion Jones of the
United States to become the first female track-and-field athlete to
win five gold medals in one Olympics. Jones has been heavily
marketed and promoted over the last year, and both Jones and
Dragila have been featured in television commercials leading up to
Sydney. A 17-year-old from the United States, Cheryl Haworth, who
is 5 foot 9 and 308 pounds, is a gold-medal favorite in weight
lifting.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear that Olympic officials and sponsors are paying more
attention to female athletes, especially after last summer's
Women's World Cup of soccer _ the largest sporting event ever for
women _ filled up large stadiums in the United States and ended any
doubt that people in large numbers would pay to watch women play
team sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``The soccer team showed that, a generation after Title IX,
women's sports are here to stay,'' said Maureen O'Toole, who is
considered the greatest female water-polo player ever and who will
make her initial Olympic appearance in Sydney at age 39.
</P>
<P>
   Stung by criticism that the gold-medal success of American women
in softball and soccer was reduced to highlight footage at the
Atlanta Olympics, NBC, which will pay $3.5 billion to broadcast the
next five Olympic Games, will show every minute of the women's
soccer and softball matches on network or cable.
</P>
<P>
   Even though he has been battered recently by scandals involving
corruption and performance-enhancing drugs, the president of the
International Olympic Committee, Juan Antonio Samaranch, can
include as one of his greatest successes the increased
participation of women as athletes and officials in the Olympic
movement.
</P>
<P>
   He named the first female member of the IOC in 1981; today 13 of
the 113 delegates are women. Four years ago, Samaranch proposed
that women should hold at least 10 percent of the decision-making
positions in the IOC, every national Olympic committee and
international sports federations by 2000, with the number rising to
20 percent by 2005. These goals may seem meager by American
standards, but they represent significant progress in many
countries where women's roles are diminished or dismissed for
cultural and religious reasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We appointed women IOC members for the first time and we
solved a very important problem, the participation of women in the
Games,'' Samaranch said in a recent interview. ``But we still have
a problem; that is, the presence of women in leading positions
running sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, women have hardly reached a level of parity with men in
the Olympic movement. Forty-eight names were proposed recently for
14 new positions as IOC members, and none of them were women.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Opportunities are coming more quickly on the playing fields, on
the track and in the pool. O'Toole will finally have a chance to
display before a worldwide audience her seminal skills in women's
water polo. After playing internationally since 1978, she retired
in 1994 to teach physical education and coach in Northern
California, believing her career would never have the validation of
the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   She would apparently have to be satisfied with decades of
success achieved in anonymity, when the American team slept on pool
tables in a bar in the Netherlands and traveled from Italy to Malta
on a fishing trawler because there was no money for more
extravagant travel. The entire team bunked at her house during
summer training in the early days, and pool time was limited for
female players to 6 to 9 in the morning and 8 to 11 at night.
</P>
<P>
   When women's water polo was added to the Sydney schedule in
1997, O'Toole quickly came out of retirement. Still, there is no
big money in the sport. Even with a training stipend from the U.S.
Olympic Committee and a pair of sponsors, she has struggled to make
ends meet. For a year, O'Toole has lived with her mother in
Huntington Beach, Calif., to train with the American team and has
traveled home to the Bay Area to see her 8-year-old daughter,
Kelly, and her boyfriend on the weekends.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first world championship was in '78 in Berlin, but it was
only a demonstration sport, not official,'' O'Toole said. ``They
had no hotel rooms for us. We had to sit around the lobby for three
or four hours. It was almost embarrassing. We worked as hard as
other athletes and put the same amount of time in, but we weren't
an Olympic sport, so no one cared about us. Being an Olympic sport
makes a difference. It really validates us.''
</P>
<P>
   As she watched American women achieve thorough success at the
Atlanta Games, Jennifer Gutierrez of Denver said she never dreamed
she would compete in Sydney in the inaugural Olympic triathlon,
which will include a one-mile swim, a 24-mile bike ride and a
6.2-mile run. A former champion swimmer at Pepperdine University,
Gutierrez took up the triathlon for fitness training in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Early success, and the realization that the sport would be
included in the Sydney Olympics, encouraged Gutierrez to increase
her training from 15 to 25 hours a week, which she has fit in
around her job teaching physical education to handicapped children.
She swims from 5:30 to 7:30 each morning, runs 6 miles on her lunch
break and bikes in the evening. She postponed her honeymoon for two
years until the completion of the Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having your sport in the Olympics raises the whole level of
competition,'' said Gutierrez, who is 33. ``You make sacrifices you
wouldn't make in everyday life to get to the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still haven't taken my honeymoon. But now I know what it
takes to be an athlete at a high level. I can appreciate the effort
of these athletes, whether they are in first place or last.''
</P>
<P>
   Dawn Ellerbe, a native of Brooklyn who has been over 6 feet tall
since the eighth grade, threw the shot-put and discus in high
school , then reluctantly attempted the hammer throw at the
University of South Carolina. The first time she grabbed the
9-pound ball by its 3-foot-long wire, spun several times and
launched the hammer, she fell down. She has ruined more than a few
suitcases, traveling with four or five of the hammers to each meet,
and has had to shovel snow off the hammer-throwing ring to train at
the University of Wyoming, where she received her master's degree
in communications and is now an assistant coach. But her
perseverance has paid off.
</P>
<P>
   At 26, the 6-foot-2, 240-pound Ellerbe has won five national
championships in the hammer throw, has set the American record of
231 feet 2 inches and has established herself as a medal candidate
in Sydney. Her event and others will provide girls with a chance to
see mature women competing, Ellerbe noted, in contrast to the
prepubescent images of gymnasts and figure skaters frequently
broadcast at the Summer and Winter Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When younger girls see a gymnast or an ice skater, they think
it's a fantasy: `I can't do that after I'm 22.''' she said. ``I
think this will show them that you can be a scholar too, and get an
education while competing in athletics.''
</P>
<P>
   The most popular of the new Olympic events for women is the pole
vault. It is an evolving sport, and thus a world record is possible
at every major competition. The pole vault also evokes danger,
strength and acrobatic grace as women plant a 14-foot pole and
invert themselves in midair to clear a bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being a little bit sexist, you've got good-looking girls and
an X-Games mentality,'' said Dave Nielsen, who coaches Dragila in
Pocatello, Idaho. A former vaulter, he began trying to get women
interested in the pole vault in hopes that gender equity could stem
the erosion of the event because of the expense, the threat of
injury, rising insurance costs and lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Having women involved would be leverage to keep the event,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Dragila, 29, grew up in Auburn, Calif., and competed in
goat-tying competitions in high school rodeos, dismounting from her
horse, flipping the goat and binding its legs with rope. She was
recruited to college as a heptathlete, the female version of the
decathlon, which requires skill in running, throwing and jumping.
The pole vault was something that few women had ever tried, and
Dragila started gingerly at a height of 6 feet, a full 10 inches
below the women's world record in the high jump.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call it pole-vaulting, just holding on for dear
life and getting over the bar,'' Dragila said. ``Getting on the
runway in '93 was very awkward. Trying to hold the pole, run with
it and plant it in this stupid little box, then trying to jump off
the ground and turn yourself over was very frightening.''
</P>
<P>
   Being in the air was disorienting, she said, and she was never
sure if she was going to land on her back, her feet or her neck. So
she began training at a gymnastics school to gain awareness of her
body in the air. A year later, she improved to 10 feet. Last
summer, the 5-7, 140-pound Dragila won the inaugural world
championship for women, clearing 15-1. She believes a 17-foot jump
for women is possible, and would be the equivalent of a 20-foot
jump for men, who possess more speed and upper-body strength.
</P>
<P>
   Dragila has also generated attention by posing nude with other
American women for a track-and-field calendar, saying it is a sign
of progress that women are confident enough in their bodies to
expose them as figures of strength and power instead of
titillation. Other athletes, officials and feminists disagree,
saying women are still conforming to societal pressure to prove
that they are feminine when they sweat.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the popularity of the event, female vaulters are still
attempting to clear the bar of equality. When Dragila won the 1999
world championship last August in Seville, Spain, tying what was
then the world record, she received only half the $60,000 prize
money available to male vaulters. Looking ahead to Sydney, she
said, ``I hope we don't get half a medal.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-00 1140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
