<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 11:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6501 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      08-19 0983
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE BATTLES INSIDE AND OUTSIDE THE LINES 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: Different spellings of Rivellino and Rivelino in last
graf are correct.) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rivellino Jones of the misspelled name was refereeing
a soccer game in Manhattan last week, a moral victory for coach
Marty Jacobson. Perhaps those other embattled friends of
thelipsite(at)aol.com, Linda Bensel-Meyers and Billy Bean, could
take heart from Jake, although hang in there is almost always the
hardest advice to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Bensel-Meyers, the whistle-blower at the University of
Tennessee, is facing the start of a football season in which she
has been portrayed as the Volunteers' most dangerous opponent. The
team has just started practicing and Bensel-Meyers has already
informed the NCAA of three freshman players who turned in
remarkably similar compositions. She calls it institutional
plagiarism and blames it on the mores of the university rather than
on the athletes or tutors.
</P>
<P>
   Most people in Knoxville call it harassing the program. The NCAA
might not even find it in violation of whatever it is that concerns
that trade organization.
</P>
<P>
   Bensel-Meyers has been decrying, for some time now, what she
sees as the exploitation of athletes and the subversion of the
humanistic values of the academy. A professor of Renaissance
literature and drama, she is also in charge of the first-year
composition program. She is only recently being heard beyond the
world of the Orange.
</P>
<P>
   In what I found the most cynical and clear-eyed approach to the
issue, Frank Cagle, the managing editor of The Knoxville
News-Sentinel, simply brushed it off. He wrote that the ``fate of
the football team has a deep impact on the morale, the business and
the general economy of East Tennessee'' and that what might be
construed as corruption in college sports was a ``national scandal,
not a local one. And it requires a national solution.'' In other
words, keeping our boys eligible by any means necessary is a
priority not to be tampered with unless every other school goes
honest, too.
</P>
<P>
   Bensel-Meyers is idealistic and fuzzy-minded; she sees
universities using a bottom-line corporate model in which athletes
are resources. Even the coaches and athletic administrators end up
being victimized, especially if they don't win.
</P>
<P>
   ``My immediate problem is how do I avoid being cast as a
harridan because I harp on the issue,'' she said last week. ``The
administration's problem is that you can't put the peel back on the
orange once you see what's underneath.''
</P>
<P>
   Bean, an outfielder whose six major league seasons on three
teams were haunted by the secret of his homosexuality, has decided
he wants to be back in baseball, the binding thread of his life
since childhood. Since he used his sports background to build
functioning teams in two restaurants, he thinks he can use his
business background in a front office. He would offer a rare
combination of experience and skills, as well as a test of sports'
institutional homophobia.
</P>
<P>
   His open, often moving description of life in a major league
closet last year in a front-page story in The New York Times led to
a number of speaking engagements and television appearances. In
talking about baseball, he realized he had not resolved that
critical part of his life; he had left before his career was over.
Even now, at 35, he tries to stay in playing shape and appear
regularly on talk radio; he is still gripping the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Bean is in the process of selling his current Miami Beach
restaurant, Mayya, and writing to baseball club executives. He said
last week that he understands that a team would have to be
``courageous'' to hire him.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jake's message has always been simple: Don't quit. A
recovering drug abuser long clean, a soccer coach in a basketball
culture, an advocate for kids among clock-watching bureaucrats,
Jacobson's saga has been struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, when his Martin Luther King Jr. High School team won
the first of its three straight city championships, mostly with
recent immigrants from the West Indies and West Africa, Jake has
been controversial in and out of his school. He was suspended from
coaching for 11 months last year when rival coaches accused several
of his players of being ineligible. He was reinstated and
vindicated, although his team lost in last year's championship
final.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bensel-Meyers, he is self-righteous and insistent on
putting the needs of the individual student ahead of the
institution. Like Bean, his charm masks a willingness to work
harder than most. And like them both, he has a larger vision. Jake
thinks the future of American soccer will rise from the cities.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the New York City Parks Department's inspired
partnership with the Parmalat milk company finished its six-week
Summer of Soccer 2000 Saturday. On weekday nights in Riverside Park
in Manhattan and Flushing Meadow-Corona Park in Queens, youngsters
played six-on-six games under the supervision of parkies and soccer
coaches and college players like Rivellino Jones. Jacobson ran the
Manhattan program, which included washing the mesh scrimmage vests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at that passion,'' he crowed last week as teen-agers from
Senegal and Brazil and Trinidad stormed up and down the turf with
bursts of heart-stopping athleticism. ``This is going to be the
urban game. These kids are going to be our future.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivellino Jones, 22, named for Roberto Rivelino, the Brazilian
star, is a symbol of that future. As a 16-year-old Trinidadian
overwhelmed by homesickness and a huge, chaotic high school, Jones
found his new roots at midfield on the King varsity. He was on
Jake's first title team and expects to graduate from Medgar Evers
College this year. He says he wants to be a public school guidance
counselor and coach. Like Jake.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-00 1142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000819.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 11:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6502 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-SOUNDOFMUSIC-SINGALON     08-19 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUNDOFMUSIC-SINGALONG-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DO YOU REALLY CALL THAT SOUND MUSIC? 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By THOMAS VINCIGUERRA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In her 1965 review of ``The Sound of Music'' for The
New York Herald Tribune, Judith Crist wrote, ``The movie is for the
5-to-7 set and their mommies who think their kids aren't up to the
stinging sophistication and biting wit of `Mary Poppins.'''
</P>
<P>
   The rest is history.
</P>
<P>
   Today, as the highest grossing film musical of all time
approaches its 35th anniversary, it is about to begin yet another
life _ this time as official, rather than accidental, kitsch. .
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 6, ``Sing-a-Long Sound of Music,'' the audience
participation version of the movie that has been playing to
delirious crowds at the Prince Charles Cinema in London, will make
its debut in New York at the Ziegfeld Theater.
</P>
<P>
   The basic premise is simple: During such deathless Rodgers and
Hammerstein standards as ``Sixteen Going On Seventeen,'' ``So Long,
Farewell'' and ``Climb Ev'ry Mountain,'' moviegoers sing along to
the lyrics, which appear on the screen as subtitles.
</P>
<P>
   Singing along, however, is just one of the evening's many
opportunities for self-expression. In London, when Julie Andrews'
fellow nuns ask, ``How do you solve a problem like Maria?'' the
crowd holds up postcards printed with question marks. When Captain
von Trapp (Christopher Plummer) first kisses Maria, they let loose
a hail of party poppers.
</P>
<P>
   Attendees wear nuns' habits and lederhosen; others dress as
Nazis, the Alps (covered in shaving cream) and as representations
of song lyrics _ like wild geese, with cutouts of the moon mounted
on their wings, as described in ``My Favorite Things.''
</P>
<P>
   Bert Fink, a spokesman for the Rodgers and Hammerstein
Organization, which controls the copyright on the composers' music
and lyrics, thinks such strenuous glee is, for the English, the
adult equivalent of the breathless outbursts at traditional English
Punch and Judy shows. Example: when Julie Andrews cannot find
material to make play clothes for the von Trapp tykes, the audience
yells, ``The curtains, Maria!''
</P>
<P>
   In July, home-grown performances were mounted in Boston and
Austin, Texas. Charmian Carr, who portrayed the eldest von Trapp
daughter, Liesl, was the guest of honor in Austin. Carr, the author
of ``Forever Liesl: A Memoir of the Sound of Music'' (Viking,
2000), recalled that during one scene in which Plummer tenderly
touched Andrews' nose, a chant of ``Get the booger, captain!''
arose.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hysterical,'' she said. ``There were 1,300 people and
they were sitting in the aisles. It was sacrilegious, but great
fun. It could just be that there are so many people who really do
love the movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Others are more cynical. Crist, for example.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's so popular because the world has come to realize
what a really godawful thing the film is,'' she said. ``In 35 years
it's become even sappier. There's a point where it's so bad that it
becomes funny.''
</P>
<P>
   As with ``Mommie Dearest'' and ``Valley of the Dolls,'' this
camp aspect of ``Sing-a-Long Sound of Music'' has made it a hit
with gay viewers. The production began as an entry in the London
Lesbian and Gay Film Festival; the Austin Gay and Lesbian
International Film Festival co-produced the Texas event to benefit
Project Transitions, a nonprofit group that provides hospice care
and housing for AIDS victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just thought it would be fun,'' said Charlotte Hale, the
executive director of Project Transitions. ``Certainly the gay
community liked it, but a lot of mainstream people were there.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the show is being dizzily promoted as all-family
entertainment. ``Wave your edelweiss!'' reads a press release.
``Cheer the von Trapp kids! Bark at Rolf (the telegram boy)! Boo
the Nazis! Hiss the baroness!''
</P>
<P>
   Camp aside, the movie also seems to have a powerful emotional
effect on a lot of apparently normal people. Even ushers at the
singalongs have been seen to choke up during the finale.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the countless renderings of ``Do-Re-Mi'' and ``My
Favorite Things'' in grade school and in Muzak-filled elevators
have left permanent musical saccharine deposits in the collective
consciousness. Perhaps, like the Kevin Bacon Game, ``Sing-a-Long
Sound of Music'' was a form of cinemania just waiting to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenneth Tynan said that movies are the most dominant
repository of memory we have,'' said the film critic Andrew Sarris.
``I suppose this is just a manifestation of that. Everyone
remembers `The Sound of Music.' You can blast it but you can't
obliterate it, I guess.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-00 1145EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000819.0063 </DOCNO>
