<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, CEDING SPOTLIGHT TO THE CANDIDATES, VACATIONS IN THE
ADIRONDACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARC LACEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAKE PLACID, N.Y. _ CNN has a correspondent and crew in place,
just in case news breaks out in the woods. The other networks are
following along as well, betting on the proposition that President
Clinton, even while on vacation, will not be able to resist a
camera and boom mike in his face.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton's public schedule Saturday was as clear as the
summer skies here, and the reporters who follow him everywhere were
advised by presidential aides, who meant no disrespect, to go take
a hike. As if to prove that he is fully capable of ceding the
spotlight to his vice president, Clinton has literally headed for
the hills for a few days of vacation in the Adirondacks.
</P>
<P>
   He has been horse riding, golfing and celebrating his 54th
birthday with his wife and daughter _ all outside the view of the
media. The plan is to lie low and allow Vice President Al Gore and
his running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman to take center stage for a
while.
</P>
<P>
   But the president has not exactly disappeared. Saturday, he
signed the Global AIDS and Tuberculosis Relief Act, which finances
the administration's worldwide response to those diseases, and the
White House broadcast his radio address on the subject that he had
taped in Washington before arriving here.
</P>
<P>
   Also, clad in the brown suede jacket he wears whenever he is
roughing it, Clinton stood at the side of Hillary Rodham Clinton at
a Friday night rally for her Senate bid and spoke, albeit briefly,
on her behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton acknowledged that even though five months remain in his
presidency, things have changed now that Gore has been officially
been tapped as the next Democratic presidential nominee. Clinton
said he no longer holds the rank of party leader _ as of Thursday
night, when Gore delivered what the president praised as an
``extraordinary speech and a great road map for the country's
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, at the crowded rally in Saranac Lake, said he was
already beginning the transition to private life. ``In this
election, though I will be president and I have a lot I'm going to
try to get done for you in the next five months, I am moving back
to where I spent the first 20 years of my active life in
politics,'' he said. That is, the president said, as an envelope
stuffer, not a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Clinton is not quite yet an ordinary citizen, as his
schedule over the coming weeks makes clear. He hops aboard Air
Force One next week for a trip to Nigeria that is designed to
follow up on his 1998 tour of Africa and lend support to Nigeria's
fledgling democracy. At the invitation of Nelson Mandela, South
Africa's former president, Clinton will also stop in Tanzania for a
day to support the Burundi peace talks that Mandela is brokering.
</P>
<P>
   After several days in Africa, Clinton returns to Washington,
spends a night in his own bed, and is off again to Colombia to
speak on behalf of President Carlos Pastrana's fight against drug
traffickers.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the president's schedule in the coming weeks is a trip
to the United Nations in New York for a gathering of scores of
world leaders that will be one of Clinton's final opportunities
before he leaves office to say farewell to some of his far-flung
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Not all his attention, of course, will be focused off shore.
Clinton already has four fund-raising speeches planned next week in
Michigan and New Jersey for House and Senate candidates. The White
House carefully arranged those trips with William Daley, the
campaign chairman for Gore, and has clearly turned over the
political arena to the Gore camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need to tell us what to do,'' said John Podesta, the
president's chief of staff. ``We're playing second fiddle. Maybe
third fiddle. How many fiddles are there in the orchestra?''
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton is still running the show when it comes to the final
budget battle with the Republicans, an end-of-the-year face-off he
has shown himself adept at maneuvering.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're back to putting our elbows on the table and
arm-wrestling with Congress,'' Podesta told reporters aboard Air
Force One as the president returned from the Democratic National
Convention last week. ``That should take us through early
October.''
</P>
<P>
   By the fall, the election will be so dominating the news that
White House aides acknowledge that they will have a tough time
grabbing headlines even if they wanted them.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, presidential aides say a bit of obscurity is
fine with them. Clinton spoke for a mere nine minutes on his wife's
behalf on Friday, a flash as far as presidential addresses go. And
even more notable perhaps is what happened after the speech. The
first lady delved into the crowd to shake hands. The president, who
relishes such hands-on contact with admirers, retreated early.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
