<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Aug. 20, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Early Saturday, temperatures fell into the 30s in portions of
the northern Great Lakes as an exceptionally cool high pressure
system built over the region. Sunday, the high will continue to
settle southeastward, providing another chilly start to the day
across the Northeast. Sunshine will be plentiful, but afternoon
readings will stay about 5 to 10 degrees below normal. An exception
to the bright conditions will be found over the high ground of New
England, where a weak disturbance brings clouds and a few
sprinkles.
</P>
<P>
   Powerful storms will erupt in the northern Plains on Sunday as a
jet stream disturbance intercepts a northward flow of humid air.
Scattered thunderstorms will also surround a front from near
Missouri to the Southeast Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Cooler air will reach the Northwest behind a departing front
while the Southwest and southern Plains remain mainly dry and hot.
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: HURRICANE CONTROLLER
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  A group of tiny islands 700 miles east of the Carolinas lends
its name to a prominent summer weather system, the Bermuda high.
The clockwise winds around this high pressure system can play an
important role in steering hurricanes. A typical hurricane moves
west along the southern part of the Bermuda high before veering to
the north along its western flank. The two-week long journey of
Hurricane Alberto from the Cape Verde Islands to its current
position in the central Atlantic has been a path controlled by the
position of the Bermuda high. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
