<SLUG> BC-GLF-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE CADDIE ONLY TIGER KNOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: To be subbed after the day's play is completed) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ In Tiger Woods' quest to add a second
consecutive Professional Golfers' Association title to his U.S.
Open and British Open championships, his caddie, 36-year-old Steve
Williams, is always out there with him. When Williams is not
lugging that big black golf bag on his sturdy shoulders here at
Valhalla, he's conferring with Woods on the distance to the
flagstick and which club to hit, or he's helping to read the line
of a putt.
</P>
<P>
   But Williams is the caddie whom only Tiger Woods knows. He
doesn't give interviews or sign autographs. In many ways, he is
virtually invisible. But not unappreciated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stevie has been a big part of my success,'' said Woods, who
was the clubhouse leader in the PGA by one stroke, at 11 under par,
after the second round of play was suspended by darkness on Friday
with 11 players still on the course. ``He's there not only to
motivate me when things are going bad, but he has the gall to tell
me what he thinks when I'm feeling uneasy about a club. He's not
afraid to get in my face about it, and that is nice. He's got a lot
of confidence in his ability as a caddie, and that is very
reassuring as a player.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods remembered getting ready to hit his second shot on the
15th hole at Pebble Beach in the U.S. Open in June when Williams
noticed a man in the gallery pulling a disposable camera out of his
pocket. Nothing disrupts a golfer more than an unexpected click of
a camera, especially during a swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stevie called me off the shot,'' Woods said. ``He said:
`Tiger, get off the shot. There's a guy with a camera.' He went
after the guy with the camera. Not too many caddies would actually
do that in the U.S. Open and to say `get off the shot' when I'm
over the ball, that takes a lot of guts, but he did it. Then I put
it up there on the green, made par and walked on.''
</P>
<P>
   During the British Open at the Old Course at St. Andrews,
Scotland last month, Woods mentioned how he and Williams had formed
a strong friendship.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gotten to know me really well, how I like to play, what
my thought process is,'' Woods said. ``He can read me, to the point
where he knows when to say something, when not to say something.
And we genuinely like being around each other. I think that makes
for a wonderful partnership, especially one that lasts a long
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Every so often here at Valhalla Golf Club, Woods and Williams
have shared a laugh or a smile, as they do at every tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stevie's so positive out there, he keeps me upbeat; I get on
him, he gets on me,'' Woods said. ``We have a good time out there.
If I'm playing good or bad, it doesn't matter, we're going to enjoy
each other's company.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods also likes the way Williams will remind him that there
might be another way to play a particular shot.''
</P>
<P>
   ``On a couple of tee shots at St. Andrews,'' Woods said, ``he
got in my head a little bit and said: `Look at this option.
Consider this.' I think that's what he's so good at. And he doesn't
force it on you. If I want to go with my thinking, I go with it.
I'm holding the club. But he has the guts to tell me what he's
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   Many tour caddies play golf at every opportunity, but Williams
does not. He occasionally drives racing cars in his native New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I race cars, mate; golf's not my game,'' he has said. ``I've
probably played only about 10 18-hole rounds of golf in the last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams doesn't talk to the news media about his life as Woods'
caddie, a life that reportedly earned him at least $600,000 last
year and might earn him even more this year.
</P>
<P>
   But many of those in Woods' inner circle, like his girlfriend,
Joanna Jagoda, don't give interviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's their life and their choice,'' Woods said. ``If they want
to do interviews, fine, but it's up to them. I can say, `I don't
think it's good for you to do that because if you do it once,
you're going to have to do it twice, then a third time, a fourth
time, then so forth and so on.'''
</P>
<P>
   Williams, who had caddied for Raymond Floyd and Greg Norman, has
been on Woods' bag since early last year after Woods lost
confidence in Mike ``Fluff'' Cowan, his first tour caddie. Woods'
swing guru, Butch Harmon, had asked Floyd's permission to hire
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known Steve a long time,'' said Harmon, who was once
Norman's guru. ``The mix with Tiger is perfect. I didn't think he'd
get caught up in the hoopla that surrounds Tiger, and he hasn't.
He's good under pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he feels the wind change, he'll stop and tell Tiger. He
knows when to say the right thing and when not to say anything. He
knows when to be aggressive and when not to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams had caddied for 11 years for Floyd, the winner of the
1986 U.S. Open, the 1976 Masters and two PGA Championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steve's very quiet, he's not looking for publicity,'' Floyd
said. ``He's a good companion out there. He knows when to pat you
on the back and he knows when to bark at you. He was like another
son to me.''
</P>
<P>
   But now Steve Williams is almost like a big brother to Tiger
Woods, who walks with him, laughs with him and listens to him. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-00 1154EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000819.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 11:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6508 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-N     08-19 0991
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MVP Candidates Helped and Hindered by Team's Position in
Standings
</P>
<P>
   No one has ever displayed a clearer definition of most valuable
player than Chipper Jones did last September when the Mets, a mere
game behind the Braves, played a three-game series in Atlanta.
Hitting four home runs and driving in seven runs, Jones dominated
the series, which the Braves swept to take a commanding four-game
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who had already had an MVP-type season, clinched the
National League award with that performance. Players should always
make it that easy for voters.
</P>
<P>
   With six weeks left in this season, the MVP races have a
collection of legitimate candidates, including one from each of the
New York teams who could give the city a matched set of most
valuable players for the first time since Sandy Koufax and Elston
Howard in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, Mike Piazza of the Mets probably has fewer rivals
for the award than does Bernie Williams of the Yankees, but too
much of the season remains to attach the letters MVP to either
one's name.
</P>
<P>
   The National League has a group who would be serious candidates
if their teams were in a better location in the standing. Todd
Helton of Colorado heads the group, which includes Vladimir
Guerrero of Montreal, Sammy Sosa of the Chicago Cubs and Jeff
Bagwell of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   As the NL leader in batting average, on-base and slugging
percentages, hits, extra-base hits, multihit games, total bases,
doubles and runs scored (he is only second in runs batted in),
Helton is clearly the league's player of the year. But that doesn't
make him MVP, too. The beauty of the MVP award is that it measures
a player's value to his team, not simply a set of statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Helton unquestionably has been most valuable to the Rockies, but
they were in the NL West race only briefly _ they were in first
place June 18 and July 3 _ and not even Helton's torrid hitting the
past couple of weeks has helped improve their standing.
</P>
<P>
   Given that the Los Angeles Dodgers are not much better off than
the Rockies, Gary Sheffield's position among MVP contenders could
be questioned. He has clearly been invaluable to the Dodgers, but
their play has undermined his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   Voting for the award is done by a panel of members of the
Baseball Writers Association, and the voters generally opt for
players on contenders over players on noncontenders and for
everyday players over pitchers. Everything else being equal _ not
that everything ever is _ shortstops and catchers receive extra
consideration for the difficulty of their positions.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza might have detractors for his catching ability, but he
plays the position and has not allowed its rigors to prevent him
from producing one critical hit after another or one series of hits
after another.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month Piazza missed three games with a sprained
left knee, then in his first three games back (1) broke open a game
with a three-run home run, (2) accounted for the first three runs
by driving in two and scoring the other and later knocked in
another run and scored another as the Mets won, and (3) ignited a
third consecutive victory by slugging a two-run home run.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Piazza cracked a grand slam that obliterated a 3-3
tie with Toronto four days after he hit two home runs in Boston,
one that tied the game and one that won it. Piazza posted that
performance less than a week after Roger Clemens hit him on the
head with a fastball.
</P>
<P>
   The last time Piazza had faced Clemens, June 9, he hit a
third-inning grand slam that started the Mets toward a 12-2
victory. A week before the beanball he hit a three-run home run
that climaxed a 10-run eighth-inning rally that beat Atlanta, 11-8.
</P>
<P>
   That shot came a couple of weeks after Piazza ripped a two-run
home run against Trevor Hoffman in the 10th for a 5-3 victory over
San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza's name doesn't appear among the leaders in as many
offensive categories as Helton's, but he does lead Helton in one
phase. Piazza entered the weekend with the NL's best road average,
.410, or 50 points better than Helton.
</P>
<P>
   If Sheffield loses votes because of the Dodgers' failure to
seriously contend, Piazza's prime challenge could come from Jeff
Kent of San Francisco. One of the league's leader in runs batted
in, Kent has been the Giants' most consistently productive hitter,
even better than Barry Bonds, though Bonds could dilute Kent's
chances in the voting.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Edmonds of St. Louis appeared to be a major contender
earlier in the season, but without Mark McGwire in the lineup, he
has not served as critical a role.
</P>
<P>
   Some AL MVP Hopefuls May Be Hurt By DH Status
</P>
<P>
   The American League balloting will be a test of the voters' view
of designated hitters as MVP. Frank Thomas of the Chicago White Sox
and Edgar Martinez of Seattle have been extremely valuable
offensively to their division-leading teams, but Martinez has been
strictly a DH and Thomas has been a DH most of the time.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas won the award in 1993 and '94, but he was a first baseman
then. Rafael Palmeiro of Texas finished fifth in last year's voting
after serving primarily as a DH, but he received four first-place
votes, including two from the Texas writers, who selected him over
Ivan Rodriguez, his teammate, who won the award.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Delgado of Toronto has compiled the most impressive
statistics, leading the league in on-base, slugging percentage and
total bases and holding top-three spots in batting average, home
runs, runs batted in and runs scored. Toronto, however, may have to
win the wild card for him to have a chance for the award.
</P>
<P>
   Williams doesn't compare with Delgado's statistics, except for
RBIs. But he has been more responsible than any other member of the
team for the Yankees' continued presence at the top of the AL East.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   From the second game of the season, which he won in Anaheim with
a two-run homer in the ninth inning, Williams has staged a frequent
one-man victory party. The Yankees were losing their home opener,
2-1, when he hit a three-run homer in an 8-6 conquest of Texas. The
next week in Texas, he tied the game with a two-run homer in the
seventh, and the Yankees won in the 11th.
</P>
<P>
   After losing two games to the Tigers late in June for a
five-game losing streak in Detroit, the Yankees were in a scoreless
game when Williams tripled home a run that ignited an eight-run
outburst.
</P>
<P>
   In the first game of the second series against the Mets,
Williams drove in the first run of what became a 2-1 victory.
Against Philadelphia he hit an early home run, singled home the
third run of a game-tying five-run rally and scored the tying run,
then singled home the tying run in the 10th before the Yankees won.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month he wiped out a 3-0 Seattle lead with a
three-run homer, sending the Yankees to a 13-6 victory. Just four
days later he hit the first home run of the remarkable two-pitch,
two-homer blitz against Jason Isringhausen of Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett of Boston is a candidate but lost ground when his
temper tantrum gained him a 10-game suspension. Alex Rodriguez of
Seattle and Jason Giambi of Oakland are candidates as well. If
voters consider Martinez despite his DH status, he could hurt
Rodriguez's chances.
</P>
<P>
   The most valuable players, however, may not yet have been
determined. The candidates have six weeks in which to do a Chipper
Jones imitation.
</P>
<P>
   An Ivy-Covered Name
</P>
<P>
   She was born in Los Angeles and lives in New York, but
17-year-old Elizabeth thinks Chicago. She has good reason to; she
and the city have something in common _ a famous name.
</P>
<P>
   She is Elizabeth Wrigley-Field and she is proud of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know of anyone else with the name,'' she said. ``I
don't believe there are any other Wrigley-Fields. I've made a few
attempts to find someone else, but I never have.''
</P>
<P>
   Her parents are not crazy Cubs fans who adopted the park's name.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom is Wrigley and my dad is Field,'' she said. ``They
named me Elizabeth Field. They thought if I was named Wrigley-Field
I'd be teased a lot. When I was in first grade, I decided that
would be a mistake. I wanted to have both my parents' names because
I thought that would be fair, but I also thought it would be cool
to have the name Wrigley-Field.''
</P>
<P>
   So cool, in fact, that she is taking steps to make that her name
legally.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been Wrigley-Field in the school system as long as I've
been in New York,'' said the Hunter High School senior, whose
family moved to New York when she was 9. ``But we're getting my
name changed now because I'm about to go to college and I don't
want there to be any question about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wrigley-Field, who has no brothers or sisters to share the
name with, recalled peoples' reaction upon being introduced to her
or hearing her name.
</P>
<P>
   ``People hearing my name for the first time, especially
substitute teachers, would have big reactions,'' she said. ``In
ninth grade I was on the debate team and that's when I was first
introduced to masses of people at tournaments. People would laugh
when I went up to get my awards. I thought it was kind of funny,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   But she has also found that her name creates an easy way to
begin a conversation with someone whom she doesn't know.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Wrigley-Field has never been inside Wrigley Field. ``I've
been outside it, for about 10 minutes when I was very young,'' she
said. But she may make a visit during the coming school year. She
hopes to attend Harvard or the University of Chicago, and if she
goes to Chicago to visit that school, she said, she hopes to go to
the park and meet Cubs people.
</P>
<P>
   Now one would think that Ms. Wrigley-Field is a big baseball
fan. ``Not really,'' she said, speaking from Kassel, Germany, where
she has been studying this summer. ``I am a Cubs fan, but I don't
believe I would be were it not for this unusual circumstance. I
don't really follow baseball, but when I'm near a baseball
paraphernalia store, I go in and look for Cubs things.''
</P>
<P>
   From her collection of Cubs things, she said she especially
likes her Wrigley Field playing cards. What teen-ager wouldn't like
a deck of cards with such a personal label?
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
