<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-FINAL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Aug. 20, moved Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   This final budget adds GORE-KISS-REVIEW.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   PARTY-LOYALTY-REVIEW (Washington) _ Although some rhetorical
sameness wafted from the two recent presidential conventions, there
was little of the partisan bite of yesteryear. Yet two-thirds of
Americans still consider themselves Democrats or Republicans. Party
still matters, and party attachment is still considered a good
predictors of how people will vote _ if they vote. But appealing to
those loyalties, while still wooing the independents who decide
elections, is a complex challenge these days. By Robin Toner.
(moved in `a' category)
</P>
<P>
   FOREST-FIRES-REVIEW (Seattle) _ Amid the worst wildfire year in
nearly half a century, much political finger-pointing is under way.
But the Forest Service, for its part, blames Smokey the Bear and
fire suppression efforts. ``Most of these areas that used to burn
every 10 years or so haven't had a fire in a half-century,'' said a
Forest Service fire ecologist. ``These forests are long overdue.
They were just ready to go.'' By Timothy Egan. (moved in `a'
catgegory)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   SUBMARINE-STORIES-REVIEW (Undated) _ The world has been
transfixed by the sinking of the Russian submarine Kursk and the
desperate attempts to reach the 118 men inside. Tales of sea
adventure and calamity, both in fact and fiction, have always held
deep appeal. But what is it about the sea _ and especially
submarines _ that makes being trapped below the waves often
resonate even more than similar disasters on land, like mine
cave-ins? Part of the answer is that for all the advances in
science, the sea remains a mysterious _ and mystical _ force. By
Christopher Drew.
</P>
<P>
   DISABILITY-STUDIES-REVIEW (San Francisco) _ Pressing the
frontier of disability: it has expanded beyond law, medicine and
public policy into academia, in which it provides another point of
view for Richard III or discusses whether the tippy-toed Barbie
doll is technically disabled. Major universities are developing
disability studies programs. This fall the first international
conference on disability studies will be held in Washington. By
Patricia Leigh Brown.
</P>
<P>
   BASEBALL-VIOLENCE-REVIEW (Undated) _ There have been some ugly
incidents on the baseball field this season but so far nothing has
approached the horrifying moment 35 years ago when politics
intruded on baseball with a shock that many recall vividly today.
What people remember is the violence that exploded on Aug. 22,
1965, during a game at Candlestick Park in the bitterly contested
National League pennant race between the Los Angeles Dodgers and
the San Francisco Giants. But few recall the politics that fueled
it. By Allen Barra.
</P>
<P>
   (will also move in `s' category)
</P>
<P>
   VEEPS-REVIEW (Los Angeles) _ With the election 79 days away,
Dick Cheney and Joe Lieberman have already done just about
everything running mates can do for their tickets, from reflecting
well on the presidential nominees who chose them to providing a
lift for their national conventions. But those contributions have
been significant. A look at Cheney, Lieberman and other vice
presidential nominees of campaigns past. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   GORE-KISS-REVIEW (Undated) _ In Al Gore's campaign to change his
robotic image, nothing may have helped more than the big smooch. It
also may have signaled that Gore (unlikes some presidents we know)
would be faithful to his wife. By Caryn James.
</P>
<P>
   SOUNDOFMUSIC-SINGALONG-REVIEW (New York) _ ``The Sing-a-Long
Sound of Music,'' the audience participation of the 1965 film
classic, will open here. During standards such as ``Sixteen Going
On Seventeen,'' ``So Long, Farewell'' and ``Climb Ev'ry Mountain,''
moviegoers will sing along to the lyrics, which appear on the
screen as subtitles. By Thomas Vinciguerra.
</P>
<P>
   MILLIONAIRE-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire'' has turned into an empire, with 27 versions being
produced and broadcast in countries around the world. The questions
are almost approaching educational. Some examples are presented.
</P>
<P>
   NY-VIRUS-REVIEW (New York) _ Commercial enterprise springs from
almost every tragedy, and the West Nile virus is no exception. Some
of these ventures, however, seem a bit more dubious than others. By
Jennifer Steinhauer.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Moved in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   IRAN-MEDIA-REVIEW (Undated) _ Iran's crackdown on
reform-oriented writers, editors and media spreads to cartoons. The
conservative courts have closed 24 reformist publications since
late April. A magazine called Tavana was banned after publishing a
caricature of President Mohammad Khatami, who is himself a
reformer. But it showed him without his clerical turban and robe.
That, the court said, amounted to defamation. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-CARTOONISTS-REVIEW (United Nations) _ At the United
Nations, where one person's joke can strike other people from other
cultures as incomprehensible or offensive, diplomats favor the
universal language of the political cartoon. Over the next few
weeks, a panel of diplomats and American celebrities will choose
the winner of a $10,000 prize for the best political cartoon on a
U.N. theme. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-JOKES-REVIEW (Jakarta) _ A look at some of the jokes
told by President Abdurrahman Wahid. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
