<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PARTY-LOYALTY-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NONPARTISANS IN A PARTISAN STRUGGLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact the Los Angeles office
(Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 By ROBIN TONER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ For all the talk about the great race to the center
this year, nobody who watched the two conventions, skimmed the
parties' platforms or scrutinized the candidates' stands would
mistake the Democrat for the Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, much of the time a certain rhetorical sameness wafted from
the main stages of the convention halls, and there was little of
the partisan bite of yesteryear. But political passions kept
bubbling up, just offstage. And even among the voters at large, at
a time of peace and prosperity, with few great burning issues
pushing people in one direction or another, two-thirds of Americans
still consider themselves Democrats or Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Party, in other words, still matters.
</P>
<P>
   Party attachment is still considered one of the best predictors
of how people will vote _ if they vote. But appealing to those
loyalties, while still wooing the Independents who decide
elections, is a complicated challenge these days. Particularly for
Vice President Al Gore, many analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times/CBS News Poll shows that the Democrats have a
slight edge when it comes to party affiliation: Asked in four
national polls this year how they identify themselves, an average
of 35 percent of Americans said they were Democrats, 30 percent
Republicans, 28 percent Independents and 7 percent (probably the
least likely to vote) said they had no opinions.
</P>
<P>
   In a Times/CBS poll conducted last month, the Democratic Party
was still considered the party that would do a better job on health
care, education and ``making the right decisions'' on Social
Security _ all issues high on the voters' agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party was given the edge on upholding traditional
family values, making sure the military stays strong and ensuring a
healthy economy. Each party, in other words, brings its nominee
certain strengths this fall.
</P>
<P>
   But until last week, Democratic voters have not embraced Gore's
candidacy with the enthusiasm Republicans have brought to Gov.
George W. Bush; the last pre-convention Times/CBS poll showed Gore
drawing 75 percent of the Democrats, while Bush got 86 percent of
the Republicans. ``I think they wasted half their convention just
trying to get strong Democrats and soft Democrats home,'' said Bill
McInturff, a Republican pollster. (Post-convention polls will tell
how successful they were.)
</P>
<P>
   There are obvious reasons why Gore has had to work harder for
voters who should be rightfully his: The Democratic Party has held
the presidency for eight years. The strains are showing between
liberals and ``New Democrats'' who want to keep the party in the
center. And the Gore candidacy has had its fits and starts.
</P>
<P>
   This was the landscape for Gore's acceptance speech Thursday
night: He needed to energize his base, but he was also keenly aware
of the swing voters turned off by partisan appeals. On one level,
his speech was profoundly Democratic. He offered himself as a
populist crusader willing to fight ``powerful forces'' _ like big
HMOs and profit-hungry pharmaceutical companies _ on behalf of
``working families.''
</P>
<P>
   But in sharp contrast to convention speeches of yesteryear,
Gore's never mentioned the words Democrat or Republican, noted
Martin Wattenberg, a political scientist at the University of
California-Irvine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's populist, but it's a broad populism,'' said Stan
Greenberg, Gore's pollster. ``It's saying, let's make sure the
whole society is able to do well.''
</P>
<P>
   To galvanize his party, and to pull back many of the
Independents who lean their way, Gore needs to draw sharp contrasts
with the Republicans, many Democratic strategists agree,
particularly on basic issues like tax cuts and health care.
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans have not made it easy.
</P>
<P>
   Frustrated Democrats say Bush is preaching a message _ that he
is a different kind of Republican, more sensitive and moderate _
that is distinctly at odds with his basic conservatism.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the task that Gore and the Democrats face in the fall
is to tell voters that George W. Bush really is an old-style
Republican,'' said Geoff Garin, a Democratic pollster. In other
words, to block Bush's move to the center, now that he has
consolidated his own party.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats are eager to make that case and highlight the
stakes: What kind of Supreme Court justices would a Bush
administration, operating with a Republican Senate, appoint?
</P>
<P>
   Who would most profit from his tax cuts?
</P>
<P>
   What would his budget proposals mean for Medicare?
</P>
<P>
   How does Bush's health care record in Texas, which ranks high
among states in the percentage of uninsured, gibe with his promise
to provide health coverage nationwide?
</P>
<P>
   But the Gore campaign is in something of a strategic box, one
Republican strategist argued, speaking on condition that he not be
identified. While the Democrats need to highlight the differences
between the parties, overt partisanship gives the Bush campaign the
higher moral ground.
</P>
<P>
   Day after day, the Bush campaign chastised the Democrats for any
hint of partisan attacks at their convention. In fact, party
strategists say, Bush is convinced that the voters are weary of
such fights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush has seriously studied what has happened since Republicans
gained control of Congress in 1994,'' said Linda DiVall, a
Republican poll taker. ``Frankly, Republicans don't do well when we
get into a fight with Clinton or a fight among ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, of course, has the luxury of denouncing partisanship and
muting the differences. Eight years in the wilderness, and a
profound disdain for the Clinton administration, go a long way
toward keeping Republican voters unified and motivated.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, Bush has ably capitalized on his party's traditional
strengths _ most notably, in the aftermath of the Clinton scandals,
the notion that Republicans have stronger moral values. And he has
dealt with his party's vulnerabilities, presenting a multi-ethnic,
family-friendly convention program.
</P>
<P>
   With all his ``rhetorical convergence,'' as the political
scientist Thomas Mann puts it, some voters might well ask just
whether there's much difference between the parties _ an argument
at the heart of Ralph Nader's third-party campaign.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, in their attitudes toward government, their
approach to social issues like abortion and gay rights, their
economic philosophy and their approach to restructuring Medicare
and Social Security, the differences are large and enduring.
</P>
<P>
   And each party's reliable supporters are quite distinctive, too.
</P>
<P>
   Party affiliation is still, quite often, passed down from parent
to child, some political scientists say.
</P>
<P>
   Economic status is still strongly linked with party attachment,
although Republicans have attracted more lower-income members
through the party's embrace of social conservatives, while
Democrats have drawn more white-collar voters.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bartels, a professor of politics at Princeton University,
maintains that party loyalty was a greater factor in presidential
voting in the 1990s than at any time since the 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   And McInturff notes that, if anything, partisan voters have
become even more so thanks to the polarizing figures of President
Clinton and former House Speaker Newt Gingrich _ but for the same
reason people in the middle may have become even more turned off by
partisanship.
</P>
<P>
   Another twist is the unpredictable but undeniable role of third
parties. Wattenberg noted that since the Civil War, third party
voting has not totaled more than 5 percent of the overall vote in
two consecutive elections _ until 1992 and 1996.
</P>
<P>
   All of which suggests the complicated politics that awaits the
voters this fall: a fierce, nonpartisan partisan struggle. For
Gore, the campaign will be about ``fighting for working families,''
and for Bush, ``compassionate conservatism.'' In other words, the
parties are dead, long live the parties.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
