<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Sunday, Aug. 20, and thereafter. The Daily News is continuing its
extensive coverage of the Democratic National Convention and
related issues with today's stories. For questions on any stories,
contact Gerri Hoppe at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   DNC-LAPD (Los Angeles) _ The Los Angeles Police Department
scored a much-needed win in the way it handled the Democratic
National Convention and related protests, officials say. The city
did not burn, no one was seriously injured, property damage was
minimal, and there were only 194 arrests, compared with 390 during
the Republican convention in Philadelphia two weeks ago. By Beth
Barrett. (Will move in the ``a'' national, ``n'' California and
``p'' political news files.)
</P>
<P>
   DNC-LOOKBACK (Los Angeles) _ For one week, Los Angeles became
the center of presidential politics, the focal point of political
dissent, the party capital of the world and a testing ground for
political restraing. A chronological recap of some of the week's
more memorable events surround the Democratic National Convention.
By Erik Nelson and Harrison Sheppard. (Will move in the ``a''
national, ``n'' California and ``p'' political news files.)
</P>
<P>
   BABYSWITCH-LAWSUIT (Northridge, Calif.) _ Linda and James Burgin
are so distraught over a brief switch made by Northridge Hospital
Medical Center on May 30, 1998, when their son Dylan was born, they
have sued the hospital, claiming negligence and malpractice.
They've also sought therapy for ``separation anxiety,'' fled
California for another state and forsaken having additional
children. By Dana Bartholomew. (Will move in the ``a'' national,
``n'' California news files.)
</P>
<P>
