<HEADLINE>
NEW HAMPSHIRE TOWN CREATES A LITTLE LEAGUE POWERHOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 repeating to add art note, fix coding (ART ADV: Photo  NYT2  is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By JAMES C. McKINLEY Jr.    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GOFFSTOWN, N.H. _ When the all-star team from this town on the
outskirts of Manchester won the Eastern Regional Championship on
Thursday night in Bristol, Conn., and a ticket to the Little League
World Series, it was hard to tell who was more excited _ the 11-
and 12-year-olds who mobbed their pitcher on the mound or the
parents in the grandstands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbelievable,'' Mark Collins, the vice president of the league
and the father of the pitcher, Ben Collins, said over and over.
``This was David and Goliath and we won. Unreal.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the stunned reactions of the parents and coaches from
Goffstown, the team's 1-0 victory over a team from the Bronx was no
fluke. It had as much to do with the efforts of adults in the
stands as with their children on the field. Coaches and league
officials say it capped a five-year campaign to make their team a
national contender.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one thing to go out there and teach them the game,'' the
manager of the team, Frank Szumiesz, said. ``But fun is not only
playing the sport. It's striving to win.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were on a mission for the last five years to get to where
we are,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Szumiesz said a core group of league officials decided in 1995
that they wanted their league to become a contender for the state
championship. They were spurred on by their rivalry with
neighboring Bedford, which won the state title in 1993 and went to
the Little League World Series. The Goffstown coaches went to
school on more successful programs in New Hampshire, borrowing
drills and coaching tips and adopting voluntary indoor practices in
the winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at some of the other towns that had quality programs
and we weren't afraid to ask questions,'' one of the Goffstown
coaches, Phil Bradley, said.
</P>
<P>
   The league also expanded and improved its five fields, which had
been built years before. Three years ago, the organizers drummed up
about $20,000 in donations from local businesses to put lights on
one field to allow for later practices and night games.
</P>
<P>
   They also set up a Web site for coaches, referring them to the
latest information on coaching baseball and sent some coaches to
Little League seminars.
</P>
<P>
   ``There definitely has been a concerted effort,'' said Collins,
40, a physical therapist who has coached his son Ben's teams for
eight years. ``We have a great group of talented kids, but for us
to get to this point a lot of other factors went into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most important change was to begin pushing the best
players to work on fundamentals outside the baseball season. ``You
have to be concerned with baseball all year round,'' said Bradley,
a 53-year-old Federal Aviation Administration employee.
</P>
<P>
   For the last three years, many of the boys on the championship
team have spent every Sunday morning from January until April at an
indoor practice facility, built in an old Manchester mill, called
Good Rips. (It helped that one of its owners was Tom French, a
coach whose son, Tom, is on the all-star team.) On snow-covered
mornings, the core of the team arrived at 7:30 a.m. to practice
their swings in eight batting cages and hone their pitching
techniques on two indoor dirt mounds. They also performed fielding
drills, snapping up ground balls and throwing into socklike targets
representing first base. Those weeks of extra work, while
voluntary, proved invaluable, the coaches said.
</P>
<P>
   The league has also used school gyms in the winter for fielding
and pitching seminars. League officials even tried a fall program
two years ago, but found the players were getting burned out and
dropped the idea.
</P>
<P>
   Little League baseball has been helped by the absence of other
strong sports programs in Goffstown, a community of 15,600. The
youth hockey program started only a year ago, and soccer has not
caught on here as it has in other towns.
</P>
<P>
   The local high school lacks a football team, but it won state
championships this year in basketball and baseball. The girls' high
school softball program has also chalked up several state titles.
One Goffstown resident, Morris Allard, built a private stadium for
the state Babe Ruth baseball championships.
</P>
<P>
   Baseball is so ingrained in the local fabric that the town holds
a parade, complete with marching bands and a barbecue, for the
opening day of the Little League and Babe Ruth League seasons. On
Friday nights, the Little League games are often well attended by
people who do not have children on the teams, but come out for an
evening of baseball and the simple pleasure of a hot dog from the
concession stand. The league has more than 100 volunteers.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the spring, the whole town turns to baseball,'' Bradley
said. ``It's hard to emphasize how special baseball is in
Goffstown.''
</P>
<P>
   That was evident Friday along the main street where business
owners were putting up banners congratulating the team. ``People
are so excited,'' said Robbie Grady, who oversees a program helping
to refurbish the town center. ``I've had several phone calls Friday
saying we need to do a parade. How are we going to do this? It was
the talk of the local coffee shops.''
</P>
<P>
   Grady said support for the Little League program was part of a
larger trend of civic-minded efforts in Goffstown. For example,
residents recently raised $200,000 to pay for the treatment of a
13-year-old boy, Evan Kavenell, who had a rare form of brain
cancer. .
</P>
<P>
   Even though it is a bedroom community for Manchester, Goffstown
is not a run-of-the-mill suburb of tract housing and strip malls.
The residents include bricklayers and stonemasons and
high-technology executives. The town is carved out of the hilly
forested country east of Manchester and includes the Uncanoonuc
Mountains. The Piscatoquog River runs through the heart of town,
green, deep and cold.
</P>
<P>
   At one end of Goffstown is the quaint row of Colonial buildings
and churches around the commons. Although some of the buildings
need painting, Goffstown's center brings to mind an idyllic New
England hamlet where baseball would surely be played on grass in
the golden dusk as it was meant to be, with the whack of horsehide
on wood and cleats stirring up the dust.
</P>
<P>
   At the other end of town is Pinardville, a nondescript
commercial strip of shopping malls and supermarkets just across the
river from the old textile mills of Manchester. In between lies the
New Hampshire State Prison for Women.
</P>
<P>
   The Goffstown Junior Baseball fields are just down the road from
the prison, sandwiched between the main road and a gash of forest,
opposite a power substation. On the outfield fences are signs of
local sponsors: True Value Hardware, Blue Ribbon Fencing, J&AMP;G
Roofing, Goffstown Auto Parts.
</P>
<P>
   But for all the effort that parents have made, Goffstown has not
poured money into its baseball program like some Little League
powerhouses. Toms River, N.J., spent more than $308,000 on a new
field and an indoor practice facility. That team won the world
series in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the baseball program here has become a powerhouse, in
part by people working together. The Goffstown group going to
Williamsport, Pa., for the Little League World Series, which begins
Sunday, has been playing together for five years. As 10-year-olds,
they were champions of the New Hampshire Little League Division I
and were runners-up for the state championship.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
