r a BC-DNC-LAPD-2TAKES-LADN     08-19 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNC-LAPD-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVENTION CONTROL RESTORES POLICE PRIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETH BARRETT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ LAPD Detective Robert Holcomb's step had the
bounce of a winner as he strode across Staples Center's security
apron in midweek of the Democratic National Convention, holding a
couple of black riot helmets and draped with an arsenal of gear.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 marchers protesting police abuse were a few minutes
to the north on Figueroa Street, but the detective had time to
chat.
</P>
<P>
   Overhead, a police surveillance helicopter beamed photos of
protesters' location, marchers were flanked by ground troops, 200
riot-gear-clad officers awaited them, and nearby 30 LAPD cars and
some 20 horses were on alert.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Police Department was ready and Holcomb, like
other police and city officials, was certain the situation was
under control.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been very good for morale,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For a department that's been unable to shake the international
shame of African-American motorist Rodney King's televised 1991
beating by white LAPD officers, the 1992 riots that followed those
officers' acquittal in state court, and more recently the Rampart
corruption scandal, the DNC was a high-stakes venture for the
department and its chief, Bernard C. Parks.
</P>
<P>
   And it turns out a much-needed win that puts some shine back on
the badge. Civil liberties lawyers and some protesters complain
bitterly about the LAPD's tactics, but nearly all local officials,
convention officials and visiting press reports gave the LAPD
credit for keeping the peace effectively.
</P>
<P>
   That the city did not burn, that no one was seriously injured,
that property damage was minimal, and that there were only 194
arrests compared with 390 during the Republican National Convention
in Philadelphia two weeks ago caused Parks to claim complete
vindication for his department.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was textbook,'' Parks said in an interview with the Los
Angeles Daily News. ``We had an outstanding operational plan that
took over a year to put together, we had trained 5,000-plus
officers, and the people we had in critical places made the right
critical decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan, and other city and county elected leaders
who were hosting thousands of out-of-towners, lavished praise on
the LAPD for checking disturbances with an overwhelming show of
force.
</P>
<P>
   ``They showed they are a world-class department and one we all
should respect,'' Riordan said.
</P>
<P>
   No one was even bringing up the $7.5 million in overtime the
city expects to pay for the 750 officers per shift.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates overwhelmingly seemed grateful to the LAPD.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we checked into the Holiday Inn (near Staples), everyone
said, You're at ground zero,'' said Indiana delegate Ray Scheele,
who watched the demonstrations from his window. ``The police did an
incredible job. It improved my view of the LAPD, after all these
incidents in the past few years. We're familiar with Rodney King,
even in Indiana.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Hicks, executive director of the Los Angeles City Human
Relations Commission, said he weighed the success of the police
response day by day as he walked with demonstrators and made notes
of the confrontations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The measure is that not many people were arrested, there were
no serious injuries, no serious property damage,'' Hicks said.
``The other measure is whether civil liberties were violated, and I
think in the main protesters were able to get their message out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks said that while LAPD officers may have appeared more
menacing in their dark blue or black riot gear than did
Philadelphia officers, who wore shorts and kibitzed with
demonstrators, he was more concerned with their behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't care what they looked like; I cared about conduct,''
he said. ``Generally, I saw LAPD reacting to what was being done to
them; I saw nothing provocative.''
</P>
<P>
   American Civil Liberties Union of Southern California lawyers -
some of their members still recovering from being struck with
rubber projectiles - and protesters said the LAPD tactics raised
tensions and violated civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Angeles looked like Eastern Europe,'' said civil rights
attorney Carol Sobel, who took one of the LAPD's flat rubber
``stinger'' rounds - which are supposed to strike below the waist -
between the eyes Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing missing were the tanks from Tiananmen Square.
The message that went out is that L.A. is a police state.''
</P>
<P>
   If you were in the streets, added D2KLA organizer Lisa Fithian,
the LAPD machine was harassing, menacing and intimidating; a dark,
forbidding shadow over what should have been a showcase for
enlightened debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Constitution was the big loser,'' said Fithian,
who worked with LAPD commanders to ease tensions and to gain
concessions. ``The police are supposed to protect and serve, but
they constantly chilled people's First Amendment rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics said the police caused the Monday night concert melee by
unnecessary displays of force at minor disturbances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We prevented it from becoming a police state,'' said ACLU
attorney Dan Tokaji, who won major concessions to get protests
closer to delegates and stop police from interfering with a staging
area near MacArthur Park. ``LAPD did their best to declare martial
law, but we didn't let it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
</TEXT>
