<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 12:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6525 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r p BC-DNC-LAPD-2TAKES-LADN     08-19 0910
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DNC-LAPD-2TAKES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVENTION CONTROL RESTORES POLICE PRIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BETH BARRETT 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ LAPD Detective Robert Holcomb's step had the
bounce of a winner as he strode across Staples Center's security
apron in midweek of the Democratic National Convention, holding a
couple of black riot helmets and draped with an arsenal of gear.
</P>
<P>
   About 1,000 marchers protesting police abuse were a few minutes
to the north on Figueroa Street, but the detective had time to
chat.
</P>
<P>
   Overhead, a police surveillance helicopter beamed photos of
protesters' location, marchers were flanked by ground troops, 200
riot-gear-clad officers awaited them, and nearby 30 LAPD cars and
some 20 horses were on alert.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Police Department was ready and Holcomb, like
other police and city officials, was certain the situation was
under control.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has been very good for morale,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For a department that's been unable to shake the international
shame of African-American motorist Rodney King's televised 1991
beating by white LAPD officers, the 1992 riots that followed those
officers' acquittal in state court, and more recently the Rampart
corruption scandal, the DNC was a high-stakes venture for the
department and its chief, Bernard C. Parks.
</P>
<P>
   And it turns out a much-needed win that puts some shine back on
the badge. Civil liberties lawyers and some protesters complain
bitterly about the LAPD's tactics, but nearly all local officials,
convention officials and visiting press reports gave the LAPD
credit for keeping the peace effectively.
</P>
<P>
   That the city did not burn, that no one was seriously injured,
that property damage was minimal, and that there were only 194
arrests compared with 390 during the Republican National Convention
in Philadelphia two weeks ago caused Parks to claim complete
vindication for his department.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was textbook,'' Parks said in an interview with the Los
Angeles Daily News. ``We had an outstanding operational plan that
took over a year to put together, we had trained 5,000-plus
officers, and the people we had in critical places made the right
critical decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan, and other city and county elected leaders
who were hosting thousands of out-of-towners, lavished praise on
the LAPD for checking disturbances with an overwhelming show of
force.
</P>
<P>
   ``They showed they are a world-class department and one we all
should respect,'' Riordan said.
</P>
<P>
   No one was even bringing up the $7.5 million in overtime the
city expects to pay for the 750 officers per shift.
</P>
<P>
   Delegates overwhelmingly seemed grateful to the LAPD.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we checked into the Holiday Inn (near Staples), everyone
said, You're at ground zero,'' said Indiana delegate Ray Scheele,
who watched the demonstrations from his window. ``The police did an
incredible job. It improved my view of the LAPD, after all these
incidents in the past few years. We're familiar with Rodney King,
even in Indiana.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Hicks, executive director of the Los Angeles City Human
Relations Commission, said he weighed the success of the police
response day by day as he walked with demonstrators and made notes
of the confrontations.
</P>
<P>
   ``The measure is that not many people were arrested, there were
no serious injuries, no serious property damage,'' Hicks said.
``The other measure is whether civil liberties were violated, and I
think in the main protesters were able to get their message out.''
</P>
<P>
   Hicks said that while LAPD officers may have appeared more
menacing in their dark blue or black riot gear than did
Philadelphia officers, who wore shorts and kibitzed with
demonstrators, he was more concerned with their behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't care what they looked like; I cared about conduct,''
he said. ``Generally, I saw LAPD reacting to what was being done to
them; I saw nothing provocative.''
</P>
<P>
   American Civil Liberties Union of Southern California lawyers -
some of their members still recovering from being struck with
rubber projectiles - and protesters said the LAPD tactics raised
tensions and violated civil rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``Los Angeles looked like Eastern Europe,'' said civil rights
attorney Carol Sobel, who took one of the LAPD's flat rubber
``stinger'' rounds - which are supposed to strike below the waist -
between the eyes Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing missing were the tanks from Tiananmen Square.
The message that went out is that L.A. is a police state.''
</P>
<P>
   If you were in the streets, added D2KLA organizer Lisa Fithian,
the LAPD machine was harassing, menacing and intimidating; a dark,
forbidding shadow over what should have been a showcase for
enlightened debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Constitution was the big loser,'' said Fithian,
who worked with LAPD commanders to ease tensions and to gain
concessions. ``The police are supposed to protect and serve, but
they constantly chilled people's First Amendment rights.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics said the police caused the Monday night concert melee by
unnecessary displays of force at minor disturbances.
</P>
<P>
   ``We prevented it from becoming a police state,'' said ACLU
attorney Dan Tokaji, who won major concessions to get protests
closer to delegates and stop police from interfering with a staging
area near MacArthur Park. ``LAPD did their best to declare martial
law, but we didn't let it happen.''
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   _ Parks said the new LAPD bears little resemblance to the
under-staffed, ill-equipped force that was pummeled by unruly
crowds and looters at the outset of the 1992 riots.
</P>
<P>
   ``People still talk like Rodney King happened yesterday,'' Parks
said. ``But 70 percent of the officers then are no longer on the
force. To still criticize us because of that is an unfair
assessment.''
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Chief Martin Pomeroy said the force since 1992 has grown
from about 7,000 to 9,500 officers. New and better communications
gear has been purchased, and more sophisticated training has been
instituted.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're a different department,'' Pomeroy said.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights attorneys and others who have monitored the LAPD
for years are skeptical, and say the department has made no more
than superficial changes. They say the DNC only cemented LAPD's
reputation for harshness and brutality.
</P>
<P>
   It's still, Tokaji said, ``Us vs. them.''
</P>
<P>
   The LAPD started planning for the Democratic convention over a
year ago, visiting Seattle in particular, where police were overrun
by protesters during the World Trade Organization conference and
the city's downtown suffered millions of dollars in damage, Parks
said.
</P>
<P>
   From the outset, it was clear a massive, deterrent force would
be part of Los Angeles' strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``A show of force has a very calming effect on a crowd,'' Parks
said. ``Our goal was not to get out of control and have to catch
up. When you put officers in place in advance, you set the tone for
the entire event.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the LAPD's confidential ``playbook'' ended up being some
six inches thick, the crucial page was that detailing how the
police would move one step ahead of the protesters wherever they
went - either beating them to intersections or shadowing them on
the sides of marches - to ensure they did not break out of
established routes.
</P>
<P>
   ``We outflanked the demonstrators,'' Pomeroy said. ``We thwarted
and frustrated those intent on criminal behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Key to the flanking actions was advance intelligence, primarily
provided by an overhead helicopter that shot ``real time'' video of
the marchers for commanders in the field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could see where they were moving in great detail,'' Pomeroy
said.
</P>
<P>
   It was the video pictures of Monday's concert, featuring the
band Rage Against the Machine, that convinced command officers to
declare an unlawful assembly, Pomeroy said. The video feeds showed
a handful of protesters at the rear of the crowd tossing bottles,
chunks of concrete and signs, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights lawyers and protest organizers said police
arbitrarily ended the demonstration without giving people a chance
to exit peacefully, firing rubber pellets as they tried to get out
and trampling them with horses.
</P>
<P>
   Police said new radios with more frequencies - some of them
encrypted to prevent jamming by anarchists - worked nearly
perfectly on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Without the disintegration in communications that occurred
during the 1992 riots, commanders were able to choreograph quick
response with mobile field forces, or specially trained platoons of
about 50 officers each, Pomeroy said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were used for rapid response, leap-frogging parades to
get to intersections while other officers walked alongside,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   It was that constant presence that also infuriated demonstrators
and led to widespread allegations of police infringement on their
constitutional right to free assembly. On Wednesday, demonstrators
protesting police brutality declined to enter the demonstration
area when they were met by more than 200 officers, many in riot
gear.
</P>
<P>
   Aware of the protesters' criticism, the LAPD made an effort to
be less conspicuous. Patrol cars and motorcycles were stockpiled in
alleys and back lots, their drivers waiting in reserve. The horse
detail was stabled on the nearby Los Angeles Trade-Technical
College athletic field.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to lower our presence, so we kept some units out (of
sight),'' Pomeroy said. ``There was no intent to have an
overwhelming show of force like a police state.''
</P>
<P>
   While police were fully armed, they used only nonlethal weapons
to deal with unruly crowds, primarily the rubber pellets that are
supposed to skip off the ground, but which demonstrators said hit
several people in the torso. Pepper spray also was used Monday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``The stinger skips off the ground indiscriminately, striking
people in the front row,'' Parks said. ``The psychological effect
is to make them want to move.''
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights lawyers said they intend to file at least one
lawsuit, and perhaps more over the use of force.
</P>
<P>
   Parks said he felt the pride of officers during the week when he
visited command posts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were excited about the end results,'' Parks said. ``There
had been doubts as to whether we could do this; whether we had the
will. There had been a lot of speculation about this department.
</P>
<P>
   ``The DNC has shown the world what the LAPD is.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
