<HEADER>
A6533 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-BABYSWITCH-LAWSUIT-LA     08-19 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BABYSWITCH-LAWSUIT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY FILES SUIT OVER BABY MIX-UP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DANA BARTHOLOMEW 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NORTHRIDGE, Calif. _ After giving birth to a boy, Linda Burgin
pressed baby to flesh for 45 minutes of newborn bonding in the dark
of her room at Northridge Hospital Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   But when the lights shone bright, it wasn't Dylan she and her
husband saw - but someone else's baby.
</P>
<P>
   The Burgins are so distraught over the brief switch in 1998 that
they have sued the hospital, claiming negligence and malpractice.
They've also sought therapy for ``separation anxiety,'' fled
California for another state and forsaken having additional
children.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had dark hair: It was a Spanish baby,'' said James Burgin,
49, of Phoenix, a former Tarzana resident, recalling the family
ordeal on May 30, 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I screamed, Linda screamed. The nurse said: `I checked his
wristband: This is your baby.'''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   A Van Nuys judge recently rejected a motion from the hospital
that sought to prevent disclosure of the switch on grounds that
publicity could affect a fair trial and the hospital's ``economic
interest.'' The case is scheduled to return to court in January.
</P>
<P>
   The Burgins, who are white, are seeking unspecified emotional
and medical damages. While they bonded with and breast-fed the
wrong baby, they said they are worried another mother may have
nursed their son and passed on a communicable disease. The child
has not been diagnosed with any malady.
</P>
<P>
   Hospital officials declined to discuss the Burgins' lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   But hospital attorneys, in a statement to the court last month,
said Northridge Hospital acknowledges the baby switch, but said no
harm was done to the Burgins or their baby.
</P>
<P>
   ``Northridge Hospital Medical Center,'' the statement says,
``does not deny this factual allegation and maintains that their
conduct complied with the standard of care in the community and
that nothing they did caused or contributed to the plaintiff's
alleged injuries.''
</P>
<P>
   The hospital, while not willing to discuss its standard of care,
issued another statement stressing its exemplary scores in its
accreditation survey last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like most hospitals, we have concise protocols, safeguards and
checks and balances in our systems,'' said Andie Bogdan, Northridge
Hospital director of marketing. ``Our commitment to professional
development is substantial.''
</P>
<P>
   Northridge Hospital Medical Center is owned by Catholic
Healthcare West and has a 426-bed facility in Northridge and a
209-bed campus in Van Nuys. It was re-accredited last year.
</P>
<P>
   Baby switches, accidental and intentional, are relatively rare
across the nation. There have been six reported incidents of baby
swaps and 11 abductions since 1995, when they were first recorded,
according to the Joint Commission on Accreditation of Healthcare
Organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not have a record of the (Northridge) incident,'' said
JCAHO spokeswoman Donna Larkin. The state Department of Health
Services, which oversees and investigates hospitals, had no record
of the Burgin incident, either. The reporting of such incidents,
both agencies said, is voluntary.
</P>
<P>
   Jay Coggan, a Beverly Hills attorney who represents the Burgins,
said the hospital was negligent because its nurse failed to follow
a procedure set up to identify newborns.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they did was absolutely egregious,'' Coggan said. ``But
what happened afterward was even worse. The hospital is now trying
to argue that, even though they admit it happened, they're not
responsible for the actions of their employee.''
</P>
<P>
   When Dylan was born, his father James was pushing 47, his mother
Linda, 30. He was their first and only child.
</P>
<P>
   Until their case is settled, the Burgins say their 2-year-old
son won't wean from his mother, won't leave his parents' bed at
night and will not accept a baby-sitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's mostly separation anxiety,'' Linda Vahl Burgin, 31, said.
''We never really bonded with our son.''
</P>
<P>
   James Burgin, a record company consultant for top-50 radio, said
he looks at Dylan and wonders about his paternity.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing has been a nightmare for us,'' he said.
``They (hospital staff) took the three most precious days of our
lives and ruined them.
</P>
<P>
   ``After this happened, this was so devastating we couldn't bring
our son up in Los Angeles.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
