<TEXT>
<P>
   Lapses in Jets' Tempers
</P>
<P>
   Now that Bill Parcells _ the grumpy
he-says-jump-players-say-how-high Parcells _ is no longer coaching
the team, do players feel as if they get away with more?
</P>
<P>
   The former Jets wide receiver Keyshawn Johnson said in an
interview that earlier this preseason, quarterback Vinny Testaverde
got into a heated argument with one of the offensive coaches.
Johnson stays in regular contact with many of the Jets players and
coaches. The team said it had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   Last week linebacker Bryan Cox and the defensive line coach Ray
Hamilton got into a profanity-laced argument during practice.
</P>
<P>
   Would these incidents have happened under Parcells? Jets players
say arguments between coaches and players have happened before,
even under Parcells, and are a part of football.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, do players need an imposing personality to keep
them in check?
</P>
<P>
   Giants players had little respect for the soft-spoken Ray
Handley when he replaced Parcells, and the laid-back Pete Carroll
was all but ignored by most New England players after following
Parcells.
</P>
<P>
   Around the League
</P>
<P>
   In Pittsburgh, the former Giants quarterback Kent Graham is
clearly having a better training camp than the starter, Kordell
Stewart. Going into this weekend, in three games, Stewart has a
43.9 passer rating. Coach Bill Cowher plans to stick with Stewart
as long as possible ... The new XFL has received 15,000
applications from players. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
