u i BC-ITALY-IMMIGRATION-NYT     08-19 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ITALY-IMMIGRATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMMIGRATION EMERGES AS EARLY ISSUE IN ITALY'S VOTE 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ August usually produces a truce in Italian politics as
party leaders head for the beaches along with everyone else. But
with national elections looming next year, the center-right
coalition leader, Silvio Berlusconi, fired an early strike last
week, issuing the outline of a 25-point political platform from his
vacation home in Bermuda.
</P>
<P>
   A crackdown on illegal immigration was one of the highlights of
Berlusconi's Bermuda study session, and a signal that immigration,
a relatively recent, but fast-rising, issue on the Italian agenda,
will help define the battle between the ruling center-left
coalition and its center-right opposition.
</P>
<P>
   The current government, led by Prime Minister Giuliano Amato, is
keenly aware of how immigration is shaping up as a political
bludgeon. That awareness was demonstrated on Aug. 16 when Interior
Minister Enzo Bianco interrupted a day at the races in Siena, home
to the famous Palio horse races, to discuss immigration issues with
his German counterpart, Otto Schily.
</P>
<P>
   In Italy, the debate does not starkly pit those who oppose
immigration against those who favor it. Many politicians agree that
Italy, with one of the lowest birthrates in the industrialized
world and one of the largest retirement age populations, needs to
import workers, skilled and unskilled, to keep its economy going.
</P>
<P>
   The center-left government voices the same aim of curbing
illegal immigration and favoring orderly, legal immigration as the
right favors. Rather, the battle is being framed around
election-year images and inchoate concerns that Italy's once
homogenous culture is being transformed into an American-style
multiethnic society.
</P>
<P>
   The current government, so badly divided that it has not yet
agreed on a candidate for the elections, is painted by Berlusconi
and others as ineffectual and infected by ``buonismo,'' an Italian
word that suggests bleeding-heart liberalism. Center-left leaders
in turn seek to portray Berlusconi as an intolerant xenophobe.
</P>
<P>
   Livia Turco, minister of social affairs, is getting ready to
propose a new law to grant citizenship to immigrants and she
advocates allowing immigrants' families to join them. She has been
heavily criticized by the right and has countered by accusing
Berlusconi of lacking family values.
</P>
<P>
   Italy, which a generation ago was a country that exported
immigrants, has become over the last few years one of the key entry
points to Western Europe for refugees from Albania, Turkey, Eastern
Europe, Africa and Asia.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, news shows and newspapers chronicle the desperate
traffic in refugees who are smuggled along the Adriatic coast in
crowded dinghies by criminal gangs.
</P>
<P>
   Every summer, some would-be immigrants die in their attempt to
reach Italy.
</P>
<P>
   Berlusconi, a media tycoon who was prime minister for eight
months in 1994, has long espoused a tough line on illegal
immigration. His junior partner in his center-right coalition,
Umberto Bossi, of the separatist Northern League, has often made
xenophobic statements. Polls suggest that three out of four
Italians say they believe that illegal aliens are responsible for a
rise in crime.
</P>
<P>
   Berlusconi's latest proposal sounds draconian: he advocates that
no immigrant be allowed to enter Italy until he or she secures a
job and a work permit.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, Italian law already imposes that requirement, at least
in theory. But tens of thousands of would-be immigrants sneak into
Italy every year.
</P>
<P>
   From Jan. 1 to July 31, the police caught 16,097 would-be
immigrants seeking to enter Italy by boat. In the same period,
37,210 illegal aliens were repatriated. Estimates of how many
foreigners live in Italy illegally vary widely, from 70,000 to more
than 250,000, and many experts suspect the numbers are far higher.
</P>
<P>
   And the law, which requires undocumented aliens to be expelled
or repatriated, is unevenly applied. ``Policemen check my papers
all the time, but they let me go,'' said a 30-year-old illegal
alien from Ecuador, who insisted on the pseudonym Christian. ``They
can tell I am here to work, not to cause trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Christian, who earns $15 a day washing dishes in a restaurant,
said he arrived three months ago, flying from Colombia to Paris,
and then taking a train to Rome. He said he chose Italy over North
America because ``it was the easiest place to get in.''
</P>
<P>
   Italy has only about 1 million registered foreigners _ 2 percent
of the population _ a far smaller percentage than in France,
Germany or Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the fears expressed by politicians and opinion polls
are irrational,'' said Mario Marazziti, director of the Community
of Sant'Egidio, a Catholic charity that works with illegal aliens
and the homeless. ``But the left is so weak right now that the
right can use people's fears of crime and disorder to demonize the
left. And that obscures the fact that business, which the right
claims to champion, needs foreign workers to survive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
