<HEADLINE>
BUSH VOWS TO SEEK FEDERAL AID TO REPAIR INDIAN SCHOOLS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.M., Tenn., Texas)   By MICHAEL COOPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Campaigning here and across the border in New Mexico,
Gov. George W. Bush planned to unveil a new education initiative
Saturday, a call to spend more than $800 million to repair
crumbling schools on the country's Indian reservations.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the Republican presidential nominee, would spend the money
on the 185 schools on tribal lands throughout the country, most of
them managed by the Bureau of Indian Affairs, a federal agency, his
aides said. His proposal calls for an additional $126 million to
replace the system's worst six schools, they said.
</P>
<P>
   The money involved is relatively little, at least when compared
with other education initiatives that Bush and his rival, Vice
President Al Gore, have already made during the campaign. But it
allows Bush to sustain his focus on education _ an issue perhaps
more traditionally associated with Democrats, but one that he has
said will be his main topic of discussion in the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   It is largely through education proposals that Bush has styled
himself as a so-called compassionate conservative, and staked his
claim to the center of his party.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tragically, schools on tribal lands are often in poor physical
condition and lack basic resources,'' Bush said in a statement
released Saturday. ``The federal government has a front-line
responsibility to fix these schools and provide an environment in
which children can learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush has already proposed spending $5 billion on a national
literacy program, while Gore has called for spending $115 billion
on education initiatives over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   And education is where the two campaigns have one of their
sharpest disagreements, over whether the government should provide
vouchers so poor families can send their children to private
schools. Bush strongly supports the idea, saying it will spur
competition, while Gore says that it will undermine public
education in the country by draining needed resources away from
public schools.
</P>
<P>
   On the trail Bush sometimes likes to joke that he is not running
for national principal or federal superintendent of schools, saying
that decisions about education are best left to localities. But the
schools on tribal lands are a special case: Because of longstanding
treaties between Indian nations and the government, they are among
the few schools in the country managed directly by the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   A rally set for Saturday morning at Southern Methodist
University was the second part of a two-day campaign trip in which
Bush is seeking to temper any momentum Gore gained at the
Democratic National Convention. The itinerary itself was a dig at
Gore. First Bush traveled to Tennessee on Friday to highlight the
fact that some polls now show him leading Gore in Gore's home
state. Saturday's rally in Dallas, his aides said, would show how
strongly Bush, the Texas governor, is supported in his own home
state.
</P>
<P>
   ``Listen to the people who know them best,'' read signs printed
for the events.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
