<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 12:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6544 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-VENEZUELA-GAS-845(2TA     08-19 0879
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VENEZUELA-GAS-845(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VENEZUELA FINDS SOURCE OF WEALTH IS ALSO CURSE 
</HEADLINE>
   By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CARACAS, Venezuela _ Like motorists everywhere, Venezuelans love
to complain about the price of gasoline, and they have been doing a
lot of that lately. But one thing sets them apart from almost
everyone else in the world: At less than 40 cents a gallon, gas is
cheaper than bottled water here.
</P>
<P>
   To Americans who are now paying nearly $2 a gallon for gas, such
carping may seem absurd. But the constant griping about gasoline
prices among Venezuelans is emblematic of their complicated and
conflicted relationship with a commodity that so dominates their
national life that it accounts for half of all government revenues
and four-fifths of the exports.
</P>
<P>
   This nation of 23 million people has the greatest petroleum
reserves outside the Middle East. Venezuela has also been the
largest oil supplier to the United States in recent years and, with
prices now at their highest level in a decade, it is looking
forward to record oil revenues of $21 billion this year. Yet oil
has come to be regarded here not as a blessing but as a curse.
</P>
<P>
   When petroleum emerged as the core of the economy in the 1930s,
governments were urged to follow a policy of ``sowing the oil,'' in
the famous phrase of the writer Arturo Uslar Pietri, to encourage
investment instead of mindless consumption. But the reality turned
out to be different, and a saying often heard here in recent years
cynically summarizes Venezuelan history this way: ``Columbus
discovered us, Bolivar liberated us, and oil ruined us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a sick society, and it is sick as a result of an
illness called oil,'' said Anibal Romero, a professor of political
science at Simon Bolivar University. ``Oil is easy to produce; it
can be done by others with imported equipment, and it always sells.
As a result, it has asphyxiated the rest of the economy and led the
majority of Venezuelans to believe that if they are not rich, it is
because someone has stolen what belongs to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, in poll after poll conducted over the past decade,
Alfredo Keller and Associates, a leading public opinion research
firm here, has found that 80 percent of Venezuelans believe theirs
is ``one of the richest countries in the world'' because of its oil
reserves.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly the same percentage believe that the main function of
government is ``to share this wealth among all,'' but they also
complain that they themselves ``have not benefited from these
riches.''
</P>
<P>
   But rather than point their fingers at an economic model that
favors oil over all other activities, thus engendering a bonanza
mentality and discouraging individual initiative, Venezuelans
prefer to blame their leaders. Up to 80 percent believe, Keller
said, that the responsibility for their own poverty ``lies with
government and politicians,'' and that it is ``because of
corruption'' that the state has failed to serve them.
</P>
<P>
   ``People here have never thought of this country's problem as
economic,'' said Carlos Sabino, a sociologist at the Central
University of Venezuela who has written extensively about oil's
impact on Venezuelan society. ``They have always considered it a
moral and political problem.''
</P>
<P>
   It was exactly that sense of resentment and moral outrage that
President Hugo Chavez rode to power in the December 1998
presidential election, in which he won 58 percent of the vote. But
with the price of Venezuelan crude having quadrupled in the 18
months since he was sworn in, he too is facing pressure to deliver
the ``golden age'' of prosperity and social justice that
Venezuelans expect and that he promised as a candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, 46, a former army colonel who in 1992 led an
unsuccessful coup, has stoked such expectations by claiming to have
almost singlehandedly engineered the worldwide rise in oil prices.
During his successful campaign for re-election last month to a new
six-year term, he reminded voters that it was his decision to cut
back production that has given new vigor to the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries, or OPEC.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the current boom in oil prices may have reawakened
memories of the 1970s and expectations that a new round of spending
and subsidies will follow. The 1970s, after all, were an era in
which oil revenues were so plentiful and Venezuelans were so
affluent that other Latin Americans referred to them as ``los
damedos,'' or ``the gimme-twos,'' a reference to their lavish
spending habits.
</P>
<P>
   ``To get out of the mess we put ourselves in then, we are going
to have to make sacrifices,'' said Luis Cortillo, 69, a retired
airline crew supervisor. ``But we don't want to accept that
solution; we want to go on living just like in the days when the
money flowed like water.''
</P>
<P>
   That sense of entitlement is so deeply ingrained that past
governments have tried to raise gasoline prices at their peril. In
February 1989, President Carlos Andres Perez did that, and the
immediate result was riots and looting, in which hundreds of people
were killed _ events followed three years later by Perez's fall
from power and Chavez's coup attempt.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``The country is rich, but its people are not,'' said Lido
Araque, a 48-year-old gas-station attendant who earns about $200 a
month, when asked why Venezuelans should continue to enjoy low
energy costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``So I would say the price of gasoline has to be kept at this
level for at least three more years, because when gas prices go up,
food and transportation costs rise too.''
</P>
<P>
   Chavez calls his movement to reform the Venezuelan state a
``revolution,'' and he clearly has the support of the overwhelming
majority of the population.
</P>
<P>
   But his government appears just as intimidated as its
predecessors by the specter of popular resistance to any effort to
bring local gasoline prices in line with international rates and
thereby discourage excessive consumption.
</P>
<P>
   ``In determining the prices of energy, it is not just economic
factors that must be taken into account,'' Ali Rodriguez, minister
of energy and mines, said in a recent interview. ``We have a
critical social situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Eventually ``there will be an adjustment made in the price of
gasoline,'' Rodriguez, who is also the president of OPEC, added.
``But it has to be done at the proper time, when there is an
economic recovery and employment is picking up.''
</P>
<P>
   At the moment, however, Chavez faces a situation that has no
precedent in Venezuelan history. Even with the price of a barrel of
locally produced crude rising so dramatically, the Venezuelan
economy shrank by 7.2 percent last year, and over half the work
force is either unemployed or working off the books in what is
euphemistically called ``the informal economy.''
</P>
<P>
   To placate his supporters, Chavez has spent hundreds of millions
of dollars on a military-run civic assistance program called Plan
Bolivar 2000, providing subsidized food and free medical care. He
has also proposed populist initiatives like the subsidized
manufacture of a relatively cheap ``People's Car'' that would
obviously encourage even greater gasoline consumption.
</P>
<P>
   But he has conspicuously hesitated to take steps that might hit
ordinary Venezuelans in their pocketbooks. Even the idea of trying,
by raising taxes, to prepare for the day when oil prices start to
decline again is controversial, and not just because the economy is
mired in a recession.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, the problem of the state here has not been how
to obtain resources through taxes to cover public spending, but how
to distribute this growing income,'' Rodriguez said. ``For that
reason, because money was so abundant, we were not charged taxes,
and that had a cultural impact on Venezuelan society, in the sense
that no one here developed the habit of paying taxes or a sense
that not to pay taxes is a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   In a speech in early August, just before he embarked on a tour
of OPEC nations aimed at keeping oil prices at their current high
levels, Chavez announced ambitious plans to develop tourism,
agriculture, mining and fishing.
</P>
<P>
   But the reality, with the rest of the economy hobbled by a
recession, is that Venezuela is probably more reliant on oil than
ever, and thus more susceptible to the impact of a downturn when it
eventually comes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governments here are always like a gambler at a casino,''
Sabino said. ``They have their run of luck, and they come to
believe that everything can be resolved with an increase in the
price of oil. Nothing that Chavez is doing tells me that he is any
different from the others, and that is the problem.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-00 1252EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000819.0106 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6546 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-R-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-ART-     08-19 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: THE BATTLES INSIDE AND OUTSIDE THE LINES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeats to add photo advisory.)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 3,4 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
(Editors: Different spellings of Rivellino and Rivelino in last
graf are correct.) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Rivellino Jones of the misspelled name was refereeing
a soccer game in Manhattan last week, a moral victory for coach
Marty Jacobson. Perhaps those other embattled friends of
thelipsite(at)aol.com, Linda Bensel-Meyers and Billy Bean, could
take heart from Jake, although hang in there is almost always the
hardest advice to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Bensel-Meyers, the whistle-blower at the University of
Tennessee, is facing the start of a football season in which she
has been portrayed as the Volunteers' most dangerous opponent. The
team has just started practicing and Bensel-Meyers has already
informed the NCAA of three freshman players who turned in
remarkably similar compositions. She calls it institutional
plagiarism and blames it on the mores of the university rather than
on the athletes or tutors.
</P>
<P>
   Most people in Knoxville call it harassing the program. The NCAA
might not even find it in violation of whatever it is that concerns
that trade organization.
</P>
<P>
   Bensel-Meyers has been decrying, for some time now, what she
sees as the exploitation of athletes and the subversion of the
humanistic values of the academy. A professor of Renaissance
literature and drama, she is also in charge of the first-year
composition program. She is only recently being heard beyond the
world of the Orange.
</P>
<P>
   In what I found the most cynical and clear-eyed approach to the
issue, Frank Cagle, the managing editor of The Knoxville
News-Sentinel, simply brushed it off. He wrote that the ``fate of
the football team has a deep impact on the morale, the business and
the general economy of East Tennessee'' and that what might be
construed as corruption in college sports was a ``national scandal,
not a local one. And it requires a national solution.'' In other
words, keeping our boys eligible by any means necessary is a
priority not to be tampered with unless every other school goes
honest, too.
</P>
<P>
   Bensel-Meyers is idealistic and fuzzy-minded; she sees
universities using a bottom-line corporate model in which athletes
are resources. Even the coaches and athletic administrators end up
being victimized, especially if they don't win.
</P>
<P>
   ``My immediate problem is how do I avoid being cast as a
harridan because I harp on the issue,'' she said last week. ``The
administration's problem is that you can't put the peel back on the
orange once you see what's underneath.''
</P>
<P>
   Bean, an outfielder whose six major league seasons on three
teams were haunted by the secret of his homosexuality, has decided
he wants to be back in baseball, the binding thread of his life
since childhood. Since he used his sports background to build
functioning teams in two restaurants, he thinks he can use his
business background in a front office. He would offer a rare
combination of experience and skills, as well as a test of sports'
institutional homophobia.
</P>
<P>
   His open, often moving description of life in a major league
closet last year in a front-page story in The New York Times led to
a number of speaking engagements and television appearances. In
talking about baseball, he realized he had not resolved that
critical part of his life; he had left before his career was over.
Even now, at 35, he tries to stay in playing shape and appear
regularly on talk radio; he is still gripping the ball.
</P>
<P>
   Bean is in the process of selling his current Miami Beach
restaurant, Mayya, and writing to baseball club executives. He said
last week that he understands that a team would have to be
``courageous'' to hire him.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jake's message has always been simple: Don't quit. A
recovering drug abuser long clean, a soccer coach in a basketball
culture, an advocate for kids among clock-watching bureaucrats,
Jacobson's saga has been struggle.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1996, when his Martin Luther King Jr. High School team won
the first of its three straight city championships, mostly with
recent immigrants from the West Indies and West Africa, Jake has
been controversial in and out of his school. He was suspended from
coaching for 11 months last year when rival coaches accused several
of his players of being ineligible. He was reinstated and
vindicated, although his team lost in last year's championship
final.
</P>
<P>
   Like Bensel-Meyers, he is self-righteous and insistent on
putting the needs of the individual student ahead of the
institution. Like Bean, his charm masks a willingness to work
harder than most. And like them both, he has a larger vision. Jake
thinks the future of American soccer will rise from the cities.
</P>
<P>
   To that end, the New York City Parks Department's inspired
partnership with the Parmalat milk company finished its six-week
Summer of Soccer 2000 Saturday. On weekday nights in Riverside Park
in Manhattan and Flushing Meadow-Corona Park in Queens, youngsters
played six-on-six games under the supervision of parkies and soccer
coaches and college players like Rivellino Jones. Jacobson ran the
Manhattan program, which included washing the mesh scrimmage vests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at that passion,'' he crowed last week as teen-agers from
Senegal and Brazil and Trinidad stormed up and down the turf with
bursts of heart-stopping athleticism. ``This is going to be the
urban game. These kids are going to be our future.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivellino Jones, 22, named for Roberto Rivelino, the Brazilian
star, is a symbol of that future. As a 16-year-old Trinidadian
overwhelmed by homesickness and a huge, chaotic high school, Jones
found his new roots at midfield on the King varsity. He was on
Jake's first title team and expects to graduate from Medgar Evers
College this year. He says he wants to be a public school guidance
counselor and coach. Like Jake.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
