<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6568 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-DEBBIE-ALLEN20-COX     08-19 1245
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEBBIE-ALLEN20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Debbie Allen `Possessed' with dance, drama
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 20.
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   You expect to see black leotards on Debbie Allen, and today she
does not disappoint. The star and choreographer of television's
``Fame'' also has on a silk jacket with zebra stripe pattern, and
those chunky, soft black shoes that dancers like to wear.
</P>
<P>
   As far as figurative apparel, Allen wears many hats _ performer,
writer, director, producer, choreographer _ and she dons all of
them except ``performer'' for ``Soul Possessed,'' her romantic
dance-drama brainchild that opens the Alliance Theatre's 32nd
season Wednesday. But somehow it all comes back to dance, the
engine of her art, and the leotards. During an interview at the
Alliance's main, mirror-walled rehearsal room, waiting for her cast
to arrive, the petite but muscular Allen stretches, twists, puts
her palms on the floor and busts the occasional graceful move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm 50 and I have no problem saying that,'' she says, ``or
being that.'' Leaning back in a metal folding chair, she raises a
straight leg to touch the kneecap to her nose.
</P>
<P>
   Among her legion of fans: Alliance artistic director Kenny Leon,
who chose Allen to kick off what we now know will be his final
season at the theater.
</P>
<P>
   ``In addition to being one of the most talented people on the
planet, Debbie has a very raw side _ she'll tell you the truth,
period,'' says Leon, who teams with Allen as supervising director
on the show. ``When I saw `Possessed' in Washington, it struck a
visceral chord in me, something disturbing to my soul. This was
before `Contact' (the Broadway dance show) hit. `Possessed' has a
similar charge, and I think it could have more weight if we pull it
all together.''
</P>
<P>
   Following are excerpts from the conversation with Allen.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was the inspiration for this piece?
</P>
<P>
   A: In my family, All Saints Day was very important, we'd pack up
for Baton Rouge and spend the whole day in the cemetery where my
father's forebears are buried. I became interested, too, in Day of
the Dead as it's celebrated in Latin America. Then four years ago I
was in Spoleto, Italy, to direct a dance piece, and I met Joaquin
Cortes _ the great flamenco dancer, a Gypsy from Spain who travels
the world like a rock star. I began to think about taking flamenco
and many dance styles _ jazz, hip-hop, the hoof-tap that Savion
Glover made so hot _ and using them to create a mythic tale. A
dance drama that tells a story with sparse dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What's the story about?
</P>
<P>
   A: It's about a girl, Ysabel, who on the eve of her wedding
leaves her betrothed for a mysterious drifter _ a flamenco dancer!
The two men fight for possession of her soul. The setting seems
like the Louisiana bayous with their mix of cultures, but it's
timeless _ no period or place. The figure of Death appears, with
human qualities.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What does Death look like?
</P>
<P>
   A: Very sexy! And beautiful. You see, when my father died in
1983, it was devastating for my family but it redefined death for
me. In vodun (voe-DOON), what Americans call voodoo, and other
African religions, the spirits of ancestors are as real and present
as the living. In our show, Death is in love with Ysabel, who
represents Life. There's a scene in a juke joint that's wild, a
scene in a church that's serene. I'll be pleased if it means
different things to different people.
</P>
<P>
   Q: And you'll have potential producers and backers coming from
New York and L.A. to see the show?
</P>
<P>
   A: Oh, yes, I came here with that in mind. ... I think we're on
to something fresh and exciting. Using dance to tell a story is not
new but it's kind of being rediscovered right now.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In fact it seems as if Broadway choreography is on the rise
again, with women leading. You've got Susan Stroman's terrific
dance in ``Contact,'' Kathleen Marshall's in ``Kiss Me Kate.'' Do
you feel it's your moment to step back into that world?
</P>
<P>
   A: I never left that world!
</P>
<P>
   Q: I just mean we haven't seen a Broadway show choreographed by
Debbie Allen since ...
</P>
<P>
   A: Since ``Carrie'' (1988). I did some good work, but the show
didn't catch on.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It's a legend among bombs.
</P>
<P>
   A: Well, anyhow, I've been as dominant as anyone in keeping
dance alive as an international phenomenon, in musical films and so
forth, so this is not a ``return.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: How did it become an Alliance project?
</P>
<P>
   A: I came here a few years ago to see my sister (Phylicia
Rashad) in ``Blues for an Alabama Sky,'' and then ``Medea.'' I met
Kenny and liked him a lot.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was it like growing up with your sister?
</P>
<P>
   A: We were always dancing and performing in the house and the
back yard. I was the biggest thorn in her side, too _ following her
around. I always wanted to be like my sister. Always wearing her
clothes when she wasn't looking. Any boyfriend she liked _ I liked
him too. If friends visited she'd say, ``Well if she comes in the
room, I'm leaving!'' But Phylicia was very protective of me. Seems
we've gotten even closer since our children were born.
</P>
<P>
   Q: As a dancer, do you still lead a special daily routine of
diet and exercise?
</P>
<P>
   A: Exercise is not a problem, because even as a director and
choreographer I'm out there demonstrating moves. And I'm so good
during the day, too! Look, I've got my hard-boiled eggs (reaching
into a bulky purse, placing objects on table). I've got my jar of
beets! My grapefruit! Oh, but at night, the terror reigns! The
demon comes! The fat fairy attacks! I say, ``I can eat this
Haagen-Dazs, damn it, I earned it! I'm gonna sweat tomorrow!''
</P>
<P>
   Q: The show's press release carries a note about ``adult
content.'' How young can the audience be?
</P>
<P>
   A: We have a child in the cast, so obviously we feel there's
nothing that child shouldn't see, but it's an individual parent's
judgment. Personally, I think it's important that young people see
that there is pain and consequences for certain actions. Young
audiences see the dark side of life everywhere, but here they'll
see it's not a joke, a game.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Did you create your piece with the MTV generation in mind?
</P>
<P>
   A: Partly, yes, because some of those videos are very
sophisticated about telling a story in a few minutes. You see, our
young people are very attuned to dance drama _ they just may not
know it yet!
</P>
<P>
   THE DEBBIE ALLEN FILE
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Atlanta role: Writer, director and choreographer of ``Soul
Possessed,'' a dance drama at the Alliance Theatre Company.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Background: Raised in Houston; graduated from Howard
University in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Acting: TV's ``Fame'' (1982-1987). Broadway's ``West Side
Story'' (1980, Tony nomination), ``Sweet Charity'' (1986, Tony
nomination).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Directing: TV's ``A Different World,'' ``Family Ties.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Choreography: TV's ``Fame'' (two Emmy Awards), Academy Awards
show (1995-1999).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Producing: The movie ``Amistad.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Home life: Lives in Los Angeles with husband Norm Nixon (a
former L.A. Laker); a son, 16; and daughter, 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``Soul Possessed''
</P>
<P>
   Through Sept. 24. Previews Thursday; opens Aug. 31. 8 p.m.
Tuesdays-Saturdays. 2:30 and 7:30 p.m. Sundays. $10-$45. A regional
premiere. Contains adult content and language. Alliance Theatre
Company, Woodruff Arts Center, 1280 Peachtree St. N.E.
</P>
<P>
   404-733-5000. www.alliancetheatre.org.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
