<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 13:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6570 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS20-COX     08-19 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKUBE-ON-BOOKS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mysterious Deep Throat still captivates old Washington lawyer
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 20.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The major characters, all but a few, have gone to their graves,
while the secondary players exist only as forgotten footnotes to a
drama now more than a quarter-century in the past.
</P>
<P>
   H.R. Haldeman, John Ehrlichman, John Mitchell _ all dead.
</P>
<P>
   And of course Richard Nixon, whose favor they curried and whose
loyalty they lost one by one.
</P>
<P>
   The show ended with President Nixon's resignation 26 years ago,
and the cast of Watergate went their separate ways. John Dean, the
presidential counsel whose devastating memory sealed Nixon's doom,
is an investment banker in California, disbarred from the practice
of law. Charles Colson, malevolent impresario of dirty tricks,
found Jesus and today counsels prison inmates. G. Gordon Liddy,
boldest of the tricksters, is a talk-radio celebrity in Washington,
unrepentant to this day.
</P>
<P>
   History is not without its follies. Eugenio Martinez, one of the
five burglars arrested in the June 17, 1972, break-in of the
Democratic National Committee headquarters, is selling cars, and
his partner, Virgilio Gonzalez, has vanished back into the
woodwork.
</P>
<P>
   But there remains someone else, and his whereabouts _ indeed his
identity _ loom larger as time goes by. Who was Deep Throat, the
unnamed source who met Washington Post reporter Bob Woodward in an
underground parking garage at 2 in the morning? Did he even exist?
Was he one person or a composite of two or more? Was he only a
fiction created as a linchpin for Woodward and Carl Bernstein's
book ``All the President's Men''?
</P>
<P>
   Over the years, candidate after candidate has been nominated _
Alexander Haig, Alexander Butterfield, Vernon Walters, Richard
Helms _ but the candidates themselves refused to be drafted. Now
Leonard Garment, an old Nixon hand who has made Deep Throat his
personal quarry, thinks he knows. ``In Search of Deep Throat''
(Basic Books, $25) is a lawyerly deduction from plausible
hypotheses but in the end an intuitive guess. ``It is my
conviction,'' Garment writes on Page 2, ``that Deep Throat ... was
John Sears.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Sears, too, has declined the honor, and
threatened to sue. But on what grounds?
</P>
<P>
   More to the point, why John Sears?
</P>
<P>
   ``At the time of Watergate,'' Garment writes, ``Sears was an
obscure political operative who had worked in the 1968 Nixon
presidential campaign and, briefly, in the Nixon White House. After
Watergate, Sears became more prominent. He gained national
attention when he served as campaign manager for Ronald Reagan in
1976 and 1980. Sears' name is well known and respected among those
who participate in or write about national politics but unknown to
most of those who have puzzled over the identity of Deep Throat.''
</P>
<P>
   Whoever it was, his identity is known to only four people:
Woodward; Bernstein, Woodward's gumshoe twin back then; Ben
Bradlee, former editor of The Washington Post; and Deep Throat
himself. Woodward and Bernstein have said they would reveal the
name only when Deep Throat dies (which already clears a number of
suspects). Otherwise, ``No comment.'' In a few cases Woodward has
``cleared'' someone, and he denies it was Sears.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Garment has written a brief whose considerable
appeal lies not only in its conclusion but, even more, in its
reasoning. As Garment acknowledges, no hard evidence exists. In its
absence, Garment read everything written about Watergate. He talked
to people who had bit parts. But mostly he read and re-read every
article Woodward and Bernstein wrote, and then compared them with
the narrative of ``All the President's Men.''
</P>
<P>
   Bernstein, the co-authors wrote, had a source who was ``a former
official in the executive branch,'' and Woodward had ``a friend''
who had been in government. The worm of suspicion began to wriggle:
The two sources were one and the same, and they were the person
Woodward met in the parking garage at 2 in the morning.
</P>
<P>
   Deep Throat smoked and he drank Scotch. Many people do, but now
Garment's memory was jogged. He heard the way Deep Throat, in the
book's narrative, spoke. Deep Throat was not an operator but
someone who saw politics as a dance of ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``More distinctively,'' Garment writes, ``Deep Throat knew
literature. He was given to conversing about large and conceptual
things. He was not good at concealing his feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   In the margin of the book, Garment wrote ``Sears,'' the name of
the young lawyer he had hired at the firm of Nixon, Mudge, Rose,
Guthrie &AMP; Alexander. They had remained friends, even after Mitchell
maneuvered Sears out of the White House. At the end of a day Sears
would drop by Garment's office, where they would smoke cigarette
after cigarette, drink their Scotch straight and talk late into the
night about politics and theology.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sears,'' Garment remembers, ``was widely read, from Aristotle
to current politics, and full of Catholic metaphysics and Irish
charm.'' He could talk about ``the relationship between the nature
of the Triune and the tripartite structure of American government
and make it seem both plausible and poetic.''
</P>
<P>
   His ideas were all the more beguiling because they were elusive,
like Deep Throat himself. Yet when Sears spoke, you listened, and
Garment has no doubt he was not his only audience.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
