<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6574 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TRAVEL-ABINGDON20-COX     08-19 1528
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-ABINGDON20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Of historic buildings, haunts in Abingdon
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 20.
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABINGDON, Va. _ It is an unseasonably cool, moonless night in
this historic Blue Ridge Mountain town, a good evening for a ghost
tour in this old place that seems to have more than a healthy
share.
</P>
<P>
   I am being urged by my guide to step behind the Cave House to
inspect the spot where a pack of wolves emerged to attack Daniel
Boone's dogs in 1760. The 1858 building that houses the Holston
Mountain Arts and Crafts Cooperative was built over the limestone
cave that was the wolves' lair. There are no wolves now, of course,
but still the hairs on my neck stand up when I peer into what seems
to be a bottomless black hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe it would be better to come here in the daytime,''
suggests storyteller Donnamarie Emmert, and I readily agree.
</P>
<P>
   Back on the better-lighted sidewalk, Emmert continues our trek
in search of the supernatural. It is a perfect way to learn about
the history of the downtown district _ and maybe encounter a ghost
along the way.
</P>
<P>
   On one cobblestoned corner, we stop to hear the tale of a slain
Civil War soldier whose riderless horse can be seen, we're told, on
certain moonlit nights.
</P>
<P>
   Up the hill we go into the dimly lit Tavern, a 1779 building
that has served as a frontier watering hole, a Civil War hospital,
a brothel, and now operates as a pub and restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Lowering her voice to a whisper, Emmert recounts the story of a
young prostitute who was stabbed to death on the second floor and
who apparently is jealous of any woman with long dark hair. A
female bartender quit her job abruptly one night, Emmert informs
us, when the glasses stored above the bar began hurtling toward
her.
</P>
<P>
   Years before the prostitute's demise, distinguished guests such
as Andrew Jackson and Henry Clay stopped to refresh themselves at
the Tavern.
</P>
<P>
   The town, named Abingdon in honor of Martha Washington's
ancestral home in England, was soon populated with doctors, lawyers
and tradesmen living in stately homes.
</P>
<P>
   Two centuries later, downtown Abingdon retains much of its
historic character.
</P>
<P>
   The Martha Washington Inn, an impressive 1832 brick mansion,
offers luxurious accommodations, elegant dining and a wide, breezy
front porch where guests can sit and rock. Elsewhere along
tree-lined Main Street, historic buildings house shops peddling
antiques, crafts, books and artwork.
</P>
<P>
   But the centerpiece of Abingdon is the Barter Theatre. Across
the street from the Martha Washington Inn, the theater is the
second oldest playhouse in America. When Robert Porterfield opened
the theater in a former Presbyterian church in 1933, it was the
height of the Depression. Admission was 40 cents, but Porterfield
also would accept food.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of swapping ham for ``Hamlet'' quickly caught on as
farmers hungry for culture carted in eggs, meat and vegetables. By
the end of the first season the Barter had made a profit of $4.35
in cash, plus two barrels of jelly. Meanwhile, the hungry actors,
fed on a steady diet of the bartered produce, gained a collective
300 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   The Barter soon established a reputation for nurturing young
actors who would later become famous. Some of the distinguished
alumni include Ernest Borgnine, Hume Cronyn, Gregory Peck, Patricia
Neal and Kevin Spacey.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Barter patrons can leave their eggs and butter at home in
lieu of plastic or greenbacks, but the performances are still
first-rate. We caught an excellent but dark and grim production of
``The Beauty Queen of Leenane'' with Josephine Hall as the Irish
daughter desperate to escape her mother's tyranny. A seasoned
actress, Hall appeared in the PBS series ``The House of Elliott.''
</P>
<P>
   The next day's performance was more cheerful, as 35 dancers in
the Egyptian Folklore Ensemble showcased the musical and cultural
traditions on a stage that seemed as vast as their country.
</P>
<P>
   Plays are staged March through December and range from musicals
such as ``My Fair Lady'' to dramas like ``The Beauty Queen of
Leenane.''
</P>
<P>
   As the Barter's reputation grew, so has that of the neighboring
Martha Washington Inn. Various owners have spent more than $8
million since 1984 to improve the infrastructure while preserving
the architectural details. The 61 guest rooms have modern baths and
authentic Victorian and Georgian-period antiques and art. The
lobby, with its larger-than-life murals, is worth a tour itself.
</P>
<P>
   Like some of the other buildings in town, the Martha Washington
claims a ghost. During the Civil War, the building served as a
hospital staffed in part by student nurses. A young nurse known
only as Beth was assigned to care for Capt. John Stoves, a wounded
Union officer. As he lay dying, Beth played a violin and sang to
him to ease his pain. Not long after Stoves died, Beth contracted
typhoid fever and died, too.
</P>
<P>
   Bell captain Pete Sheffey, who conducts tours of the hotel, says
he still sees and feels Beth's presence. ``Furniture in the rooms
gets disarranged and doors open and close by themselves,'' he says.
``She'll come down the main staircase late at night wearing her
nurse's apron and old-fashioned clothes.''
</P>
<P>
   If you need a breath of fresh air after ghost stories like that,
Abingdon more than obliges. The town is ideal for casual walkers,
but serious hikers can venture past the Tavern down the hill and
across the railroad tracks to the Virginia Creeper trailhead. The
National Recreational Trail follows the former route of the
Virginia-Carolina Railroad through Damascus to Whitetop Mountain 34
miles across the state's highest mountains. Once a main route for
Native Americans, the trail is open to travel by foot and bike, or
on horseback.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 miles of additional trails can be found in nearby
Mount Rogers National Recreational Area, including a 60-mile
stretch of the Appalachian Trail. Camping is available along the
way, but those who prefer more comfortable accommodations will want
to head back to Abingdon.
</P>
<P>
   After a short hike on the trail and another trek up the rolling
hills of Main Street, the cool porches of the Albert and Victoria
Inn were a welcome sight. Almost as welcome as the rack of lamb and
bananas Foster that owner Hazel Ramos-Cano had prepared as a
special treat.
</P>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN MUSTS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to hang your hat: The Victoria &AMP; Albert Inn is an
elegantly restored 1892 home in Abingdon's historic district. The
five guest rooms rent from $99 to $125 nightly and include private
baths and gas log fireplaces. Smoking prohibited. 224 Oak Hill St.,
540-676-2707; www.naxs
</P>
<P>
   .com/victoria&AMP;albertinn.
</P>
<P>
   In the heart of downtown across the street from the Barter
Theatre, the Martha Washington Inn offers a historic atmosphere
with modern conveniences. The rooms, all furnished in Victorian and
Georgian antiques with private baths, range from $159 to $309. 150
W. Main St., 540-628-3161; www
</P>
<P>
   .marthawashingtoninn.com.
</P>
<P>
   For a pastoral setting close in, the Shepherd's Joy provides
accommodations on a working sheep farm. Guests can stay in one of
four rooms in this Victorian house and watch sheep graze. Rates
range from $85 to $95. 254 White's Mill Road, 540-628-3273;
www.shepherdsjoy.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tying on the feedbag: The Alta Cucina is the restaurant most
recommended by the locals. The best choices are fresh fish such as
sauteed wild striped bass with saffron orzo and lump crab or the
grilled salmon in white wine and dijon sauce. 414 Main St.,
540-676-3003.
</P>
<P>
   For an elegant lunch, the dining room of the Martha Washington
Inn offers an assortment of salads, pastas, fish, chicken and a
specialty of Savannah she-crab soup. 150 Main St., 540-628-3161.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Best place to go when the sun goes down: Built in 1779, the
Tavern in Abingdon has been restored to its original condition.
That means the interior is dark and cozy, the floors slanted and
the beer cold. In addition to a full bar, the Tavern serves
burgers, sandwiches, Cajun jambalaya, salmon, shrimp and steak. 222
E. Main St., 540-628-1118.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Great place to see fall color: The peak season in this part of
Virginia is from mid-September through mid-October. For best
viewing, head to White Top Mountain on U.S. 58 or to Elk Garden on
Va. 600 about 20 miles from Damascus. Other good spots can be found
anywhere in the Mount Rogers National Recreation Area,
1-800-280-2267.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to get crafty: An arts and crafts cooperative, the Cave
House features quilts, split-oak baskets, pottery, dried flowers,
hammered dulcimers, dolls and fine art. 279 E. Main St., Abingdon,
505-628-7721.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bringing home a taste of the mountains: In Damascus, the
Grandfather Country Storgsport-Bristol,Tenn., about a half-hour
southwest of Abingdon. Fare is $158 with a 14-day advance purchase
and a Saturday night stay.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Abingdon Convention and Visitors Bureau, 335
Cummings St., 1-800-435-3440; www.abingdon.com/tourism.
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
