<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6576 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TRAVEL-BLOWROCK20-COX     08-19 3382
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-BLOWROCK20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Refreshing winds waft through Blowing Rock
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 20
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLOWING ROCK, N.C. _ The legend goes that a Cherokee brave dived
off the Blowing Rock to appease his gods and was caught in an
updraft so powerful that he was lifted back to his sweetheart's
arms.
</P>
<P>
   I wasn't feeling quite that lucky on my visit to this popular
Blue Ridge Mountains attraction. In fact, I hung on to the flat,
upturned rock _ the parapet, it seemed, of a mighty castle _ for
dear life. My wife was capturing the iffy moment in snapshots. The
famous winds, funneled up from the Johns River Gorge 3,000 feet
below, sometimes make snow fall up and indeed felt strong enough to
knock me into the abyss (though not reverse the process).
</P>
<P>
   The view was thrilling. Ten miles south, Grandfather Mountain
reared up and tucked his rocky pate into wisps of cloud, like a
codger in the smoke of his own pipe. Vast expanses of forested
hills rolled eastward under a brilliant sun, while the shadows of
puffy white clouds swept across them like a tide.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere down there in the horizon-hugging haze were the
Atlanta heat, traffic and crazy-making distractions that we had
fled. Here, the wind and prospects did more than wake up the body _
they braced and cleared the head.
</P>
<P>
   The trip to the rock was the first of many peak experiences we
enjoyed on a hiking trip to the 111-year-old, 4,300-foot-high
resort town of Blowing Rock.
</P>
<P>
   We arrived the evening before to find the village full _ but not
jammed _ with people enjoying the cool of a mountain summer
twilight. Strollers lapped ice cream cones and window-shopped Main
Street's three-block stretch of sophisticated shops. Others kicked
back and enjoyed the scene from the benches and gazebo in the
pretty park across the street.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where an upscale crowd comes to decompress. That's why
it's so down-to-earth,'' says Vance Baker, a Duluth preacher's son
who came here 12 years ago to start Vance's Main Street Cafe and
Pub and is now stationed on the sidewalk to greet his customers.
``We get folks from New York and Miami and Atlanta, and they expect
the best _ you can't put anything past them.''
</P>
<P>
   Our accommodations, the Gideon Ridge Inn, south of town, were
just an arrow's flight from the rock, and with a view almost as
spectacular. This 1940s guesthouse evokes an English hunting lodge:
slate roof, exposed beams, leatherbound books, little lawns and
flower beds that spill down the hillside like pools of a mountain
stream. Our rooms (a cozy attic-like perch the first night, a
cedar-paneled cabin the second) were superb. We had no dinner
plans, so innkeeper Leslie Barnes sprang into action with her phone
and within minutes had us set up for both nights.
</P>
<P>
   Before we drove back into town, we sat on the Gideon's lawn and
watched dusk settle over the valleys. An ocean of green spread far
below us _ the parallel ridges like huge waves frozen in time. The
blue-gray mist that filled the distant hollows looked like the
ghosts of ancient lakes.
</P>
<P>
   The next day's battle plan was to cruise the scenic Blue Ridge
Parkway _ which has more good trailheads than, say, Buford Highway
has gas stations _ by starting at Grandfather Mountain and working
back toward town.
</P>
<P>
   Ol' Granddad, a privately owned preserve with a nature museum
and picnic areas, is, at 6,000 feet, one of the higher peaks east
of the Mississippi. Its upper climate is like Newfoundland's, and
we got a snootful of it. The wind was blowing so hard (65 miles per
hour) when we stepped onto the mile-high footbridge that it bowed
to one side and the cables made an eerie tuning-fork hum. Prayers
were murmured midspan. On the rocky outcrop at the far side, people
watched the mountain's rare resident ravens perform their wild
mating display of backward loop-de-loops. One buzzard-size
daredevil flapped up behind me and nearly scared me into orbit.
Quoth the raven: ``GURRRRRK!''
</P>
<P>
   Surveying the magnificent view, Donald Jackson, a 30-year-old
engineer from Delaware, Ohio, pointed along the jagged wall of the
Blue Ridge and said, ``Look _ they really do look blue in that
haze! Awesome!''
</P>
<P>
   Among Grandpa's many paths, the 3.7-mile Grandfather Trail _
which starts at the footbridge parking lot _ is reputedly tops for
views, well worth its strenuous ladder climbs. I leave that
judgment to hikers with enough sense to bring a jacket.
</P>
<P>
   Here are the hikes we enjoyed firsthand (distances are one way
unless otherwise indicated):
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The No-Car, Surprisingly Splashy Hike: Since Glen Burney Trail
begins just steps from Blowing Rock village, walkable from several
inns and motels, in the Cannon Garden off Laurel Lane, you might
expect a larky little stroll in your sandals. But noooooo _ you
need boot traction in this ferny, ever-plunging gorge. New Year's
Creek cascades over huge boulders along a 2.4-mile trail. Watch the
midday sun fall in pin-spotlight beams as if from cathedral
windows, setting sandy pools aglow.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Splashy Hike II: The Linville River, named for William
Linville, who mapped the area in the 18th century, pours over two
falls, including a 90-foot plunge basin (a slit gorge through one
tremendous mass of quartzite). You reach the falls from a half-mile
trail off Route 221, or you may forge farther to dizzy overlooks in
the 440-acre Linville Falls Recreation Area, which has picnic and
camping sites. Some hemlocks are as big as California redwoods.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Lazy Lake Loop Hike: For those not inclined toward steep
inclines, this flat 2.4-mile route circles the clear, picturesque
Price Lake, with a trailhead on the Blue Ridge Parkway. There are
many views of the lake, where you're liable to greet people
drifting drowsily in rented rowboat or canoe. The lake is part of
4,300-acre Julian Price Park, which has a campground and more
difficult paths connecting to the Tanawha Trail (see below).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  The Cool-Enough-for-a-Preteen Hike: My favorite trail, the
13-mile Tanawha, can hug the parkway too closely (motorcycle noise,
anyone?) but compensates with its rugged beauty. A particularly
scenic stretch from Rough Ridge parking lot near milepost 303 to
Stack Rock parking near 305 winds far longer than the two miles
measured by the road. Linn Cove Information Center is a pleasant
pit stop where maps and hiking guides are sold. This stretch of
trail has bridges, stairs and boardwalks to carry you to
magnificent overlooks, across ``rock falls'' (fields of colossal
boulders that look frozen in mid-avalanche) and beneath the
parkway's Linn Cove Viaduct, so graceful it almost qualifies as a
rock formation itself. Tanawha means ``fabulous hawk'' _ also the
Cherokees' name for Grandfather Mountain, looming above.
</P>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN MUSTS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to hang your hat: The award-winning Gideon Ridge Inn has
matchless mountaintop views, delicious breakfasts and afternoon
tea. $115-$260. 202 Gideon Ridge Road, 828-295-3644;
www.ridge-inn.com. A golfer's dream, adjacent to Blowing Rock
Country Club, is the Green Park Inn, a rambling 1880s hostelry with
swimming pool. Guests have included Eleanor Roosevelt and John D.
Rockefeller (who according to legend tipped everyone a dime).
$99-$169. Route 321, 1-800-852-2462; greenparkinn.com. The grounds
of the Inn at Ragged Gardens _ a 1900s manor house _ are like a
piece of fresh countryside, with bark siding and wild-ish gardens,
wedged into the heart of the village. $145-$275. 203 Sunset Drive,
828-295-9703; ragged-gardens.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tying on the feedbag: It's not easy to find (on a steep
hillside above a Food Lion), but the Best Cellar is a 24-year-old,
lodgelike restaurant where the locals party and don't begrudge
having the tourists join in. Mostly it's for those who like their
drinks strong and their meat red (excellent prime rib), but the
menu is varied. U.S. 321 bypass, 828-295-3466. Twigs, a casual but
sophisticated restaurant with contemporary art, is likewise just
loud enough to be convivial and justly renowned for its crab cakes
and fresh local trout. U.S. 321 bypass, 828-295-5050.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sights from the heights: The Blowing Rock is a small,
privately owned park renowned for its spectacular overlooks and its
namesake rock, which gets powerful updrafts from the Johns River
Gorge. $4. U.S. 321,
</P>
<P>
   828-295-7111. Grandfather Mountain is a privately owned
3,000-acre preserve with a nature museum, picnic areas, overlooks
and hiking trails for all levels of ability. $10. U.S 221,
1-800-468-7325; www.grandfather.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Great place to see fall color: The rocking chairs on the front
porch of the manor house in Moses Cone Memorial Park. From this
vantage point on the 19th-century estate of the philanthropist
known as ``the denim king,'' you look out on lawns that slope down
to 22-acre Bass Lake, and surrounding you are 3,500 acres of
foothills covered with beech, oak, ash and sugar maples _ which
Cone imported from New England. Milepost 294, Blue Ridge Parkway,
828-295-7938.  &QR;  Where to get crafty: From the rocking chairs
mentioned above, look over your shoulder into the Parkway Craft
Center in the Cone manor house. Operated by the Southern Highland
Handicraft Guild, the shop has striking pieces in glass, wood,
fabric and stone, and is miles above the usual
scented-candle-and-dulcimer-tape joint that's overgentrifying
Appalachia these days. (See address, phone above.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Best place to go when the sun goes down: Vance's Main Street
Cafe and Pub, housed in an old brick storefront, is a casual bistro
hung with modern art, the one true nightclub in an early-to-bed
kind of town. We heard a jazz trio make a smooth, funny segue from
``Satin Doll'' to the ``I Dream of Jeannie'' TV theme. 1121 Main
St., 828-295-7737.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Other nearby fun: Linville Caverns, filled with eerily
molten-looking rock formations and the echoing gurgles of a
subterranean stream, makes a good 30-minute family foray. U.S. 221,
1-800-419-0540; www.linvillecaverns.com. The Tweetsie Railroad is a
refreshing mountainside variation on a kiddie theme park, with
rides, stage shows and a narrow-gauge railroad. U.S. 321,
1-800-526-5740; www.tweetsie.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: The drive is five hours from Atlanta. Take I-85
and turn north on U.S. 221 in Spartansburg, S.C. Just after the
Grandfather Mountain entrance, turn north on the Blue Ridge
Parkway, exit again on U.S. 221 eight miles farther on and continue
to town crossroads at U.S. 321.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Blowing Rock Chamber of Commerce, 1-800-295-7851;
www
</P>
<P>
   .blowingrock.com.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for thmbering out of the car and racing to
the porch, we hear at last the soothing sounds of Hot House Creek.
Wooden stairs from the lower deck lead directly to the chilly
waters.
</P>
<P>
   Inside there's a great room with fieldstone fireplace and
cathedral ceiling. The floors, ceiling and walls form a cocoon of
knotty pine. There's a fully equipped kitchen (and gas grill on the
porch), washer-dryer and satellite TV. Three large windows in the
dining room provide a splendid view of the lazy creek.
</P>
<P>
   The master bedroom downstairs has a quilt-covered king-size bed
and hot tub on the porch through the sliding glass doors. The loft
bedroom, with its own bath, opens on to a third-story deck. It's
perfect for the 12-year-olds _ my daughter, Caroline, and her
friend Allison Rohan. They quickly jump into their bathing suits
and soon are floating down the creek in a single hot pink tube.
</P>
<P>
   Tearing ourselves away isn't easy, but soon we are happily
trekking horseback with Rachel Callihan's Adventure Trail Rides
($35 for two hours; 706-632-9704).
</P>
<P>
   I'm not sure our trusty steeds _ easygoing Jasmine,
high-spirited Thunder, steady Chance and the fidgety Forrest Gump _
are nearly as thrilled. Still, they tramp dutifully through 400
acres hard by the Chattahoochee National Forest, down century-old
logging roads edged with blackberry bushes and leafy rhododendron,
along ``Granny Callihan's Ridge'' (named after Rachel's
great-great-great-grandmother), across green meadows sprinkled with
purple clover and Queen Anne's lace and through McClure's Creek,
where the horses pause to drink.
</P>
<P>
   The smell of newly mowed grass mingles with leather and horse
manure as we cross a country road into a field. The sun is slipping
behind the mountain that Callihan says once belonged to her great
uncle Sam Callihan _ ``but he sold it to the federal government for
$17 during the Depression.''
</P>
<P>
   I let slow and sweet-tempered Jasmine cool her heels while the
others gallop across the pasture. Caroline is shouting, ``Awesome!
Awesome!'' and my husband, John, is striking a Marlboro Man pose as
they trot back.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the stables, I'm wobbling like a drunk on shaky legs.
Oh, I'm gonna be sore. Crank up the hot tub.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Ridge Scenic Railway waits for no man (woman or child),
so the next morning we are up and at 'em. Promptly at 9:40 a.m.,
the cry goes out, ``All aboard!'' and we climb up the steps to
open-air car 2929, named Ridge Runner. Others ride in closed
vintage coaches as the bright red diesel-powered locomotive chugs
northward on 100-year-old tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The 13-mile excursion follows the Toccoa River, which is called
the Ocoee on the Tennessee side. In Georgia, the river is wide and
fairly docile; the narrower Ocoee is rough and ready, with
challenging Class IV rapids (classifications range from I to VI)
bearing ominous names like Broken Nose, Tablesaw and Diamond
Splitter.
</P>
<P>
   At the depot in McCaysville, where most of the passengers have a
one-hour layover before returning to Blue Ridge, we and others who
have opted for the Ocoee Rail Adventure package are met by the
Wildwater Ltd. van.
</P>
<P>
   I approach the Ocoee with trepidation. Make that fear and
trembling: This was the proving ground for world-class kayakers
during the 1996 Olympics. Granted, though, our trip would be in the
less challenging middle Ocoee, not the rock-'em-sock-'em upper
course.
</P>
<P>
   During orientation we are taught simple self-preservation
techniques _ how to avoid falling out of the raft and what to do if
it happens, and how to safely handle the paddle so as not to render
one's raftmates toothless.
</P>
<P>
   We are assigned to a raft along with a Knoxville-area high
school ROTC instructor who calls himself Ski (for good reason _ his
name is Steven Wrzesniew-
</P>
<P>
   ski) and his son Eric, a freshman at Maryville (Tenn.) College.
A retired Air Force man, Ski knows all about survival. He brings
students here twice a year. I am glad he is in my raft.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best classroom for me to teach fear management and
team building,'' Ski says. I hope his methods rub off on me.
</P>
<P>
   Our guide, Matt Sloan, is studying creative writing at the
University of North Carolina, Asheville. He assures me he has
rafted dozens of rivers in several states. I notice his tongue is
pierced; he obviously knows no fear.
</P>
<P>
   We hit whitewater right out of the chute. The river rumbles
around us as we finesse our way through the rapids Grumpy and Gonzo
Shoals, which give us a tease of what's to come. The surging river
winds on, serving up one rush after another.
</P>
<P>
   For near two hours, we obediently respond to Matt's paddling
commands. I am concentrating on staying high, if not dry, but
occasionally I glimpse folks on the woodsy riverbanks waving to us.
</P>
<P>
   When I face my worse fear _ the twin terrors Slice 'N Dice,
back-to-back Class IV rapids _ I whoop and holler and shoot 'em
like a pro.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, our team is home free. Awesome.
</P>
<P>
   My fear is gone, but something's in its place: tired, aching
muscles. Man, this relaxation business is a workout.
</P>
<P>
   Time to get back to Up the Creek _ and rev up that hot tub.
</P>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN MUSTS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to hang your hat: Up the Creek is one of 70 cabins
available through Tica Cabin Rentals. Prices run $100-$250 (per
night, plus $50 cleaning fee per stay; weekly rates available).
Most have two or three bedrooms. Guests have privileges at the Tica
Swim &AMP; Racquet Club in town, which has a swimming pool, kiddie pool
and four tennis courts. Pets are welcome in most cabins. You can
make reservations for horseback riding, whitewater rafting,
fly-fishing and pontoon boat tours through the office, at 699 E.
Main St. in downtown Blue Ridge. 1-800-871-8422;
www.ticacabins.com.
</P>
<P>
   Other cabin rental agencies serving the area include Black Bear
Cabin Rentals (1-888-902-2246; www
</P>
<P>
   .blackbearcabinrentals.com), Heavenly Creekside Cabins
(706-632-4625; www.georgiacabinsbyowner.com), the Last Resort Hot
Tub Cabins (1-800-959-5562; www.thelastresort.com), Toccoa Valley
Cabins (706-838-4706; www.toccoavalleycabins.com) and Sunnybrook
Bend Cabins (1-800-974-
</P>
<P>
   3620; www.sunnybrook.com).
</P>
<P>
   Mountain River Resort is a complex of four upscale cabins on the
Toccoa River (706-632-6053; for a three-minute audio brochure, call
706-632-3168).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tying on the feedbag: The rustic Toccoa Riverside Restaurant
overlooks the Toccoa, eight miles south of town on Aska Road. Steak
and trout are specialties; pecan-encrusted trout was fabulous
($13.95). No alcohol, but brown bagging is allowed. Open 11:30
a.m.-3:30 p.m. and 4:30-9 p.m. except Mondays and Tuesdays.
706-632-7891.
</P>
<P>
   Good bets downtown include the Deli Difference (great
sandwiches, including a portobello mushroom on bun), 611 E. Main
St., 706-632-3094; and Lindsey's Malt Shop ('50s-style soda
fountain with malts, shakes, sundaes and a wicked concoction called
Frito Pie), 644 E. Main St., 706-632-1950.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Best place to go when the sun goes down: Back to the cabin.
However, you might want to visit one of the state's last drive-in
movie theaters, the Swan (706-632-5235), or listen to bluegrass at
Sugar Creek Music Park if a show is scheduled (706-632-2560).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Great place to see fall color: Drive out Aska Road on the west
side of Blue Ridge Lake and the Toccoa River. From U.S. 76, turn
right (south) at the Conoco station, then left at the stop sign and
right on Aska Road.The Aska Trails Area for mountain biking and the
Toccoa River Canoe Trail are off Aska Road. Another scenic route is
Ga. 5 between Blue Ridge and McCaysville.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to get crafty: The Aska Bargain Store (1014 Aska Road,
706-632-6464) houses Jerry's Mountain Creations, handcrafted log
funiture crafted on site, and Anthony's Creations, which features
canoes, willow furniture and custom chandeliers, lamps and sconces
made from antlers. Also, check out Toccoa River Pottery and Arts
(143 Stanley Creek Road, 706-632-0520).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bringing home a taste of the mountains: Mercier Orchards
features more than 30 varieties of reds, golds, greens and
burgundies well into December. This roadside apple house on Ga. 5
just north of town also sells apple cider, jams, jellies,
dressings, baskets, apple cakes, apple breads, fruit turnovers and
_ one of my favorite libations _ frozen apple cider slush. Open
daily. 706-632-3411; www.mercier-orchards.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mountain duds: Drop into Blue Ridge Adventurewear on East Main
Street for T-shirts, hats, activewear, boots and river sandals
(706-632-3991). Pop across the street to Anasazi for a nice
selection of hiking/walking sticks (706-632-7661).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Best CD for those winding roads: ``Mountain Valley Music,'' a
compilation of music from North Georgia and Western North Carolina,
was produced by the Folklore Project at the John C. Campbell Folk
School in Brasstown, N.C. You can purchase one at the school's
Craft Shop. 1-800-365-5724; www.grove.net
</P>
<P>
   /(tilde)jccfs/.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Taking the train: Trains depart at 10 a.m. and 2 p.m.
Fridays-Saturdays and 2 p.m. Sundays. During fall leaf season _
October through Nov. 13 _ the train will run at 11 a.m. Mondays as
well. $23; $20 ages 65 and older; $12 ages 3-12; ages 2 and under
free if sitting on parent's lap. Ocoee Rail Adventure, $65
(includes train, rafting and lunch; participants must be 12 or
older). 1-800-934-1898; www.brscenic.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Take I-75 north to I-575, then continue north
as it changes to Ga. 515/U.S. 76. It's about a 1 1/2 hour drive.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Fannin County Welcome Center, 1-800-899-6867;
www.blueridgemountains.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
