<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-CASHIERS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chill out in mountain air of Cashiers
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CASHIERS, N.C. _ The only thing that keeps you from feeling
completely away from it all is Clark Howard. And not only Clark _
ordinarily a congenial presence _ but the less welcome noise from
certain stations whose backseat lobbyists could not be satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   You're only a little more than two hours from Atlanta up here,
but you have to turn on the radio to realize it.
</P>
<P>
   The temperature on the July day we left the city was already 86
degrees, and in a few hours would be knocking on the door of 100.
The farther we drove, the cooler it got. It never rose above 80 the
two days we were in Cashiers, and you're more often in shade than
in sun. This is, after all, in the Nantahala National Forest.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the Cashiers-Highlands plateau is the only alpine rain
forest east of Oregon. It boasts the most abundant concentration of
waterfalls in the United States, with the Whitewater Falls being
the highest.
</P>
<P>
   But there are other reasons for coming here, and not just in
summer. There is, for one thing, the High Hampton Inn &AMP; Country
Club, a 1,400-acre antebellum estate that will fill your belly
three times a day and house you in a rustic cottage free of certain
conveniences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Son,'' I told our 12-year-old before we left, ``this resort
where we're staying is going to cost about $350 a night, and it
won't have a telephone or a television.''
</P>
<P>
   It was enough to turn his face away from the computer screen.
``You're kidding, right?''
</P>
<P>
   Assured I wasn't, he said with undisguised skepticism, ``That's
going to have to be some kind of hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   It is certainly that, and yet it is not for everyone. (The hotel
acknowledges as much: ``Over the years we've found that not
everyone likes it here, especially those who want plush
accommodations,'' a brochure says.)
</P>
<P>
   If it is not plush, it is more than comfortable. But it is also
pricey. If you go on the American Plan (which most people do), your
room rate goes up according to the number of people in it. And if a
holiday for you means, among other things, a vacation from a coat
and tie, you're going to have to string something other than rope
around your neck if you want dinner. The resort's vast dining hall
_ where a buffet is offered at breakfast, lunch and dinner _ bows
to tradition at the evening meal.
</P>
<P>
   For a hotel that makes a concession to formality, a stay at the
High Hampton Inn is nothing if not casual. Plamen Parvanov, a
porter from Bulgaria in his third season, needlessly apologized for
the lack of a telephone in the cottage (phones are available in the
lobby), saying, ``That's why people come here. They want to get
away from it all _ from the telephone, the television, the radio,
all of it.''
</P>
<P>
   One such couple was Connie and David Thomas, from West Palm
Beach, Fla. This year they recruited friends to share one of the
four-bedroom, fully-furnished Colony Homes on the estate. ``We love
the weather, the food, the golf and tennis, and just being away
from South Florida,'' Connie Thomas said. ``And you don't have to
worry about where to eat.''
</P>
<P>
   If you're a golfer or a gardener, a hiker or a tennis player,
the High Hampton Inn is a kind of Valhalla. There's even a
meticulously kept croquet lawn (do they have par in croquet?), with
a lake beyond it and the rock face of a mountain on the far side of
the lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``The par-71 course is a scenic favorite with mountain views on
every hole and bent grass greens,'' according to Golf Magazine.
``At High Hampton you are away from the crowds, and you might be
able to hear the keening of a mountain hawk soaring overhead.''
</P>
<P>
   Alas, I am not a golfer. But who doesn't appreciate getting away
from it all in his own fashion? The inn's eight hiking trails are
excursions into the natural world that city folks too easily
forget. Wild azalea, mountain laurel and huge rhododendrons cover
the grounds, and at night the only sound you might hear is that of
a waterfall.
</P>
<P>
   And you needn't confine yourself to the inn. Cashiers itself is
a town of modest charms and a growing number of shops and
restaurants. For many years, it existed in the shadow of
better-known Highlands, 10 miles south. Highlands was a bit more
chic and, at 4,100 feet, could claim an extra 600 feet in altitude.
</P>
<P>
   But there are also more people and more cars in Highlands.
Cashiers affords the daytripper and the weekender a more relaxed
experience. As one Highlander told me, you learn to go where the
crowds aren't, and it's easy to find yourself going up the road to
a town almost beyond radio's reach.
</P>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN MUSTS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to hang your hat: The High Hampton Inn &AMP; Country Club is
not the Econo Lodge. If you go on the America Plan (three buffet
meals a day), your room rate escalates according to the number of
people in your party. For example, a single person might pay $103
per night, but that same person and a spouse would pay $182. If
they brought a child, it goes up to $244. If they brought three
children and those kids' ages were (as ours were) 12, 10 and 3,
that same room would cost $353. But your meals are paid for, and no
one could ever go hungry.
</P>
<P>
   1-800-334-2551, Ext. 150; www.highhamptoninn.com.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of options, including:
</P>
<P>
   Laurelwood Mountain Inn. $67-$135 (the latter for a two-bedroom
suite). Fully equipped kitchens, fireplaces, whirlpool tubs. A
short walk from shops and restaurants. 828-743-9939;
www.laurelwoodmountaininn
</P>
<P>
   .com.
</P>
<P>
   Millstone Inn. A bed-and-breakfast one mile east of town. Eleven
furnished rooms and suites, each with a fireplace and a sitting
room. But no children under age 10, no pets and smoking limited.
$131-$159 weeknights, $171-$198 weekends. Two-bedroom suites
available. 1-888-645-5786; www.millstoneinn.com
</P>
<P>
   Cabins in the Laurel. One- and two-bedroom log cabins, each with
complete kitchen, stone fireplace, satellite TV, VCR, front porch
with barbecue grill and rockers. Walking distance to shops and
restaurants. $110-$140 nightly, but two-night minimum. Children
welcome. No pets. Open year-round. 828-743-2621; www.nc-cabins.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tying on the feedbag: If you stay at the High Hampton, your
meals are amply provided. Many small restaurants available in
Cashiers (or in Highlands, 10 miles south). The Market Basket, near
the center of town, is only one of many good restaurants. Less than
quarter mile from U.S. 64 and N.C. 107. 828-743-2216.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Best place to go when the sun goes down: On a cool night, the
four-sided fireplace in the High Hampton's lobby invites you to
sink into one of the comfortable chairs with a snifter of cognac.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Great place to see fall color: The High Hampton Inn and
unincorporated Cashiers are in the Nantahala National Forest. Half
an hour to the east is Pisgah National Forest. Whether you're
staying at the High Hampton Inn or lodging elsewhere, the fall
colors are all around you.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to get crafty: In Cashiers, as in better-known
Highlands, myriad crafts shops line the main street (and side
streets). One is Southern Hands, where the wares include blown
glass, fireplace accessories, Churchill Weavers throws, pottery and
turned wood. N.C. 107 N., one block from intersection of U.S. 64
and N.C. 107 (in Cashiers Commons). 828-743-5499.
www.southernhands.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bringing home a taste of the mountains: Don't miss the places
selling locally made (or made close by) jams, sourwood honey,
apples from western North Carolina and other produce. But the
Cashiers Farmers Market covers all bases. 828-743-4334. On U.S. 64,
less than a quarter-mile east of the intersection of U.S. 64 and
N.C. 107, the crossroads at the heart of Cashiers.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Spotted along the road: Outside Cashiers a sign reads
``Eastern Continental Divide. Elevation: 2,964.'' Geography is no
respecter of maps, and you realize it when you cross a continental
divide.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Other nearby fun: Arrowmont Stables, seven miles north of
Cashiers on N.C. 107, offers adults and children English and
western riding on Arabian, appaloosa and Tennessee walking horses.
Also, catch-and-cook fishing, campfires and cabin rentals.
1-800-682-1092; www.arrowmont.com.
</P>
<P>
   The par-71 course at the High Hampton Inn is one of the most
scenic in the country. (Greens fees are $32 per player per day.)
The inn also has six tennis courts ($5 per hour per player).
</P>
<P>
   On the grounds of the High Hampton Inn are eight walking trails,
varying in length from 45 minutes to three hours, and a 35-acre
lake that offers rowing, sailing, pedal boating and fishing.
</P>
<P>
   The North Carolina Botanical Gardens will conduct a wildflower
workshop Oct. 8-10, including walks, field trips, lectures and
demonstrations.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: I-85 north to Exit 1 in South Carolina, where
you pick up S.C. 11. Take S.C. 11 to Walhalla, S.C., and turn left
onto S.C. 107, which takes you into North Carolina and directly
into Cashiers (and right past the High Hampton Inn &AMP; Country Club).
</P>
<P>
   Another route would involve less travel on I-85. Exit onto 1-985
and take it to Ga. 23. At Dillard, near the North Carolina line,
exit east and look for signs for Highlands. Take N.C. 106, which
courses through the Nantahala National Forest. Cashiers is 10 miles
beyond Highlands.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Cashiers Area Chamber of Commerce, 828-743-5191;
www.cashiers-nc.com.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
