<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6580 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TRAVEL-HENDERSONVILLE     08-19 1720
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-HENDERSONVILLE20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Fun's fine and footloose in the `dancingest town'
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 20.
 &HT;    By Paula Crouch Thrasher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HENDERSONVILLE, N.C. _ The social ``hour'' at the Waverly Inn
was already two hours old when those of us rocking and sipping wine
on the porch decided to move the party a few blocks down Main
Street to the Monday night street dance. That's right, a street
dance. On a Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   But first things first: dinner. We counted heads, added in the
kids and asked innkeeper John Sheiry to call Cypress Cellar to
reserve a table for a party of nine.
</P>
<P>
   Besides myself, there was my husband and daughter, Michael and
Corinne Larsen and their two children from Switzerland and Cecil
and Jonette Eason from New Bern, N.C. Off we went, down the
sidewalk toward town, laughing and gabbing _ a bunch of strangers
who had become fast friends. At least for the evening.
</P>
<P>
   That's the kind of place this is: a small mountain town in the
heart of North Carolina apple country, where hundreds of folks cut
a rug (or just watch from lawn chairs) during the summer street
dances.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's square-dance time in the dancingest town in America,''
announces longtime caller Bill McEntire as the Thunder Rose Band
cranks up. And the first hometown hoedown of the season was under
way in the middle of Main Street.
</P>
<P>
   Our hungry party ducked in to the Cypress Cellar for dinner, and
when we emerged, the square dancing had given way to free-form as
the band played ``Achy-Breaky Heart.'' Moms holding babies swayed
to the music, young and not-so-young couples locked arms, and
daddies swung their little girls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a family get-together,'' McEntire tells me after the last
dance. ``We have 'em from 2 to toothless. Nobody's drinking.
Nobody's fighting. I'm guessing there were 1,000 people tonight.
I've had as many as 3,000 people out here.''
</P>
<P>
   McEntire is in his 51st year of calling the dances, which have
been held since 1918, except for two years during World War II.
(There are three more dances this year _ through Labor Day.)
</P>
<P>
   If you happen to be in town Friday night, you can catch the
summer's final Music on Main Street program on the courthouse lawn.
Bring a chair. And over Labor Day weekend, the 54th North Carolina
Apple Festival will be in full swing downtown and in surrounding
areas.
</P>
<P>
   In any season, the pedestrian-friendly downtown is a magnet for
residents and visitors alike.
</P>
<P>
   Main Street _ from Sixth Avenue on the north end to First Avenue
on the south _ is framed with shade trees, planters filled with
seasonal color and benches along wide sidewalks made for strolling.
</P>
<P>
   A sign at the north end of the shopping district advises
visitors they are entering an international peace zone. More like
an international shopping zone, I'd say.
</P>
<P>
   This is a great little shopping town, chockablock with wonderful
antique emporiums, gift shops, galleries, a gem and mineral museum,
restaurants and great places to have a cup of gourmet coffee, ice
cream or a little something for the ol' sweet tooth.
</P>
<P>
   After two hours of shopping on Monday morning, we had made it
down one side of the street, landing at the nostalgic Days Gone By
_ the circa-1882 Justus Pharmacy _ for soda fountain-style
sandwiches and old-fashioned milkshakes.
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding the midday heat, we slipped into the cool, dark Skyland
Arts Cinema Center to catch ``Chicken Run.'' This intimate movie
house has bistro seating and a cafe menu featuring pizza, other
snacks and beer and wine.
</P>
<P>
   But the fun isn't exclusively on Main Street. Tuesday morning,
before leaving town, we checked out the bounty of Henderson County
at the old-fashioned Curb Market, a farmer's co-op in operation
since 1924. Although it started with eight sellers under umbrellas
on Main Street, it has been doing business in the brick building at
Church and Second streets since 1955.
</P>
<P>
   A don't-miss attraction that's open Tuesdays, Thursdays and
Saturdays, the market features homegrown fruits and vegetables,
flowers, baked goodies, home-canned jellies and relishes, woven and
braided rugs, dolls, folk toys, quilts, afghans, table linens,
handwoven purses and cakes baked in Mason jars.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the oldest farmer-owned farmers market in the
South,'' says Larry Ball, who sells dried and fresh cut flowers
along with very unusual lamps with shades made from hornets' nests
and bases of deer feet.
</P>
<P>
   Summer resident Jill Monroe stops to buy sunflowers from Ball
and shares a tip: ``Put a fourth cup of vodka in the water and it
makes them very happy flowers. They'll last a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Monroe, who has been summering in Hendersonville since 1940,
proclaims, ``I love this town. Although it's growing, it still
maintains the small-town atmosphere. Everyone is friendly. Nobody
is in a hurry. And I love this market. They bake the best buttered
biscuits you ever put in your mouth.''
</P>
<P>
   Half the fun of a visit is chatting with the 100 or so friendly
vendors, some of whom are the fifth generation to run their booths.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been coming about all my life,'' says Joyce Pace, who
uses her married name, Mrs. Herbert J. Pace, to label her canned
goods. ``My mother had this booth, and she passed it on to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Her most popular item is artichoke relish. ``One man said it's
good enough to open up, get a spoon and get under a shade tree and
just go to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the market, you'll see the homemade ice cream tent where
the putt-putt-putt of a John Deere tractor engine turns the churn.
If you're lucky, it will be churning up a creamy frozen treat
called apple pie.
</P>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN MUSTS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to hang your hat: The Waverly Inn is known for its
afternoon social hours on the veranda and enormous breakfasts. The
three-story inn with two broad verandas has 14 rooms and one suite
named for mountain wildflowers. The cookie jar is never empty, and
there's always a freshly baked cake waiting when you come in at
night. Innkeepers John and Diane Sheiry and Darla Olmstead, who
live on the premises, make sure your visit is going well. Rates:
$109-$195. 783 N. Main St. 1-800-537-8195; www.waverlyinn.com.
</P>
<P>
   Next door to the Waverly is the Claddagh Inn, a AAA
three-diamond property that brings a bit of Ireland to Main Street.
Breakfasts are bounteous here, too. 755 N. Main St. 1-800-225-4700;
www.claddaghinn.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tying on the feedbag: Try Cypress Cellar for a taste of
southern Louisiana (321-C N. Main St., 828-692-6333), Sinbad for
exotic decor and Middle Eastern fare (202 S. Washington St.,
828-696-2039) or the upscle Expressions for creative American
cuisine (114 N. Main St., 828-693-
</P>
<P>
   8516).
</P>
<P>
   For lunch, we love Days Gone By, an old-fashioned ice cream soda
parlor that serves breakfast, sandwiches, burgers and homemade
chili. 303 N. Main St. 828-693-9056.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Best place to go when the sun goes down: Unless something's
happening downtown, I doubt I'd be inclined to leave the front
porch of the Waverly Inn. But I could be talked into taking a pint
at Hannah Flanagan's Pub, which has live music Thursday and
Saturday nights (300 N. Main St., 828-696-1665).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Great place to see fall color: Five miles from downtown at the
end of Laurel Park Highway is Jump Off Rock Park. So named because
legend has it that a young Cherokee maiden jumped off when she
learned her lover had been killed in battle, Jump Off Rock is a
scenic overlook that provides a panoramic view of the Blue Ridge
and Pisgah mountain ranges. 1-800-828-4244.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to get crafty: Downtown is a mecca for crafts _ both
traditional and contemporary. As you stroll along North Main
Street, pop into Touchstone Gallery, Wickwire Fine Art/Folk Art,
Brightwater Art Glass, Sweet Memories Gallery, Four Seasons
Crafters and Carolina Mountain Artists.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bringing home a taste of the mountains: Apples, apples
everywhere _ with Red Delicious, Golden Delicious and Rome Beauty
being the most plentiful. Drive east out of town on U.S. 64 to the
apple houses. Harvest season is early September through
mid-October. Or stop by the Curb Market downtown for produce, jams
and jellies, sausage biscuits, baked goods and homemade ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mountain duds: Sherman's Sports and Army Store, 126 N. Main
St. (828-693-5422), stocks great outdoor gear, rain gear,
camouflage, boots, socks and sweaters. Or outfit yourself head to
foot at Mast General Store, 527 N. Main St. (828-696-1883;
www.mastgeneralstore.com).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Spotted along the road: Driving east on U.S. 64, look for
Grandad's Apples in a big gray barn and note the bright green John
Deere tractor atop a faux silo.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Other nearby fun: Listed on the National Register of Historic
Places, Historic Johnson Farm was a late-19th-century tobacco farm
that became a boardinghouse for summer tourists. The heritage
center features an 1870s farmhouse, a 1923 boardinghouse, a museum
and 10 historic buildings. Guided tours 10:30 a.m. and 1:30 p.m.
Tuesdays-Saturdays through October (Wednesdays-Saturdays,
November-March). 3346 Haywood Road, four miles north of
Hendersonville. 828-891-6585
</P>
<P>
   The newly designated 7,500-acre Dupont State Forest, managed by
the North Carolina Division of Forest Resources, is 10 miles
southwest of Hendersonville. The area features fishing on wild
streams, hunting by special permit and 55 miles of trails for
hiking, biking and horseback riding. 828-251-6509;
www.main.nc.us/eco/dsf.
</P>
<P>
   In neighboring Flat Rock, the Flat Rock Playhouse season
continues through Dec. 17. Upcoming productions: The comedy ``Here
on the Flight Path,'' Wednesday through Sept. 3; the musical ``West
Side Story,'' Sept. 13-Oct. 1; the mystery ``The Woman in Black,''
Oct. 4-22; the comedy ``A Tuna Christmas,'' Nov. 8-19; and ``The
Littlest Angel'' and ``The Gift of the Magi,'' Nov. 29-Dec. 17.
828-693-0731.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Take I-85 north to U.S. 25 on the western
outskirts of Greenville, S.C. Travel north about 40 miles directly
into Hendersonville. It's about a 3 1/2-hour drive.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Visitors Information Center, 1-800-828-4244;
www.historichendersonville.org.
</P>
<P>
   Paula Crouch Thrasher writes for the Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
