<DOCNO> NYT20000819.0121 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6581 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TRAVEL-LITTLESWISS20-     08-19 1907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-LITTLESWISS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A mountain retreat, Swiss style
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 20.
 &HT;    By Michael Skube
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLE SWITZERLAND, N.C. _ In the summer of 1909, three men and
their mules poked their way through virgin forest to the grassy
uplands where mountain folk had lived isolated for generations. One
of the three was a Charlotte lawyer looking into investment
possibilities, and the other two were real estate agents showing
him the neighborhood. They reached a plateau atop Grassy Mountain,
and the lawyer, a man named Heriot Clarkson, looked out upon the
valley below.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Ninety years later, not far from where Clarkson and his guides
stood, the parking lot of the Switzerland Inn is crowded with
sedans of substance _ Lincoln Town Cars, Cadillacs, Jaguars.
License plates one weekend last month were about evenly divided _
half from North Carolina, half from Florida, South Carolina,
Georgia, even Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Other places in the North Carolina mountains are better-known,
but none are like this faux-alpine hideaway nestled at 3,500 feet
in the southern Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our grandparents built here in the late '40s,'' Laura
Guissinger says while her sister, Ann, browses in the Grassy
Mountain book shop. They grew up in Baton Rouge, La. One still
lives there and the other lives in Louisville, Ky.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been coming here every summer since we were kids,''
Laura Guissinger says.
</P>
<P>
   Now they were bringing their own families to this smallest of
dots on the North Carolina map. It has a post office, only a
handful of shops and eateries within walking distance and offers no
night life to speak of. But it brims daily with color and
tranquillity. In the fall, especially, Little Switzerland, just off
the Blue Ridge Parkway, is a place many folks come for a long
weekend. Many come to like it so much they plan ahead, booking a
week at the Switzerland Inn or another nearby mountain lodge.
</P>
<P>
   To the west stands Mount Mitchell, highest peak east of the
Mississippi. To the south, Linville Mountain. To the east and
northeast, Table Rock and Grandfather Mountain. To the north, Roan
Mountain, where Daniel Boone left his exhausted roan horse when the
animal could carry him no farther (Boone ventured on foot and
returned the next year to find his horse rested and nourished).
</P>
<P>
   The view is the familiar one of postcards and calendars. But
they never quite capture the reality of it on a clear day _ a blue
haze resting on mountains older than the Rockies, older than the
Alps. It must have been on such a day that Heriot Clarkson looked
out upon the valley from Grassy Mountain.
</P>
<P>
   But there was something more than the view, one of the real
estate agents pointed out. Three quarters up the mountain were
seven full-flowing springs, ensuring a source of fresh water.
Clarkson was sold, and thus began a mostly peaceful commingling of
cultures _ outsiders bringing their money and manners, mountain
people receiving them with suspicion and unease.
</P>
<P>
   I'd come to Little Switzerland many times over the years,
staying at in-laws' family cottage up Bearwallow Road. This was one
of the cottages that Clarkson and his first round of investors
built, home today to descendants of Charles Duls, a law partner of
Clarkson's, and to countless generations of spiders and crawly
creatures that have never taken in the view that brings people to
the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Forty miles east of Asheville and 15 miles north of Marion,
Little Switzerland has grown beyond the intimate summer colony its
founders envisioned _ but not by much.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot busier now than it used to be _ more people, more
traffic,'' Laura Guissinger says.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. But no one coming here from Atlanta would call it
crowded. And it's anything but hurried.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just stumbled on it,'' says Trudy Hough of College Park.
She and her husband, Don, were enjoying a drive along the parkway
and looked for a room in Waynesville, N.C. When they couldn't find
one, they asked a park ranger if he knew where they might stay. He
suggested Little Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd never heard of it,'' Hough says. ``It sounded like Helen,
Ga., and I told him, `I'm from Germany and if it's anything like
Helen, I want nothing to do with it.'''
</P>
<P>
   The Houghs found a room at the Switzerland Inn, planning to
spend the night. They ended up staying two.
</P>
<P>
   ``They showed us a cabin with a wonderful view, and when we
decided we'd stay two,'' she says, ``they gave us a cabin with an
ever better view.''
</P>
<P>
   At dinner both nights, they enjoyed that view over a bottle of
Moselle wine.
</P>
<P>
   Like most people who spend any time in Little Switzerland, Trudy
Hough soon heard people recommending the Orchard at Altapass, a
restored apple-packing house that has become a community crafts
center and, on weekends, music hall. Six miles up the parkway, it's
in what once was the town of Altapass but today has come to be part
of the experience of going to Little Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw there was a little dance floor,'' Trudy Hough says,
``and I asked them, `Do you ever have music?'''
</P>
<P>
   They have it every weekend, kids and adults clicking heels to
the bluegrass that lives in these hills and hollows.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know whether the Houghs ran into 63-year-old Jack
McKinney when they were there, but he's around a lot. Descendant of
one of the oldest and most prolific mountain families in the area,
McKinney is an oral historian and part-time musician who remembers
only too well a less happy time.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was seven of us, and we had 12 half brothers and
sisters,'' he says, biting into a red and yellow Stayman apple. The
Orchard's 280 acres had become rundown when Bill and Judy Carson,
along with his sister Kit Truby, bought it several years ago. Bill
Carson, a retired IBM software manager, wanted to live a more
peaceful life and became enamored of the people and culture of the
hills.
</P>
<P>
   And the people became enamored of him. The Orchard became more
than an apple-packing plant or even a place selling artifacts to
tourists. It became a community center that brought dignity and
worth to a culture that hadn't known any. ``Things that we didn't
feel like we could talk about, they let us talk about,'' McKinney
says of the Carsons.
</P>
<P>
   The Carsons' store manager, a New Jersey native named Ann
Kernahan, came to the mountains often while attending the
University of South Carolina. She moved to Oklahoma upon
graduating, but left something of herself behind. ``I'd been
waiting 20 years to get back,'' she says. ``This is where I want to
be.''
</P>
<P>
   Listening to her, McKinney affectionately says, ``She says she's
from New Jersey, but I know that can't be true. She's a
hillbilly.''
</P>
<P>
   The acceptance is mutual, native and outsider finding in one
another more than they would have expected. In its modest way, it's
the story of the southern Appalachians. The moneyed peopled who
founded Little Switzerland had no particular interest in the
mountainfolk living in the area. A summertime retreat for their
friends and families was enough. They had no idea, beautiful as the
view was, what riches were waiting to be cultivated.
</P>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN MUSTS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to hang your hat: We stayed at the Switzerland Inn,
where the view is one of the best along the Blue Ridge Parkway.
Out-of-season rates range $95-$150 a night ($110-$180 starting in
October). The hotel closes for winter on Nov. 5. If you're on the
Blue Ridge Parkway, it's just off mile marker 334 (otherwise, off
N.C. 226A). 828-765-2153 or 1-800-654-4026; www
</P>
<P>
   .switzerlandinn.com. Also nearby: Big Lynn Lodge, 828-765-4257;
www.biglynnlodge.com. Rooms are $85-$129 through Nov. 5, when it
closes for the winter.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tying on the feedbag: The Chalet Restaurant at the Switzerland
Inn offers a fine buffet at breakfast and dinner, and the
Switzerland Cafe, just down the hill, is superb for lunch, offering
delicious soups and sandwiches, salads and entrees. And the
desserts are scrumptiously rich. (It's closed for dinner.) The
excellent beers from Highlands Brewing Co. of Asheville are
available at both places, along with respectable wines.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Best place to go when the sun goes down: By mid-October, dusk
is settling in by 6 p.m., leaving little more to see. The
Switzerland Inn's restaurant and bar are among the few choices.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Great place to see fall color: Anywhere along the Blue Ridge
Parkway.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to get crafty: The Orchard at Altapass is a place to
spend half a day, crafts being only one reason. Other
arts-and-crafts places are plentiful, especially in nearby
Burnsville and Bakersville. Among those worthy of checking out:
</P>
<P>
   Emerald Village and North Carolina Mining Museum. Prospect for
your own gems _ aquamarine, beryl, smoky quartz, even emeralds _ at
this underground mine. McKinney Mine Road and Crabtree Creek Road,
Little Switzerland. 828-765-6463.
</P>
<P>
   Blue Ridge Soap Shed. A new shop that lets folks see how soap
(everything from oatmeal to olive) is made. And if you have
particular skin condition, they'll suggest a soap best for you.
Six-tenths of a mile north of Gillespie Gap exit off Blue Ridge
Parkway at 179 Meadow View Road, Spruce Pine. 828-765-6001.
</P>
<P>
   Barking Spider Pottery. Stoneware pottery. 1446 Conley Ridge
Road, Penland. 828-765-2670 or 1-888-765-2670;
www.penlandpottery.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bringing home a taste of the mountains: Again, the Orchard at
Altapass. Apples and peaches, jams and sourwood honey.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Best CD for those winding roads: Guitar great Doc Watson
captures much of the flavor, but so do many others. You might, like
me, prefer the quiet of just observing.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Other nearby fun:+ We never go to Little Switzerland without
going to Carolina Hemlocks, a National Forest Service Recreation
Area on N.C. 80, about seven miles northwest of the parkway from
Buck Creek Gap. Kids and some adults ply the (mild) rapids of the
South Toe river in innertubes, leap and dive off rocks and
generally frolic in ways city kids no longer do. But the waters are
cool even in summer.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny used and rare bookstore Grassy Mountain Shop, two doors
down from the Switzerland Cafe, is one of the better ones in the
Southeast. 828-765-9070; www.johnsonc(at)mitchell
</P>
<P>
   .main.nc.us. (The store plans to close for the winter in late
October.)
</P>
<P>
   At the Orchard at Altapass, fiddlin' and hayrides are a popular
favorite. In addition, there is Grandfather Mountain, Linville
Caverns, the Linville Gorge Wilderness Area, Lake James State Park
_ all nearby.  &QR;  Directions: Take I-85 north to I-24 west at
Greenville-Spartanburg. Follow I-24 to Asheville and pick up I-40
east. That will take you to Marion, where you'll exit north onto
U.S. 221. Follow it about 15 miles to N.C. 226A, where you turn
left and wind your way up a mountain. It's a five-hour drive from
downtown Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   A more scenic route takes I-85 north to I-985 through Toccoa to
U.S. 23-441. This takes you into North Carolina. At Dillsboro, turn
right onto U.S. 23-74 and drive east toward Asheville. Pick up U.S.
70 in Asheville and drive east through Swannanoa and Old Fort to
U.S. 221. Turn left and drive to N.C. 226A.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Mitchell County Chamber of Commerce,
828-765-9483; www.mitchell-county.com.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Skube writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
