<HEADER>
A6582 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TRAVEL-MNT-FESTS20-CO     08-19 1071
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MNT-FESTS20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Finding fun at the peaks
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 20.
 &HT;    By Michelle Brooks
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEPTEMBER
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sept. 1-2: Smoky Mountain Folk Festival, Waynesville, N.C.
Featuring two nights of the traditional music and dance of the
Southern Appalachian region at Stuart Auditorium at Lake Junaluska.
Also, Children's Tent and Jamming Under the Big Tent each night.
828-452-1688
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sept. 1-4: 54th Annual North Carolina Apple Festival,
Hendersonville, N.C. An apple orchard tour; apple pancake
breakfasts; downtown sidewalk sales; a street fair with arts and
crafts, food and apple vendors; 19th annual Mineral and Gem
Spectacular; 10K road race; 15th Annual Apple Country Bike Tour;
King Apple Parade; and street dance. 828-697-4557.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sept. 2: Third annual Chicken Festival, Sautee, Ga. Food, fun,
history and art surrounding North Georgia's chicken industry, at
the Sautee-Nacoochee Arts and Community Center. 706-878-3300.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sept. 9: Mountain Music Festival, Blairsville, Ga. Celebrate
Appalachian music, including dulcimer and bluegrass, while
overlooking a scenic lake at Vogel State Park. 706-745-2628.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sept. 10- Nov. 4: 30th annual Oktoberfest, Helen, Ga. Lots of
food, beer, oompah music dancing and bands. Thursdays-Saturdays in
September. Mondays-Saturdays in October. 706-878-2181.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sept. 15-17: Heritage Weekend, Folk Art Center, Asheville,
N.C. Mountain music, dance, storytelling, historic craft
demonstrations and the 20th annual Gee Haw Whimmy Diddle contest.
828-298-7928.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sept. 15-Oct. 31: Fourth annual Smoky Mountain Harvest
Festival, Pigeon Forge, Tenn. This festival adds to the pleasure of
leaf-watchers with music, arts and crafts and food. 1-800-251-9100,
www.pigeon-forge
</P>
<P>
   .tn.us.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sept. 16: Dixie Land Specials, Chattanooga. The Tennessee
Valley Railroad vintage rail excursion features the steam-powered
Rails to Wings Special running to the LaFayette Airport for an air
show with classic airplanes. 423-894-8028.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sept. 16-17: 20th annual Roan Mountain State Park's Fall
Festival, Roan Mountain, Tenn. Mountain fair features arts and
crafts, music, flint-napping demonstrations and more. 423-772-0190,
www.tnstateparks.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sept. 16-17: First Annual North Georgia Wildlife Art Festival,
Blue Ridge, Ga. More than 75 wildlife artists from throughout the
Southeast display original works. 706-632-2144.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sept. 16-17, 23-24: Apple Pickin' Jubilee, Ellijay. Pick your
own apples, visit the petting zoo, take a wagon ride and enjoy
food, entertainment and a haunted house at Hillcrest Orchards.
</P>
<P>
   706-273-3838.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sept. 21-24: World Chicken Festival, London, Ky. Presented by
the county where Col. Harlan Sanders opened his first Kentucky
Fried Chicken outlet, fest features a display of the world's
largest skillet (filled with frying chicken, of course).
1-800-348-0095.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sept. 29-30: Townsend Heritage Festival and Old Timers Day,
Townsend, Tenn. A celebration of mountain culture, including
bluegrass music, arts and crafts, and storytelling.
</P>
<P>
   1-800-525-6834, www
</P>
<P>
   .smokymountains.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sept. 29-Oct. 29: Harvest Celebration, Pigeon Forge, Tenn.
Fest at Dollywood theme park features handmade crafts, fall foods
and colorful autumn decorations. Coincides with the Southern Gospel
Jubilee. 1-800-365-5996; www.dollywood.com .
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Sept. 30-Oct. 29 (weekends only): Michaelmas English Harvest
Fair, Asheville, N.C. Biltmore House hosts fest with mountain
music, arts and crafts, food and live jazz at the winery.
1-800-543-2961.
</P>
<P>
   OCTOBER
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 4-22: 25th annual Gatlinburg Craftsmen's Fair,
Gatlinburg, Tenn. Features demonstrations of quilting, wood
carving, pottery, dulcimer making, candle dipping, stained glass,
metal work and basket weaving. Music daily. 865-436-7479;
www.craftsmenfair.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 6-7, 13-14, 20-21, 27-31: Tweetsie Ghost Train Halloween
Festival, Blowing Rock, N.C. Experience a haunted house, a trip
through the black hole, and a scary ride on the ghost train.
828-264-9061; www.tweetsie.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 7: Forest Festival Day, Cradle of Forestry, Brevard, N.C.
Celebrate forest heritage with mountain music, food, crafts, live
animals and a lumberjack competition. 828-877-3130.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 7: Fifth annual Heart of Tennessee Scottish Celebration,
Murfreesboro, Tenn. Gathering of clans, piping, highland dancing,
Celtic music, Scottish country dancing, food and fun. 615-848-9193.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 7-8: Georgia Marble Festival, Jasper. Features tours of
open-pit marble quarries, sculpture, fine arts exhibit, crafts,
music and food. 706-692-5600.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 7, 14, 21, 22, 28, 29 and Nov. 4: Dixie Land Specials,
Chattanooga. The Tennessee Valley Railroad presents the 32nd annual
steam-powered Autumn Leaf Specials from Chattanooga to Summerville.
423-894-8028.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 13-15, 20-22: 31st annual Sorghum Festival, Blairsville.
Celebrates the ancient art of cooking sweet syrup from sorghum
cane. Features handmade crafts, mountain music and clogging, and
old-time games and contests. 706-745-4745.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 14-15, 21-22: 29th annual Georgia Apple Festival,
Ellijay, Ga. Arts and crafts, live entertainment, food and lots of
apples. Parade and antique car show on Oct. 14. 706-635-7400.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 19-22: Craft Fair of the Southern Highlands, Asheville,
N.C. More than 170 booths of fine crafts by members of the Southern
Highland Craft Guild. Demonstrations of blacksmithing, woodcarving
and flameworked beads. 828-298-7928; www.southernhighlandguild.org.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 21-22, 28-29: 31st annual Mountain Harvest Sale, Blue
Ridge, Ga. Features antiques, mountain art, crafts and food, at the
Farmers Market. 706-374-2335.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 21: Valle Country Fair, Valle Crucis, N.C. Features arts
and crafts, food, and a main stage where musicians, cloggers and
storytellers perform throughout the day. 828-963-4609.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oct. 28-29: Southeastern Animal Fiber Fair, Asheville, N.C.
Featuring hundreds of animals such as llamas, alpacas, Angora goats
and rabbits and many breeds of sheep at the Western North Carolina
Agricultural Center. Workshops on spinning, weaving, felting and
dyeing. Also, vendors with spinning wheels, fleeces, handspun yarn,
looms, books and handmade garments. 828-891-2810.
</P>
<P>
   _Compiled by Michelle C. Brooks
</P>
