</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Biltmore view from the top takes in turrets, gargoyles
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 20.
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASHEVILLE, N.C. _ If you're heading here to look at the fall
leaves, one of your best viewing sites might be from the roof of
the Biltmore House.
</P>
<P>
   No kidding. The roof. The guided 75-minute Rooftop Tour will
take you up amid the turrets and gargoyles, where you can get a
panoramic view of the gardens, the French Broad River and Mount
Pisgah.
</P>
<P>
   You also can get a closer look at the architectural, structural
and technological details that architect Richard Morris Hunt
incorporated into Biltmore House. These include tall dormers over
vertically linked windows, gothic-style spiraling sta
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
