<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GODZILLA-TIMELINE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Godzilla, still a thrilla
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   The king of the monsters is back. In ``Godzilla 2000,'' which
opened Friday in metro Atlanta, there's no Matthew Broderick, no
New York and, best of all, no pansy lizard. The Japanese have
returned the series to its original _ and often campy _ sci-fi
glory in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Godzilla, King of the Monsters'' (1956)
</P>
<P>
   Forget stop-motion animation. God-zilla, aroused from the
ocean's depths by H-bomb testing, is an actor (Haruo Nakajima) in a
100-pound suit. The get-up looks like a T. rex with dorsal fins.
</P>
<P>
   ``King Kong vs. Godzilla'' (1963)
</P>
<P>
   The ultimate ape gets his comeuppance. It's one of about a dozen
flicks where Godzilla battles formidable foes _ like Mothra,
Megalon and the robot Mechagodzilla.
</P>
<P>
   ``Godzilla 1985''
</P>
<P>
   Here comes that other big guy again. Raymond Burr, awkwardly
plopped into the '56 film release to entice U.S. audiences, returns
with a beard and more bogus oratory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Godzilla'' (1998)
</P>
<P>
   A botched U.S. effort with unending marketing of toys. Die-hard
fans dissed it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Godzilla 2000''
</P>
<P>
   The new Japanese film sets the monster's height at 170 feet.
From the mid-'50s to 1975, he was 164 feet tall. From 1984 to 1989,
he was 262 feet, and in the '90s, he was 328 feet.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-00 1326EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
