<DOCNO> NYT20000819.0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6589 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-REL-LOTZ20-COX     08-19 2440
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REL-LOTZ20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Graham's daughter one of the country's foremost Bible teachers
 &HT;    By Gayle White
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RALEIGH _ A portable potty in the yard of the traditional
red-brick ranch accommodates workers on a two-month remodeling
project that has stretched into eight months. Inside, on the floor
of a light-filled family room, a flat-faced white Persian cat with
drippy black markings around his eyes sleeps near his mistress's
feet. He is known both as Xerxes, for the historic King of Persia,
and Tammy Faye, for the former PTL hostess. A washing machine chugs
rhythmically in the background.
</P>
<P>
   In the midst of all this, Anne Graham Lotz calmly submits to an
interview. Last week, she was a featured speaker at a gathering in
Amsterdam of 10,000 evangelists from around the world. Today, by 9
a.m., she is on her third load of laundry. Next weekend, she'll be
in the spotlight again, leading a revival at Atlanta's Philips
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   As the second daughter of evangelist Billy Graham and his wife,
Ruth Bell Graham, Lotz is used to a life that mixes the monumental
and the mundane. While her father rubbed his angular elbows with
royals and presidents, the five little Grahams exchanged typical
siblings' blows and insults in the mountain community of Montreat.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Lotz, 52, has gained a reputation of her own as one of the
country's foremost Bible teachers and as the best preacher in her
illustrious family.
</P>
<P>
   With her mother's elegant bone structure and sharp sense of
humor and her father's height and intensity, she draws in and holds
a congregation, telling them about ``Jee-sus'' in a soft, rich
Southern drawl.
</P>
<P>
   But whereas her father preaches the same message repeatedly _
eternal life comes through Jesus Christ _ Lotz delves into
Scripture, extracting volumes from a few verses.
</P>
<P>
   She compares her role to that of her father and his heir
apparent, her brother, Franklin: ``Daddy and Franklin are
obstetricians, bringing the babies into the family of God. I take
them, once they're in the family, and help them to grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Became 'child of God' early
</P>
<P>
   Lotz knew God loved her ``from the day I was born,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   While her father traveled the world as the most famous Baptist
since ``John the,'' his children sat on the third pew of the little
Montreat Presbyterian church with their grandparents, who had
served as missionaries to China.
</P>
<P>
   ``My grandmother always put a little slice of bread in her
pocketbook and Luden's cough drops,'' Lotz recalled. ``And she let
us draw on the bulletins.''
</P>
<P>
   The church and the community were close-knit. ``It was full of
retired missionaries who loved us,'' she said. ``They weren't
impressed at all with Daddy being an important person in their
midst.''
</P>
<P>
   But some of the seasonal visitors to the mountains were _ and
peered in the windows of the Graham house.
</P>
<P>
   The little Grahams were not above taking advantage of the
tourists. Once, according to family lore, big sister Gigi talked
Anne into helping her create a makeshift tollbooth by stretching a
rope across the road and charging people to pass.
</P>
<P>
   The attention made Lotz self-conscious, she said. ``I think I
retreated a little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   With the world's best known evangelist as a father, Lotz
committed herself to the Christian faith at age 5 or 6 through the
Cecil B. DeMille film ``King of Kings.'' When she wept at the
Crucifixion scene, her mother recognized it as religious conviction
and prayed with her. ``At that time, I became a child of God,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   By her senior year in high school, Lotz struggled with how to be
herself when, as one of the ultimate preacher's kids, she was being
scrutinized and judged. ``I decided at that point to please God,''
she said. ``It's a very freeing thing to live your life to please
one person.''
</P>
<P>
   This did not mean being boring. She lightened her hair and
dabbled in fashion modeling, hoping one day to make it a career.
</P>
<P>
   During one of his stays at home, her father realized his little
girl was growing up and had begun dating. He decided to take
matters into his own hands by calling the Fellowship of Christian
Athletes to try to set her up with the right kind of young man.
Steve Sloan, former star quarterback at the University of Alabama
and later college football coach, turned him down. Danny Lotz
didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Lotz, 6 feet 7, was a former University of North Carolina
basketball star who had finished dental school and was completing a
stint in the Air Force. He was in his late 20s. She was 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``It never occurred to me this was something that would develop
into anything,'' she said. ``I was just going out with him to
please Daddy.''
</P>
<P>
   A severe case of mononucleosis kept her from going away that
fall to Wheaton College in Illinois, where her parents had met.
Danny Lotz visited her at home every weekend. A year later, in
1966, they married in the same Montreat chapel where Ruth Bell had
become Mrs. Billy Graham.
</P>
<P>
   Domestic deeds
</P>
<P>
   Danny Lotz, son of a Baptist New York street preacher, was
living in Chapel Hill, establishing a chapter of the Fellowship of
Christian Athletes there, and setting up a dental practice in
Raleigh.
</P>
<P>
   When their first child, Jonathan, born in 1970, was a toddler,
the family moved into their current brick ranch home in Raleigh.
Jonathan was joined by two sisters, Morrow, named after her mother,
Anne Morrow Graham, and Billy Graham's mother Morrow Coffee Graham,
and Rachel-Ruth, named for Ruth Bell Graham.
</P>
<P>
   By 1976, Anne Lotz was frustrated with a life of ``small talk
and small toys and small clothes and small sticky fingerprints.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Graham had kept open Bibles around the family's mountain
home to sustain her through the single-parent days when her husband
was taking the Gospel to the world. Lotz knew she needed to delve
into the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   She wanted to take a course through Bible Study Fellowship, an
in-depth nondenominational program. ``Nobody would start it,'' she
said. ``I decided if nobody else would, I would.''
</P>
<P>
   Busier than ever as she prepared for class week by week, ``I was
a better mother,'' she said, ``more patient. I was growing on the
inside in my relationship with God.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She was a wonderful mom,'' said daughter Rachel-Ruth Wright,
who works with her mother's ministry. ``She wasn't the kind of mom
who's froufrou and writes little notes in your lunch. She taught us
what's important_God's love. What you see in public is exactly what
she is in private.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, all three children are Christian and married to
Christians. Lotz enjoys her grown children and revels in small
domestic deeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's the only person I know who still makes pie crust from
scratch,'' says longtime friend Dody Ragsdale.
</P>
<P>
   Not always welcomed
</P>
<P>
   Lotz gave up teaching her Bible study in 1988 to found AnGeL
Ministries, which takes its name from her initials and her sense of
calling. In the ensuing years, she has written several books and
traveled the world on speaking engagements.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember one time in Brazil we were sharing a room and I
heard some wild knocking in the bathroom,'' recalled Lotz's
assistant and confidante Helen George. ``When I went in there, she
was throwing shoes at cockroaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Another time, in South Africa, George was slipping down the hall
in her bathrobe with uncombed hair and an unmade-up face to join
Lotz for an early morning cup of coffee from the pot Lotz takes on
trips. Lotz threw open the door _ and greeted her unkempt friend
with a camera flash.
</P>
<P>
   Lotz has chalked up some significant achievements as the only
woman speaker at numerous international events. She has spoken on
every continent except Antarctica but, as a woman, has not been
universally welcomed.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, the Oklahoma Baptist Convention rescinded an invitation
after some pastors complained about being addressed by a woman. On
another occasion, some pastors near the front of an ecumenical
gathering conspicuously rose and turned their backs to Lotz as she
stood up to speak.
</P>
<P>
   The rejection sent her to the Scriptures.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Gospel of Matthew, the resurrected Jesus sent
Mary Magdalene to ``go and tell my brothers to go to Galilee; there
they will see me.''
</P>
<P>
   Lotz concluded that a prohibition against women in ministry in
the Book of Timothy cited by opponents of women in ministry,
including her denomination, the Southern Baptist Convention,
specifically refers to women speaking from a position of authority
over men.
</P>
<P>
   Like Mary Magdalene, she said, ``I feel I am commanded and
commissioned to share my testimony and God's Word. I do it from the
authority of Scripture, not from a position of authority over
men.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is significant that here you have a woman rising to
prominence in a subculture that, on the whole, looks askance at
women preachers or religious leaders,'' said Randall Balmer,
chairman of the religion department at Barnard College and producer
of a public television documentary on Billy Graham. ``The fact that
she doesn't bill herself as a preacher or a pastor may make her
more effective as a wedge, sort of an advance guard.''
</P>
<P>
   Tough times
</P>
<P>
   Just as Lotz trusted in God to lead her down the right path in
her ministry, she has relied on prayer and Scripture through the
tough times of family life.
</P>
<P>
   There was the miscarriage after Jonathan's birth. ``I look back
now and if I had had that baby, I wouldn't have Morrow,'' she said.
``God takes away and he gives. He does it so perfectly. You look
beyond the roadblock _ that's not the end.''
</P>
<P>
   In her most recent book called, like her revival series, ``Just
Give Me Jesus'' (Word Publishing, $19.99), she frankly describes a
time when she was disillusioned with her marriage: ``I will never
forget that panicked, trapped feeling as I knelt in prayer with
tears streaming down my face, desperately pleading with the Lord
for help.''
</P>
<P>
   Through focus on her faith, she recaptured the romance.
</P>
<P>
   Lotz said she shared her personal feelings to help others. ``I
think a lot of people opt to get out of a marriage at that point
because they feel there is no hope,'' she said. ``I know from
personal experience there is.''
</P>
<P>
   She applied her faith in more drastic circumstances two years
ago when Jonathan was diagnosed with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Apparently cancer is part of God's plan for your life,'' Lotz
counseled her 28-year-old son. ``God's purpose for us is not to be
healthy and wealthy and problem-free. God's purpose for us is to
glorify him.''
</P>
<P>
   They prayed that Jonathan's cancer could be used to glorify God.
</P>
<P>
   After surgery and radiation treatment, the cancer is in
remission.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like God gives you what you need when you need it,''
Lotz said. ``I would think I could never face something like that
with one of my children.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, she is facing the aging and declining health of both
parents. Her father, who has Parkinson's disease, was unable to
make the trip to Amsterdam for the evangelists' conference and was
too weak even to deliver a message by satellite.
</P>
<P>
   Lotz was with her father when he underwent treatment in June.
``It was so precious to be needed,'' she said. ``I had never seen
my daddy in that kind of weakness. He had always been so strong I
never felt like I could do anything for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ruth Graham had back surgery in Raleigh and stayed in the Lotz
home to recuperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like one of the highlights of my life was caring for
her,'' Lotz said.
</P>
<P>
   'Ministry all around us'
</P>
<P>
   Asked how she decided to undertake the latest phase of her
ministry, a series of five revivals in different cities including
Atlanta this year, Lotz replied simply, ``God leads.''
</P>
<P>
   For some time, she said, she had not been satisfied with only
accepting speaking engagements arranged by other people. Sometimes
she felt less than fully effective. Occasionally she felt used to
help accomplish a hidden agenda.
</P>
<P>
   After some false starts, including a dispute with a professional
event company that insisted she charge admission, Lotz looked into
staging the events herself. She asked God whether that was the
right thing to do.
</P>
<P>
   She found the answer in her daily devotional that directed her
to the story of Jesus walking on water. When his disciple Peter
wanted to join him, Jesus commanded him, ``Come.'' She believed
Jesus was telling her through the verses to strike out on unknown
waters.
</P>
<P>
   With two revivals down and three to go, ``we're on our way.''
</P>
<P>
   With no admission fees, the events have yet to break even
financially. ``But all our bills are paid,'' Lotz said. ``I feel
like if God wants us to continue, he'll bring us the money.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she has ``no idea'' what else God has in store for her,
but she's sure it will be larger and more exciting than anything
she could conceive in her own mind.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, she continues to travel and speak whenever she
feels the circumstances are right. She has made friends with the
bell captains who check luggage at the Raleigh-Durham airport, the
security guards there and the people behind the ticket counters.
</P>
<P>
   She is constantly aware that any encounter may be arranged by
God.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can go to Amsterdam and say God has me there to speak to
10,000 evangelists,'' she said. ``But maybe God's purpose isn't
only to have me there, but to have me speak to somebody on the
plane. Ministry is all around us.''
</P>
<P>
   ANNE GRAHAM LOTZ FILE
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Born: May 21, 1948, in Asheville, N.C., second daughter of
Billy and Ruth Bell Graham
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Married: Sept. 2, 1966, to dentist Dr. Daniel Lotz
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Children: Jonathan (1970), Morrow Lotz Reitmeier (1972),
Rachel-Ruth Lotz Wright (1974)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Religious affiliation: Raised Presbyterian; Southern Baptist
as an adult
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Professional activities: Founded AnGeL Ministries in 1988;
sponsoring Just Give Me Jesus revivals, 2000
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Books: ``The Vision of His Glory: Finding Hope Through the
Revelation of Jesus Christ'' (Word Publishing, 1996); ``God's
Story: Finding Meaning for Your Life in Genesis'' (Word Publishing,
1997); ``Just Give Me Jesus,'' (Word Publishing, 2000)
</P>
<P>
   JUST GIVE ME JESUS
</P>
<P>
   Revival led by Anne Graham Lotz with Kay Arthur and Jill Briscoe
at Philips Arena. Aug. 25, 7-9 p.m., and Aug. 26, 8 a.m.-5 p.m.
Free. Information: 404-253-3188
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  What: Revival led by Anne Graham Lotz (above) with Kay Arthur
and Jill Briscoe
</P>
