<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6591 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TRAVEL-MAGGIEVALLEY20     08-19 1648
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TRAVEL-MAGGIEVALLEY20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smokies: Taking paradise by the reins
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 20.
 &HT;    By Doug Hamilton
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAGGIE VALLEY, N.C._ The Smoky Mountains look different from the
back of a horse.
</P>
<P>
   Lovelier. Less familiar. These prolific peaks, viewed so many
times before _ through a dusty windshield on road trips to
Asheville, from hiking trails in the Pisgah National Forest,
through the gaudy neon glare of Cherokee _ seem to radiate fresh
beauty.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe it's the pungent smell and unhurried gait of Noble, a
14-year-old draft- and quarter-horse mix. Maybe it's the
refreshingly cool temperature, which rarely climbs above 75 degrees
at this elevation. Maybe it's the company, an affable band of
strangers who've gathered for a bit of riding and relaxation.
</P>
<P>
   Or maybe it's because this place, the 1,000-acre Cataloochee
Ranch, is so close to paradise you half expect to enter it through
pearly gates.
</P>
<P>
   Nuzzling up to the edge of Great Smoky Mountains National Park,
the ranch sprawls over three peaks, the tallest of which, Hemphill
Bald, rises 5,600 feet above sea level. Its horse pastures cling to
the side of Moody Top, the second highest peak, while guests bunk
down in cabins and lodges on Fie Top. Earth-tone steeds stand out
against the vast green of Moody Top's rising meadows, grazing high
above the stable roof.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to forget where we are, just a three-mile uphill
drive from Maggie Valley, sort of the Myrtle Beach of Western North
Carolina. On the town's ultra-commercialized U.S. 19 strip you'll
find the scruffy theme park Ghost Town in the Sky, along with
myriad mini-golf courses, go-cart tracks and souvenir shacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a different world _ you don't see any signs of
civilization,'' says Ellie Roemer, 63, of the ranch's bucolic
setting.
</P>
<P>
   A retired real estate agent from Tryon, N.C., Roemer and her
husband, Lee, 64, are spending some quality time here with their
son Glenn, daughter-in-law Ines and grandson Dominic, visiting from
Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, a retired veterinarian, loves the mild climate and relaxed
pace. ``You can breathe deep here,'' he marvels.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta native Tom Alexander and his wife Judith opened the
ranch in 1939, after a three-year run with another horse haven in
nearby Cataloochee Valley. Alexander, who studied forestry at the
University of Georgia, was smitten with the Smokies at a young age.
``He wanted to figure out a way to live on top of a mountain and
make a living,'' says daughter Alice Aumen, 62.
</P>
<P>
   Aumen and other members of the Alexander brood ran it after the
patriarch died in 1972, and management responsibility recently
passed to her son Alex, 31.
</P>
<P>
   The all-in-the-family feeling extends to the guests. Young
couples with children mix amiably here with groups of singles and
seniors. Kids frolic over the grounds, playing horseshoes and touch
football. Other activities include wagon rides, fishing, hiking and
cycling.
</P>
<P>
   Meals are belt-loosening affairs. One night we gorged on
barbecue ribs, corn on the cob and banana pudding, only to wake up
the next morning to a bounteous breakfast of eggs, bacon, sausage
and pancakes. Aumen urges weight watchers not to worry about the
waistline. With a sly smile, she quotes her mother (who died in
1997) as saying, ``calories don't live up here.''
</P>
<P>
   After-dinner entertainment ranges from bluegrass concerts to
presentations by wildlife experts and Native American folklorists.
Local naturalist Rob Gudger and his timber wolves are a favorite
with youngsters, who squeal with delight when he brings the beasts
up close for some frisky face-licking.
</P>
<P>
   The big draw, of course, is the horses. Cataloochee's stable can
accommodate a wide range of riders, from skittish beginners to old
hands. The only restrictions: You have to be at least 6 years old
and weigh 55 to 225 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'll get a horse that will challenge me,'' says Brenda
Dempsey, 43, of Greenville, S.C. An avid rider since she was a
teenager, Dempsey has come back to the ranch for the second time in
two years with husband Steve and 12-year-old daughter JenniLynn.
``At a lot of places, they'll only allow you to walk in a line. I
can go beyond a walk here.''
</P>
<P>
   Novices needn't fret. There are beginner rides that proceed in a
reassuringly dawdling, head-to-tail fashion. The Roemers don't
consider themselves serious riders _ ``We're retired, we're not
serious about anything,'' jokes Lee _ but they quite enjoyed their
slow morning ride up Hemphill Bald, though Lee admits to a little
soreness afterwards. ``I'm glad I brought the Ibuprofen,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The Hemphill Bald ride, one of four routes on the ranch, may be
the most breathtaking _ a steep, winding climb that the unflappable
Noble handles with ease. Ambling past dense thickets of
rhododendron, over trickling streams and through a herd of bulls,
our group ascends to the peak, pausing for a rest under a crooked
buckeye tree.
</P>
<P>
   The peak drops away into layer upon layer of mountains that fade
into the horizon. Far below us we can see the rooftops of the ranch
cabins. The air is still, interrupted only by an occasional snuff
from one of the horses, idly dozing at their hitching post.
</P>
<P>
   The pause stretches on. None of us seems to want to leave. All
that awaits us below is real life, with its deadlines and
appointments, its headlight blare and construction-site cacophony.
Who can blame us for lingering?
</P>
<P>
   MOUNTAIN MUSTS
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to hang your hat: The Cataloochee Ranch can accommodate
65 guests; rooms in the main house and Silverbell Lodge rent for
$145-$210 per couple, cabins are $195-$275 for two, $385 for four.
(Single accommodations are $140.) Breakfast and dinner are
included, lunch is available for an additional charge. Half-day
horse rides are $40, full-day rides $90, for guests.
</P>
<P>
   Weekends in October, typically the busiest month, are sold out,
but some rooms and cabins are available weekdays. The 2000 season
ends Nov. 26, when the horses are sent to Charleston for the
winter. The ranch reopens for ski season Dec. 15, offering the
closest lodgings to the adjacent Cataloochee Ski Area.
1-800-868-1401, www.cataloochee-ranch.com.
</P>
<P>
   Less picturesque, but still cute, are Mountain Joy Cottages,
just off Soco Road/U.S. 19. No horses here, but there is a covered
pool and trout pond, and the location offers easy access to Maggie
Valley's amusements. $130-$185 a night, $840-$1,225 a week. 121
Setzer Cove Road, Maggie Valley. 1-888-926-1257,
www.mountainjoycottages.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Tying on the feedbag: Barbecue lovers should haul their
booties to Butts on the Creek for a heaping helping of sliced or
diced pork served with a variety of sauces, from sweet to spicy to
vinegary. 1584 Soco Road/U.S. 19, Maggie Valley. 828-926-7885.
</P>
<P>
   For a romantic night out, try J. Arthur's, a semi-upscale steak
and seafood restaurant that serves up prime rib and local trout, as
well as pasta, lamb chops and ribs. Entrees $13.95-$24.95. 2843
Soco Road/U.S. 19, Maggie Valley. 828-926-1817.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Best place to go when the sun goes down: The two liveliest
nightspots in Maggie Valley are alcohol-free. The Stompin' Ground
offers square dancing and clogging Fridays and Saturdays, May
through October. Adults $7, kids under 12, $3. 3116 Soco Road, U.S.
19. 828-926-1288.
</P>
<P>
   The Maggie Valley Opry House features bluegrass pickers Raymond
Fairchild and Josh Crowe, plus the musical comedy of Humphammer.
Adults $7, kids under 10 free. 3605 Soco Road/U.S. 19, Maggie
Valley. 828-648-7941.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Great place to see fall color: Leafers may feel intoxicated
after drinking in the brilliant hues along the Cataloochee Ranch's
horse trails. Pause for a peep at a natural cove called the Devil's
Britches, so named because many of the maple trees turn bright red.
You don't need to be an overnight ranch guest to enjoy the view _
you can book horseback rides, $45 for a half-day, $100 for a full
day.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Where to get crafty: Different Drummer Pottery showcases the
hand-thrown creations of Terance Painter, including multihued
plates, oil lamps and decanters. 2614 Soco Road/U.S. 19, Maggie
Valley, 828-926-3850.
</P>
<P>
   Craft shops and galleries line Main Street in Waynesville, 15
miles east of Maggie Valley. Drop by Twigs &AMP; Leaves (98 N. Main
St., 828-456-1940) for natural-material creations such as pottery,
woodcarvings and willow chairs. Then stroll over to Deja View
Gallery (132 N. Main St., 828-452-9787) for a look at
owner-photographer Jon D. Bowman's vivid shots of local flora and
fauna.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Bringing home a taste of the mountains: Late September brings
bushels of apples and jugs of tart cider to Maggie Mountaineer
Crafts, which will also sell pumpkins and gourds during the fall.
Try the homemade fudge, available year-round. 2394 Soco Road, U.S.
19, Maggie Valley. 828-926-3129,
www.cheta.net/maggievalley/mmcrafts.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Mountain duds: Locals swear by Mast General Store in
Waynesville; the two-story emporium stocks a mountain of outdoor
gear, including hiking boots, flannel-lined jeans, hats and gloves,
as well as sleeping bags, backpacks and tents. 63 N. Main St.
828-452-2101, www.mastgeneralstore.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: Maggie Valley is about 185 miles from Atlanta.
Take I-85 north to I-985 north, which becomes U.S. 23. Continue
through Clayton, Franklin, N.C., and Sylva, N.C., until you reach
the Maggie Valley exit, 102-B, U.S. 276. Turn left on U.S. 19 and
continue into Maggie Valley. To reach the Cataloochee Ranch, turn
right on Fie Top Mountain Road, just past Ghost Town in the Sky. Go
three miles to ranch entrance.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Haywood County Tourism Development Authority,
1-800-334-9036, www.smokeymountains.net.
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hamilton writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
