<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6607 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-ABORIGINE-ART20-COX     08-19 2056
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ABORIGINE-ART20-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Titles to the Land': Aboriginal works reveal the heart and the
soul of a native people
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, Aug. 20.
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALICE SPRINGS, Australia _ Aborigines like to say that they have
the world's oldest culture, having inhabited this continent for
more than 40,000 years. But their best-known artistic expression is
hardly prehistoric; in fact, it's younger than rock 'n' roll.
</P>
<P>
   On a hot, buggy night in 1971, Geoffrey Bardon steered his VW
van into Papunya, a bleak, treeless settlement where the government
had moved more than 1,000 Aborigines from their traditional home in
the bush. He was there to teach their children. Noticing them draw
in the red sand, he encouraged them to try a mural at the school.
Some elders volunteered to help.
</P>
<P>
   Make it authentic, Bardon insisted. ``Nothing whitefella.''
</P>
<P>
   When the mural was done, the men asked for more paint. Working
on castaway boards and, later, canvas, they set down their
ancestral stories with dot patterns and strange-looking hieroglyphs
that had been seen only in ritual sand mosaics. They poured their
hearts into it, as if by baring something of their souls they could
make Australia understand their mystical attachment to the land
they had lost to British colonization. The paintings attracted
buyers, and other artists in other settlements began to commit
their stories to canvas.
</P>
<P>
   Three decades later, the Aboriginal painting style that began in
Papunya has become one of the most evocative symbols of Australia,
its distinctive dots and squiggles seen everywhere from gift shops
to the fuselages of Qantas 747s. The abstract artwork hangs in
museums around the world and fetches hundreds of thousands of
dollars at auction. Some of the finest examples will be featured
during Sydney's Olympic Arts Festival in a retrospective at the Art
Gallery of New South Wales.
</P>
<P>
   Like ``Souls Grown Deep,'' the critically praised show of black
Southern folk art during the Atlanta Olympics, the Sydney
exhibition promises to bring wider acclaim to another flowering of
vernacular genius. Both are outsider art in the truest sense. They
emerged from the fringes of society, out of the pain and pride of a
dispossessed people, through the vision of artists who had little
formal education.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best of the dot painting is as good as any contemporary
painting,'' says Robert Hughes, the Sydney-born art critic of Time
magazine. ``The problem is that so much of it now is tourist
kitsch. But I feel conflicted even saying that, because this is
very often the only source of income these people have.''
</P>
<P>
   At their simplest level, the desert paintings are a sort of
aesthetic cartography. They describe the features of the
continent's sun-blasted interior through a system of icons thatwere
the closest thing to a written language among Australia's
indigenous people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regard these paintings as titles to the land,'' says Ken
Watson, an Aborigine who is assistant curator of Aboriginal art at
the Art Gallery of New South Wales. Indeed, some tribes have used
paintings to dramatize their land claims against the Australian
government.
</P>
<P>
   But there's more than geography at work. The most traditional
desert paintings depict ``dreamings,'' the creation parables and
collective wisdom that Aborigines pass down through the generations
in song and ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   Dreamings are considered sacred. When the first paintings
depicting them appeared in Alice Springs, the closest town of any
size to Papunya, the gallery was picketed by Aborigines who thought
the images revealed too much to the uninitiated.
</P>
<P>
   That was 1972. Back then, Alice Springs had only one art outlet.
Today, it's a virtual Taos of the Outback, the grassy scent of
fresh canvas filling more than a dozen fine-art galleries. They
share the busy main street with a mob of souvenir shops that sell
dot-painting designs on boomerangs, mouse pads and anything else a
tourist can cart home.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've probably got too many people making place mats instead
of paintings,'' grouses Daphne Williams, manager of Papunya Tula,
the artist cooperative that grew out of the first years of the
desert painting movement.
</P>
<P>
   Aboriginal art in all its guises has become a thriving business
in Australia, accounting for $200 million in annual sales by some
estimates. With counterfeiters angling for part of the action,
authorities are advising visitors to look for labels of
authenticity. Foreign backpackers have been known to pick up travel
money by dashing off faux-Aboriginal designs.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, it wouldn't have occurred to anyone to rip off
indigenous art.
</P>
<P>
   When the British arrived in the 1780s, Aborigines had been
painting and carving for eons _ some of their cave renderings
predate the ones in Europe by thousands of years. Yet the newcomers
didn't seem interested in collecting anything beyond some craftwork
and artifacts for ethnographic purposes. No art museum bothered
with the natives until well into the 20th century.
</P>
<P>
   The first Aboriginal painter to gain recognition was, tellingly,
a European-style watercolorist. Albert Namatjira's work was so
popular among white Australians that the government granted him
full citizenship in 1957, a first for an Aborigine. (It turned
around and jailed him the following year for supplying alcohol to
his relatives.)
</P>
<P>
   Things were changing by the time Bardon arrived in Papunya a
little more than a decade after Namatjira's death. Aborigines were
pressing for civil rights and land reforms. The mood was right for
an artistic statement of native pride, and 20 untutored men in the
middle of nowhere were the ones to deliver it.
</P>
<P>
   Bardon still marvels at their achievement. ``You have to realize
that Australia is a country of cultural imitation,'' he says. ``We
have McDonald's and Coca-Cola and this superficial imitation of
European art. These men, in their humble way, triumphed over that.
To see it emerge from a place of such squalor and poverty makes it
that much more amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   The artists came from different tribes and had difficult family
names that were usually shortened to monikers that could have
belonged to blues singers: Old Mick, Long Jack, Clifford Possum.
Though they have been lumped together, they had varying styles.
Some painted with the graphic simplicity of a Southern quilt.
Others wove a dense visual tapestry that could have passed for op
art. Most of them used dot patterning, a technique derived from
body paintings and ground mosaics fashioned in the sand for
dreaming ceremonies that could rock the desert for hours with
chanting and stomping.
</P>
<P>
   Dotting was crucial in making the transition to canvas, says
Margo Smith Boles, curator of the University of Virginia's
Kluge-Ruhe Aboriginal Art Collection, perhaps the largest in
America. ``Dots create the illusion of movement. When an artist
represents a sacred place with concentric circles, and then paints
dots radiating out from them, it creates a shimmering effect. You
can feel the power emanating.''
</P>
<P>
   Dot paintings don't just look different; the way they're made is
uniquely Aboriginal.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall students at Kennesaw State University got to see the
process up close as the college hosted three painters-in-residence
from Fitzroy Crossing, a small town in the Kimberly country of
northwestern Australia. Art professor Roberta Griffin watched them
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``There weren't any easels,'' she recalls. ``They laid the
canvases on the floor and walked around them as they painted. When
they were finished, we had to ask which side was up.''
</P>
<P>
   The paintings are hanging at Kennesaw State, along with the
artists' explanations of what they signify. Ngarralja Tommy May, a
former cattle hand in his mid-60s, portrayed a water hole where his
people could always find grubs and lizards that were ``really good
to eat.'' It's part of the land he grew up on _ the only land he
can paint, according to Aboriginal custom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not allowed to tell other people's stories,'' he says, by
telephone, back home in Australia. He adds that he remembers his
stay in Georgia every time he slips on the spiffy cowboy boots he
bought at Horse Town, a western wear store in Marietta.
</P>
<P>
   Ngarralja's art is in museums and private collections across
Australia. Yet his work has brought him few material comforts other
than a very used Holden station wagon. He certainly hasn't earned a
full-time living. Few Aboriginal artists do.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason is the social structure. Artists in
traditional communities are expected to spread the wealth around
their extended families.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have an almost communistic system of distribution,'' says
Tim Klingender, director of Aboriginal art for Sotheby's Australia.
``If someone catches a kangaroo, he doesn't just eat it. There's a
protocol: His father gets the tail, his mother gets a leg, his
uncle gets a leg. It's the same way if the artist makes a big sale.
He's likely to buy a four-wheel drive for the community, and the
money is gone by the afternoon.''
</P>
<P>
   The annals of Aboriginal art are full of hard luck stories. One
of the latest concerns one of the best, Johnny Warrangkula
Tjupurrula, one of the Loritja people who was a pioneer among the
Papunya artists. When Bardon met Tjupurrula, he spoke only broken
English, and that with a stutter. But when he reached for one of
the paintbrushes he kept tucked in his hatband, he was as lyrical
as an old master. In 1972, he painted a remarkable canvas that
pulses with the hypnotic detail of a van Gogh night vision. ``Water
Dreaming at Kalipinya'' sold for $150 _ a good sum for an unknown
painter _ and went into an artist's private collection in
Melbourne. It re-emerged in June when Sotheby's auctioned it to an
American collector for more than $287,000 _ a record price for an
Aboriginal painting.
</P>
<P>
   Tjupurrula didn't get a cent. Only France requires that
royalties be paid to artists when their work is resold at
appreciated prices.
</P>
<P>
   Tjupurrula painted into the '90s and earned thousands of dollars
that supported his relations and otherwise sifted through his
gifted hands like sand. Now in his 60s and almost blind with
cataracts, he lives in a government nursing home in Alice Springs
and no longer paints. When he was told of the sale, he was puzzled.
</P>
<P>
   ``He still thinks of it as his painting,'' says Liz Tepper of
Warumpi Arts, the last gallery to represent Tjupurrula. ``He
doesn't understand the processes of white culture.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet the artist is said not to be bitter _ only sad. Bardon, his
old friend and mentor, says that Tjupurrula finds it disheartening
that other Australians don't share his people's deep spiritual
connection to the land, the ultimate inspiration for all his
paintings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Johnny,'' he says, ``feels sorry for white people.''
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB: The Art Gallery of New South Wales: www.artgallery
</P>
<P>
   .nsw.gov.au
</P>
<P>
   To see contemporary Aboriginal painting offered for sale by the
Papunya Tula artists cooperative: www.papunyatula.com
</P>
<P>
   The Kluge-Ruhe Aboriginal Art Collection at the University of
Virginia: www.virginia.edu/kluge-ruhe
</P>
<P>
   Links to Aboriginal art galleries across central Australia:
www.desart.com.au
</P>
<P>
   On the web:
</P>
<P>
   To learn more about the Art Gallery of New South Wales:
www.artgallery.nsw.gov.au
</P>
<P>
   To see contemporary Aboriginal painting offered for sale by the
Papunya Tula artists cooperative in Alice Springs:
www.papunyatula.com
</P>
<P>
   To learn about perhaps the best assemblage in the United States,
the Kluge-Ruhe Aboriginal Art Collection at the University of
Virginia: www.virginia.edu/kluge-ruhe
</P>
<P>
   For links to Aboriginal art galleries across central Australia:
www.desart.com.au
</P>
<P>
   THE EXHIBIT
</P>
<P>
   ``Papunya Tula:
</P>
<P>
   Genesis and Genius''
</P>
<P>
   The first major exhibition tracing the beginnings of the
Aboriginal art movement of the Australian desert continues through
Nov. 12 at the Art Gallery of New South Wales in Sydney. ``Water
Dreaming at Kalipinya,'' the painting that recently sold for a
record price, is in the show. Afterward, it will be part of an
exhibition touring the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Auchmutey writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
