<HEADER>
A6613 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-PHILIPPINES-ESTRADA-A     08-19 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PHILIPPINES-ESTRADA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PHILIPPINE LEADER, BESET BY BAD REVIEWS, IS READY FOR A CHANGE IN
IMAGE
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MANILA, Philippines _ ``If they want war, we will give them
defeat,'' declared President Joseph Estrada not long ago in the
latest version of his tough-guy political credo: ``Don't dare me.''
</P>
<P>
   He was speaking this time about Muslim rebels and, like his
earlier turns at belligerence, this one worked. His poll numbers
went up last week.
</P>
<P>
   The public is desperate for its president to pull himself
together and start getting things done. A former movie actor with a
lackadaisical approach to government, Estrada has increasingly
become the subject of jokes, gossip and that old Philippine staple,
coup rumors.
</P>
<P>
   Halfway into his six-year term, the economy is faltering,
corruption and cronyism seem to be ascendant and Muslim separatists
and kidnappers are getting out of hand in the southern Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with his options narrowed, Estrada has unleashed his army
in a cathartic take-no-prisoners campaign against the rebels on the
island of Mindanao. He is also determined to resolve a kidnapping
of Western vacationers that has continued for almost four months on
the tiny neighboring island of Jolo.
</P>
<P>
   Three Malaysian hostages were freed Saturday. There were hopes
that the remaining nine Westerners and one Filipino could be
released over the weekend, officials said, though negotiators said
on Saturday that so far their talks had not been successful.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently as a result of the effort to end the hostage
situation, though, those polled gave the president a positive
rating of over 50 percent for the first time in months.
</P>
<P>
   But political commentators seemed unimpressed. Rep. Raul
Gonzales recalled the boost former President Bush enjoyed after the
Persian Gulf war in 1991 _ only to be undercut by his perceived
failure to manage the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Even that comparison is on the rosy side, said Amando Doronila,
a columnist for The Philippine Daily Inquirer. Bush had just won a
war; Estrada does not even have a workable strategy for victory.
</P>
<P>
   Fighting has flared in the three-decade-old insurgency following
his failure to build on the peacemaking and economic development
policies of his predecessor, Fidel Ramos. Analysts here say there
cannot be a lasting peace unless those policies are creatively
pursued.
</P>
<P>
   A recent spate of bombings in Manila that many people attribute
to the Muslim rebels heightened popular fears about the president's
inaction. At least now, people say, Estrada is doing something.
Last month, soldiers captured the headquarters in Mindanao of the
main insurgent group, the Moro National Liberation Front, and
Estrada traveled there to hoist the Philippine flag.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's enjoying a sort of windfall from Mindanao, but that
windfall is like opium,'' Doronila said. ``The opium deadens
people's awareness to the really serious problems that are hurting
them. They have temporarily forgotten the corruption and the
economic issues.''
</P>
<P>
   The country's growth rate of less than 4 percent is well below
projections, slower than the growth in most other nations in the
region, and far too low to absorb soaring birthrates. One-third of
the population of 76 million remains below the poverty line and
unemployment has risen to more than 13 percent.
</P>
<P>
   What is particularly damaging among investors is the atmosphere
of old-style cronyism that surrounds Estrada's government, with
favored friends receiving both political appointments and
protection in questionable business deals. The World Bank recently
estimated that corruption was costing the Philippines $46 million a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Eschewing the hard work of making policy and legislation _ as a
senator, he once said his favorite moment was when the speaker
shouted, ``Recess!'' _ Estrada has fallen back on presidential
decrees, issuing hundreds of them in his first two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``His presidency is very erratic, not driven by any coherent
vision or planning,'' Doronila said. ``It's very much an ad hoc
presidency. But he has a sure touch for what is popular.''
</P>
<P>
   Estrada, a former B-movie actor who cultivates an image as a man
of the people, is entranced by the example of Ronald Reagan, but
the parallels go only so far. Unlike his American hero, he has
little philosophy of government and is not leading the nation in
any clear direction.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike Reagan, he is not a natural in the role of president.
</P>
<P>
   ``One has the feeling that in reacting to a situation his first
words are, `How do I play this scene?' _ not whatever issues are
there,'' said the Rev. John Carroll, an American sociologist who
teaches here.
</P>
<P>
   But like Reagan, Estrada enjoys seeing the world in movie
images. The persona he projects as president _ along with the
public perception of him _ is based on his movie roles as a
pugnacious little guy who faces down the slick and the powerful.
</P>
<P>
   Because of this image, his base of support is among the nation's
poor. With most of the political and economic elite against him, he
swept to office in May 1998 with a huge plurality of 40 percent in
the field of nine.
</P>
<P>
   Now even the poor have begun to turn against him. Drivers of the
gaudy converted Jeeps, known as Jeepneys and used as public
minibuses, have said they no longer want him to use the Jeepney as
his symbol.
</P>
<P>
   So he has promised a new President Estrada.
</P>
<P>
   ``A nation's life is like a motion picture,'' he said last year.
``With proper direction, the next scenes will change.''
</P>
<P>
   The new scenes he has written look like this: He will get to
work at 8 a.m. _ rather than in the afternoon _ and he will stay on
the job all day long. He will set aside his beloved Johnnie Walker
whiskey and drink red wine instead.
</P>
<P>
   And, he promised, he will curtail his ``midnight Cabinet,''
all-night karaoke-bar-style sessions with his cronies that one aide
said sometimes produced presidential decrees that had to be quickly
countermanded in the light of day.
</P>
<P>
   ``At 4 in the morning, I am the only sober one in the room,''
said the aide, Aprodocio Laquian, last March. He was promptly
forced to resign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
