<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICA'S-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MULTIBILLIONAIRE LEAVES THE OPEN OCEAN FOR THE CHALLENGE OF
AMERICA'S CUP 
</HEADLINE>
   By HERB McCORMICK    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Storm-tossed, soaked and seasick, Larry Ellison watched as his
hired posse of professional sailors scrambled to repair yet another
piece of broken equipment aboard his 80-foot maxi-yacht Sayonara.
It was the final days of December 1998, and Ellison and his 22-man
crew were battling fierce weather off the coast of Australia in the
54th running of the annual Sydney-Hobart Race.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison, the chief executive officer of Oracle Corp., was far
removed from the Silicon Valley boardrooms where he has become a
multibillionaire. In the now infamous Hobart race, sailing with as
good a crew as money could buy, Sayonara overcame a litany of gear
failures to win line honors as the first boat to finish. Far
astern, six sailors perished in the storm.
</P>
<P>
   After dabbling in the sport in the '70s, Ellison took a long
hiatus before commissioning Sayonara in 1995. In the intervening
years, he has campaigned the boat vigorously. But Ellison's
commitment to yacht racing escalated to new, rarefied heights last
week when he announced his challenge for the America's Cup in New
Zealand in 2003, an effort that will cost $80 million or more.
</P>
<P>
   Traveling in Europe, Ellison was not on hand for the
announcement, leaving that duty to his chief operating officer,
Bill Erkelens, and his campaign manager, Paul Cayard. And Ellison
also declined an interview request for this article.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the disastrous Hobart race, however, in
early 1999 Ellison spoke about his experiences in a rare talk at
San Francisco's St. Francis Yacht Club, which will most likely
represent his cup challenge. During the speech, Ellison described
how one crewman broke an ankle, another a thumb, and a third
cracked his ribs. He strongly intimated that he was finished with
offshore ocean racing.
</P>
<P>
   But closed-course, around-the-buoys, America's Cup-style match
racing appears to be a different matter. And the next cup
competition has enticed several other billionaires to enter the
fray for the first time, including the Seattle businessman Craig
McCaw and the Swiss pharmaceutical heir Ernesto Bertarelli.
</P>
<P>
   As the former captain and project manager for Sayonara, Erkelens
was at Ellison's side during the Hobart race. So too was the Kiwi
skipper Chris Dickson, who will reprise that role with the Oracle
Racing challenge, and the former Team New Zealand America's Cup
sailor Robbie Naismith, who has also joined the team. In fact,
Erkelens said Ellison's interest in the cup was piqued when he
learned that the New Zealand crewmen who sailed aboard Sayonara
might be available for his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``He likes the team aspect of Sayonara, and the people,''
Erkelens said. ``Being able to relax with a group of people
completely outside of work seems to be a major draw to him.''
</P>
<P>
   To bolster the core group of Sayonara sailors with other
experienced cup players, Ellison hired Cayard, the skipper who
headed the America One challenge in the last cup, as well as
several of that program's key personnel, including the operations
manager, Bob Billingham. Ellison also purchased all of America
One's assets, which became available when Cayard decided that the
billionaires had essentially priced him out of the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cap on our old fund-raising model for America One, which
was based on corporate sponsorship and raising money from private
donations, seems be around 30 or 40 million dollars,'' Cayard said.
``That's less than half of what you're going to need to be
competitive now.''
</P>
<P>
   But money is not an issue for Ellison, who also purchased the
two Aloha Racing cup boats sailed by John Kolius' Hawaii-based
challenge earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   It is difficult to conjure a scenario in which Ellison will be
outspent, but it is also hard to lay odds on the success of a
Dickson-Cayard collaboration. Both are known for being fiercely
competitive, and neither suffers from a lack of self-esteem. But
Cayard is coming off a fresh, tough cup challenge, while Dickson
sat out the last event.
</P>
<P>
   Cayard said that he planned to be aboard Ellison's cup racer,
but in what position remains uncertain. ``Dickson has a long
relationship with Larry as Sayonara's skipper, so he's the
incumbent skipper,'' Cayard said. ``I think we just have to wait
and see how things go. In two-and-a-half years, anything's
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though Cayard is known as a team player, it will be
interesting to see how comfortable he will be if not unequivocally
in command. And if Cayard finds himself unhappy in a limited role
in a Dickson afterguard, Ellison may find himself with a
quarterback controversy not seen in the Bay area since Joe Montana
and Steve Young were both wearing the uniform of Cayard's beloved
49ers.
</P>
<P>
   How close Ellison will be to the day-to-day operation remains to
be seen. In the Hobart race, between bouts of nausea, Ellison took
a regular turn at the wheel, and he is said to be a good helmsman.
``Larry would like to be involved as much as his schedule allows,''
Erkelens said. ``But he doesn't want to be on board unless he has
spent enough time training to participate at the level required.''
</P>
<P>
   A lasting image of Sayonara's Sydney-Hobart ordeal is an aerial
photograph of the boat in the final miles, with Ellison slumped
over the lifelines, visibly drained. Now, in a manner of speaking,
he is again at sea. Only time will tell if the voyage is
triumphant, or plagued by that old, queasy feeling.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
