<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYPD-CHIEF-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI APPOINTS NEW POLICE COMMISSIONER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 repeating to add photo note  (ART ADV: Photo  NYT5  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani named Correction Commissioner
Bernard Kerik as New York City's next police commissioner Saturday,
turning to a former undercover narcotics detective and familiar
member of his administration to command the nation's largest police
department.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik, 44, will replace Howard Safir, a retired federal agent
and Giuliani's confidant and friend of 25 years, who announced his
resignation this month after four and a half years in the job.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik will be sworn in this week as the department's 40th
commissioner in just under 100 years, taking command of the
40,000-member force during a time when crime has fallen sharply but
the department has suffered intense criticism, from within and
without.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik's achievements have been significant at the city
Department of Correction, where he brought about substantial
declines in violence in the jail system and reduced overtime. But
some critics have said that his lack of a college degree, a
requirement for the rank of captain and higher in the Police
Department, sends the wrong message when the department is
struggling to recruit qualified candidates to the force.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik, who won the Medal of Valor as a police detective, is 24
credits short of a degree in labor relations at Empire State
College.
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Kerik is the most prominent element of a
broader change in the city's police hierarchy. Giuliani said
Saturday that he would promote Chief of Department Joseph P. Dunne
to be his new first deputy commissioner, replacing Patrick E.
Kelleher, who retired last week. Dunne was one of the three
finalists for the job of commissioner. The other was Dennison Young
Jr., counsel to the mayor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last three candidates that I considered were Dennison
Young, Joe Dunne and Bernie Kerik,'' Giuliani said, ``and the city
is going to have the good fortune of having all three of them
working together, along with others because we work as a team, to
continue to build on this record that is such a superb one.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerik will have the opportunity to fill the positions of deputy
commissioner of organized crime control and chief of personnel, two
of the highest posts in the department. The men who hold those jobs
are retiring.
</P>
<P>
   As commissioner, Kerik's challenges will be many and his window
of opportunity will be small, with 16 months left in Giuliani's
second and final term as mayor. And in spite of the department's
successes, it has endured sharp criticism in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   Relations between the police and minority residents are strained
after the torture of Abner Louima in a Brooklyn station house in
1997 and the fatal shootings of four unarmed black men in a
13-month period that ended last March. The department is also
facing the possibility of federal oversight because of a finding by
the U.S. attorney's office in Brooklyn that it has failed to
adequately discipline officers who use excessive force.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the department is struggling to recruit members and
retain its veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik, a native of Paterson, N.J., who lives in Riverdale, the
Bronx, spent eight years in the Police Department, served as one of
Giuliani's bodyguards during his 1993 campaign and joined the
Department of Correction in 1994 as the director of investigations.
He was appointed first deputy commissioner in 1995 and commissioner
in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Before joining the New York Police Department, Kerik was warden
of the Passaic County Jail in New Jersey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
