A6677 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OUTDOORS-NYT &LR;      08-19 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FLY-FISHING GUIDE FOR HOLLYWOOD HABITUES 
</HEADLINE>
   By RAY OTTULICH    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The phone call came unexpectedly; he said that he was Aidan
Quinn and that he wanted to book a day of guide/instruction as a
birthday present for a friend and left it at that. We figured out a
time block last August. I penciled it in on the calendar and when
the window narrowed down, it was agreed he would call me back. Of
course, I mentioned it to friends who immediately bandied about the
names of possible candidates for Quinn's fly-fishing mystery man.
The women and their much-vaunted intuition finally parsed it down
to Brad Pitt.
</P>
<P>
   On the chosen day, with a litany of Brad Pitt and Aidan Quinn
movies running around in my head, I jumped in my rig and headed for
the appointed rendezvous. The last few miles were down a winding
dusty gravel road with a backdrop bookend vista of the distant blue
highlands of the Catskills and the Berkshires. I pulled off on a
drive that led to a gentle clove flanked by a large white farmhouse
and a small barn. I parked by the barn, walked over and mounted the
porch. Rang the bell. Nothing.
</P>
<P>
   I waited a few minutes, sat on a chair and began to wonder if I
was at the right house. I walked off the porch and around the side
of the place. A large extension pushed out toward the backyard,
there were a couple of reassuring vehicles parked out of view from
the front. At a side door was a rigged up fly rod. Eureka! It had
to be the right place. I made my way back around front and rang.
Again nothing, but emboldened by the sight of the rod I was
determined to check out the two back doors. As I again turned the
corner, Liam Neeson stepped outside calling my name with a smile
and hand extended.
</P>
<P>
   Neeson invited me in, and we had coffee, tea and rolls while
waiting for the tardy Quinn. Naturally, after fixating on Brad
Pitt, my mind now drew a complete blank and I couldn't think of a
single movie of Neeson's, but thankfully we had serious fly fishing
to talk about.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn showed up about five minutes later, we finished our
breakfast and headed to the lawn out back to practice a little
warm-up casting at a small pond. It was reminiscent of the old
``Chip 'N' Dale'' cartoons, with Liam and Aidan each insisting that
I help the other. Neeson had standard casting down already; I just
demonstrated how to haul, a technique that increases line speed and
distance. Quinn was a beginner, and we concentrated on the basic
cast.
</P>
<P>
   Back at the house we met Neeson's wife, Natasha Richardson, saw
the twins, picked up lunch, said good-bye and took off for Liam's
local stream. A guide's forte is knowing his territory, years of
angling the same streams brings an intimate knowledge. Take a fish
out of water and he's lost, but a guide has a bulwark of fish lore
and habit to fall back upon _ you know where you should find fish.
</P>
<P>
   It was a very dry August and streams were down to trickles, the
fish would be concentrated in the deeper holes and below
oxygen-rich riffles. Neeson's stream had a dam with stairstep
spillway and a small plunge pool at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   The tailwater was teeming with large crayfish. We worked our way
with dry flies toward the dam, and the fish were hungry. Both Quinn
and Neeson easily caught aggressive sunfish, and Liam missed a
hookup on a trout. He cast to the spot again a number of times but
couldn't raise it. It was midday now and much too bright, so we
broke for lunch at a small pavilion.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward we jumped into a small aluminum boat. I rowed them
around the edges of the impoundment, targeting the shadowed shore
and the numerous fallen trees that provided additional cover. They
traded Hollywood stories to while away the lulls.
</P>
<P>
   Quinn was casting a Turks Tarantula, an attractor fly. A good
way to describe it is as sort of a year-round hopper pattern; it
works everywhere and most seasons. I told him to give it a twitch,
its small rubber legs tantalizingly vibrating in the center of the
spreading concentric circles.
</P>
<P>
   The rainbow shot up out of the depths like a missile and busted
the fly on the surface. Neeson and I shouted encouragement, and
Quinn, a quick study, deftly brought the fish to the boat. It was
his first trout on a flyrod, a 14-inch beauty. Aidan, the beginner,
was top rod that day, always a good way to start.
</P>
<P>
   We drove back to the homestead and had a leisurely late
afternoon repast on the terrace.
</P>
<P>
   Liam asked me to show him how to tie a few practical knots. My
last memory of that day is of his big thumbs twisting leader into a
barrel knot, Alaskan guide style. A few months later Liam was
reported as saying he was going to take a hiatus from movies, stay
in New York, do theater and fly fish. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-00 1418EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
