   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ADULT-TYPICAL _ Theresa Johnson works. She's 36. She is divorced
and raising two kids. She's an undergraduate at Iowa State
University. In other words, she fits the College Board's composite
criteria for the typical adult college student. Johnson fervently
believes that the pros of attending a university with schedules and
programs heavily weighted toward much younger students still
outweigh the cons. (Mollison, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-FRIEND _ DAYTON _ Vernon Courtney, director of the National
Afro-American Museum and Cultural Center, was in the same dorm as
Al Gore at Harvard in the mid-1960s. The two used to shoot pool and
play ping pong, alternating victories, and also shared an interest
in hunting. Courtney, a young black man from the seaport town of
Hampton, Va., was recruited to attend the Ivy League university. He
recalled Gore as a guy whose ``daily uniform'' then was bib
overalls and who always presented himself as a guy from Tennessee,
downplaying the senator's son in an effort to be one of the guys.
``The thing I find interesting is he comes off so dry now. He
wasn't that way at all. He was pretty gregarious,'' Courtney
recalled. They haven't stayed in contact but after someone told Al
he ran into Courtney, Gore fired off an e-mail to him that said
``Don't forget to vote for me.'' Courtney also knew Tommy Lee
Jones, who wasn't around much because he was wrapped up in drama
even then, and he had fleeting contact with Tipper, who would visit
Big Al on campus. (Kissell, Dayton Daily News) 15. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GA-EXECUTION _ Alexander Williams was not yet an adult and he
was mentally ill when he kidnapped, raped and murdered a
16-year-old Augusta, Ga., girl. His lawyers argue that the state's
plan to execute him on Thursday violates international common
decency that says it's wrong to execute the mentally ill and
children _ or those who commit crimes before they are adults.
(Cook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 35. WITH PHOTO (mug of
Williams)
</P>
<P>
   MINER-URANIUM _ A Moab, Utah, man might die before he can get
the $100,000 payment he's due from the federal government for his
work in uranium mines during the Cold War. His attorney has been
unable to prod a Senate Committee to break out of budget lockstep,
but there might be a glimmer of hope from another senator. (Grand
Junction Daily Sentinel) 30. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FLATRAIN _ Trying to unclog its highways from Miami to Orlando
to Tampa, planners in Florida had proposed a high-speed train that
would reach speeds of 240 mph. But Gov. Jeb Bush killed the $6.3
billion project, which included annual payments from the
Legislature for 20 years, because he was not convinced the train
would have enough riders to justify its cost. Now, a retired
Lakeland businessman, is on the verge of putting the proposal on
the November ballot. Using a provision of the state constitution
that lets referendums be placed on a ballot if their are sufficient
petitioners to do so, fast-train advocate C.C. Dockery is waiting
on the state Supreme Court to rule on his request. Fast trains are
the latest fad among urban planners; turning their use into reality
is a different thing. Metro Atlanta planners also dream of a
high-speed train linking the city with Chattanooga. (Manuel, Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   UNC-QA _ Q&AMP;A with James Moeser, the new chancellor at the
University of North Carolina, who arrived on campus this week from
the University of Nebraska. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 9
p.m.
