   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN-SABBATH _ WEST PALM BEACH _ Sen. Joseph Lieberman
chooses which biblical laws to follow literally and which he will
modify to suit his needs. Most religious conservatives condemn that
approach. But Jesus would applaud it. (Gushee, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TWINS _ WHITE PLAINS, N.C. _ To the world and to this day, they
are mostly objects of curiosity _ Chang and Eng, the conjoined
brothers whose May 1811 birth in Siam also spawned the phrase
``Siamese twins.'' But in the northwestern corner of North Carolina
where they settled some 30 years later, they have always been the
Bunker brothers _ hard-working tobacco farmers who married sisters,
fathered 21 children between them and lived utterly ordinary,
small-town lives. Officials recently renamed a bridge after the
twins on the White Plains farm where they lived and are buried.
Still, locals don't quite understand the outside world's
fascination with the twins, which has only grown with the
publication this summer of New Yorker Darin Strauss' acclaimed
novel ``Chang and Eng.'' To the folks who showed up at Strauss'
book signings last week in nearby Mount Airy and Wilkesboro, and to
the1,000-plus descendants who gathered for one of their
semi-regular reunions in White Plains Saturday, it's actually a
pretty familiar story around these parts: The one about strong
family bonds. (Vejnoska, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   SCHOOL-ADVICE _ With the school year approaching, it's time for
teachers and parents to reopen the lines of communication. To save
everyone time and stress, we asked working teachers and frenzied
moms and dads exactly what advice they would give the other side in
order to make this school year the most productive ever. (Dayton
Daily News) WITH ILLUSTRATION. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   DIGITAL-COMPASS _ You may remember a time when you were a kid
and you got a toy compass maybe from the neighborhood candy store
or maybe even from a box of Cracker Jacks. Those cheesy little
devices featured a jiggling needle balanced on a pin, and the
painted end of the needle always pointed north. Unless there was a
magnet nearby or the needle fell off the pin. Today you can carry
around a digital device that does the same thing more reliably. The
Co-Pilot from Precision Navigation Inc. gives you a digital readout
that tells you exactly which way you're headed with an accuracy of
plus or minus 5 degrees. (Cummings, Dayton Daily News) 12. WITH
PHOTO. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: This is James Cummings' Gadgets Column.
