<HEADLINE>
BOTH SLOPPY IN THE MUD, JETS MANAGE TO BEAT GIANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   By RAFAEL HERMOSO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Jets' annual preseason game with the New York
Giants is usually a bonfire of emotions, from the pregame
tailgating outside Giants Stadium to the testosterone on the field.
</P>
<P>
   Afternoon showers dampened the parking lot plans and kept many
fans home for Friday's game. The players were slowed down by their
own mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   The Jets' emerged with a sloppy 27-24 victory that had nothing
to do with a wet field. The final score was deceptive without
considering that the beleaguered Jets secondary was unable to stop
the Giants' offense. The Giants missed a 45-yard field goal and the
Jets had a field goal blocked.
</P>
<P>
   Playing without their injured quarterback, Vinny Testaverde, the
Jets relied on his backup, Ray Lucas, and their running back,
Curtis Martin, to slice through the Giants' defense and finish
their preseason at 2-2.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants lost their third straight game, with one more
exhibition left against Baltimore on Friday. They struggled to
comprehend how they had gone backwards since training camp opened
and hoped this latest stumble was an exception, not a prelude.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seemed like we lost our heads at times,'' said Giants
quarterback Kerry Collins.
</P>
<P>
   Jets coach Al Groh preferred to discuss a victory without
Testaverde, who was scratched from the lineup just before the
opening kickoff because he sprained his left big toe against
Baltimore last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to let prudence take over,'' Groh said. ``He and I both
wanted him to play. Because we have a player like Ray, it was an
easy decision to make.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were unable to apply any pressure on Lucas and had
trouble covering his receivers. Lucas had a game reminiscent of his
run late last season: he completed 19 of 26 passes for 286 yards
and three touchdowns, including a flea flicker that left the Giants
bewildered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Vinny's team but if he goes down I'm ready,'' Lucas said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin capped off what he termed his best preseason ever by
rushing 18 times for 107 yards. Lucas called Martin the Jets'
``lethal weapon.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants were left to cover their embarrassment with jokes.
Linebacker Mike Barrow suggested that an instructional video could
be made from the game on how not to defend the run.
</P>
<P>
   Giants coach Jim Fassel lambasted the team's sloppiness in being
penalized 16 times for 105 yards, including a surreal 11 penalties
in the second quarter. The Giants had only been penalized nine
times for 101 yards in their first two preseason games.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have two weeks before we open up the season, but some guys
are going to get a wake-up call,'' Fassel said without naming
players. ``I wanted to progress and we digressed.''
</P>
<P>
   Fassel questioned why his team lacked intensity. He has had
reason to get flustered in previous weeks, with special teams'
debacles and the infamous fumble forced by Jack Golden, a rookie,
that gave Jacksonville the victory last week.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel criticized Friday night's nonexistent pass rush, which
was supposed to be upgraded this season with Barrow's addition.
Barrow, the middle linebacker, returned after missing the first two
games with a sprained right knee, but he was one of the game's
guilty parties.
</P>
<P>
   During one disconcerting second quarter sequence, the Giants'
defense nudged the Jets downfield to an eventual field goal with
four penalties in one series, including penalties on three straight
snaps. Barrow was penalized twice, although one was declined
because cornerback Dave Thomas also committed a penalty on the
play. Twice the Jets gained first downs on Giants' mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's lit into us before,'' cornerback Jason Sehorn said.
``It's frustrating to see something, to see potential in the team
and then go out and do nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' rebuilt offensive line provided the most cause for
worry. After looking solid in the first two preseason games, it
allowed its first sack and was called for four false starts. That
contributed to 11 offensive penalties.
</P>
<P>
   Collins continues to show an ability to compensate for his
team's mistakes. He completed 16 of 28 passes for 275 yards and two
touchdowns, including a 73-yard touchdown to Amani Toomer.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Dayne continued to struggle, rushing 12 times for 37 yards.
Dayne, the Giants' first-round pick, fumbled his first carry and
carried only two more times in the first half. Fassel again said
that from the sidelines he could not judge the holes Dayne was
getting.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
