<HEADLINE>
LIBERTY, AT THE BRINK, PLAYS AT HOME
</HEADLINE>
   (EDS: Chasity is correct) 
  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Liberty, which was the best team in the Eastern
Conference this season, returns to Madison Square Garden on Sunday
afternoon, facing elimination in the two-of-three-game Eastern
Conference finals after losing to Cleveland by 56-43 on Thursday
night in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockers shut down New York's offense, limiting its top four
scorers _ Tari Phillips, Vickie Johnson, Tamika Whitmore and Becky
Hammon _ to 27 points combined.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty entered Thursday night's game having won 15 of its
last 18 games. The Liberty defeated the Washington Mystics in the
first round of the playoffs by convincingly winning the first two
games of the series.
</P>
<P>
   The Rockers, who finished 7-25 last season, advanced to the
conference finals this season by beating Orlando in the first
round. The Rockers won that series by winning both games at home,
where they won 16 of 19 games this season. But the Rockers are just
4-13 on the road.
</P>
<P>
   Center Chasity Melvin, a third-year pro, led the Rockers with
nearly 12 points a game this season. But on Thursday night, Rushia
Brown led all scorers with 18.
</P>
<P>
   The Liberty beat the Rockers twice at Madison Square Garden
during the season, both times by double digits.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
