<HEADER>
A6682 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-KANSAS-REAL-2TAKES-NY     08-19 0967
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KANSAS-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN KANSAS CITY AREA, UP TO DATE IS DOWN TO EARTH 
</HEADLINE>
   by SHIRLEY CHRISTIAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LENEXA, Kan. _ This suburb in the bistate Kansas City
metropolitan area prides itself in being on the cutting edge when
it comes to attracting growth-oriented business and industry to its
modern corporate parks _ a philosophy that might seem to rule out
much interest in a declining limestone mine.
</P>
<P>
   But as extraction slowed a few years ago at a 200-acre mine in
the path of the community's westward growth, city officials wrote
and enacted special building and zoning codes to permit the
development of the cavernous space, 50 to 100 feet below the
surface, as an industrial park.
</P>
<P>
   Today, 250,000 square feet of the underground Lenexa development
is occupied by tenants, and 200,000 square feet is being readied
for occupancy. The operator of the park, the Minneapolis-based
Meritex Enterprises, is seeking tenants for the remaining area of
about 2.5 million square feet.
</P>
<P>
   Lenexa and Meritex are the newest players in a half-century-old
pattern in the urban area of Kansas City, Mo.-Kan., where an
estimated 20 million square feet of business and industrial space _
more than 10 percent of the total _ has been created in former
limestone mines. There are about 30 distinct underground business
parks, led by the mammoth Hunt Midwest SubTropolis, a 913-acre
world in itself with 6.5 miles of roads and 2.1 miles of rail
corridors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cost is probably the most important reason why we are here in
the underground _ it's a lot cheaper,'' said Garland J. Nall, site
manager of Love Box Co., who supervises a 265-by-750-foot warehouse
with 21 loading docks in the Lenexa development.
</P>
<P>
   But he said worker comfort was also a big plus. The natural
temperature underground ranges between 56 and 64 degrees, rising
according to the number of people working in a space and the length
of time it has been occupied. Nall said the temperature level is
ideal for warehouse workers, who usually have to tolerate extreme
summer heat and chilly winter drafts in surface warehouses. Office
workers often find the underground a bit cool and usually wear long
sleeves and use small electric heaters.
</P>
<P>
   About 400 businesses have operations in underground parks in and
around Kansas City, employing about 4,000 people. There are a few
other areas of the country that have, or are beginning, underground
industrial development _ including Indianapolis, Louisville, St.
Louis and an area north of Pittsburgh _ but Kansas City has the
overwhelming majority of the space in use.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the result of a combination of geology and geography,''
said William E. Seymour, senior vice president of Meritex.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its central location, Kansas City is appealing as a
national and regional distribution point, with easy access to
interstate highways and rail lines. And the fact that it is on two
thick layers of high-quality limestone _ the only source of
construction aggregate for the area, which has no gravel piles _
led to a lot of mining, which, in turn, opened up vast underground
spaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mining started here around 1875-80,'' said Dr. Syed E. Hasan,
a geology professor at the University of Missouri-Kansas City, who
has written extensively on underground development and mining. ``At
first they were quarrying it, then around 1900 they started cutting
into hillsides.''
</P>
<P>
   By the 1950s, the mining was being done with the future
industrial use of the space in mind. Mine operators started using
the ``room and pillar method'' _ carving the supporting pillars in
a regular grid to allow space between them for roads and buildings.
Today's pillars are typically 25 feet in diameter and spaced 60 to
65 feet apart, center to center.
</P>
<P>
   More than 10,000 massive whitewashed pillars support the
16-foot-high ceilings of the Hunt Midwest complex along the north
bank of the Missouri River within the city limits of Kansas City,
Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The pillars have numbers to help visitors locate specific
businesses; regular exit signs help them find their way out.
Fluorescent lights line the roadway ceilings, but looking down the
long rows of pillars, especially in the unoccupied areas, still
gives a sense of peering into the limitless unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, about 400 tractor-trailer trucks make their way in
and out of Hunt Midwest directly off Missouri Highway 210 just east
of Interstate 435. They enter through a series of tunnel-like
openings in a hillside that has been sliced open to reveal a wall
of limestone. The surface of the site is occupied by two giant
theme parks, Worlds of Fun and Oceans of Fun, and the mining
operation of Hunt Midwest continues to extract two million tons of
rock a year from part of the site.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas E. Steadman, vice president and general manager of Hunt
Midwest Real Estate Development, said that adapting underground
space for industrial and other uses is relatively simple. It
involves painting the pillars, pouring concrete floors and roads,
installing lighting and sprinkler systems, then putting up walls as
required by tenants. Except for the ubiquitous rock pillars and the
absence of outside light, an office in the underground looks very
much like an office anywhere. As Seymour of Meritex said jokingly,
``The corner office doesn't get a window; it gets a pillar.''
</P>
<P>
   Operators of underground industrial parks say a tenant can
occupy space in the underground for about half what it costs to
occupy a similar amount of space above ground. Lease rates start at
about $2 a square foot annually, compared with about $3.50
aboveground. In addition, there are savings for construction
because no roofs, foundations or exterior finishing are required.
Energy savings are substantial.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Seymour and Steadman said that tenants could expect to pay
cheaper insurance rates, in part because the underground is secure
from floods, tornadoes and other weather problems. Further,
transient traffic through underground parks is rare; there are only
a few entrances and exits, and breaking into a limestone cave is
more than most burglars would attempt.
</P>
<P>
   Underground developments have their own building and safety
codes. Although there have been occasional mine collapses in this
region in recent years, all are thought to have involved abandoned
mines, most of them worked as much as a century ago without the
balanced distribution of support pillars found in today's
underground industrial parks.
</P>
<P>
   Brant Gaul, a Lenexa city planner who worked on the codes for
the Meritex project, said that before any building permit is issued
for the underground, every pillar is inspected for stability. The
code also provides for annual inspections by independent
geotechnical engineers. He added that the city government had so
much confidence in the safety of the Meritex development that it
had purchased 40 acres on the surface to build a public works
service center.
</P>
<P>
   Underground developments are considered apt for a variety of
uses _ particularly warehouses and distribution centers, and light
industry such as printing, records storage, and offices. Steadman
said that about 70 percent of the 4.3 million square feet of
occupied space in Hunt Midwest SubTropolis is used for warehouses
and storage, 15 percent for manufacturing, 8 percent for freezing
and cooling of food, and the rest as offices.
</P>
<P>
   The largest single tenant of the Hunt Midwest underground is the
Postal Service, which operates two facilities in a total of 550,000
square feet. The larger operation is the nationwide distribution
center for the booming business in collector's stamps. The other is
a regional distribution center for regular stamps.
</P>
<P>
   Seymour said that no business that uses hazardous or highly
flammable processes can locate in an underground park, nor can any
business that uses explosives or stores things that have a strong
smell, such as rubber tires.
</P>
<P>
   At the other extreme, Hunt Midwest uses some of the SubTropolis
space to play host to a biannual charity ball that attracts more
than 1,000 people in black-tie finery. SubTropolis is also the site
every February of a 10K race called the Groundhog Run. Laurie
Wimberly, who has taken part in the Groundhog Run twice, said that
the underground provided ``the perfect temperature'' for running in
the middle of winter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
