<HEADER>
A6684 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k BC-GARCIA-COLUMN0820-COX     08-19 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARCIA-COLUMN0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Parties must move beyond rhetoric to win minority voters
 &HT;    By Arnold Garcia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Minorities watching the recently concluded
political conventions may be forgiven if they feel a little giddy
from all the attention from their new-found Republican and
Democratic suitors. But those who have had the good fortune to
experience romance know that courtships always produce hyperbole.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping some perspective in a courtship is a most effective way
to avoid making decisions based on ardor, not logic. The Republican
and Democratic valentines addressed to minorities _ especially
Latinos _ demonstrate that the leadership of both parties have gone
from demographic denial to acceptance of the fact that the face of
America is darkening and that the voice of America has a bit of an
accent.
</P>
<P>
   There are pretty big howevers, however, before either courtship
can be declared a success. Declaring love and acceptance isn't
going to be enough for Democrats to keep Hispanics from defecting
or for Republicans to make converts.
</P>
<P>
   There is a lot of history to overcome on what George and Ira
Gershwin so aptly described as this ``bumpy road to love.''
Rhetoric about a record of inclusion doesn't mean much to those who
grew up in the Texas of the 1940s and 1950s and recall firsthand
that the Democratic Party of those days was about as welcoming as a
federal grand jury.
</P>
<P>
   In those days, minorities were discouraged from voting, much
less running for office. Republicans then were virtually
nonexistent, so Democrats were the devil minorities knew.
</P>
<P>
   And rhetoric about inclusion doesn't mean much for a new
generation of minorities who are as diverse as the country itself.
Political parties are going to have to undergo a cultural shift _
if you'll pardon the expression _ to appeal to minorities in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   One size does not fit all when it comes to dealing with what's
called ``minority issues.'' A small-business owner isn't going to
view the world the same as an employee; an established professional
isn't going to respond to a message that assumes all minorities are
poor and need government salvation.
</P>
<P>
   Simple stuff really, but the evidence to date indicates that
those old stereotypes and assumptions about what minorities
``want'' will die hard.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't been too long ago that I heard politicians saying to
minority constituents to ``get together.'' Translation: ``You
people try to get together and pool your feeble intellects to
figure out what you want and get back with me.''
</P>
<P>
   And you don't have to listen too hard or too long before some
blithering idiot decries the lack of minority ``unity.'' Anglos
aren't united about anything. That's why there are Republicans and
Democrats and Libertarians and none of the above. So why should
minorities have to agree on all issues?
</P>
<P>
   It is encouraging that some forward thinkers in both political
parties realize where the future lies and are trying to move there.
Even so, there are going to be occasions as we move down this road
when questions arise about motive.
</P>
<P>
   Texas Democrats see a party in ruins, and some want minorities
to salvage it. A quarterback sent in the last 15 seconds of the
last quarter to reverse a 14-point lead doesn't have much of
chance, but is sure to catch hell if he doesn't.
</P>
<P>
   That point was made effectively by Ron Kirk, Dallas' first
African American mayor. Kirk tells a joke about how African
Americans become mayors: ``There's an airplane hurtling along at
top speed. Suddenly, the navigation system dies. The engine fails.
The wing catches fire. The pilot bursts into the cabin and singles
out a black passenger. You, he says, haven't you always wanted to
fly a plane?''
</P>
<P>
   Ain't love grand?
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
