u a BC-GORE-FRIEND0820-COX     08-19 0666
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-FRIEND0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gore acquaintance recalls Harvard years
 &HT;    By Margo Rutledge Kissell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Not everyone can claim he has played ping-pong or
shot pool with Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Vernon Courtney does.
</P>
<P>
   The director of the National Afro-American Museum and Cultural
Center in Wilberforce, Ohio, said he got an early glimpse of the
competitive side of the vice president and Democratic presidential
nominee when the two attended Harvard University more than 30 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The Hampton, Va., native had been recruited to attend the Ivy
League college. Courtney majored in English and American literature
from 1965 to 1969 and said that during his sophomore and junior
years, he and Gore were in the same dormitory.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to play him a fair amount in both those table sports.
He was pretty competitive,'' Courtney said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the two knew each other ``just in passing'' but had also
talked about hunting, which Courtney said was a common interest.
</P>
<P>
   He recalled Gore as someone who wore bib overalls and presented
himself as ``a guy from Tennessee,'' downplaying being a senator's
son to fit in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there was a conscious effort to be one of the guys,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I find interesting is he comes off so dry now. He
wasn't that way at all. He was pretty gregarious,'' Courtney
recalled. ``I've heard a number of other people who have kept up
their friendship with him say he's pretty animated in private but
tends to quiet down in public settings.''
</P>
<P>
   Courtney's biographical sketch said he was a National Merit
commended scholar. While an undergraduate at Harvard, he was active
in Harvard Student Agencies, the Black Student's Union and
represented his dormitory, Dunster House, on several intramural
sports teams.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney said he didn't stay in touch with Gore after they left
campus, but said he recently received an e-mail from the
campaigning vice president.
</P>
<P>
   When the museum hosted an Alex Haley exhibit this summer, a
high-ranking Coast Guard official was there because of the guard's
newest cutter, named in honor of the writer-historian to honor
contributions of black Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney said the official later apparently told Gore he had run
into Courtney, who had known him in college. Soon after, Courtney
said he received the brief electronic message.
</P>
<P>
   ``The message sent was `don't forget to vote for me,' ''
Courtney laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is a really, really smart guy and I think his
intellect would certainly put him in good stead to be a decent
president. There is no doubt in my mind he could do the job,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Courtney wouldn't reveal how he will vote come Election
Day, adding, ``I'm one of those Independent characters who makes
that decision in the booth.''
</P>
<P>
   While Gore's path after Harvard eventually led to the White
House, Courtney took a different route.
</P>
<P>
   After serving two years in the Army, he returned to the seaport
town of Hampton, Va., where he worked in public schools serving
adult learners. He later attended graduate school at Pennsylvania
State University, earning a master's degree in education in 1978
and advancing to doctoral candidacy in 1979. He was a Woodrow
Wilson Foundation Fellow from 1981 to 1984, during which time he
worked as director of institutional advancement at Wilberforce
University. In 1987, he was named assistant director of the
National Afro-American Museum and Cultural Center, where he became
director two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Courtney said he also knew another member of the dormitory,
football All-American Tommy Lee Jones, whose path led to Hollywood
and film fame.
</P>
<P>
   Back then, he wasn't like the tough-talking characters he has
portrayed, according to Courtney. He remembered him as someone who
``never had very much to say. He wasn't around very much. Even
then, he was very much into drama and theater.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
