A6686 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-JEWS-AMERICA0820-COX     08-19 0539
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEWS-AMERICA0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Lieberman choice not a world's first
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Only in America . . . is the elliptical refrain
that immigrants and their descendants use to thank their lucky
stars that they are here in the land of opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only in America, right?'' Joseph Lieberman asked cheering
delegates in Los Angeles the other night, suggesting that the U.S.
is the one nation in which the grandson of Jewish immigrants could
grow up to be the Democratic vice presidential candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Upon closer examination, the answer to Lieberman's question is,
not really.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is overwrought and it is simply not true
historically,'' said Rabbi Arthur Hertzberg, the Bronfman Professor
of the Humanities at New York University.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman's nomination certainly is historic, as has been noted
daily since his selection. He is the first Jewish candidate for
high office on a major party's ticket.
</P>
<P>
   But if elected, he would not be the first Jewish politician
chosen to lead his nation.
</P>
<P>
   Even leaving aside the obvious case of Israel, history provides
several examples.
</P>
<P>
   In France, Leon Blum headed the Popular Front Socialist regime
in the 1930s, ``after which he was jailed by the Nazis,'' Hertzberg
said. Pierre Mendes-France and Rene Mayer held power briefly in the
1950s.
</P>
<P>
   Remi Marechaux, the press attache at the French embassy in
Washington, said that a politician's religion typically does not
take center stage in France, suggesting that some French voters
might even be unaware of the religion of their candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In Austria, the Socialist Bruno Kreisky served as chancellor in
the 1970s and '80s after spending World War II in exile in Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   In Victorian England, Benjamin Disraeli (baptized in the
Anglican church) spoke and wrote frequently about his Jewish
heritage in the course of a long political career in which he twice
served as prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in the Western world regarded Disraeli as a Jew even
though his father in a fit of pique at the London synagogue had
converted him before his bar mitzvah,'' Hertzberg said.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore picked Lieberman for reasons other than
his religion, which is as it should be, he said. ``You can argue
that Lieberman's nomination came on time just as Kennedy's
nomination came on time 40 years ago,'' he said. ``In a country
this complicated and plural, who is going to throw rocks, a few old
Ku Kluxers?''
</P>
<P>
   But Deborah Lipstadt, the director of Judaic Studies at Emory
University, said that Lieberman's nomination deserves the
spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're talking about a man who is two generations away from
immigrants, whose father drove a bakery truck, who is a traditional
Jew,'' Lipstadt said.
</P>
<P>
   She agreed, though, that the self-congratulatory tone may be a
bit strong, given that such barriers still stand for blacks and
Hispanics, and only once has a woman, Democrat Geraldine Ferraro in
1984, been a major party's candidate for vice president.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only in America may be too much,'' Lipstadt said. ``But maybe
thank God, at long last in America.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
