<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 14:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6689 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-TWINS0820-COX     08-19 1335
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWINS0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Together by choice
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WHITE PLAINS, N.C. _ They're buried as they lived, side by side,
in a plot that seems at once too small for their stature and a
perfect fit with their surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   Their grave marker is no bigger or more ornate than most others
in the cemetery located behind the small white Baptist church they
helped build on land they donated nearly 150 years ago. The few
facts carved in stone _ Chang and Eng came into the world together
on May 11, 1811, and died together on Jan. 17, 1874 _ barely
scratch the surface of this richly complex, real-life saga of the
original Siamese twins.
</P>
<P>
   They surely were among the most exotically foreign creatures
this part of the world had ever seen. And yet their story _ and
that of their descendants _ is quintessentially American.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once when I was 8 or 9, we were sitting around the table at
home talking about famous people,'' recalls Milton Haynes, 64, of
Raleigh. ``And I said, `Who are we?' I can still remember my daddy
saying, `You can tell 'em we're descended from Siamese twins.' ''
</P>
<P>
   It's the last Saturday in July, and Haynes is waiting his turn
in a long buffet line in the White Plains Recreational Building. To
his right, the U.S. and North Carolina flags are displayed on a
beige brick wall. Dead ahead, a couple of tables laid end-to-end
nearly buckle beneath the weight of homemade casseroles, platters
of chicken and bowls of baked beans and banana pudding. The excited
chatter of reunited cousins and great-aunts fills what little air
circulates in the low-slung building.
</P>
<P>
   It could be any one of countless family reunions held in small
Southern towns on sultry summer afternoons. On their name tags,
Haynes and his wife, Chase, also have printed the name ``Chang.''
Across the room, Jessie Bunker Bryant, a statuesque woman in her
early 70s bent low over a table of fat notebooks filled with
genealogical information, has written ``Eng'' on hers.
</P>
<P>
   So has Sarah Bunker, at 11 one of the youngest of the
approximately 150 descendants of the twins packed into this small
building.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how many `greats' I am,'' sighs Sarah, who has no
siblings and shudders slightly at the thought of being permanently
attached to a certain pesky young relative.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, most family ties are figurative. For Chang and Eng
Bunker, they were literal, although it is the way the two men
worked with, around and through their condition, rather than the
physical oddity itself, that their descendants come together to
recall and celebrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They left us a great legacy,'' says Tom Atkins, 39, the
self-described ``youngest great-grandchild'' (by Eng), who moved
three years ago from Gwinnett County to Winston-Salem.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine taking off from home for a foreign country when you're
still a kid and doing what they did. I don't know how anyone could
do that, let alone people in their situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Born in what is now Thailand, connected by a band of cartilage
at the base of the breastbone, Chang and Eng unwittingly spawned
the phrase Siamese twins (the accepted term now is ``conjoined'')
and were initially considered to be such a bad omen that they were
ordered put to death. Though they were spared, even being invited
at age 13 to visit the Bangkok palace of King Rama III, Chang and
Eng's shared life was hardly their own for years.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the twins turned 18, a Scottish trader paid a
small sum of money to the boys' mother and got permission from the
king to take them to New York. ``The Siamese Double Boys,'' as an
exhibition poster billed them, spent the next three years touring
the United States and Great Britain with an act that largely
featured them tumbling and audiences staring at them curiously. In
Britain alone, more than 300,000 people paid to see them. But after
promoters and exhibitors took their cuts, there was little money
left for the twins. Soon after turning 21, the twins went into
business for themselves in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   By 1839, Chang and Eng were in need of a vacation and a career
change. They found both in Wilkesboro, N.C., where they applied for
U.S. citizenship and set about becoming farmers in an area known as
Trap Hill. Adopting an arbitrary last name, Bunker, they began
sinking roots. In a double ceremony in April 1843, Chang married
Adelaide Yates, with whom he would eventually have 10 children, and
Eng married her sister, Sallie, with whom he would have 11. In
1845, the two growing families moved to a bigger house on a large
piece of farmland near Mount Airy.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Mount Airy is best known as the picturesque birthplace of
TV's Andy Griffith. Its downtown is dotted with a Floyd's City
Barbershop, a Snappy Lunch and other establishments offering fond
reminders or actual souvenirs of the fictional Mayberry. But in the
mid-1800s, the Bunker twins _ having toured with P.T. Barnum and
appeared onstage around the world _ loomed largest in this area.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the I-74 connector highway runs through what was once
their vast expanse of farmland in White Plains. The original White
Plains Baptist Church stands on their donated land, not far from
Bunker Road. The ``double chop'' method Chang and Eng developed to
fell large trees is still used by pairs of woodchoppers.
</P>
<P>
   The Bunkers grew tobacco, among other crops, and owned slaves.
</P>
<P>
   Sue Shoemaker, a Duluth resident who accompanied her husband,
Dick, an Eng descendant, to his third reunion this year, summed it
up: ``They apparently fit in.''
</P>
<P>
   It may have been their biggest accomplishment.
</P>
<P>
   But life wasn't perfect in White Plains. The Civil War nearly
destroyed the twins financially, and it touched them emotionally as
each saw his eldest son march off to fight for the Confederate
cause. By then, their families had grown too big and the tension
level had risen too high to be contained in one house. In 1857, the
twins divided their farm in two along Stewart's Creek and
alternated living in each house for three days at a time. Each man
was treated as the master in his own house.
</P>
<P>
   Fast-forward now to 1989. A Thai TV producer contacted Milton
Haynes in Raleigh. Could Haynes, a great-grandson of Chang, get a
bunch of the descendants together for a documentary being done on
the twins?
</P>
<P>
   The two sides of the family hadn't held a joint reunion for as
long as anyone could remember.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were always known as `the other side of the creek' to
us,'' says Haynes, who thinks it was simply a matter of so many
descendants becoming so spread out over time. ``And we to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Haynes contacted Jessie Bunker Bryant, one of Eng's
great-granddaughters, and the resulting reunion at a church in
Wallberg, N.C., drew about 175 people. Since then, Chang and Eng
descendants from as far away as Idaho and Washington state have
come to North Carolina for the annual reunion held on the last
Saturday in July.
</P>
<P>
   ``We figured since these two gentlemen had never been separated,
we should try to get together,'' says Haynes, inching his way along
the buffet line at this year's gathering.
</P>
<P>
   Surely the most unlikely guest at this year's reunion was
30-year-old Darin Strauss of New York. Strauss' first novel,
``Chang and Eng,'' was published this summer to much acclaim.
Starting with details from the twins' history, Strauss broadened
his story into a haunting exploration of themes relating to
identity and the conflicting need to belong to someone else and to
break away. ``A spirited _ and promising _ debut,'' the New York
Times chief book critic wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Some descendants' reviews were less glowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really tried to be objective, but I just can't be,'' says
Tanya Rees, 50, a great-great-granddaughter of Eng and the
executive director of the Surry County Arts Council, housed in the
Andy Griffith Playhouse. ``In terms of interest and fascination,
it's really hard to improve on the truth about their lives. From a
family perspective, it's quite disappointing t
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
