<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Know where you're headed with digital compass
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ You may remember a time when you were a kid and
you got a toy compass.
</P>
<P>
   Those cheesy little devices featured a jiggling needle balanced
on a pin, and the painted end of the needle always pointed north.
Unless there was a magnet nearby or the needle fell off the pin.
</P>
<P>
   Today you can carry around a digital device that does the same
thing more reliably. The Co-Pilot from Precision Navigation Inc.
gives you a digital readout that tells you exactly which way you're
headed with an accuracy of plus or minus 5 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   The Co-Pilot comes in three models and the basic model, the
V500, is designed to be used exclusively in a car. The unit
attaches to the windshield and gives continual readouts of the
car's direction of travel.
</P>
<P>
   The compass warns the driver if its readings are being distorted
by outside influences such as a nearby metal bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The device is 2.5-by-2.5 inches, and has large digits that are
illuminated for night navigation.
</P>
<P>
   Precision Navigation also makes two other Co-Pilot models, the
V550 and V600, that are designed to be used both inside and outside
the car.
</P>
<P>
   Co-Pilots can be ordered from www.precisionnav.com. The
compasses also are available from specialty retailers such as
Sharper Image.
</P>
<P>
   The V500 sells on the Web site for $39.95, the V550 costs
$49.95, and the V600 for vehicle and handheld use sells for $59.95.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
