A6691 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-LIEBERMAN-SABBATH0820     08-19 0452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIEBERMAN-SABBATH0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't be fooled; nobody follows Bible to the letter
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Sen. Joseph Lieberman chooses which
biblical laws to follow literally and which he will modify to suit
his needs.
</P>
<P>
   Most religious conservatives condemn that approach. But Jesus
would applaud it.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman does not drive on the Sabbath because rabbis teach
that driving is a form of prohibited work, and he is an observant
Jew.
</P>
<P>
   But the Democratic vice presidential nominee often does hard
work on the Sabbath that he has decided the Bible permits.
</P>
<P>
   He admits walking to his office on the Jewish day of rest to
consider and cast votes in the Senate, shuffle papers and attend
meetings. But that work is for the public good, he insists, and is,
therefore, allowed by the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   Critics say that is playing fast and loose with Holy Writ and
amounts to taking a ride on the slippery slope to moral relativity,
where they fear anything goes.
</P>
<P>
   They insist that the Bible be read literally and followed
religiously. But no one does that. No one ever has.
</P>
<P>
   All people of faith, despite what they say, are selective
literalists. That is, like Lieberman, they accept parts of
Scripture literally. They liberally interpret other parts or simply
ignore them.
</P>
<P>
   There is good precedent for doing so. David took forbidden bread
from the tabernacle to feed his troops. Jesus healed on the
Sabbath. He forgave the woman taken in adultery when stoning was
the biblical remedy.
</P>
<P>
   Neither Jew nor Christian follows the biblical laws for ritual
sacrifice in the Hebrew Scripture. Yet, none has been repealed.
</P>
<P>
   Some Christians insist that the sacrifice of Jesus made them
unnecessary, but they are still on the books to be followed by
those who claim to read Scripture literally.
</P>
<P>
   Most Christians manipulate the Ten Commandments to make Sunday
the Sabbath in place of Saturday. Seventh-Day Adventists do follow
the commandment to hallow the actual Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   The great majority of Christians believe the literal teaching
about the death and resurrection of Jesus that is the heart of
their faith.
</P>
<P>
   But few Christians in this day of family values and the
condemnation of homosexuality follow St. Paul's strong
recommendation to avoid marriage.
</P>
<P>
   And no one, save the lunatic fringe, follows his advice that
married couples should live together as brother and sister (1Co
7:29).
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman is confident in his faith. He accepts parts of God's
word literally and interprets the rest.
</P>
<P>
   All people of faith do. Some just won't admit it.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
