A6693 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-LIES0820-COX     08-19 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIES0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Conduct unbecoming
 &HT;    By Maria Mallory
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ You don't want much: just a fair wage for an honest
day's work.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, many workers say that fairness, honesty and
integrity are far too often absent from the workplace.
</P>
<P>
   The consulting firm KPMG recently reported in its 2000
Organizational Survey, which was released this spring, that
American workers are witnessing a high level of illegal and
unethical conduct on the job. Workers say the misbehavior is
serious, the firm reports, and that Corporate America is doing very
little to deal with the problems effectively and may even be
discouraging employees from reporting problems to their superiors.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers don't look good. Seventy-six percent of employees
across all industries admitted to observing violations of the law
or company policy during 1999. And 49 percent of those employees
said they believed if the misconduct they observed were made
public, their employers would ``significantly lose public trust,''
the consulting firm said.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the law isn't at issue, in much of the American
workplace, there is a corporate culture of lying. And it seems to
be getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   All the layoffs of the last 15 years have eroded the trust and
respect between employers and employees. And just as parents tell
their young children when they catch them in a white lie, people
can get into the habit of lying. Once they do, it's a hard habit to
break.
</P>
<P>
   If you want to buck the trend and make a go for that fair pay,
honest work deal, it's best to try upfront to get a sense of the
integrity of a potential employer.
</P>
<P>
   Although standards and codes of conduct vary by industry, says
Win Swenson, national managing director of KPMG's integrity
management services, your bosses ``need to have standards that are
going to tell people what it is they are supposed to do.'' So, the
first thing to look for when sizing up the company is a written
code of conduct, he advises.
</P>
<P>
   ``If companies have good published statements of here's our code
of conduct, that's (an) indication that people in the company think
this important enough to talk about. That's a good sign,'' Swenson
says.
</P>
<P>
   Second, management ought to have a system in place to monitor if
the codes and standards are being kept. ``There needs to be a
management structure to ensure that compliance and ethics are
occurring,'' Swenson says. ``It's not enough to say `Here are the
standards' and (management) not ensure that things are happening''
in accordance with them, he says.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, a company that is serious about promoting a
workplace of integrity and ethical business practices will also
have performance measurements and systems in place to reward
employees who measure up to or exceed them.
</P>
<P>
   When something does go wrong, an employee must have a safe and
confidential way of reporting misconduct without fear. ``There has
to be a healthy way by which people can raise issues,'' Swenson
says. ``If there's generally a shoot-the-messenger mentality about
the raising of ethical issues, people certainly won't raise them.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, says Swenson, companies that are serious about an
ethical and honest work environment will thoroughly communicate
their standards to employees and provide training that helps
workers achieve their stated performance goals.
</P>
<P>
   Judging how your future employer is faring may take some
investigation, but it's time well spent, Swenson says. Start by
checking the corporate Web site.
</P>
<P>
   Says Swenson, ``If they do make their code of conduct available
on the Web site, evaluate it this way: Where is the CEO? Does the
CEO have a cover letter? How does it strike you? Is he behind it?
Or is it a perfunctory statement? A little bit of a threat? How do
you as a reader react to it? If it sounds real, there's a better
chance that it is.''
</P>
<P>
   If you can't find a code of conduct or statement of company
standards online, ask for a written copy, Swenson says. ``It is not
in any way a taboo to say, `I'm just curious how you guys look at
this stuff,' '' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Other ways to find out? Swenson suggests asking, ``How will I be
evaluated?'' ``What will it take for me to be promoted?''
</P>
<P>
   If you're concerned, you definitely should ask, he says. By
asking, ``You run the risk of suggesting that ethics is important
to you, but it may be a risk you want to run,'' Swenson says.
</P>
<P>
   You might also conduct an Internet or news database search for
reports on company performance and conduct, Swenson advises. ``Find
out what comes up with the company,'' he says. ``Have they been
involved with some aromatic litigation or that sort or thing?''
</P>
<P>
   If you run across something, don't hesitate to ask management
about it. Don't just jump to conclusions, Swenson counsels. ``I've
seen bad things happen at very good companies, and what they do is
try to do better. If you've found it, I wouldn't cross the company
off the list at all. I'd ask about it. If you find a whole lot of
it and the industry scuttlebutt is that that is just how this
company operates, then that's a different story.''
</P>
<P>
   Lastly, talk to folks who work at the company, Swenson says.
They can be an invaluable source of information about the work
environment and ethical standards at a company.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ask them what it's really like here,'' Swenson says. ``People
tend to be happier at companies that do manage these issues well.
They don't feel good if they feel they are working in an
environment where they feel _ even subtly _ that they are being
pressured to work in an unethical environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
