<HEADER>
A6694 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-SCHOOL-ADVICE0820-COX     08-19 0945
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-ADVICE0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Chalk it up to mutual understanding
 &HT;    By Jim DeBrosse
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Can we talk?
</P>
<P>
   With the school year approaching, it's time for teachers and
parents to reopen the lines of communication.
</P>
<P>
   Everybody agrees that children learn best when education becomes
a team effort between families and schools. But often teachers are
afraid of losing their authority and parents are just too busy for
much partnering to occur.
</P>
<P>
   To save everyone time and stress, we asked working teachers and
frenzied moms and dads exactly what advice they would give the
other side in order to make this school year the most productive
ever.
</P>
<P>
   Here are lists of the top suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT TEACHERS WISH PARENTS WOULD REMEMBER:
</P>
<P>
   _ Get to know your child's teacher. ``Share the news from home.
Teachers want to celebrate good things in a child's life and want
to offer support and understanding during times of trial,'' said
Judy Whelley, a teacher coach.
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't overschedule your child. ``They're so involved in their
other activities _ dancing, soccer, music lessons _ they're tired
when they come to school, or they haven't done their homework,''
said Susan Lightcap, an elementary school teacher. ``School should
come first.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Make sure they're rested. ``Start with an early bedtime well
before school starts, so they're in the habit of going to bed on
time,'' said Beverly Horowitz, an early childhood instructor.
</P>
<P>
   _ Provide a comfortable, well-lit homework area. Check homework
daily, but also encourage your child to work independently, Whelley
said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Model reading and writing. ``Talk with your child about
something from the newspaper or from a book you're reading. Let
them see you making grocery lists, writing notes . . .,'' Whelley
said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Go to the library. Use your card and be sure your child has
his or her own card, Whelley said. ``It's important to keep your
child reading over the summer, whether it's from library books or
newspapers,'' said Lori Anger, a teacher at McKinley Elementary in
Xenia.
</P>
<P>
   _ Limit television time. Encourage your child to be physically
active and to spend time doing household chores, talking with
family members, playing board games and more, Whelley said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Read to your child daily. ``Establish a time every day that is
inviolate, that you don't allow anything else to interfere with,''
said Becky Brunsman, who teaches kindergarten. Two good resource
books are ``The New Read Aloud Handbook'' by Jim Trelease (1995);
and ``Black Books Galore! A Guide to Great African American
Children's Books,'' by Donna Rand, Toni Trent Parker and Sheila
Foster (Wiley, $15.95).
</P>
<P>
   _ Keep your child in school. ``Don't schedule camping trips and
vacations during the school year,'' Lightcap said. ``They can't
learn if they're not here.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Visit school often. Don't just put in face time at
parent-teacher conferences. ``Come for the special performances and
happenings,'' Whelley said. ``Stop by during the day once in a
while to observe your child in class and meet classmates. If at all
possible, volunteer.''
</P>
<P>
   WHAT PARENTS WISH TEACHERS WOULD REMEMBER:
</P>
<P>
   _ Dare to discipline. ``Be assertive. You are the authority
figure in the classroom, not the students. They need and expect
this,'' said Richard Melson, who has four children in the Dayton
public school system.
</P>
<P>
   _ Stress the value of education. ``Because the kids are dropping
out. They don't want to go to school,'' said Martina Rose McKever,
whose daughter Elita is entering third grade.
</P>
<P>
   _ Accept each child as an individual. ``Keep an open mind and
accept the child for what they are,'' said Edward Breen, a parent.
</P>
<P>
   _ Be a friend. ``I know teachers want to start out the school
year knowing that they have control of their classroom,'' said
Patty Nogle, whose youngest daughter Jenny graduated last year from
high school. ``But they have to be approachable, so the kids aren't
just floundering on their own.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Do not try to be a friend. Yes, parents are split on this
issue. But many insist buddying up with students is a bad idea.
``Especially at the high school level. . . . Children do not always
understand why you must `come down on them' if you're their
friend,'' Melson said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Set high standards and expect children to meet them.
``Teachers should do that instead of settling for mediocrity,''
said Georgia Cox, who has two childrenin elementary school. ``They
should treat children as though they expect them to rise to the
level they have set.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Communicate often. ``The bottom line is communication both
ways,'' said Noreen Atkins, a parent and teacher. ``The student
really benefits when he knows that parents and teachers are in
constant communication.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Prepare families before school starts. ``My children would
rather have open house before school starts to give them a chance
to see where things are in the building and to meet their
teachers,'' said Suzanne Geisler. ``The first week of school we get
so many fliers and forms they're overwhelming. . . . I wish I could
get those before school started so I would have a little more time
to go through them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Be honest. ``You are human and will make a mistake. Let both
the parent and student know that you understand this,'' Melson
said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Do more guided self-learning and less lecturing. ``I think
children really learn best . . . when they are actively engaged in
the process of finding out things on their own,'' said Mary Walker,
who has a child in high school.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
