u s BC-RUN-DISABLED-MARATHON     08-19 0908
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-DISABLED-MARATHON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISILLUSIONED, DISABLED RACERS TURN THEIR BACKS ON NYC MARATHON 
</HEADLINE>
   By DIANE HERBST   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Disabled marathoners will have another opportunity to
compete in New York City next year, in the Achilles Marathon,
scheduled for April 1 in Prospect Park in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   But officials of the Achilles Track Club, an athletic group for
the disabled and the organizers of the new race, say that getting
approval for the marathon as well as maintaining their status quo
in the New York City Marathon has not happened without a struggle.
The result, at least to Achilles, is that its relationship with the
New York Road Runners Club, which runs the New York City Marathon,
has deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there is a conscious and deliberate attempt to
diminish the contribution of disabled runners,'' said state Sen.
David A. Paterson, who is legally blind and ran in last year's New
York City Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Laufer, general counsel for the Road Runners, says the
club is neither anti-Achilles nor anti-disabled.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pro-athletes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Achilles was created as part of the Road Runners before becoming
a separate nonprofit organization. A sign of its independence is
the creation of its eponymous marathon _ with 500 disabled and
1,500 able-bodied athletes, including elite competitors _ and one
that its members say was supported enthusiastically by City Hall
last fall. But, said Dick Traum, who runs the Achilles club,
support from city officials later vanished.
</P>
<P>
   ``From November on, it sounded like someone stepped in and put a
halt to it, and the only reasons would have been the arrogance of
power and political connections,'' said Paterson, a Democrat from
upper Manhattan serving his 15th year who joined the board of
Achilles at the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of a sudden it became hush-hush and by March it was
over,'' Paterson said. ``When you work in government, you learn to
recognize the signals. When people are all for something and then
no one talks, you know someone played a card.''
</P>
<P>
   In March, the marathon gained approval after Traum met with
Parks Commissioner Henry Stern, who determined that the marathon
would indeed be held in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   ``Henry came to the rescue,'' said Traum, himself a disabled
marathoner whose right leg was amputated after a car accident.
``He's the one who said `Let's go ahead with it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Stern denied that support from City Hall had waned, but he said
that the Road Runners and the city were not going to support a
marathon that would be in Central Park, where the Achilles race was
originally proposed, in direct competition with the New York City
Marathon.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are people in the Road Runners club who didn't want to
extend themselves and why should they?'' Stern said. ``They've
spent years building up the New York City Marathon.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The issue was when and where,'' Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Steinfeld, the Road Runners president, did not return
repeated calls for comment. Laufer said that although he did not
know about anyone trying to block the new marathon, ``people had
differing opinions'' about holding it.
</P>
<P>
   The Achilles Marathon is not the only disabled issue facing the
Road Runners. In January, the club settled a discrimination suit
filed by another group of disabled athletes, agreeing to create a
separate division for wheelchair athletes in the New York City
Marathon. In March, the Road Runners announced that this division
will be highly competitive and will include prize money next year.
</P>
<P>
   But the gains for the professional wheelchair athlete threatened
to affect the nonelite disabled athlete negatively. The Road
Runners decided to cancel the 8 a.m. start for about 100 disabled
athletes severely slowed by multiple sclerosis, organ transplants,
heart problems, amputations or age who need extra time to complete
the 26.2-mile race before dark.
</P>
<P>
   Marathon organizers said the early start was canceled because of
safety concerns. These competitors would already be on the course
when elite wheelchair racers sped by. Instead, the slowest
participants would have been placed at the back of the pack, behind
the 30,000 able-bodied runners at the Verrazano Narrows Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   But on Aug. 1, following months of protest from Achilles
members, marathon organizers ruled that the disabled would start at
8:50 a.m., two hours before the main start on Nov. 5.
</P>
<P>
   While some Achilles members say it's better than no early start
at all, others remain furious.
</P>
<P>
   ``That extra hour means so much, it means finishing in daylight,
not in the cold, it makes it safer, it means finishing with the
support of the crowds at the end,'' said Maureen Lally, 47. She has
malformed hips and couldn't walk more than half a block until she
started training with Achilles. She finished the 1998 and 1999
marathons in over nine hours. ``Why after 24 years would you change
it?''
</P>
<P>
   In July, the Road Runners made another significant change, one
that has not been reversed: ousting Traum from the club's board of
directors, after he had served 24 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're trying to stick it to me,'' said Traum, who said there
is now no voice in the Road Runners for Achilles.
</P>
<P>
   Laufer disagrees with Traum's assessment. While declining to
comment on Traum's ouster from the board, citing confidentiality
restrictions, he said the board ``acted in the best interests of
the club.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
