<HEADER>
A6696 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-MURALS0820-COX     08-19 0442
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MURALS0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Blending art with nature
 &HT;    By John Head
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. _ When the Bird House at Riverbanks Zoo in
Columbia, S.C., opens early next year, visitors will experience the
beauty of birds and their habitats. And, as added treats, there
will be the works of muralist David Rock.
</P>
<P>
   But Rock wants his lush paintings to be wallflowers, both
literally and figuratively. He hopes people will appreciate them
without even realizing they're there.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm successful, you're not really supposed to notice my
work,'' says Rock, who has done murals for zoos and aquariums
around the country. ``It should be a continuation of what people
are seeing around them.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Riverbanks Zoo Bird House, what people see around them
will be 14,000 square feet of displays of tropical birds from
Africa and South America, as well as penguins. The $5 million
expansion of the aviary is part of $20 million in improvements
under way at the 26-year-old zoo.
</P>
<P>
   Satch Krantz, executive director of the zoo, says the expansion
isn't about having more birds in the facility; rather, the intent
is to improve the way the various species are displayed. He says
zoo officials wanted Rock's paintings in the Bird House because of
the reputation he has established with his work for the Bronx Zoo
in New York, the Cleveland Zoo, the Shedd Aquarium in Chicago and
other places.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's extremely well-known in the zoo community,'' Krantz says.
``He's considered the best among the handful of people who do
this.''
</P>
<P>
   Rock's career as a zoo muralist started in a roundabout way. He
graduated from college with an art degree, but he went to work as a
carpenter. While putting up scaffolding for a zoo mural, Rock met
an artist who encouraged him to switch from a hammer to an
airbrush.
</P>
<P>
   Rock says he likes to keep a certain amount of spontaneity in
his work, changing colors or repainting scenes if what he's done
doesn't suit him. However, there was one thing he was certain he
wanted to include as soon as he saw drawings of the Bird House
design that showed a creek flowing up to one of the building's
walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm creating the illusion that the creek continues into the
building,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike other exhibits for which he created one large painting,
projects where he created one large painting for an exhibit, Rock's
work at Riverbanks Zoo involves a variety of habitats.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what makes this more fun,'' Rock says. ``Rather than
painting one scene, there's a good diversity of things here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
