<HEADER>
A6698 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-GYMNASTICS-NYT &LR;      08-19 0846
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-GYMNASTICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLACING FIRST IN OLYMPIC TRIALS, GYMNAST AIMS FOR NICHE 
</HEADLINE>
   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It was hours before the preliminaries of the U.S.
Olympic trials on Friday when anxiety began creeping into Elise
Ray's thoughts like smoke slithering under a door.
</P>
<P>
   Gradually, she was consumed by trepidation as she went through
her morning practice. This wasn't normal at all. Usually, she is
jitter-proof, butterfly-free. After all, Ray was the unflappable
gymnast who managed to stay in one piece while her neophyte
teammates crumbled around her at the forgettable 1999 world
championships. And Ray was the confident risk-taker who
spontaneously increased the difficulty of her final vault to place
first at the nationals in July.
</P>
<P>
   But now there was the burden of expectation on her compact
frame, and there was the unnerving upheaval surrounding the
subjective selection process for the six-woman Olympic team. Was
the national champion safely on her way to Sydney, Australia, if
she slipped out of first at the trials?
</P>
<P>
   ``I was feeling the pressure more than I expected to,'' Ray said
late Friday. ``I went back to my hotel room after the morning
workout, calmed down, closed my eyes and did a little visualizing
before the meet. I just thought about each of my routines and
thought positively.''
</P>
<P>
   This daughter of a psychotherapist had found her own solution to
her jangled mental state. She took the edge off her fears, settled
her mind and then delivered an unwavering performance that left her
in first place after the preliminary round of the trials.
</P>
<P>
   By combining her top score from nationals with her work so far
at the trials, Ray seems as if she's certain to make the team if
she can maintain a lofty standing through the finals Sunday night.
If anyone might safely expect to make the team, it's Ray. At least,
for now.
</P>
<P>
   But there are no guarantees. As the blustery voice of a
selection panel that will choose the team just minutes after
Sunday's finals, Bela Karolyi has made it clear that he will not be
bound by the order of finish. With the 18-year-old Ray leading a
new generation that is trying to pry an Olympic opportunity from
the 1996 golden oldies _ 1996 gold medalists Shannon Miller and
Dominique Dawes, both now 23, and Amy Chow, now 22 _ some wonder if
the scores of young and old will mean anything at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't know what will happen,'' said Vanessa Atler, who
fell to sixth place over all after blowing her dismount on the
balance beam. ``If Bela doesn't like you, you could be out the
door. If Bela does like you, it's OK if you mess up. It's a
difficult situation for a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   It's obvious that Karolyi's comfort zone with those gymnasts who
once wowed the world in Atlanta does count for something. He has
watched Chow and Dawes improve their performances since nationals.
And he seems to have faith in Miller, America's most decorated
gymnast, even though she had a bad fall on the vault.
</P>
<P>
   ``The veterans all have the edge,'' said Miller's coach, Steve
Nunno, who watched his pupil finish seventh in the preliminaries.
``I think Bela knows that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray understands that, too. And she embraces all of the former
gold medal winners at the meet as her close friends, but she is
also eager to carve out her own niche in women's gymnastics.
</P>
<P>
   Although it is not her motivation, Ray realizes the adulation,
attention and financial boost she would receive by doing well in
the Olympics. In small but uplifting ways, she has already begun to
be recognized, like inside the malls around her hometown of
Columbia, Md.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was also in a bank and wrote my name on the slip and was
recognized, so that was fun,'' Ray said. ``It's kind of nice to
have people notice you.''
</P>
<P>
   It's hard to miss Ray on the arena floor as well. Belying her
sunny last name, Ray isn't one of those gymnasts who pastes on a
phony game show-host exuberance when she performs. The intensity
she revealed when nailing a 9.812 on her first event of Friday
night, the uneven bars, did not change even in the more graceful
moments of her high-flying floor routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm comfortable with my level of pizazz,'' Ray said, smiling
after the competition, on the heels of a 9.8 on the floor exercise.
``You have to balance personality with how much focus you need. I
think the judges look for a general air about you, like confidence.
Everyone, whether they feel it or not, tries to put off an air of
confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   For a few hours Friday afternoon, Ray's faith was a little
unsteady. But she found comfort in visualization and peace from a
tiny silver pin. Before every meet, Ray's family sends her a card
and an angel pin to stick on her USA team jacket. On Friday night,
she arrived in the interview room with a silver angel playing a
harp under her left lapel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a lot of pins,'' Ray said. ``I keep them all in a
little box at home. I think having one on reminds me that my family
is always with me, and in a way, it makes me feel a sense of
protection.''
</P>
</TEXT>
