<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Court could let Florida voters decide on high-speed rail
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ More than a year ago, Florida Gov. Jeb Bush derailed a
deal to build a French-style bullet train from Miami to Tampa.
</P>
<P>
   Too expensive, too uncertain, Bush explained in January 1999
when he killed state funding for the $6.3 billion project
</P>
<P>
   Now retired businessman C.C. ``Doc'' Dockery is one court
decision away from letting voters decide the fate of high-speed
trains in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Dockery met a deadline to produce more than 450,000
signatures from registered Florida voters. He is pushing a proposed
state constitutional amendment using a state statute that allows
citizens to put initiatives on the ballot if they get enough
verified signatures plus Florida Supreme Court approval.
</P>
<P>
   Dockery's attorney, a former Florida Supreme Court justice,
presented arguments to the state's highest court in June. If the
Florida Supreme Court complies with a request for an expedited
opinion, a ruling may come soon. A passion for trains and a love of
Florida led Dockery, 67, to propose the amendment. He wants to help
unclog Florida's interstates, loaded with commuters and tourists.
</P>
<P>
   Dockery, whose former company helped settle workers compensation
claims, said he would not profit by the amendment, which lacks only
state Supreme Court approval before landing on the Nov. 7 ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Since fall, Dockery estimates he's spent $1.5 million gathering
more than 600,000 signed petitions. He said he pushed forward after
positive reactions from four focus groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an investment, believe me. I've spent a lot of the
inheritance of my wife and kids. I'm just passionate about this,''
said Dockery, who served on the state's high-speed rail commission.
</P>
<P>
   His proposal would compel the governor and Legislature to begin
construction by November 2003 on a ``magnetic levitation'' train,
monorail or other high-speed ground transportation system that
travels on pathways separate from motor vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The prospective ballot question says the speed of the system
should exceed 120 mph and connect the state's five largest urban
areas.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida's 1996 fast-train deal with private companies,
planners envisioned the so-called Florida Overland Express (FOX), a
train based on French bullet-train technology.
</P>
<P>
   The Dockery amendment encourages a look at all technology
available.
</P>
<P>
   Magnetic levitation _ known to planners as ``maglev'' _ uses
magnetic currents to make train cars float on a guideway. Another
magnet propels the trains. Fully developed, such a maglev train
could exceed 500 mph, according to a report by the U.S. Army Corps
of Engineers.
</P>
<P>
   Experimental maglev trains are being developed in Germany and
Japan. Wendell Cox, a former member of the Los Angeles County
Transportation Commission and a frequent author on rail policy,
wrote that high-speed rail in Florida ``would not materially
improve the environment, air traffic congestion or highway traffic
congestion.''
</P>
<P>
   FOX planners, Cox said, overestimated potential ridership and
underestimate potential construction costs. Florida needs bigger
and better roads to fix gridlocked traffic.
</P>
<P>
   Cox said it would be wrong to construe Dockery's proposal as a
FOX resurrection, mainly because it calls for a speed of only 120
mph _ not truly high-speed rail, he said.
</P>
<P>
   French trains on which FOX would have been based could attain
220 mph or better.
</P>
<P>
   ``If 220 mph doesn't solve the problems, then a 120 mph train
isn't going to do it,'' Cox said.
</P>
<P>
   The federal General Accounting Office last year reported FOX
construction could run up to at least $8 billion. The GAO said
ridership might never be enough to offset operating costs.
</P>
<P>
   The FOX cost included $70 million a year from the Legislature
for 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Bush said, ``The only way I could see for this thing
to work would be for the state to accept greater and greater
liability, which was never the intention.''
</P>
<P>
   Dockery argued that through the referendum, Bush could develop a
high-speed system ``as expensive as he wants it to be or as
inexpensive as he wants it to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Dockery said Bush sent him an e-mail on the proposal, calling it
``interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the sum total of what he had to say to me,'' said
Dockery, a Republican supporter and a former lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   Bush officials did not return requests for comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The financial structure of this deal was not viable,'' the
governor said last year. ``I am absolutely convinced of that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
