<HEADLINE>
NEW SURVEY OF PROPERTY CAN HELP HOME BUYERS AVOID SNAGS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Boldface words should be set in italics.) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Good fences make good neighbors, right?
</P>
<P>
   But suppose your neighbor puts  &UR; his &LR;  fence on  &UR; your &LR;  property?
</P>
<P>
   ``This happens more frequently than most people think,'' said
William Selsberg, a Stamford, Conn., real estate lawyer. ``That's
why I always advise clients to get a new survey when they're buying
property. The problem is that only about 40 percent of them take my
advice.''
</P>
<P>
   Selsberg and other real estate lawyers say that any
boundary-line dispute _ including those involving misplaced fences,
sheds, shrubs, gardens, decks, pools, patios and driveways _ should
be addressed promptly and if possible resolved before closing to
avoid expensive, drawn-out backyard feuds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If there's going to be a problem with a property line, I want
to know about it before the closing takes place,'' Selsberg said.
``The last thing a lawyer wants to do is represent someone in a
closing and then have them end up in litigation five or 10 years
down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, he said, boundary-line problems can be readily
identified if the buyer obtains a new survey of the property before
the purchase. That is something many buyers are unwilling to do,
because a survey can cost $800 to $1,500 or more. Unfortunately,
Selsberg said, most lenders do not require a new survey as a
condition of providing a mortgage. Instead, lenders will often
accept an old survey if it is accompanied by an affidavit from the
seller indicating that there have been no changes since the prior
survey. The problem with that, Selsberg said, is that while sellers
may make such representations honestly, they may not be making them
accurately.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people believe they know where their boundary lines
are,'' he said. ``But then the day comes when they want to sell the
house, the new buyer gets a new survey, and they suddenly find out
that their neighbor's vegetable garden has been on their property
for the last 13 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Under ideal circumstances, Selsberg said, such problems can be
resolved with little more than a neighborly chat. But what happens
when there is bad blood between the two neighbors, or when the
neighbor who originally planted the garden moved and sold the house
to a new owner who now truly believes he is planting in dirt he
owns? And what happens if, instead of a garden, the neighbor has
erected a shed, a patio, a deck or even a pool?
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when you end up in litigation,'' Selsberg said. ``I had
a client in Westport who decided to clear some trees out of his
backyard. Unfortunately, he cleared some trees out of his
neighbor's yard, too. We ended up settling the case for $20,000.''
</P>
<P>
   John G. Hall, a real estate lawyer in New York's Staten Island,
said that in most cases the severity of a boundary-line
encroachment _ the legal term used to describe one property owner's
use of an adjoining owner's property _ depends on the degree of the
encroachment.
</P>
<P>
   ``Upstate, an encroachment of a foot or two may not be as
serious as a six-inch encroachment in the suburbs,'' he said. ``But
in Manhattan, an encroachment of an inch and a half could be a
disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   A serious encroachment, Hall said, could render title to the
property technically ``unmarketable.''
</P>
<P>
   That means that unless a prospective buyer agrees to buy the
property ``subject to'' the encroachment, the buyer could decline
to conclude the purchase unless the encroachment is removed. And
that could be a problem if the encroaching property owner is not
inclined to cooperate.
</P>
<P>
   Peter G. Brav, president of Good Deed Abstract, a title agency
in Valley Stream, N.Y., said that it was prudent to resolve
boundary-line issues even when an encroachment did not seem to
bother either owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a friend who bought a house, didn't do a new survey, and
found out only after he moved in that the fence he thought was on
his property was really a foot and a half onto the property of the
lady next door,'' Brav said. ``And although the lady didn't mind
having his fence on her property, when she died and a builder
bought the land, the builder quickly notified my friend that the
fence had to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Another major property-line problem, Brav said, can occur when
adjoining owners use the same driveway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most driveway easements are reciprocal agreements that are
spelled out in both deeds,'' he said, explaining that a reciprocal
easement occurs when each property owner grants the other the right
to use part of his or her land. ``But in some cases, there's
nothing in writing and nothing in the deeds, and that's where you
get into trouble.''
</P>
<P>
   Accordingly, Brav said, if a person is buying property and it is
clear that it will be necessary to use part of a neighbor's
driveway to get to a garage or parking area, the purchaser should
ensure that there is something in writing _ preferably in the deed
to the property _ giving him the right to use the driveway. In
fact, he said, even if there is an easement specified in the deed,
the purchaser should try to determine whether there are any special
conditions or agreements that govern the use of the neighbor's
property.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be issues of maintenance or repair of the driveway
that have been worked out between the former owner and the
neighbor,'' he said. While such agreements may not affect title to
the property, he said, they could have an impact on the
relationship between the new neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   Another reason to have a survey conducted when buying property
is to determine whether all of the improvements on the property
being bought are legal, within the property lines and do not
encroach on the neighbor's property.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know what a previous owner may have done with a
property that could later cause problems,'' said William Trang, an
engineer with the Staten Island surveying firm of Wohl &AMP; O'Mara.
Besides showing property lines, Trang noted, a survey also shows
the location of pools, decks fences and anything else that has been
added to the property.
</P>
<P>
   One common problem that purchasers encounter, he said, is buying
a house with a deck built without the required permits. ``It's not
only the size of the deck that's an issue,'' he said, ``but the
height and location as well.''
</P>
<P>
   For example, Trang said, it is not uncommon for decks built
without a permit to violate zoning code provisions that require the
deck to be a certain distance away from the side and rear property
lines.
</P>
<P>
   And while a new survey will not tell a prospective buyer whether
an improvement like a deck is legal, it does give the buyer's
lawyer the information he needs to obtain such a determination from
the local building department.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
