<HEADER>
A6710 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-ERSTAD-NYT &LR;      08-19 1028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ERSTAD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.D.)  
 ANGELS' ERSTAD HITS WITH ALL HE'S GOT
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Darin Erstad decided to give himself a week away from
baseball at the end of last season, a major concession. His
instinct has always been to try harder, and he had just finished a
frustrating season in which he batted .253, and he wanted to know
why. He wanted to understand.
</P>
<P>
   But he forced himself to take a vacation. Seven days, he
determined.
</P>
<P>
   After four days, he pulled out videotape at his home in Fargo,
N.D., and began reviewing his at-bats _ all of his at-bats _
charting the pitches, searching for trends. When he finished the
1999 season, Erstad did the same for all of his at-bats in 1998,
and all of his at-bats in 1997 and in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad, who had tried to keep hitting as simple as possible,
believes he has developed a better understanding of his swing and
his approach, as borne out by his production this year.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad is batting .358, and with 189 hits and six weeks to play
in the regular season, he has a chance to approach the
single-season record for hits. George Sisler had 257 hits for the
St. Louis Browns in 1920, and if Erstad maintains his current pace,
he would finish the year with 251.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad had two hits Friday, including the game-winning home run
off Mike Stanton in the top of the 11th inning, as the California
Angels came back from a five-run deficit to beat the New York
Yankees, 9-8.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad also saved the game for Anaheim in the bottom of the 10th
inning by making a spectacular diving catch in left-center field
with two outs and the winning run on third base; Roger Clemens
called it one of the three best catches he had seen in his 17 years
in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``He plays so hard,'' Joe Torre, the Yankees' manager, said.
``He's a throwback. I don't think there's ever a day they can hang
his jersey in his locker. They've always got to throw it in the
washer.''
</P>
<P>
   In an era when adolescents are often forced to specialize in one
particular sport, Erstad is something of a throwback. Growing up in
North Dakota, he played hockey and football and baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't say what my best sport was,'' Erstad said, ``but I can
say I was most comfortable on skates.''
</P>
<P>
   The baseball seasons were short, his instruction simple. Keep
your left elbow high when you hit, his father told him, the
standard advice given to all kids by their parents. Except that
Erstad turned out to be a better athlete than other kids, scoring
bundles of goals as a forward in hockey, punting for the University
of Nebraska on their national championship team in 1994. In spite
of his limited experience in baseball, the Mets drafted him in the
13th round in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad stayed in college and was the first pick in the 1995
draft. Yankees catcher Chris Turner was in the Anaheim organization
at that time and when Erstad advanced to Triple-A in 1996, Turner
and the others waited to see if Erstad was a prima donna, if he
would flash around his money. Erstad kept mostly to himself,
however, and played hard. Someone brought a hockey net into the
Vancouver clubhouse, just for fun, and someone donned the catcher's
gear and pretended to be a goalie _ not Turner. The puck they used
was small and hard and made of plastic, and Erstad's teammates
gawked as he peppered the fringes of the net with slap shots.
</P>
<P>
   Erstad jumped to the majors in 1996, hit .299 in 1997 and .296
in 1998. He was seen as a potential candidate for the most valuable
player award in 1999, but he started slowly and soon scouts
chattered about how he seemed to fight himself at the plate, how he
turned his intensity on himself and how it hurt him. It's the same
thing scouts once said about Yankees right fielder Paul O'Neill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The saying that people always give me is, `Try easier,''' said
Erstad, sitting at his locker in the visitors' clubhouse at Yankee
Stadium Friday.
</P>
<P>
   He looked his questioner directly in the eye and continued,
evenly. ``But I don't necessarily agree with that,'' he said.
``I've tried that, and I end up standing up there and not having
any intensity. You need to have an intensity, a calm intensity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to think how to put this into words. It's almost
like a volcano _ calm, calm, calm, building, building, building.
And then you go to swing and _ bwap!''
</P>
<P>
   His hands moved, as he mimicked the motion of a swing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't go, tight, tight, tight, and then swing,'' he continued.
``It's got to be bop-bop-bop, and then you go. Every time you
swing, you want to feel like you're exploding on the ball.
Sometimes I do that too early. You see a pitch you want to hit and
you try to reach back for more or want to hit it further and
harder. I do that, especially on fastballs.''
</P>
<P>
   Realizing all this, Erstad waited four days after last season
before diving into the videotape. ``People had told me, `Just
forget about it like it never happened,''' Erstad said. ``That just
never made any sense to me. So I said, OK, I'm going to stare this
thing in the face and figure out what the heck is going on. You
want to know: `What's going on out there? Why did I stink so
badly?'''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad does not possess the sweeping, arching swing typical of
left-handed batters; rather, he swings with a chopping motion,
almost downward. He made some mechanical adjustments he chooses not
to discuss, and tried to relax his approach. Rod Carew, the Angels'
former hitting coach, told Erstad repeatedly that he should ``take
what the pitchers give you'' _ in other words, if there is a tough
pitch outside, then hit it to left field, and if you get a good
pitch inside, then drive it. ``Maybe I was too stubborn last
year,'' Erstad said.
</P>
<P>
   He singled in his first at-bat this year, against the Yankees,
went 9 for 14 in that three-game series and batted .449 in April.
He has 62 multihit games, 12 more than any other American League
player.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill said: ``He's an intense player, and after last year, he
came back and really found his confidence in April. He has just
battled and battled to the point where he's probably afraid to go
back to where he was.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-00 1506EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
