<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 15:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6713 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-SUB-0820-COX     08-19 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUB-0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BRITISH RESCUE TEAM ARRIVES AMID REPORTS SUB CREW LIKELY ALREADY
DEAD
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ A British rescue team reached the waters above the
foundered submarine Kursk early Saturday evening, hours after a top
Russian navy official said that the 118 crewmembers aboard probably
are already dead.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear how the British team, equipped with a
state-of-the-art rescue mini-submarine, would proceed. British
officials have said that the team's only mission has been to save
lives, but it had become clear that this goal may have been
impossible even before they departed from Scotland on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Commander David Russell, who is with the team, told the
BBC that his crew intended to proceed until they are certain there
are no survivors. ``It may be that it's a simply an impossible
task, but we're going to keep going until we know until there's
nothing more we can do,'' Russell said.
</P>
<P>
   As the rescue team was approaching the site on the Barents Sea,
a top Russian navy official went on live television to tell his
country that the crewmembers almost certainly were all dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hard as it is to say this, we will most likely have to say
that our worst expectations have come true,'' said Vice Adm.
Mikhail Motsak the head of the navy's general staff. He made the
statement sitting grimly behind his desk in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   He said a colossal explosion sent the Kursk to the seabed in
seconds killing most off the crew almost immediately. A Russian
government commission investigating the disaster said the explosion
was apparently in the forward torpedo compartment, which was loaded
with up to 30 conventional warheads.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the submarine hit the seabed at high speed, its torpedoes
apparently detonated,'' Motsak said. ``Most likely the whole of the
front section of the submarine has been flooded and the staff in
those sections died in the first minutes of the accident.''
</P>
<P>
   The surviving crewmembers tapped out messages on the Kursk's
hull after the accident describing their circumstances, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crew in the compartments in the stern were telling us that
water was filtering into their sections and they wanted us to
provide air supply.
</P>
<P>
   ``As water slowly filled the compartments in the stern the
pressure inside built up, inevitably reducing the life expectancy
of the crew and affecting their condition.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that the air pressure in the non-flooded compartments
must now be intolerable. ``There are pockets of air but in fact we
have crossed the critical survival threshold which we set for the
crew according to our guidelines,'' he said. ``We've been crossing
this threshold yesterday, today and maybe tomorrow. That is how I
see the situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moreover, I want to say that the absence of any signals from
the submarine leads us to conclude that the critical point has been
reached.''
</P>
<P>
   Motsak said the focus of the rescue mission was therefore
changing: ``I think that the essence of the second stage of the
operation we are conducting is to retrieve them, dead or alive, to
be able at least to give them their due on land.''
</P>
<P>
   He described the incident as ``the gravest disaster that I, as a
sailor, have known in the history of the submarine fleet.''
</P>
<P>
   Specially trained Norwegian divers are also on the way and are
expected to arrive Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian navy said it was eager to receive the assistance.
``We hope that the British or Norwegian rescuers will manage to do
at least something,'' navy spokesman Vladimir Navrotsky told
reporters in Murmansk, near the submarine's base. ``Even if one
person is saved, that will already be a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   The team, which arrived at about 11 a.m. (ET), was expected to
send down a remote-controlled, unmanned probe to carry out a
photographic reconnaissance of the submarine before launching the
30-foot LR5 mini-sub.
</P>
<P>
   In perhaps the only good news of the day, the weather in the
area had improved dramatically after whipping Russian rescue teams
with high waves and wind for nearly a week.
</P>
<P>
   Russian rescue teams have been gathered at the scene of the
accident for days, but high currents and zero visibility have
frustrated the rescue efforts. On Saturday, Russian rescue teams
failed to latch on to the badly damaged rescue hatch at the rear of
the submarine.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Saturday, navy spokesman Capt. Igor Dygalo said the
situation was 'beyond critical.''
</P>
<P>
   Adm. Vyacheslav Popov, commander of the Northern Fleet, said
there had been no contact of any kind with the submarine since
Monday despite repeated claims that knocking had been heard from
inside the vessel.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian navy had given wildly contradictory estimates of how
long the Kursk's emergency oxygen supplies could last, ranging from
a few hours to two weeks. But officials admitted they had no idea
of conditions inside the submarine.
</P>
<P>
   Russian officials have not determined precisely how the
submarine got into trouble in the first place. There have been no
reports of other vessels in the area with which the Kursk might
have collided. A likely scenario was that a torpedo in the Kursk's
forward compartment exploded, setting off a much bigger explosion.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. and Norwegian authorities detected two explosions in the
area Aug. 12 at the time the Kursk was lost. A Norwegian seismic
center said the second blast registered at magnitude 3.5,
equivalent to a mild earthquake.
</P>
<P>
   Many Russians are distressed that the military was slow to
accept help and are angry at President Vladimir Putin for keeping a
low profile and staying on vacation at a Black Sea resort when the
vessel went down.
</P>
<P>
   Putin returned to Moscow from Ukraine early Saturday, cutting
short his trip to a summit of former Soviet republics. He said he
did not fly to the rescue site because it would have been a
distraction to the recovery efforts.
</P>
<P>
   As bleak as the situation seems, it is impossible to rule out
the possibility that there are survivors, said a British submarine
expert. ``I have come across examples of men surviving a couple of
weeks in these kind of scenarios,'' said Commander Geoff Tall,
director of the Royal Navy Submarine Museum in Hampshire, England.
``We still have to go for it. It has to be worth it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s e-mail address is BertR(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.janes.com/
</P>
<P>
   http://www.government.gov.ru/english/
</P>
<P>
   http://www.mod.uk/
</P>
<P>
   http://www.perrytritech.com/pssub00.html
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
