<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 15:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6716 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-KNICKS-EWING-730&AMP;ADD-     08-19 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KNICKS-EWING-730&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS, PRESSED TO MAKE CHANGES, CONSIDER EWING TRADE 
</HEADLINE>
  By SELENA ROBERTS    c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   During their unsettling summer, the New York Knicks watched
Grant Hill ignore their welcome mat, failed to land free agents
like Brian Grant and Danny Fortson and watched their competition
get stronger. As a result, an organizational policy shift has taken
place, with the team pursuing deals to trade Patrick Ewing,
according to an Eastern Conference official.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Knicks officials would not comment on trade
discussions. But they have at least entertained the idea of dealing
Ewing before. In February, just before the trade deadline, there
was a brief conversation between the Knicks and Wizards that
involved Ewing. Ewing has a clause in his contract that gives him
the right to refuse any trade, but the Wizards would be a likely
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   As a Georgetown University hero, Ewing is beloved in Washington
and would be received with open arms. He has never been granted
such affection in his 15 seasons without a championship as a Knick,
and he would probably be receptive to returning to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they come to me with a deal, we'll talk about it then,''
Ewing said in an interview when the Wizards trade speculation arose
in February. ``Right now, all I can say is I'm playing for the
Knicks.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, there were heavy hints by Ewing that he could see
himself ending his career in another location. While he was
recovering from the partial tear in his Achilles' tendon early last
season and feeling more unappreciated by the organization and his
teammates, Ewing repeatedly mentioned Miami as a place he would
like to play.
</P>
<P>
   Now Seattle has emerged as a potential site for Ewing to play
out his career. Ewing has given the Knicks permission to shop him
and provided Knicks general manager Scott Layden with a list of
eight teams he would accept, The New York Daily News reported on
Saturday. Among them are the Wizards and Sonics. The Daily News
reported a deal for Sonics forward Vin Baker was being discussed.
The Sonics would likely be the more attractive team for Ewing,
considering that Seattle has the potential to be a playoff
contender.
</P>
<P>
   But any deal for Ewing is made cumbersome by the $14 million
salary he will make in the last year of his deal this coming
season. The Wizards would be in the best position to take on his
salary in an exchange that would involve Juwan Howard or Rod
Strickland going to the Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   With Ewing at the end of his contract, the Wizards would have
his cap space for next summer's free-agent crop. The only way for
Michael Jordan, the Wizards' head of basketball operations, to use
his cache to woo name players and build a playoff team is with cap
money. There is a catch, though _ Ewing is believed to want a
contract extension wherever he ends up. He has said he wants to
play at least two or three more years, a scenario few teams would
want to entertain for a 38-year-old. There could be a compromise,
though.
</P>
<P>
   If Ewing plays out his deal in Washington, the common
denominator between Jordan and Ewing _ the agent David Falk _ might
be able to assure Ewing a position in the Wizards organization
after he retires.
</P>
<P>
   Much of this is speculation, though. At the end of the season,
an Eastern Conference official said trade scenarios concerning
Ewing were in the works. But Layden was unwavering in his support
of the beleaguered Ewing. At the time, the Knicks had just lost the
Eastern Conference finals in six games to the Pacers. The two games
the Knicks won in the best-of-seven series were the two games Ewing
missed due to injury. A year earlier, the Knicks went to the NBA
finals without Ewing.
</P>
<P>
   In June, just before Game 6 against Indiana, Latrell Sprewell
was asked if the team played better without Ewing. His answer?
``The numbers don't lie.''
</P>
<P>
   On June 4, two days after the Knicks were eliminated in Game 6
with Ewing, Layden stood in the parking lot at SUNY-Purchase, the
Knicks' practice facility, and said: ``I believe in order to get
back to the finals, Patrick has to be part of the team. That's very
important. I think Patrick is a critical part of the team.''
</P>
<P>
   But two months later, after failing miserably to bolster their
team with free agents, watching Miami land Eddie Jones and all but
finalize a deal for Grant, the Knicks are in the mode to rethink
their position on Ewing. And Ewing, after all the years of being
blamed for every team failure, may be willing to acquiesce.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In some ways, Dave Checketts, the Madison Square Garden
president, foreshadowed such a potentially tumultuous end to
Ewing's career with the Knicks. In March, Checketts discussed the
future of Ewing with the team and whether No. 33 would retire as a
Knick. ``The fact is that whether he plays beyond his contract or
not, Patrick will be one of the greatest to ever play in the NBA
and certainly one of the best to ever play for the Knicks,''
Checketts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how it will end. It's always tough. Was it time
for Dan Marino? Was it time for John Elway? Was it time for Michael
Jordan? When is a guy done physically? And when should he retire
because he is at the pinnacle? You can ask all these questions, but
it should be up to Patrick. And obviously, we'll have to play a
role in that decision.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
