u i BC-MEXICO-FOX-0820-COX     08-19 0950
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-FOX-0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FOX LAYS OUT VISION FOR A NEW FUND FOR MEXICO, MORE U.S. VISAS
FOR WORKERS
 &HT;    (550&AMP;ADDS)
 &HT;    By SUSAN FERRISS 
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ When he visits the United States next week,
Mexican president-elect Vicente Fox will ask leaders to show ``a
vision for the future'' and seriously consider his ideas for ending
illegal immigration and spurring job growth here to prevent it, Fox
said in an interview Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Those ideas include opening the U.S. border to more legal
Mexican workers and contributing to an international development
fund with as much as $10 billion to $20 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not begging or asking for charity,'' Fox told Cox
Newspapers. ``That's not done between friends or partners. What I'm
asking for is understanding, intelligence, talent, a vision for the
future and an integral vision.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If the United States has something, it's that kind of
talent,'' said Fox, who was once president of Coca-Cola in Mexico.
``And if the United States has done something in the past, it's
been to look at immigration with a vision. It is a country
constructed by immigrants.''
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 1, Fox _ who will visit Washington D.C. and Dallas,
Texas _ becomes the first Mexican president in 71 years not to
belong to the Institutional Revolutionary Party, or the PRI in its
Spanish initials.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that his government, which breaks that monopoly on
power, has ``moral authority'' to propose new ways of tackling
tough problems like illegal immigration and drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to understand that we are friends, neighbors and
partners, but we are very unequal neighbors and partners,'' Fox
said. ``We have to remember that Mexico lacks resources . . .
That's why my proposal is to create a very large fund that each
country will contribute to based on the size of its economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox envisions perhaps using a poorly-funded bank established by
the North American Free Trade Agreement (NAFTA) as a vehicle for
billions in donations from the United States, Canada and Mexico to
help invest in businesses in poor areas of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be for all countries, as is done in Europe,'' Fox
said. ``Certainly most funds would go to Mexico, and we are
certainly asking the United States and Canada to contribute more.
You ask more of big brothers.''
</P>
<P>
   Fox will arrive in Canada Tuesday for a visit and head for New
York and Washington D.C. on Wednesday. He will meet with President
Clinton and Vice President Al Gore, the Democratic presidential
nominee on Thursday. On Friday he heads to Texas to meet with Texas
Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Begin optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's relationship with ``Texas is super intense,'' Fox said.
``It's not just commerce. The number of people (legally) crossing
the border is impressive. These are people who are active, people
who are contributing to the development of the region, people who
are working on one side of the border and living on the other.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Until today, I think most relationships between countries have
almost always between central governments,'' Fox said. ``And that's
a departure point. However, an intense relationship can't be forged
unless there are relationships established between states _ states
like Texas, with its magnitude, its economy and the great number of
Mexicans who are there.''
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: End optional trim.)
</P>
<P>
   Because he is not yet president, Fox said his visit is
``exploratory,'' and that he will meet with Gore or Bush again
after the U.S. presidential election. But he wants to get started
on discussing his ideas.
</P>
<P>
   In the long term, he proposes opening the U.S.-Mexico border to
the free transit of workers, like the European Union. In the short
term, he'd like to obtain more legal visas for Mexican workers to
fill specific labor shortages.
</P>
<P>
   Fox also supports a proposal for a new amnesty for undocumented
immigrants in the United States, which is being pushed by the
Democratic Party and U.S. labor unions.
</P>
<P>
   (EDs: Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   Federal Reserve chairman Alan Greenspan, Fox noted, has said
that the United States needs more ``human resources.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those could easily come from Mexico,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has suggested various time-frames _ including 10 years _ for
his vision of opening North America's borders to a free flow of
workers.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday he said he believes his idea would take longer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're talking about a project whose final arrival could be 30
years down the road,'' Fox said. ``But all projects need steps to
get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Opening borders, Fox said, would probably require a pact of
``economic convergence.'' Mexico would have to meet goals of
reducing unemployment, increasing wages to close the gap with the
United States and controlling inflation.
</P>
<P>
   To help control drug trafficking through the border _ a problem
some say is a major obstacle to liberalizing transit _ Fox
suggested that the United States also work harder to reduce
consumption and money-laundering.
</P>
<P>
   ``This new Mexican democratic government, the government of
Vicente Fox, is going to wage the mother of all battles against
drug trafficking,'' Fox said. ``If we set goals for each year and
each month, and each (country) meets them, then in probably six,
eight or 10 years, we can end or at least reduce substantially the
problem of drugs and be in a position to open the border.''
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Ferriss' E-mail address: susanf(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information, see:
</P>
<P>
   http://migration.ucdavis.edu/
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
