<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 16:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6728 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-FAMILY-COURT-705&AMP;A     08-19 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FAMILY-COURT-705&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN COURT, FAMILIES SIT WAITING ON THE LAW 
</HEADLINE>
   By SOMINI SENGUPTA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the cramped law library on the top floor of Kings
County Family Court, in Brooklyn, the day begins with frilly
dresses, wide grins and cheers of congratulations.
</P>
<P>
   A 3-year-old twig of a boy, an orphan since birth, gets parents
of his own. A pair of brothers _ one 20 and disabled, the other 10,
with eyes like darts _ are adopted by the quiet couple who took
them in seven years ago. A 5-year-old girl with a lispy whisper of
a voice gets a new name.
</P>
<P>
   The dozen or so adoptions completed on this morning represent
the rare moments of brightness in this theater of boredom and
despair _ not least because they have been so long in coming.
</P>
<P>
   The woman adopting the 5-year-old girl, for instance, has been
waiting to do so ever since the birth of the child, who was left by
her 13-year-old biological mother in a hospital. The woman, whose
name was not revealed, because of confidentiality laws on adoption,
could almost feel the birth pains, she said. She has cared for the
baby ever since.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gimme a kiss!'' she demands, showing the girl the adoption
papers. The girl climbs on top of her, smothering her face and arms
with kisses.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting is the leitmotif of Family Court. Well before court
begins at 9 a.m., hundreds of men, women and children line up to
pass through a metal detector. Then they line up to get on an
elevator. Then they wait to see a judge. Sometimes they wait past
sundown.
</P>
<P>
   One day last week it seemed fitting that the clock in the
waiting room in front of the intake court _ Family Court's
emergency room _ was over two hours slow.
</P>
<P>
   On this day the hard wooden benches were packed in this
windowless waiting room in the courthouse. The water fountain on
this floor didn't work. The women's bathroom lacked the luxuries of
many restrooms _ no diaper-changing stations, no toilet-seat
covers, only one functioning stall.
</P>
<P>
   Only a handful of people in the waiting room on this day had
brought something to read. Most of the others stared into space. A
few rested their heads on their arms in an effort to sleep, which
seemed impossible in the din. Children wailed. Every now and then,
someone became agitated and started muttering or yelling. Every few
seconds, a court officer bellowed the name of the next person to
appear before a judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like a circus,'' declared Debra Benders, 40, who was
seeking custody of her granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not only what you're going through, but what everybody
else is going through,'' said Urcelina Ortiz, who was there to try
to prevent her son, accused of selling drugs, from being locked up.
(Family Court handles most criminal charges against children under
16.)
</P>
<P>
   She watched another mother, whose son was released from custody,
burst into tears. She stared at a woman covered with bruises. It
was a painful reminder for Ortiz, 41, who years ago had come into
this courthouse seeking an order of protection from her ex-husband.
</P>
<P>
   Tara Caver, 29, a slight, soft-spoken mother of four, arrived at
10 a.m. to try to prevent the termination of her parental rights.
Her children had been placed in foster care four years ago, when
she was diagnosed with manic-depressive disorder. Since then, she
said, she had tried to do all that was asked of her _ taking
medication, attending therapy. Mostly she had waited for the legal
system to return her children.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, she and her husband, Burnard Hayes, 36, spent the
hours holding each other tightly on a bench, dozing on each other's
shoulders. Not until 5 p.m. did she learn that her case would be
adjourned.
</P>
<P>
   Some people call Family Court the candy store of melodrama. But
it is also a theater of the most ordinary betrayals, the place
where the most intimate details of domestic life are revealed,
where the violations of trust and love between men and women,
parents and children are scrutinized by strangers.
</P>
<P>
   Family Court, with a branch in every borough, offers a lopsided
demographic picture of the city. Most of those passing through it
are poor. More than half are black, according to a study by the
Vera Institute of Justice, and more than 40 percent are Hispanic.
Only 7 percent are white, and 1 percent are Asian.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Inside Room 276, the intake courtroom, a fluorescent light
flickered disconcertingly. Every time the doors opened and the
court officers yelled a name, they practically drowned out Lee
Elkins, the quiet-spoken judge handling a roster of 183 cases that
day. The telephone rang. Lawyers chatted with each other, and when
the murmur grew too loud, a court officer yelled ``Order!''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you come into this courthouse, see the facility, suffer the
long wait, if you're talking about the most intimate details of
your life and doors are opening around you and people are harried,
it has to give you the impression that your dignity as a person is
not respected,'' Elkins said. ``If anything, Family Court should be
the opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   The physical state of the courthouse alone, he added,
exacerbates what is already a distressing situation. ``It's
uncomfortable, it's hot, there's no privacy, the noise level,'' he
said. ``If anything, we need an environment that makes people
calmer.'' (A new courthouse is scheduled to be built, but work has
not yet started on it.)
</P>
<P>
   When he is not assigned to intake, Elkins, known for his
reflective demeanor, handles 25 to 30 cases a day, all involving
the perilous decisions of child protection: whether to return
children to a mother who beat her son with a hanger; whether to
hand over a toddler to a mother with acute depression.
</P>
<P>
   Now there is the urgency imposed by a new federal adoption law;
a child who has been in foster care for 15 of the previous 22
months must be either freed for adoption or reunited with parents.
Few believe the city's Family Court system will be able to comply.
</P>
<P>
   Family Court caseloads are growing faster than those of any
other court, state officials say. More than 232,000 cases were
handled last year citywide by 42 judges, a caseload that has
tripled in the last 20 years. On this day, Elkins' work began,
happily, with the adoption certifications at 9:30 a.m. It didn't
end until well past 8 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The study by the Vera Institute found that three-fourths of the
people interviewed were still waiting, after three hours, to see a
judge. They had been to court an average of 4.7 times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
