<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6731 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-VOCATIONAL-EDUC-83     08-19 1020
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-VOCATIONAL-EDUC-830&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VOCATIONAL SCHOOL TRAINING PROGRAM FAILS, AUDIT SAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN SULLIVAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ After an auspicious start seven years ago, a program
designed to help vocational students find jobs after graduation has
fallen into complete disarray, according to an audit by the city
comptroller.
</P>
<P>
   The program, called Project Pathways, was started in 1993 by the
School Construction Authority as a way to funnel qualified students
from the city's vocational high schools into apprenticeship
programs in the construction trades. In its first years it was very
successful, placing 98 percent of the students in apprenticeships
within two years of their graduation.
</P>
<P>
   But according to the report from Alan Hevesi, the city
comptroller, the program was quickly derailed by mismanagement and
lack of oversight by the construction authority, the agency in
charge of building schools in the city. In 1998, only 38 percent of
the students were placed in apprenticeship training after
completing the Project Pathways program, and by early this year
only 3 percent of the students who graduated in 1999 had entered
the apprenticeship training.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result of poor administration, a lack of monitoring, and
the failure to ensure that all parties were adhering to their
obligations, a program with a successful record for providing
valuable opportunities for the students in the city's vocational
high schools is being allowed to fail,'' said the report, which was
completed on June 28. ``This does a disservice to all the parties
involved with the program, especially to the students who, in good
faith, did what was expected of them in the program and expected
help with placements in union apprenticeship programs.''
</P>
<P>
   The construction authority, which is one of several agencies
involved in the program and has the primary responsibility for
administering it, issued a statement Friday praising the success of
the program. The response disputed Hevesi's conclusions and said
auditors had not fairly measured the success of the program, in
part because they focused on the placement rate for graduates
rather than on the number of students who eventually entered
apprenticeship programs.
</P>
<P>
   The authority also said a moratorium on new apprenticeship
programs issued by the state Labor Department reduced the number of
placements, but the auditors said the decline had begun years
before the moratorium.
</P>
<P>
   The scathing audit comes at a time of declining enrollment in
the city's vocational high schools, even though construction
industry representatives have loudly and repeatedly complained of
shortages of trained workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the Board of Education is caught up in the move to
higher academic standards, which is very important, but the trap is
they forget about or neglect everything else,'' said Frank Carucci,
vice president of the United Federation of Teachers for vocational
and technical high schools.
</P>
<P>
   Officials of the Board of Education said the city schools
intended to focus on vocational training, and said Chancellor
Harold Levy had scheduled a meeting with construction industry
representatives next month to discuss expanding the program.
</P>
<P>
   David Klasfeld, the deputy chancellor for operations, said
Friday that the board intended to maintain a route to ``the
industries in the city and to give kids the opportunity to get into
these long-term high-paying jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Project Pathways has only been a small part of the vocational
education program, and each year only a few hundred of the 25,000
students in the system were involved. Acceptance into the
senior-year program, which is offered at 10 of the city's 18
vocational high schools, is based on grades, attendance and
interest in the program. Students take a nine-week course to
introduce them to the construction trades, and when they graduate
from the program are given an opportunity to enter an
apprenticeship program.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many students view the Project Pathways program as a
door-opening opportunity for a career right out of high school that
they might not otherwise have had,'' the audit said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the audit, principals complained about a lack of
information for available positions and about long waiting lists
for those that were available.
</P>
<P>
   One union official said the program started failing to work well
after the first three years, the audit said. Another said he called
the construction authority ``several times when he needed
apprentices, and no one returned his calls,'' according to the
audit.
</P>
<P>
   The audit specifically criticized the construction authority's
record-keeping and its inability to match graduates with available
apprenticeship slots. Auditors also reported long delays when they
asked the authority to supply records for their review of the
program.
</P>
<P>
   The Project Pathways program may soon be replaced. The authority
and groups representing city builders and construction unions are
working on a plan for a new program run by a new nonprofit
organization, Construction Skills 2000.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Debra Perry, a spokeswoman for the construction authority, said
the details of the new organization were being worked out by the
Port Authority of New York and New Jersey, the construction
authority and the industry and union groups.
</P>
<P>
   Louis J. Coletti, chairman of the Building Trades Employers'
Association, said the groups thought that a training program could
be run more effectively by a nonprofit group than by the
construction authority.
</P>
<P>
   Coletti said the original program lost its focus as the
construction authority gave increasing emphasis to its primary
task, building and repairing the city's schools. He gave the
authority credit for pioneering the training effort but said
greater reliance on private industry could produce a better system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We sat down and asked the question `Is it really the role of
any public agency to administer a program of this nature?''' he
said. ``We needed to create a public-private approach.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
