<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 16:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6751 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NYPD-CHIEF-PROFILE-NY     08-19 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYPD-CHIEF-PROFILE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 KERIK SEEN AS STREET-SMART LAW ENFORCEMENT INNOVATOR 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NYPD-CHIEF) 
 By ELISSA GOOTMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the five and a half years that Bernard Kerik held
the proverbial key to the New York City jail system, first as the
top deputy and then as commissioner of the Department of
Correction, slashings and stabbings fell by 93 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Overtime pay plummeted by 44 percent. Trends were monitored,
statistics compiled.
</P>
<P>
   If that sounds familiar, it might be because Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani's choice of a new police commissioner is regarded as a man
much like the mayor himself. As commissioner and first deputy,
Kerik was charged with matching the decline in crime on the streets
with a decline in violence in the city jails, which were seen as
abysmal. By most accounts, he succeeded, transforming what had
traditionally been a chaotic department into one of the
best-managed agencies in the city.
</P>
<P>
   A former undercover narcotics detective, Kerik, 44, knows how to
navigate the streets. He received the Police Department's Medal of
Valor after a 1991 drug arrest in Washington Heights: a cocaine
dealer, cornered by Kerik and his partner, Hector Santiago,
unexpectedly leapt from a taxi and started shooting, hitting
Santiago once in the elbow. Kerik jumped from his car and chased
the gunman in a running gun battle into a housing project two
blocks away. The dealer finally collapsed, next to 6 kg of cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Santiago credits Kerik with saving his life.
</P>
<P>
   Bernard Bailey Kerik was born in Paterson, N.J., in 1956. He
dropped out of high school and enlisted in the Army, serving in the
military police and training members of the Special Forces in
karate (he holds a black belt). Later, after about four years
working as an investigator and a guard for Saudi Arabian royalty,
Kerik returned to New Jersey, where he became warden of the Passaic
County Jail. Kerik reportedly took a $27,000 pay cut to join the
New York Police Department in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik joined the New York Department of Correction in 1994 as
the director of investigations. He was appointed first deputy
commissioner in 1995 and commissioner in late 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik has since trimmed his ponytail and exchanged his street
clothes for suits. But colleagues say he is still nimble, and still
in touch with the streets. He consults subordinates, listens to
union leaders and subjects long-standing policies to scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will say one thing for Kerik, which is that he gives me an
open door,'' said Peter Meringolo, the president of the Correction
Captains Association. ``Unfortunately, that hasn't always been
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years ago, Meringolo went so far as to crown Kerik man of
the year, the only time a manager ever received the honor.
</P>
<P>
   Decisiveness is another trait Kerik is known for: Once he has a
plan, he executes it with determination.
</P>
<P>
   For example, convinced that the Correction Department's battered
buses were contributing to its negative public image, he declared
that only spotless vehicles be allowed off Rikers Island, the
city's largest jail.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik's biggest accomplishment has been the reduction in
violence in the city's jails, where inmates used to frequently
slash and stab one another _ and sometimes the guards _ with
homemade weapons. Brutality by the guards had also been reported,
as some took the offensive and began beating unruly inmates.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, inmates were usually punished for violence with
time in special confinement wards, but Kerik began proceedings to
prosecute them for new crimes in such cases.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik brought to the jails a version of the Police Department's
Compstat program, in which practices are altered and resources
allocated in accordance with carefully monitored trends. In the
beginning, he used the program to stop much of the violence by
inmates. He then expanded the idea into a tool for holding managers
at all levels of the department responsible for their actions.
</P>
<P>
   The approach, called TEAMS, for Total Efficiency Accountability
Management System, is a semifinalist in an annual competition at
the John F. Kennedy School of Government at Harvard that rewards
innovations in law enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik has told friends that he plans to expand the Police
Department's use of Compstat to monitor and improve not just
crime-fighting but community relations.
</P>
<P>
   Another area on which Kerik is likely to focus is reducing
expenditures for overtime work. Using his TEAMS approach, Kerik has
cut the annual overtime budget at the Correction Department to
about $50 million, or about half what it was when the jails seemed
to be exploding with violence in 1990. By contrast, the Police
Department's overtime costs have mushroomed in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   According to critics, changes in the city's jails may have more
to do with legal pressure than the commissioner's desire to make
things better.
</P>
<P>
   ``From our standpoint, his administration has been a very mixed
bag,'' said John Boston, the director of the Prisoners' Rights
Project at the Legal Aid Society of New York City. ``His candor was
refreshing, but I think his accomplishments have been somewhat
exaggerated.''
</P>
<P>
   Some within the New York police force wonder whether Kerik will
find it difficult to command respect in a department that he left
as a detective third grade, the lowest rank of detective. Captains
in the department must have a college degree, but Kerik is pursuing
his now at Empire State College, where he is 24 credits short of a
bachelor's degree in labor relations.
</P>
<P>
   Kerik's friends say he is devoted to his 15-year-old son from a
previous marriage and to the baby daughter he has with his current
wife. ``Bernie Kerik brings new insight, new vision,'' said Lenny
Lemer, a sergeant with the Police Department who has known him for
12 years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-00 1630EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
