<DOCNO> NYT20000819.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 16:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6752 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-UPSHAW-NYT &LR;      08-19 0762
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UPSHAW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UPSHAW FINDS A HOME AS MANAGER IN THE `ADVERSITY LEAGUE' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)   By ANDREW R. TRIPALDI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Willie Upshaw, like any good catch-and-release angler, is
maintaining the delicate balance between playing his fish and
letting them go.
</P>
<P>
   In three years as the manager of the Bridgeport (Conn.) Bluefish
in the independent Atlantic League, Upshaw, who played 10 seasons
with the Toronto Blue Jays and the Cleveland Indians, has grown to
realize that there is a lot more to managing than filling out the
lineup card. He now understands that his players do not want to be
Bluefish for the rest of their careers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get the players to look at it as playing in the Adversity
League,'' Upshaw said recently. ``They have to fight back, play
hard if they want to get out of here and get to the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   Balancing the best interests of the team with those of his
players has been the biggest challenge Upshaw has faced, not to
mention dealing with the nagging fear that he could lose his best
player to a major-league team at any moment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been frustrating for me the last couple of years,'' he
said, ``but I try to win with the hand I am dealt.''
</P>
<P>
   In 2000, the Bluefish struggled early, compiling a 35-35 record,
but they have gone 21-12 since, and at 56-47 overall are in first
place in the North Division. The nine-team Atlantic League has no
formal affiliation with major-league baseball, but it serves as an
alternative developmental route to and from the majors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being healthy has been huge for us in the second half,''
Upshaw said. ``We could not put out a steady lineup in the first
half. Our hitting and defense have also improved.''
</P>
<P>
   Upshaw, now 43, was hired by Bridgeport in October 1997, mostly
because of his qualifications, partly because as a resident of the
neighboring town of Fairfield he was the sentimental choice.
</P>
<P>
   He was coming off major-league coaching stints, as a hitting
instructor with Toronto from 1991 to '92 and a batting instructor
for the Texas Rangers from 1993 to '94. He returned to the Blue
Jays in 1995 as the hitting instructor and was promoted to batting
coach from 1996 to '97.
</P>
<P>
   With the inception of the Atlantic League three years ago,
Upshaw put down roots in Connecticut. He and General Manager
Charlie Dowd have built the Bluefish into one of the league's most
successful franchises, fielding a winning team each season _ they
won the league championship in 1999 _ and drawing about 4,300 fans
a game.
</P>
<P>
   Upshaw now enjoys the sweetest things in both his professional
and personal life: running his own team and spending time at home
with his wife, Cindi, and their four children, Brock, Courtney,
Chad and Kendall. Nevertheless, he said he would love to manage in
the major leagues some day.
</P>
<P>
   ``Willie would be able to succeed at the next level, because he
commands respect from all of his players,'' said Steve Schoenfeld,
the assistant general manager of the Bluefish. ``He would make them
check their egos at the door.''
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeport, under Upshaw's leadership, has developed a
reputation as a place for players seeking to work their way back to
the majors. The former Yankee Mariano Duncan played with the
Bluefish in 1999, and the former Pirate Jose Lind and Alex Cole are
regular starters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I deal with them a little differently,'' Upshaw said of former
major-leaguers. ``I try to get them to be leaders and to set
examples for the rest of the players. As the manager, I'm in a
position where they're going to listen to me. All I ask is that
they be on time and play hard. They have never taken advantage of
me. They know I'm not going to take a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Bluefish have an inviting park; 10,000-seat
Harbor Yard is the independent league equivalent of Camden Yards.
Located in the middle of Bridgeport, Fairfield County's largest
city (population 141,686), the stadium, with moderate ticket costs
($5 to $11), convenient parking, state-of-the-art facilities but
minor-league coziness, provides a warm family feeling for Upshaw's
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a great place for baseball,'' Upshaw said. And baseball
is the heart of the matter. So when Upshaw deals with players who
are not producing and, as a result, consider quitting the game, the
manager tries to point out the positives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell them the advantages of still being here, '' he said.
``Once they leave, they can't ask themselves woulda-coulda-shoulda.
They should stick around a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeport hopes Upshaw does the same.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
