<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6754 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-1STL     08-19 0360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 MOSCOW: worst expectations. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The admiral's sober report was issued a day after President
Vladimir Putin returned to Moscow and cut short a vacation amid
criticism that he had neglected the stricken families and delayed
too long on a decision for foreign assistance in the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Putin made no public appearance. Kremlin spokesmen
reported only that he met with his national security advisers and
discussed the status of the rescue operation.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in Murmansk said there were still no plans for Putin
to travel to the area, where relatives again Saturday were shown on
local television mourning what now appears to be the certain loss
of their loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   Rescue crews have reported that when they twice docked on the
rear hatch and then tried to pump water out of the docking
corridor, water just kept flooding in. At first, navy officials
believed that deformed deck plates around the hatch were preventing
a tight lock. Now, Motsak said, they also believe that the rear
compartment under the hatch may have been flooded and so water was
rushing into the docking corridor from inside the submarine.
</P>
<P>
   The causes of the explosion that proved fatal to the ship and
crew are still unknown, the admiral said. But a new possibility, he
said, was that the 14,000-ton submarine hit a World War II mine. He
said that between 1992 and 1999, six such mines have been
discovered in the Barents Sea, the most recent last September.
</P>
<P>
   The admiral said it was difficult to pronounce the crew beyond
hope ``because I have known the submarine's commander,'' Capt.
Gennadi Lyachin, ``for many years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I appointed him to that post,'' Motsak said. ``I went to sea
with him to inspect the training of that crew, and this was one of
our best crews.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the rescue operation would now move to the ``second
stage,'' to concentrate on penetrating the hull of the 490-foot
submarine to begin evacuation of bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Motsak said that the navy would eventually raise the submarine
to remove its weapons and nuclear reactors from the seabed, but
that ``it may take time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
