<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-NOTES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
O'NEILL ACCUSES UMPIRE OF RETALIATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Paul O'Neill leaned on the railing in front of the
Yankees' dugout in the first moments after their extra-inning loss
to Anaheim on Friday night, glaring at the home plate umpire, Gary
Cederstrom, as Cederstrom passed on his way to the dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope you can sleep tonight,'' O'Neill said he yelled at
Cederstrom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't threaten me,'' Cederstrom retorted, according to
O'Neill, who was furious.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill often debates with umpires after balls and strikes, but
his rage with Cederstrom reached a higher level: He believes
Cederstrom called strikes on him in retaliation for complaints
O'Neill made in the fourth inning. ``The most intentional thing
I've ever seen in my life,'' O'Neill said. ``In 14 years.''
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, O'Neill griped to Cederstrom about a strike call
he had made. The two debated; at one point, O'Neill stepped away
from home plate. Anaheim's Ramon Ortiz threw a pitch that appeared
to be well outside the usual parameters of the strike zone, and
Cederstrom called O'Neill out on strikes.
</P>
<P>
   O'Neill was incensed, turned and argued with Cederstrom, until
both Bernie Williams and Manager Joe Torre pushed him away. For the
remainder of the game, the tension built between O'Neill and the
umpire. Cederstrom declined to comment; Torre did not.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's disturbing, it really is,'' he said. ``I didn't hear any
of the conversation, and I really didn't get into it with Paul. But
it certainly looked like Gary was bothered by something and sort of
pranced around a little bit. It's disturbing to me, the strike
zone, and you hope there's nothing more than that. There's a lot of
dignity in this game, and that's the way it should be. You have the
best people in the world doing their job, and you hope everybody
does their job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cederstrom didn't throw him out, and he restrained himself in
that regard. He kept him in the game, and that was the important
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Players have theorized throughout history that umpires will
retaliate, but it is extremely rare when a player suggests this
publicly. The Yankees have issued informal complaints against
umpires in the past. Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general manager,
said he had no plans to ``pursue anything against Gary
Cederstrom.''  &QL; 
RIVERA SHRUGS OFF A BAD GAME  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   When Mo Vaughn's three-run homer disappeared into the
right-field stands Friday night, Mariano Rivera had five blown
saves for this season _ one more than during the 1999 season, when
he converted 45 of 49 chances. Rivera, unavailable for questions
after Friday's game, spoke amiably with reporters Saturday,
accepting blame for the loss. ``That was ridiculous,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked why he thinks he isn't as dominant as he was last
year, why he seems to have trouble keeping his fastball down on
some nights, and whether he should have taken a couple of warm-up
pitches Friday, just before Vaughn's home run; Vaughn fouled
Rivera's first pitch off the right big toe of catcher Jorge Posada,
who slumped to the ground for a couple of minutes before resuming.
Rivera waited on the mound throughout the delay, without throwing,
and Vaughn slugged his next pitch over the wall.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera responded to all of these questions in a similar fashion:
``Today is a new day,'' he kept saying with a smile, effectively
declining to contribute to the analysis. ``It's a shiny day, a
sunny day.''
</P>
<P>
   Rivera allowed just 43 hits and 18 walks in 69 innings last
year, striking out 52. This year he has surrendered 45 hits and 17
walks in 54 1/3 innings, with 40 strikeouts, and has 26 saves in 31
chances.  &QL; 
TWINGE PUTS WILLIAMS ON BENCH  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bernie Williams, who played in the Yankees' first 118 games this
season, was scratched from the lineup after feeling a twinge in his
side during batting practice. The Yankees announced that the injury
was not serious and that he was not expected to miss any more time;
it may be that the twinge provided a convenient reason for Joe
Torre to give Williams _ who has been slumping a bit _ the day off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sense he's a little tired, I do,'' Torre said before making
the lineup change.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
