</P>
<P>
   OLYMPICS
</P>
<P>
   OLY-GYM-TRIALS _ Coverage of Olympic Gymnastics trials, second
half. (Rosen, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 14.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SWM-JOSHDAVIS _ Four years ago, Josh Davis had to be the
happiest and luckiest man in Atlanta. Although he didn't win a
single individual medal at the Olympics, he struck gold three times
as a relay swimmer for the United States and left the Games with
more of that precious metal draped around his neck than any male
athlete from any country. Times change, and so has Davis' role. He
still is not the individual star of the U.S. team, but the
27-year-old former Texas Longhorn is its leader, the emotional rock
for a squad that certainly will need one in Sydney, Australia.
These Olympics will be no house party for the U.S. swimmers the way
the Atlanta Games were. The rest of the world has been improving,
and the talented Aussies will be defending their home surf in a
country that's fanatical about the sport. ``Everyone's talking
about swimming there. It's kind of like the NBA and NFL over
here,'' said Olympic swim coach Richard Quick. (Maher, Austin
American-Statesman) 35.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-SWM-TEXAS _ At the recent U.S. Olympic Swimming Trials there
were times when there were so many Longhorns in the final it was a
wonder they didn't turn the pool orange. The Three Amigos, seniors
Jamie Rauch, Scott Goldblatt and Nate Dusing, all finished in the
top six in the 200 meter freestyle and are eligible to swim on the
U.S.'s 800 meter relay team in Sydney. The 100 meter butterfly was
another Texas affair with Longhorn recruit Ian Crocker beating
Tommy Hannan. If you count Gary Hall, who had a cup of coffee at
Texas, eight of the 24 men selected to the team were either former,
current or incoming Longhorns. And there were a rash of Texas
swimmers who didn't make the team but still turned in impressive
performances, including incoming freshman Brendan Hansen, who
finished third in both the 100 and 200 meter breaststroke. (Maher,
Austin American-Statesman) 24.
</P>
<P>
   OLY-BKO-FORTNER _ Former Longhorn basketball standout Nell
Fortner has a big task at hand. She is head coach of the U.S.
women's Olympic basketball team. Like the men's national team, they
are expected to return home from the 2000 Summer Olympics in
Sydney, Australia next month with a gold medal ? and nothing else
but souvenirs. But the U.S.'s trip to the Olympics every four years
in basketball is not as easy as it used to be, as other countries
have closed the talent gap. There's as much pressure on Fortner to
carry on a tradition of dominance as on her 12-player superstar
roster. She's looking forward to it. (Estwick, Austin
American-Statesman) 25.
</P>
