<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6757 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-UNC-QA0820-COX     08-19 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNC-QA0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    New UNC chancellor wants voters to fund costly renewal
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   On Tuesday, his first day as the ninth chancellor of the
University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill, James Moeser sipped
water from a campus landmark, the Old Well, for good luck. He's
going to need it. The Texas-born former chancellor of the
University of Nebraska at Lincoln takes over North Carolina's
flagship public college at a critical juncture. The state's
16-campus university system wants to borrow $2.5 billion _
UNC-Chapel Hill would get nearly $500 million _ for improvements,
but North Carolina voters must approve the bonds in a Nov. 7
referendum. Moeser, 61, talked to staff writer Chris Burritt about
challenges at UNC-Chapel Hill, the first public university to open
its doors, in 1795, and its role in examining and influencing the
South.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How much time will you spend promoting the bonds?
</P>
<P>
   A: A big chunk of it. I am simply going to make the case that
this is the best investment that people can make in their own
future. This is a university that literally feeds and stimulates
the economy of the state by the research that we do and the
transfer of that research into the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Of the roughly half a billion dollars that comes to this campus
out of the bond issue, I will pledge to double or triple that with
private dollars. We will marry state dollars from the bond issue
with private dollars that we will raise.
</P>
<P>
   Q: How long will raising the private funds take?
</P>
<P>
   A: It will probably be the life of my tenure here. It could go
over the next decade.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In a tour of some of the university's buildings badly in need
of repairs, what did you see?
</P>
<P>
   A: The thing that just amazes me is we have this faculty here,
doing work of an incredible quality, attracting the best students
in the country to come here to study, and yet they are hampered by
facilities that are woefully inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   One lab had $3 million worth of very sensitive scientific
equipment, and it was a lab that . . . regularly floods. Tiles were
coming down because the roof was leaking.
</P>
<P>
   This is a great university that has been basically neglected. .
. . Struggling with this kind of deficiency is like running a race
with a concrete block tied around your ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Before you officially began as chancellor, you approved the
recent hiring of Matt Doherty as UNC's men's basketball coach.
Explain the balance of athletics and academics.
</P>
<P>
   A: We are a university first. . . . I will never say to the
coaches that I expect you to win national championships. I think
that puts unfair and undue pressure on coaches to win at any price.
Obviously, I want to have successful programs. . . . But far more
important to me is that we have coaches who first of all are
teachers who see their student-athletes as students.
</P>
<P>
   I think athletics at its best can be a character-building
experience. I am very concerned about what I see in America with
the cost of intercollegiate athletics (and) with the pressures to
win _ sometimes to win at any price.
</P>
<P>
   I think there is a kind of ugliness that is getting into sports,
the undue taunting on the field or by people at sporting events. .
. . We have gotten a long way from respecting our opponents and
treating them with . . . civility.
</P>
<P>
   Q: UNC likes to think of itself as a beacon of wisdom for the
South and having some role in shaping the debate about the South.
Do you believe that?
</P>
<P>
   A: I think Chapel Hill is the flagship of the South. That goes
right to Southern studies. I want Chapel Hill to be the place if
you are going to do Southern studies. If you are going to study the
American South, this ought to be where you go.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In the year 2000, is the South still worthy of study? Is it
still different enough, or its past intriguing enough, for academic
interest?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, it is not just a matter of looking at the past and
looking at the Civil War. What are the interesting questions to ask
about the contemporary South? The state of race relations? The
state of economic development?
</P>
<P>
   The South, probably more than any other sector of the country,
has people who know that they are Southerners and where the South
is. You can't tell me where the Midwest is, but the South is very
clearly identifiable, partly because of an event that took place in
the middle of the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
