u s BC-BBO-FURCAL0820-COX     08-19 0916
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-FURCAL0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Furcal tough baserunner to pin down
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Speed in baseball is easy to identify, not so easy to
explain.
</P>
<P>
   In Minnesota, Cristian Guzman might be the fastest man in the
majors, but he has difficulty stealing a base. In Florida, Luis
Castillo might be the game's foremost base-stealing threat, but it
took him more than three years to get the green light.
</P>
<P>
   In Atlanta, Rafael Furcal has stolen just 26 times, but he has
sat out 30 games. As a rookie, he's still deciphering opposing
pitchers. As a 19-year-old, he will challenge a respected outfield
arm just to see what happens next. On a team of All-Stars and even
future Hall of Famers, he is the most watched man on the field.
</P>
<P>
   How to explain that? Furcal is not the fastest man in the
National League. He isn't even the fastest in the Braves system.
George Lombard is, according to manager Bobby Cox. But what Furcal
becomes every time he reaches base is a situation. And that is
better.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as quickness, I don't think there's anyone better,''
Braves right fielder Brian Jordan said. ``This guy gets started as
quick as I've ever seen. You don't think he's going to tag up, and
he takes off like he's shot out of a gun. Pretty exciting to
watch.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Otis Nixon,'' Braves pitcher Greg Maddux said. ``Kenny
Lofton, Castillo, Vince Coleman, Ozzie Smith. Like all those
little, pesky squirts.t 3.9 on a routine grounder. Mickey Rivers
could go 3.7. Mickey Mantle, the legends say, was quicker than
that.
</P>
<P>
   What distinguishes Furcal and the game's current class of quick
players is that they are running at a time when baseball has
stopped to wait for the long ball. The running game popularized in
the 1980s has been reeled in. The home run is more important. Speed
around the majors is down.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a guy like this comes along, it'd be great to say this is
the wave of the future,'' said Gary Hughes, director of pro
scouting for the Cincinnati Reds. ``But the problem is creating the
wave. There's not that many guys with that kind of speed that can
play at this level.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an aspect of the game that's kind of lost now a days,''
said Dick Balderson, Atlanta's director of scouting. ``The thing
about it is, we don't get many athletes in the baseball business
anymore, kids who can run like that but have the skills to play the
game. The guys who can run usually end up being football players.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, a recent managers' survey in Baseball America
listed Castillo, Los Angeles' Tom Goodwin and Arizona's Tony Womack
as the fastest players in the National League, and Guzman, Kansas
City's Johnny Damon and Toronto's Raul Mondesi as the fastest in
the American League.
</P>
<P>
   How fast is fast? When Marlins manager John Boles finally set
Castillo loose last year, after he'd already appeared in 230 career
games, he stole 34 bases in the final 50 games. With a major-league
high 48 steals thus far this season, he has accumulated 82 steals
in his last 170 games.
</P>
<P>
   That's good, but as a rookie in 1985, Coleman stole 110 bases in
St. Louis, when the Cardinals routinely were stealing 200 bases a
season over a seven-year run. In the last seven years, only one
team has reached 200, the Colorado Rockies in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Guzman, in his second season, has stolen just 28 bases in his
career. He has made a far bigger impact by reinventing the triple
in Minneapolis. With 19 triples entering the weekend, he is on pace
for 24, a total unseen since Ty Cobb did it in 1917.
</P>
<P>
   Furcal, who leads all rookies with 26 steals, put a dent in
Cobb's portfolio when he passed 23, Cobb's 1906 total, which had
lasted as the most steals by a 19-year-old. Cobb hit .320 that
year. Furcal entered the weekend at .304, having legged out 16
infield singles, nearly 20 percent of his 88 hits this year.
</P>
<P>
   Furcal had just three steals this month, but the rookie said he
thinks he can steal between two and three bases a week, now that he
has replaced the injured Quilvio Veras atop the order. He had hit
seventh or eighth 31 times earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I think I can go,'' he said. ``When you're hitting
eighth every time in the National League, the pitcher behind you is
going to try to bunt. In the minors, you don't have the pitchers
hitting.''
</P>
<P>
   What has distinguished the first five months of Furcal's career
is the eye-rubbing, did-that-just-happen play that transcends
statistics. Such as on Aug. 8 when he dropped down a bunt double in
Cincinnati and in the same inning forced a throwing error on a
routine grounder to shortstop before tagging up from third on a
pop-up to center field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes the outfielders have to get to the ball quick,
because you don't know what this guy is going to do,'' Jordan said.
``It makes no matter where the ball is hit. You got to make sure
you know where this guy is.''
</P>
<P>
   The National League is just getting used to that, making sure
when Rafael Furcal is. The task will become only more vexing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, as you see him get more comfortable at the major
league level and a little more understanding of what goes on,''
Balderson said, ``I think you'll see a lot of stolen bases. I mean,
a lot.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's outrun a lot of things. His technique needs to be worked
on, his knowledge of the pitchers and when to do things and not to
do things, that will all improve.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
