<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6760 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-TEXAS-PREVIEW0820     08-19 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-TEXAS-PREVIEW0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Texas' state pleases Brown
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In December 1997, Mack Brown was introduced to the
Texas fans as the new football coach at a basketball game on
campus. Just before walking on the floor, Brown found himself
seated next to Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Brown asked the future Republican candidate for president what
he should say in this, his first public appearance before the Texas
people. ``Doesn't really matter what you say,'' Bush replied.
``Just make sure you end it by saying how happy you are to be in
the great state of Texas.''
</P>
<P>
   ``So I got up there and mumbled something for about a minute,''
Brown said. ``And then I said, `And Sally and I are just so proud
and happy to be in the great state of Texas.' I thought the roof
was going to come off the place.''
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS CONVERSION
</P>
<P>
   Brown was born in Cookeville, Tenn., played at Florida State,
and has been a head coach at Appalachian State, Tulane and North
Carolina. But today he is Texas through and through and loving
every minute of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this stage in my life, I feel really fortunate to be
here,'' said Brown, who coached 10 seasons at North Carolina before
making a quick, and controversial, exit from Chapel Hill to Austin.
``There is a passion for winning, which is what you would expect.
But the people here love to have fun. We just love this place.''
</P>
<P>
   That love has been returned. Texas fans have found in Brown what
they believed was the perfect antidote for the buttoned-down
corporate image created by John Mackovic. Makovic was a very good
football coach who beat Nebraska for a Big 12 championship in 1996.
But Texas fans wanted more than competence from their coach. They
wanted passion.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, a salesman, quickly immersed himself in the Texas culture
and embraced every tradition as his own.
</P>
<P>
   ``Coach Brown loves tradition and makes us realize how important
it is not just now but many years from now when we look back on
playing football at Texas,'' running back Hodges Mitchell said.
``The people I know just love the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   WINS, MIXED RESULTS
</P>
<P>
   So far, the results on the field have been respectable. In 1998,
Texas rode the powerful legs of running back Ricky Williams, who
won the Heisman Trophy. The Longhorns finished 9-3 after beating
Mississippi State in the Cotton Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, Texas stunned No. 3 Nebraska (24-20) on Oct. 23,
handing the Cornhuskers their only loss of the season. But things
fell apart at the end. Texas lost at Texas A&AMP;M 20-16 after the
bonfire tragedy at College Station. And Nebraska beat the Longhorns
22-6 in a rematch in the Big 12 championship game. A 27-6 loss to
Arkansas in the Cotton Bowl left Texas with a 9-5 record.
</P>
<P>
   Despite losing its last three games of the 1999 season, Texas is
ranked in everybody's top 10 going into 2000. With the talent and
the schedule, which does not include Nebraska or Kansas State in
the regular season, some think the Longhorns might get in the
national championship race ahead of schedule.THE QB QUESTION
</P>
<P>
   Before Texas can begin the pursuit of anything, however, it must
choose a quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Junior Major Applewhite, the All-Big 12 quarterback in 1999, has
started 21 games and thrown for 5,601 yards in just two seasons.
Applewhite, named for former Alabama running back Major Ogilvie,
was the Big 12 co-offensive player of the year last season. But he
suffered a knee injury in the Cotton Bowl that kept him out of
spring practice.
</P>
<P>
   The injury cleared the way for sophomore Chris Simms, considered
by many to be the nation's top quarterback coming out of high
school in 1998. The New Jersey native, the son of former Giants
All-Pro Phil Simms, originally committed to Tennessee but changed
his mind and signed with Texas. Simms is 6 feet 5 and 222 pounds
but played sparingly last season. Offensive coordinator Greg Davis,
who coached Eric Zeier at Georgia, plans to play both passers when
Texas opens the season with Louisiana-Lafayette on Sept. 9. After
that, nothing is certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good problem to have,'' Davis said. ``Most of the time,
schools play two quarterbacks because they have two No. 2s. We have
two No. 1s.''
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite (6-1, 207) said he is fully recovered from knee
surgery and is not going to give up the job without a fight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it's going to be a fair process,'' the native of Baton
Rouge, La, said. ``I'm no different than the coaches. I want the
best quarterback to be out there because I want to win. I just want
that quarterback to be me.''
</P>
<P>
   Simms is not as intense as Applewhite, but he is just as intent
on leading the Longhorns. ``This is why you come to a place like
Texas,'' he said. ``All I want is an opportunity. Then the rest is
up to me.''
</P>
<P>
   ``When you coach, that's what you dream about,'' Brown said.
``Great players competing with other great players. That should be
the goal at Texas. Always.''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Brown can't contain the smile of a man just happy
to be in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
