<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6763 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-BKO-FORTNER0820-C     08-19 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BKO-FORTNER0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Push on Fortner to bring home the gold
 &HT;    By Gary Estwick
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ U.S. women's Olympic basketball coach Nell Fortner has
a big task at hand.
</P>
<P>
   Like the men's team, the women are expected to return home from
the 2000 Summer Olympics in Sydney, Australia, with more than
souvenirs. There had better be gold medals in those suitcases.
</P>
<P>
   But the U.S. women's quest for Olympic gold is not as easy as it
used to be because other countries' basketball teams have closed
the talent gap. There's as much pressure on Fortner to carry on a
tradition of dominance as there is on her 12-player superstar
roster.
</P>
<P>
   But what, her worry? Fortner is looking forward to the
challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really hard to put into words,'' said Fortner, who played
at Texas from 1977-81. ``It's something that was three years away
in '97 that was hard really to grasp at that time. I feel good
about where we're at, and it's just exciting to finally be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Players understand the pressure on Fortner. ``The pressure is
also on Nell because she is the head coach and under her guidance
we go,'' said team member Dawn Staley. ``I think it's a
double-edged sword. She has a responsibility, and we have a
responsibility to her to put what she prepares for us out there on
the basketball court.''
</P>
<P>
   Fortner's Olympic dream started three years ago, when she left a
head coaching job at Purdue to coach the Olympic team. From there,
she has spent the last three years traveling the globe, coaching 10
U.S. squads to a combined 84-14 record. The USA Women's National
Team, which trained from September through April, compiled a 29-2
overall record before breaking for the WNBA season.
</P>
<P>
   Also last year, Fortner was named head coach of the expansion
WNBA Indiana Fever. She will join the team after the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   The pressure to win comes at a time when several of Fortner's
Olympic players are still competing in the WNBA playoffs. On the
way are the Houston Comets' Sheryl Swoopes and Olympic alternate
Tina Thompson and the Los Angeles Sparks' Lisa Leslie and DeLisha
Milton.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets lead the Sparks 1-0 in the WNBA's Western Conference
finals.
</P>
<P>
   None of the players are in a big rush to exit the playoffs. When
the time comes, though, they'll be united with one goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a difficult transition at all, especially
when you look at team spirit and competition,'' Thompson said. ``We
know the Olympics doesn't have anything to do with the WNBA, the
Houston Comets or the Los Angeles Sparks. It has to do with the
United States. We're all representing our country. It's a different
thing altogether.''
</P>
<P>
   Last Monday, U.S. team members Staley, Teresa Edwards, Katie
Smith, Natalie Williams and Kara Wolters had their first training
session together since April in Colorado Springs, Colo. Olympic
alternates Jennifer Azzi and Katrina McClain also participated in
the workouts. Chamique Holdsclaw and Nikki McCray arrived late this
week. Ruthie Bolton-Holifield and Yolanda Griffith will arrive
shortly.
</P>
<P>
   Fortner said it's been difficult running practices with only
seven players. The short-handed team at times has practiced against
men.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it's been a challenge, we've still been able to get in a
few things as far as teaching new things, just going over and
reviewing things we've done in the past, and also conditioning,''
Fortner said. ``Right now we're moving along as best we can with
the number of players that we have, but they've come in with great
attitudes, trying to get this thing going and setting the tone for
the weeks ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that the players currently working out don't have good
credentials. Consider the veteran Edwards, a three-time Olympic
gold medalist (1984, '88 and '96).
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said this year's team will face stiffer competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at one time it was considered to be easy, that we
could just go out, train two to three weeks and just beat
everybody,'' she said. ``The fact that we can't do that anymore
just proves that these countries have really gotten better, paid
attention, grown and produced quality athletes on the basketball
court.
</P>
<P>
   Not that Edwards doesn't foresee another gold medal being added
to her collection.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think we're head and shoulders better than everyone
else,'' she said. ``It's just recognizing that and feeling the
sense of urgency about that and having that desire to go out time
and time again to keep proving that.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
