<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 17:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6764 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-OLY-SWM-JOSHDAVIS0820     08-19 1286
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWM-JOSHDAVIS0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Josh Davis is a solid anchor for U.S. swim team
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Four years ago, Josh Davis had to be the
happiest and luckiest man in Atlanta. Although he didn't win a
single individual medal at the 1996 Summer Olympics, he struck gold
three times as a relay swimmer for the United States and left the
Games with more of that precious metal draped around his neck than
any male athlete from any country.
</P>
<P>
   Times change, and so has Davis' role. He still is not the
individual star of the U.S. team, but the 27-year-old former Texas
Longhorn is its leader, the emotional rock for a squad that
certainly will need one in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   These Olympics will be no house party for the U.S. swimmers the
way the Atlanta Games were. The rest of the world has been
improving, and the talented Aussies will be defending their home
surf in a country that's fanatical about the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone's talking about swimming there. It's kind of like the
NBA and NFL over here,'' said Olympic swim coach Richard Quick. He
added that the last time the Aussies and Americans hooked up in
Sydney, at the Pan Pacific championships last year, the ratings for
the showdown were the highest of the year for any TV show. At the
pool in Sydney, the fans once again will be deafening in their
support of the home team.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches know that the Olympics can be like a college meet,
when momentum can carry the day. Swimming fast _ or slow _ can be
contagious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think leadership and chemistry are the key. Americans are
used to a team effort. They thrive on a team effort,'' Quick said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think these young guys can learn from the veterans, and we
have tremendous veterans and tremendous leadership on this team,''
men's coach Mark Schubert added.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the other U.S. veterans have more eye-popping times and
better individual medal hopes than Davis, but none is more
respected.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to be the leader of the team. Even the Toms
(Wilkens, Dolan and Malchow) will tell you Josh is the leader,''
said Texas' Jamie Rauch.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has all that experience,'' Neil Walker said. ``And if
you've got a problem, he'll listen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been the team captain for four years. It's a role I
enjoy,'' Davis said, laughing about some of the chores he's picked
up since the last Olympics. ``When guys don't like something the
coaches are doing they'll say, `Let's get Josh. The coaches will
listen to Josh.'''
</P>
<P>
   Davis is almost always upbeat. At the trials, while some other
swimmers had to be coaxed to talk with reporters, Davis would bound
over and announce, ``Hi. I'm Josh Davis. Who needs to talk to me?''
</P>
<P>
   QUIT? NEVER
</P>
<P>
   Davis loves what he's doing, which is being a full-time swimmer.
He'll probably be buried in a Speedo or one of those new
full-length body suits. People who don't know him might assume
he'll retire from swimming after these Olympics. They'd be wrong.
He plans to swim in 2004, when he'd be on the wrong side of 30, and
again in 2008, when he'd be 35.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel stronger and better than ever, like a fine wine getting
better with age,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   That kind of enthusiasm for the sport is contagious. Walker, a
former Longhorn, said at the Olympic trials that he'll probably
keep swimming after the Games and cited Davis as an example of how
a swimmer can keep improving.
</P>
<P>
   At the Olympic trials, Davis finally broke a record he'd been
chasing for years, one he'd seen as a wide-eyed 15-year-old
visiting Austin _ Matt Biondi's American record in the 200-meter
freestyle. That was set in 1988 when Austin played host to the
Olympic trials. At the time, Davis, who started later than almost
any other Olympic-caliber swimmer, had only been swimming
competitively for a few years.
</P>
<P>
   There's no secret for how Davis has continued to improve or why
he has a physique that stands out even on the pool deck at the
Olympic trials.
</P>
<P>
   ``He swims with us, and Josh is a real hard worker,'' UT
Olympian Nate Dusing said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel I have an edge on most people out of the pool,'' Davis
once said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis is deeply religious and a committed family man. He and his
wife, Shantel, have two children and a third one is on the way.
That's one of the reasons Davis now trains with Texas coach Eddie
Reese's brother, Randy, at Circle C. The Davis family had outgrown
its other place and figured Circle C would be an ideal setup.
There's been another benefit to the arrangement as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eddie was real comfortable with me and I was real comfortable
with Eddie,'' Davis said. ``I needed someone like Randy to kick me
in the butt.''
</P>
<P>
   Although known as a dedicated worker, Davis also has a sense of
humor. At the trials, he made a point of not looking at former
Longhorn Gary Hall Jr. when he raced him. It wasn't any part of a
psyche-out routine. It's just that Hall's antics can crack Davis
up, something he doesn't want to happen before an important race.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, Davis suffered a string of disappointments in
his individual events. At the 1996 Olympic trials, he finished
third in the 100 freestyle, just missing making the team in that
event. He also was fourth in the 400 freestyle and qualified only
in his specialty, the 200 meters. He was ranked No. 1 in the world
at that distance in 1995 but finished seventh in the Olympic Games.
In the relays, however, he flourished.
</P>
<P>
   ``I seem to swim faster in relays,'' Davis said back then. Maybe
that's part of being a team player. After finishing third in the
semifinals of the 100 freestyle this year in Indianapolis, Davis
wasn't shooting any higher in the finals, saying that the team
needed Walker and Hall to take on Alexander Popov and some of the
other world-class sprinters.
</P>
<P>
   Davis ended up finishing sixth in the finals of the 100
freestyle behind Walker and Hall.THORPE LOOMS
</P>
<P>
   Davis is also one of the best U.S. swimmers in the butterfly and
the backstroke, just not quite good enough to nail down one of the
top two spots to make an Olympic team. He briefly thought about
trying to swim the 200 medley at the trials, as he has in some
other meets, but discarded that idea, figuring he couldn't make up
the two seconds he needed on the likes of Wilkens and Dolan. He's
as good as anyone in the world for three legs, but is a fish out of
water in the breast stroke.
</P>
<P>
   His forte remains the 200 freestyle, but that race has changed
with the emergence of the ``Thorpedo,'' Australia's hugely talented
teen-ager, Ian Thorpe. Thorpe's world record is more than a second
faster than Davis' American record.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I can go 1:46 and then 1:46 low. At that point it's
anybody's game,'' Davis said. A defeat of Thorpe would be daunting
for the Australians and a huge momentum swing for the Americans. In
the 800 freestyle relay, Davis should be the anchor of a young
squad that includes three UT swimmers, Dusing, Rauch and Scott
Goldblatt. The Aussies are loaded for that relay.
</P>
<P>
   Schubert said, ``We're going to focus on improvement in the
training camp and building a great team atmosphere and getting
everybody excited about improving and swimming faster than they did
in Indianapolis . . . I think the old guys can foster them (the
younger athletes) and get them through this Olympic experience,
which sometimes for a younger athlete can be a bit overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   With typical confidence Davis plans to break camp and head home
for the birth of the family's third child on Sept. 4th and then
head to Sydney to lead the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you serve people, you end up being a leader,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
