<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MALL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HASSEN MALL, 78, FIRST NONWHITE SOUTH AFRICAN JUDGE 
</HEADLINE>
   By HENRI E. CAUVIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JOHANNESBURG, South Africa _ Judge Hassen Mall, an Indian
immigrant who was South Africa's first nonwhite jurist and a key
figure in the nation's effort to lay to rest its apartheid past,
died Friday. He was 78, his son said.
</P>
<P>
   Mall, who had been suffering heart and kidney problems, was the
chairman of the amnesty committee of the country's Truth and
Reconciliation Commission. In that role he weighed some of the
worst atrocities of the apartheid era and the fate of those who
perpetrated them.
</P>
<P>
   With his health declining and his eyesight diminished in the
last year because of cataracts, Mall had greatly scaled back his
work but he remained a devoted presence at the commission, his
family and colleagues said.
</P>
<P>
   While the committee that he headed hoped to finish hearing
applications for amnesty by October, its work will last months
beyond then as it considers the latest raft of cases.
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to expose the truth of the apartheid era and impart a
spirit of reconciliation, South Africa offered amnesty to anyone
who was candid and complete in accounting for acts of violence and
could convince the commission that his or her actions were
politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of government agents and anti-government activists who
tortured, bombed, killed and otherwise roiled the country during
the liberation struggle have applied.
</P>
<P>
   Many have won amnesty; some have not, and the country itself is
still not of one mind about the ultimate merit of a process that
has answered many questions but offered little justice.
</P>
<P>
   Mall was convinced of the commission's crucial place in the
peaceful transformation of South Africa, his associates said. A
bust of Gandhi adorned his office in Durban and he approached his
work on the amnesty committee in a sober, deliberate manner,
recalled Deborah Quin, an investigator for the committee, which was
based in Durban, where Mall also lived.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a kind of very wise man, not cautious, but slow to come
to a decision,'' Quin said Saturday in an interview. ``He was very
concerned about hearing all the sides. It was difficult to read in
a hearing which way he was going to go. Some of the panel members
are obvious, but he wasn't at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Born July 19, 1922, in the Indian village of Ghala, about 125
miles from Bombay, he came to South Africa with his family at the
age of 4, his son Enver said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Raised in Durban, he went on to study first at the University of
Fort Hare and then at the University of Cape Town, where he earned
his law degree, his son said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, after decades of practicing law, he was named an acting
judge, the first nonwhite to be appointed to the bench. It was one
of a number of signals during that tumultuous period that bigger
changes lay ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Named a full judge in 1993, as the country prepared for the
historic multiracial 1994 election, he served on the bench a few
more years before being chosen by former President Nelson Mandela
in 1995 to lead the Truth and Reconciliation Commission's amnesty
committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``He brought a certain independence of spirit,'' Yasmin Sooka, a
commission member who worked with Mall's committee, said Saturday.
``He was not tainted or compromised.'' Indeed, he was widely
respected among the country's human rights lawyers, she said, and
they saw him as someone who would judge their cases fairly.
</P>
<P>
   Even as his health slipped, he remained dedicated to the work of
the commission, Sooka said, because he believed that it was ``one
of the pillars on which democracy was built in our country.''
</P>
<P>
   Mall was buried Friday evening. In addition to his son, he is
survived by his wife, Sylvia, and two daughters, Marcina and
Shereen.
</P>
</TEXT>
