<P>
   (NYT4) KADUNA, Nigeria -- Aug. 19, 2000 -- NIGERIA-OBASANJO-3 --
In tranquil Abuja, Nigeria, the troubles of the nation that has
long represented both Africa's highest hopes and deepest despair
seem unimaginable. Drive two hours north to Kaduna, however, and
the despair is on stark display. In a city that once had a
cosmopolitan tone and religious integration, riots killed thousands
of residents this year, and neighborhoods reduced to rubble have
become segregated between Muslims and Christians. ``If we want to
get proper peace in Kaduna, we have to divide the state into two,''
says Simeon Achi, 61, Christian community leader, with his son,
Musa, 31, in Kaduna. (Norimitsu Onishi/The New York Times)
