<P>
   COX-GORE _ ON THE MISSISSIPPI _ Bolstered by a fresh Newsweek
poll putting him ahead of Republican presidential nominee George W.
Bush, Democrat Al Gore continued to campaign hard in the Midwest
swing states on Saturday. Developing. (Shepard, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   JEWS-AMERICA _ WASHINGTON _ Only in America . . . is the
elliptical refrain that immigrants and their descendants use to
thank their lucky stars that they are here in the land of
opportunity. ``Only in America, right?'' Joseph Lieberman asked
cheering delegates in Los Angeles the other night, suggesting that
the U.S. is the one nation in which the grandson of Jewish
immigrants could grow up to be the Democratic vice presidential
candidate. (Sherman, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   TEMPLE-FEUD _ PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Saturday the rabbi led his
congregation in Sabbath prayer. Sunday the rabbi punched the temple
president in the face. And since that moment last November,
animosities simmering for months at Temple Emanu-El in Palm Beach
have boiled over and split this well-to-do religious community into
two infuriated camps. (Belkin, Palm Beach Post) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ADULT-STUDENTS _ WASHINGTON _ Older students are changing higher
education, and it is changing them. This fall, more than 40 percent
of the students at the nation's 2-year and 4-year colleges and
universities will be 25 or older, according to the Education
Department. Most of them work, commute to classes and raise kids.
Why and where they go, and what the impact is. (Mollison, Cox News
Service) WITH PHOTOS. WITH ADULT-DATA _ Graphics material.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ADULT-SINCLAIR _ DAYTON, Ohio _ On campus or via the internet,
students from near and far flock to Sinclair Community College, the
only two-year college among six cited nationally for ``best
practices'' in serving adult students. Its 21,000 students include
8,000 in their 20s, 3,700 in their 30s and 4,000 older than that.
How Sinclair accommodates their needs. (Jo Smith, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   ADULT-TYPICAL _ Theresa Johnson works. She's 36. She is divorced
and raising two kids. She's an undergraduate at Iowa State
University. In other words, she fits the College Board's composite
criteria for the typical adult college student. Johnson fervently
believes that the pros of attending a university with schedules and
programs heavily weighted toward much younger students still
outweigh the cons. (Mollison, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-FRIEND _ DAYTON _ Vernon Courtney, director of the National
Afro-American Museum and Cultural Center, was in the same dorm as
Al Gore at Harvard in the mid-1960s. The two used to shoot pool and
play ping pong, alternating victories, and also shared an interest
in hunting. Courtney, a young black man from the seaport town of
Hampton, Va., was recruited to attend the Ivy League university. He
recalled Gore as a guy whose ``daily uniform'' then was bib
overalls and who always presented himself as a guy from Tennessee,
downplaying the senator's son in an effort to be one of the guys.
``The thing I find interesting is he comes off so dry now. He
wasn't that way at all. He was pretty gregarious,'' Courtney
recalled. They haven't stayed in contact but after someone told Al
he ran into Courtney, Gore fired off an e-mail to him that said
``Don't forget to vote for me.'' Courtney also knew Tommy Lee
Jones, who wasn't around much because he was wrapped up in drama
even then, and he had fleeting contact with Tipper, who would visit
Big Al on campus. (Kissell, Dayton Daily News) 15. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GA-EXECUTION _ Alexander Williams was not yet an adult and he
was mentally ill when he kidnapped, raped and murdered a
16-year-old Augusta, Ga., girl. His lawyers argue that the state's
plan to execute him on Thursday violates international common
decency that says it's wrong to execute the mentally ill and
children _ or those who commit crimes before they are adults.
(Cook, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) 35. WITH PHOTO (mug of
Williams)
</P>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE-MURDERS _ GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ The police warn you
before you go in: People faint when they see these crime-scene
pictures. Or get violently ill. Or go numb with shock. And nobody
sleeps well for months after they look in the albums. Nobody.
Nobody can forget the faces of the five students Danny Rolling
murdered on Aug. 24, 25 and 27, 1990. (Lomartire, Palm Beach Post)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MINER-URANIUM _ A Moab, Utah, man might die before he can get
the $100,000 payment he's due from the federal government for his
work in uranium mines during the Cold War. His attorney has been
unable to prod a Senate Committee to break out of budget lockstep,
but there might be a glimmer of hope from another senator. (Grand
Junction Daily Sentinel) 30. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   FLATRAIN _ Trying to unclog its highways from Miami to Orlando
to Tampa, planners in Florida had proposed a high-speed train that
would reach speeds of 240 mph. But Gov. Jeb Bush killed the $6.3
billion project, which included annual payments from the
Legislature for 20 years, because he was not convinced the train
would have enough riders to justify its cost. Now, a retired
Lakeland businessman, is on the verge of putting the proposal on
the November ballot. Using a provision of the state constitution
that lets referendums be placed on a ballot if their are sufficient
petitioners to do so, fast-train advocate C.C. Dockery is waiting
on the state Supreme Court to rule on his request. Fast trains are
the latest fad among urban planners; turning their use into reality
is a different thing. Metro Atlanta planners also dream of a
high-speed train linking the city with Chattanooga. (Manuel, Cox
News Service)
</P>
<P>
   MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   UNC-QA _ Q&AMP;A with James Moeser, the new chancellor at the
University of North Carolina, who arrived on campus this week from
the University of Nebraska. (Burritt, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 9
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUB1STLEDE _ LONDON _ The latest developments on the
efforts to rescue the 118-member crew of the Russian navy sub
Kursk, as the British mini-submarine arrives on the scene to aid in
the rescue. Russian navy officials are saying, however, that there
is little or no chance of finding anyone alive on the vessel
sitting at the bottom of the Barents Sea about 350 feet below the
stormy surface. Developing. (Roughton, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-FOX _ MEXICO CITY _ Mexican President-elect Vicente Fox
said he would propose the creation of an development fund aimed at
strengthening Mexico's economy and thereby reducing his country's
outflow of migration when he meets with U.S. and Canadian officials
this week. Fox, who has made migration a key issue for his
administration after he takes office on Dec. 1, offered the
proposal in a face-to-face interview with Cox Newspapers Saturday.
Developing.
</P>
<P>
   (Ferriss, Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-CHIAPAS-1STLD _ From the tropical coast to the Mayan
highlands, the fever for political change _ through ballots, not
bullets _ is sweeping Mexico's Chiapas state. On Sunday, Aug. 20,
the state famous for its armed Zapatista Mayan Indian rebels will
elect a new governor. In the wake of Vicente Fox's historic
opposition victory in last month's presidential election, polls
show that change could be contagious: Even in Indian communities
once under tight control by the ruling party, posters for a Fox
ally are up on dirt-floor homes. Chiapans appear to be slightly
favoring Pablo Salazar, a former ruling party member who is now
representing an alliance that includes Fox's conservative National
Action Party and the left-wing Democratic Revolution Party. If
Salazar wins, one of the main reasons for the Zapatistas rising in
protest is eliminated. And those clashes between pro-Zapatistas and
PRI-backed paramilitaries are still continuing. (Ferriss, Cox News
Service)
</P>
<P>
   EDS: With photo mugs and information for locator map.
</P>
<P>
   MOVED in advance Wed., Aug. 16.
</P>
<P>
   COSTARICA-INVEST _ SAN JOSE, Costa Rica _ Lured by cheap land, a
gorgeous countryside and pleasant climate, thousands of U.S.
citizens have moved to Costa Rica in recent years. Profile some of
these folks, from retirees to surfers. Have they found the dream
they wanted? Do locals accept them? Has the recent upswing in crime
tainted their tropical paradise? (Williams, Cox News Service) WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: With information for locator map.
</P>
<P>
   MOVED in advance on Thu., Aug. 17, on the NYT Wire in both
International and Financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS
</P>
<P>
   WEBVAN - ATLANTA _ Lynda Reis, who spends more than $180 a week
on groceries for her family, is convinced she saves money using
Webvan.com. That's because she avoids impulse purchases at the
local grocery store. ``I spend less money per week,'' Reis said
while inspecting an order delivered to her home by the online
grocer. ``I would have bought what I didn't need if I went to the
store.'' The economics of buying groceries online and having them
delivered to the home may make sense for Reis. The question is
whether they will work for Webvan. While the company has generated
a lot of positive buzz and impressed many customers, it is a long
way from making money. (DeGross, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
MOVED Friday.
</P>
<P>
   LIES _ As you consider that new job, here's a question to
ponder: Will you have to lie at work? In much of the American
workplace there is a corporate culture of lying. If you value
honesty (tell the truth!) we'll look at clues to judge how
forthcoming your new employer really is. (Mallory, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) WITH ILLUSTRATION. MOVED.
</P>
