<P>
   Photo clients will automatically receive our photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
213-237-4577 or PressLink at 800-888-6195. Non-clients can make
individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Aug. 19, 2000 -- NYPD-CHIEF-PROFILE -- Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani's choice of a new police commissioner is regarded
as a man much like the mayor himself. As commissioner and first
deputy, Bernard Kerik was charged with matching the decline in
crime on the streets with a decline in violence in the city jails,
which were seen as abysmal. A former undercover narcotics
detective, Kerik, 44, seventh from right, knows how to navigate the
streets. Kerik with fellow narcotics officers and officials after
an undated drug bust and cash seizure. (The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Aug. 19, 2000 -- NYPD-CHIEF-2 -- Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani's choice of a new police commissioner is regarded
as a man much like the mayor himself. As commissioner and first
deputy, Bernard Kerik was charged with matching the decline in
crime on the streets with a decline in violence in the city jails,
which were seen as abysmal. Newly appointed Police Commisioner
Kerik receives a warm welcome from officer Marchia Bage as he
visits the Midtown South Precint in Manhattan, Saturday. (Vincent
Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) DUBUQUE, Iowa -- Aug. 19, 2000 -- GORE-2 -- With the
sprawling Mississippi River as a backdrop, Al Gore touted his
environmental record Saturday in Dubuque, Iowa, and maintained that
Republican presidential rival George W. Bush would allow polluters
to foul the air and water. ``I will clean up the environment,''
declared Gore. ``My opponent does not reflect that commitment in
what's going on in his home state.'' Members of The East Dubuque
VFW band waiting to play for Vice President Gore and wife Tipper,
who was celebrating her 52nd birthday, Saturday. (Paul Hosefros/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) DUBUQUE, Iowa -- Aug. 19, 2000 -- GORE-1 -- With the
sprawling Mississippi River as a backdrop, Al Gore touted his
environmental record, Saturday, and maintained that Republican
presidential rival George W. Bush would allow polluters to foul the
air and water. Opening the second day of his picturesque four-day
riverboat ride down the Mississippi, Gore said the trip caused him
to reflect on the need to focus on the environment. Gore and his
wife Tippper celebrating her 52nd birthday in Dubuque, Iowa,
Saturday. The Gore's planned a birthday party in Clinton, Iowa
later in the evening. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- Aug. 19, 2000 -- NYPD-CHIEF -- Former Police
Commissioner Howard Safir, left, presents the official police
commissioner's badge to the newly named New York City police
commissioner, Bernard Kerik, center, as Mayor Rudolph Giuliani
looks on, at New York's City Hall, Saturday. Kerik, 44, a former
New York City corrections commissioner, is the city's 40th police
commissioner. Chief of Department Joseph Dunne, also a contender
for the commissioner's job, was named First Deputy Commissioner,
the second in command in the department. (Suzanne DeChillo/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) KADUNA, Nigeria -- Aug. 19, 2000 -- NIGERIA-OBASANJO-3 --
In tranquil Abuja, Nigeria, the troubles of the nation that has
long represented both Africa's highest hopes and deepest despair
seem unimaginable. Drive two hours north to Kaduna, however, and
the despair is on stark display. In a city that once had a
cosmopolitan tone and religious integration, riots killed thousands
of residents this year, and neighborhoods reduced to rubble have
become segregated between Muslims and Christians. ``If we want to
get proper peace in Kaduna, we have to divide the state into two,''
says Simeon Achi, 61, Christian community leader, with his son,
Musa, 31, in Kaduna. (Norimitsu Onishi/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) ZAMFARA, Nigeria -- Aug. 19, 2000 -- NIGERIA-OBASANJO-2
-- Faced in eight northern states with the declaration of Shariah
law, the legal code of Islam based on the Koran, Nigeria's
president Olusegun Obasanjo, who took power 15 months ago, has
reacted cautiously and called for a political solution to the
challenge of Islamic extremism. Traders pray outside the main
market in the Zamfara state of Nigeria, where Islamic law has been
adopted. (Norimitsu Onishi/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) BRISTOL, Ct. -- Aug. 19, 2000 -- BBO-LITTLE-LEAGUE --
Baseball is so ingrained in the local fabric of Goffstown, N.H.,
that the town holds a parade, complete with marching bands and a
barbecue, for the opening day of the Little League and Babe Ruth
League seasons. Goffstown, N.H., players celebrate after they
reached the Little League World Series by defeating a Bronx team
last Thursday at the A. Bartlett Giamatti Little League Leadership
Training Center in Bristol, Ct. (Vincent Laforet/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) ABUJA, Nigeria -- Aug. 19, 2000 -- NIGERIA-OBASANJO-1 --
On the continent with the world's richest natural resources and
poorest people, Nigeria has so much oil that it may eventually rank
second only to Saudi Arabia, but its inhabitants have one of the
lowest standards of living. On a continent riven by cleavages among
ethnic groups, Nigeria has the most, perhaps as many as 400. A
mosque in Abuja, Nigeria, left, faces a Christian church, right.
Tensions between Christians and Muslims have grown recently.
(Norimitsu Onishi/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
