<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS DEFENSE, FLAGGING IN PRE-SEASON, MAY BE NEW SCAPEGOAT 
</HEADLINE>
  By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years now, it has become almost routine to blame whatever is
going wrong with the Giants on the team's offense. But in the 2000
season, as promised, these are the new-look Giants.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday night's shabby performance in a 27-24 loss to the
Jets, that means there's a fresh place to look when placing blame
after a debacle.
</P>
<P>
   The offense had its share of problems _ the unit committed 11 of
the preposterous 16 Giants penalties in the game. But they moved
the football, scoring three touchdowns. They were 13 yards short of
accumulating 500 yards in offense.
</P>
<P>
   It was the Giants' once-proud defense that appeared in disarray.
From front line to back line, they not only lacked cohesion, but
were mired in confusion.
</P>
<P>
   It is only the preseason, but Michael Strahan has registered
half a sack after three games and there has been too little
pressure applied on the opposing quarterback from his mates.
Linebacker Jessie Armstead is playing ably but not dominating. His
new soul mate in the middle, Mike Barrow, debuted for the Giants
Friday and was trapped out of the play repeatedly on draws up the
middle. The secondary played a step behind the Jets' smaller,
quicker receivers and disregarded their coverage assignments, too.
</P>
<P>
   Again, it is only the preseason, but the Jets, led by their
backup quarterback Ray Lucas, ran just 57 plays Friday night and
still gained 446 yards. That's an average of 7.8 yards per play _
10 yards per pass play and 5.7 per rushing play.
</P>
<P>
   And while the Giants, who are without a victory in the
preseason, pointed to the team's reserves for their troubles before
Friday's game, it was the starters who gave up nearly 80 percent of
the yardage and the scoring against the Jets.
</P>
<P>
   The Giants' defensive players are still a confident lot, and
they were somewhat defiant after the game, insisting they are still
one of the top defensive teams in the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to push the panic button,'' defensive tackle
Keith Hamilton said. ``I still feel good about the defense. It
doesn't change anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstead added: ``We'll correct this. I guarantee our very first
practice next week will be different.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Giants look a long way from their form in 1997, when
they were the third-best NFL defense against the run and opposing
offenses averaged 3.4 yards per rushing carry and 4.7 yards per
play over all.
</P>
<P>
   Since defensive end is one of the most pivotal positions on the
field, it is hard not to wonder what has happened to Strahan, who
had 29 sacks in 1997 and 1998 but 5.5 last season. So far this
year, he has not displayed a return to his old form.
</P>
<P>
   Strahan has not been particularly forthcoming about the
drop-off. After Friday's game he told reporters: ``Don't be coming
over here with those questions. You're just trying to tick me
off.''
</P>
<P>
   But Strahan had to acknowledge there is a different feel about
this defense than the one that seemed on the rise in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're definitely not as comfortable a defense as we were back
in '97,'' he said. ``But we're learning to play together.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jim Fassel wasn't taking the situation with the same
aplomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've gotten a pass rush all preseason,'' he
said. ``There's been no pressure on the quarterback.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrow, meanwhile, conceded the defense looked awful, saying the
Giants could take the video tape of Friday's game and use it as a
training video on ``how not to play the run.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrow's middling play could be chalked up to his unfamiliarity
with his new teammates. Armstead, however, is counted on for his
stellar play. If he does not excel once the regular season begins,
there will be new questions about the health of his right knee,
which troubled him last season.
</P>
<P>
   In the secondary, right cornerback Jason Sehorn made one mistake
that gave the Jets a touchdown, though he played solidly
thereafter. The left cornerback, Dave Thomas, was picked on
repeatedly by Lucas, who frequently looked to that side of the
field from the moment he started dropping back in the pocket.
</P>
<P>
   This could easily be the strategy employed by Giants opponents
for the rest of the year, which means Thomas may need help from the
safeties. But free safety Shaun Williams hasn't played yet because
of a sprained toe and strong safety Sam Garnes was fooled just as
Thomas was on the run fake part of a flea-flicker that became the
second Jets touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   This, too, could be a recurring problem for the Giants because
both Garnes and Thomas are strong against the run and less skilled
in pass coverage.
</P>
<P>
   It is just one preseason game, but it gave the Giants evidence
there is plenty to fix _ on the defensive side of the ball, for a
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating to look at the talent and potential we
have on defense and to see us play that way,'' Sehorn said. ``When
you see all those breakdowns you say, `What were we practicing all
that other stuff for?' We've got a lot of work to do to prove
ourselves again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
