<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ANGELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH PETTITTE PITCHING ENTIRE GAME, YANKEES TROUNCE ANGELS 9-1 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Andy Pettitte departed Yankee Stadium Friday in the
sixth inning, before the Yankees' collapse, before they blew their
five-run lead in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte saw the 11th inning in his living room, saw Anaheim's
Darin Erstad slug the game-winning home run, and Pettitte became
cognizant of the burden shifting onto his broad shoulders.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte, the Yankees' starting pitcher Saturday, knew he had to
quickly establish himself _ and the whole team, for that matter _
and quickly exorcise the feelings lingering from Friday's defeat.
The left-hander struck out Erstad with a cut fastball to start the
game, the Yankees struck for seven runs in the first three innings
and ultimately smashed the Angels, 9-1. Pettitte pitched the entire
game and is 15-6, having won his last six starts.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Sojo lined a two-run homer in the first inning, and David
Justice mashed a pair of home runs, his 33rd and 34th.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just had to forget about yesterday,'' Sojo said. ``We just
had to forget about it and come back today.''
</P>
<P>
   As many of his players fled the Yankees' clubhouse after
Friday's disaster, Torre lingered in his office and identified a
silver lining: Thank goodness, Torre said, that the Yankees had an
afternoon game in about 13 hours, so that they could immediately go
about the business of pushing Anaheim's staggering comeback into
their past.
</P>
<P>
   It was not easy.
</P>
<P>
   Mariano Rivera, who had surrendered the game-tying home run to
Mo Vaughn in the ninth, said the loss bothered him more than any in
his career. Torre passed Tino Martinez in the clubhouse and
Martinez asked the manager how he was feeling, perhaps trying to
decide whether the look on Torre's face betrayed tiredness or the
hangover of disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   But Torre said before the game he expected they would rebound.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been through this so many times before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had not taken batting practice outdoors for three
days, skipping Wednesday's session because of the hot weather in
Texas, missing Thursday because of overnight travel from Texas, and
missing Friday because of the rain that showered the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   The sun was out and the air was pleasantly cool Saturday
morning, and shortly after 11 a.m., the Yankees started departing
their clubhouse and warming up on the field, with Martinez and
Scott Brosius and others playing catch in front of the Yankees'
dugout. It was impossible to tell whether Friday's defeat weighed
on any of them, if they were even thinking about it.
</P>
<P>
   Sojo had been more concerned about whether or not he was in the
lineup, waiting in front of his locker until the hitting coach
Chris Chambliss posted the batting order on the clubhouse door,
then walking across the room to find his name.
</P>
<P>
   Sojo started at second base, batting second, and after the
Anaheim starter Brian Cooper (4-8) nailed Derek Jeter with a
fastball leading off the first, Sojo drilled a two-run homer into
the left-field stands. The Yankees added a walk, three singles for
two more runs, freeing Pettitte to pitch aggressively. He was
throwing hard, and his fastball had unusually sharp movement, and
Pettitte attacked, striking out four of the first six batters he
faced, breezing through the Anaheim lineup most of the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte has compiled a 2.41 earned run average in his last six
starts, and has a chance to win 20 games for the first time since
1996, when he finished 21-8.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably about as strong as I've felt this late in the
season,'' he said. ``Even in my bullpen work, I feel like
everything is in a real good slot.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Gant misplayed one fly ball in the third and forgot how many
outs there were when catching another, helping the Yankees scored
three times on three sacrifice flies. The game was an 8-0 wipeout
after five innings, and already Friday's debacle seemed like just
another forgettable result during the course of the long season.
</P>
<P>
   When the Angels began to stir in the sixth, putting runners at
second and third with a walk and a double, Pettitte snagged Tim
Salmon's hard grounder through the middle and caught Kevin Stocker
off third base _ Anaheim's fourth major base-running snafu in the
first three games of this series. Sojo dove to stop a grounder by
Vaughn and threw to first to end the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   The rest was just window dressing: the home runs by Justice,
Torre clearing his bench and resting some of his regulars. The good
thing, from the perspective of the Yankees, is that they don't play
again until Sunday afternoon, giving them one full day to remember
this crisp victory, and one more day to forget Friday's nightmare.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
