<HEADER>
A6775 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-2000-2NDLD-W     08-19 1064
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-2000-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH AND GORE PLAN AD BLITZES AS 80-DAY ELECTION DRIVE BEGINS 
</HEADLINE>
   (DELETES ``Midwestern'' from 3rd graf)  
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Moving on several fronts to capitalize on the
afterglow from their conventions, the presidential contenders plan
next week to open the biggest television advertising blitzes of
their campaigns, in which Gov. George W. Bush will emphasize
education and Vice President Al Gore will trumpet himself as a
champion of ``working families.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides said they were preparing for the hectic 80-day
marathon to Election Day and had begun making critical decisions
about where to campaign and where to funnel resources, including an
infusion of nearly $68 million in federal subsidies each.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is seizing the offensive and plans to advertise and
campaign in historically Democratic states. Among the 21 states
chosen for an advertising drive that begins on Monday is West
Virginia, which Republicans have not carried since 1984. The
commercials will also appear in the swing states of Pennsylvania,
Michigan, Ohio and Missouri, and in states like Oregon, Washington
and New Mexico, where President Clinton prevailed in 1992 and 1996
but where Bush thinks his chances are good.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the point at which the campaign pivots,'' said Karl
Rove, Bush's chief strategist. ``Our focus has been preparing for
the conventions. Now we're making major forays onto the turf that
the other guy considers his own.''
</P>
<P>
   The commercials lay out Bush's broad goals for education,
including greater local control of schools, stricter standards and
increased federal spending to promote reading and strengthen
teacher training and math and science.
</P>
<P>
   Gore officials said they would focus largely on the battle
ground states of the Midwest and make particular appeals to women
who seemed enticed by the Republicans. They also said they would
continue to cite Bush's record in Texas as demonstrating his
failure to tackle health care for children, improving the
environment, gun control and other issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``The battle lines are drawn,'' said Robert Shrum, one of Gore's
leading strategists. ``Al Gore comes out of the convention much
more clearly defined to people. There's a choice on a thematic
dimension: Who's going to stand up and fight for middle-class
families on prescription drugs, a patients' bill of rights and
education?''
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign officials said they were also working closely with
state Republican Party organizations to develop ambitious programs
to identify potential supporters and encourage them to vote. The
Gore campaign is making such efforts as well, but is more reliant
on unions to help drive turnout.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Democratic convention, polls showed that Bush was
ahead of Gore. The Gore campaign's objective has been to build on
the publicity and good feeling from the convention to help Gore
pull even with Bush by the end of the month.
</P>
<P>
   In 1984 and every presidential campaign since, the candidate who
was ahead in the polls after the conventions won the election. But
because there is an open race and both camps seem relatively evenly
matched, Republican and Democratic strategists predict that the
2000 race may be closer to 1980, when President Jimmy Carter and
Ronald Reagan were neck-and-neck in the polls after the convention
_ and Reagan pulled out a victory in the closing days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see how it can be anything but a competitive race,''
said Tom Cole, chief of staff for the Republican National
Committee. ``Our biggest advantage right now is our base unified
quicker than theirs. But that's going to happen at some point for
them. Then we're going to be in a very close race.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of Gore and his vice presidential candidate, Sen.
Joseph Lieberman, Cole added, ``They're not going to go gently into
that good night.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Tommy Thompson of Wisconsin, a Republican, said the best
evidence of the competitiveness was in his state, which was
Clinton-Gore territory in the last two elections but now appears to
be a tossup.
</P>
<P>
   ``George W. Bush has every opportunity to win this election,''
Thompson said. ``To give you an idea, George Bush has already been
here three times and Al Gore has been here four or five times. And
both of them are going to be in Milwaukee next week.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dick Gephardt of Missouri, the Democratic leader, said now
that the public might be beginning to pay attention to the contest,
Gore should hammer away at a theme he introduced at the convention:
how the policies of a president can touch the lives of ordinary
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people weren't watching this _ they were watching
`Survivor' or something else,'' Gephardt said. ``Al Gore should
articulate the stakes in this election and in people's everyday
lives.''
</P>
<P>
   Public opinion needs to settle for at least several days before
polls can give an accurate picture of how the relative standing of
Gore and Bush might have shifted after the two biggest political
events of the summer: the national party conventions and selection
of running mates.
</P>
<P>
   But the consensus in interviews with a variety of strategists
and campaign officials on both sides is that both campaigns did
themselves some good on both counts _ or, at the very least, did
not lose ground.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Tom Vilsack of Iowa, a Democrat, said his initial fears
that Clinton's appearance would siphon attention from Gore had been
allayed. ``This whole issue of contrasting Clinton and Gore _ I
wasn't sure how this would all work out,'' Vilsack said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, referring to Gore's speech, he added, ``But I will tell
you _ with no disrespect at all to the president _ I thought
halfway through the speech, `Bill who?'''
</P>
<P>
   Though both conventions seemed to be helpful to the nominees, if
anything, strategists in both parties seemed to agree, Bush put on
a slightly better convention than Gore. Several experts said that
was because the Republicans seemed more harmonious and laid out a
broader message of inclusion. By contrast, many strategists said,
the vice president's convention was a bit more uneven and seemed
less successful in reaching beyond the party's core voters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush had a better convention week, but not a better speech,''
said David Axelrod, a Democratic strategist in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Gore campaign officials said they were pleased that during their
convention they had made significant in-roads in presenting Gore as
more than a vice president; as a nominee with a populist streak who
will energetically fight for ``working families'' _ a favorite Gore
phrase _ on a variety of issues, from health care to Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   But even loyal Democrats here expressed some distress about Gore
and his difficulty in winning clusters of voters _ like women _ who
are historically inclined to vote Democratic. And they cited the
ball and chain of Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm worried that the people of America will not give him a
fair hearing,'' said Raymond Ensher, a delegate from Colorado.
``They continue to associate him, I think unfairly, with the
problems Bill Clinton has had.'' Ensher added: ``What really
worries me are the women. That really worries me.''
</P>
<P>
   Rove, Bush's strategist, noted that Bush had already succeeded
in staking out issues that Bob Dole, the nominee four years ago,
did not dare discuss. ``Can you imagine if Bob Dole had stood up
and said, `I want to reform Social Security,''' he asked. ``The
race would be over. Can you imagine a Republican candidate saying,
`We've got to get rid of so many nuclear bombs?' We did it and got
away with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the slightly better reviews for the Republican
production than the Democratic one, people in both parties said
Gore's choice of Lieberman seemed, at least in the short term, to
be better than Bush's choice of Dick Cheney, the former secretary
of defense, on the Republican side. That is because Lieberman, the
first Jew on a major party ticket, was greeted with euphoria among
Democrats and caused people to take more notice of Gore. The choice
of Cheney underscored Bush's determination to pick a competent No.
2 who would know how to govern. Yet it stirred little excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good pick for him,'' Sen. Sam Brownback, R-Kan., said
of Lieberman. ``It generated some excitement and interest that
wasn't there. Cheney solidified Bush, but I couldn't really measure
what he's done broader.''
</P>
<P>
   Brownback warned, however, that the Lieberman pick could come
back to haunt Gore. If the Democrats attack Bush for their
positions on Social Security privatization and education reform, he
said, Republicans can simply invoke Lieberman's record on those
issues, which is not too far from Bush's.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides are also looking to the nationally televised
presidential debates beginning in October _ three are tentatively
scheduled _ to provide the last opportunities to scramble the
dynamic. Unless a candidate performs poorly, as Ronald Reagan did
in the first debate against Walter Mondale in 1984, debates usually
do not do much more than reinforce partisan allegiances. (Reagan,
however, improved his performances in later debates and went on to
win in a landslide.)
</P>
<P>
   The closer the race, the more influential the debates will be,
Rove said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if it affects only 1 percent that could make a
difference,'' he said, ``because I think the race is going to be
very tight.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Sturla, a Democratic state representative in Pennsylvania
who was a delegate here this week, said the debates would be
critical. But in the next breath he wondered aloud whether the
build-up of Gore as an accomplished debater _ and criticism of Bush
as lackluster _ could play right into the Bush strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Republicans, knowing they will get crushed, have lowered
expectations so much that Bush would have to wilt and slither off
the stage,'' Sturla said, ``for his performance to be judged a
surprise and a failure.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the debates, the candidates will mostly convey their
messages through paid commercials. Bush, who did not accept public
money in the primaries so he could exceed the federal spending
limit, has agreed in the general election to join Gore in financing
his campaign with federal money.
</P>
<P>
   Bush campaign advisers and supporters seem almost preoccupied
over the possibility that the Democrats will begin broadcasting
harsh commercials that try to scare voters away from their
candidate _ all in a drive to gain an edge over Bush. The
Democrats, preferring not to portray the commercials as negative,
say they will not shrink from what they call issue comparisons.
Some Democratic operatives say it seems that the Republicans want
to goad Gore into a slash-and-burn posture so they can turn around
and paint him as mean-spirited, and then attack him right back.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Gore campaign will probably go pretty negative,'' said
Gov. Paul Cellucci of Massachusetts, a Republican. ``It's important
that we respond right away to that.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore's advisers said their hope was that in the speech on
Thursday, the vice president diffused some of the concern that he
was not sufficiently likable, so voters were not more inclined to
warm up to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt, for his part, conceded that Bush had a winning
personality that made it easier for his party to put on a moderate
face in Philadelphia. The hope, he said, is that people recognize
that a candidate's beliefs are at least as vital as personality.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're good at public relations,'' Gephardt said of the
Republicans. ``They are good a manufacturing an illusion. They are
expert at it. They may succeed. But I hope they don't.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-00 1820EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
