<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6778 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GAINESVILLE-MURDERS08     08-19 2736
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAINESVILLE-MURDERS0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    The Gainesville Murders: 10 Years Later
 &HT;    By Paul Lomartire
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GAINESVILLE, Fla. _ The police warn you before you go in: People
faint when they see these crime-scene pictures. Or get violently
ill. Or go numb with shock.
</P>
<P>
   And nobody sleeps well for months after they look in the albums.
Nobody.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody can forget the faces of the five students Danny Rolling
murdered on Aug. 24, 25 and 27, 1990.
</P>
<P>
   The stoic calm of Christina Powell.
</P>
<P>
   The eerie peace of Christa Hoyt.
</P>
<P>
   The shocked grimace of Manny Taboada.
</P>
<P>
   The dazed disbelief of Sonja Larson.
</P>
<P>
   The pain and defiance of Tracy Paules.
</P>
<P>
   Five kids, just kids. Three of them asleep and waking to stare
up at a monster in a ski mask.
</P>
<P>
   The traces of their short lives are scattered across each of the
8-by-10s:
</P>
<P>
   One photo catches a glimpse of Christa Hoyt's kitchen, a
red-and-white KFC box, one drumstick left, sitting next to a
Dunkin' Donuts box.
</P>
<P>
   Another shows Manny Taboada's and Tracy Paules' apartment, the
living room wall decorated with pictures of Bon Jovi and Paula
Abdul.
</P>
<P>
   In another, Christina Powell's purse is spilled out on the
carpet next to her living room couch. Family pictures, change, a
checkbook, a Bic pen.
</P>
<P>
   Ordinary things, juxtaposed against unimaginable violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the cumulative amount of horror'' that haunts people,
says Capt. Sadie Darnell of the Gainesville Police Department, who
was the department's spokesman during the mayhem. Ten years have
gone by, but time hasn't dimmed her bad dreams.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a nightmare about it again, just last night,'' she says.
``For whatever reason, I was thinking about those photos . . . ``
</P>
<P>
   THE FIRST CRIME SCENE: TERRIBLY VIOLENT, 'TERRIBLY SAD'
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, after Rolling was sentenced to death, the photos
were made available to the public but only by appointment and only
at the courthouse with a clerk sitting by.
</P>
<P>
   At first, 50 to 75 people lined up each day to spend 15 minutes
looking at the albums, each filled with approximately 100 photos.
Teachers, criminology students, prison guards, morticians and the
morbidly curious.
</P>
<P>
   After three weeks, the binders were loaded into a common, white,
storage box and shipped to the Florida Supreme Court to be
available to justices hearing Rolling's perfunctory appeals over
the next three years.
</P>
<P>
   When the photos returned to the Alachua courthouse in November
1997, viewers dwindled.
</P>
<P>
   Today, requests are rare. But when they do come, the nightmares
start where the albums do: With a photo of an apartment door.
</P>
<P>
   Flip the first plastic page of one album and there's the
Williamsburg Village apartment of Christina Powell and Sonja
Larson.
</P>
<P>
   ``Williamsburg just struck me as terribly sad,'' says Florida
Department of Law Enforcement special agent Ed Dix, who worked the
case for four years from crime scenes to courtroom. ``They're all
sad, but that one hit me.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell, 17, from Jacksonville, and Larson, 18, from Deerfield
Beach, became friends during summer-session freshman classes when
they shared the same University of Florida dorm. With a third
roommate from Ormond Beach, they rented an apartment for the fall
and settled on No. 113 at Williamsburg, a quasi-colonial style
complex popular with medical students because it's close to Shands
and the VA hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The UF freshmen had much in common.
</P>
<P>
   Larson had come from a math and science magnet high school where
she made National Honor Society, played softball and was a manager
for the girls' varsity basketball team. She planned to major in
education and someday open her own daycare.
</P>
<P>
   Powell, also a high school athlete, was the youngest of seven
children. She had graduated from an Episcopal high school, excelled
at Bible study and planned to major in theology.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 24, 1990, they were busy shopping for move-in stuff at
Wal-Mart. They would make their way through the checkout line
within minutes of a violent Louisiana ex-con named Danny Rolling.
</P>
<P>
   Rolling had arrived by bus from Sarasota five nights before, and
that Friday night, he had made his way out to camp in the woods on
UF property. At Wal-Mart, he bought a $20 tent and shoplifted two
pairs of black gloves, duct tape and a screwdriver.
</P>
<P>
   Did he see Powell and Larson there? No, he told police later.
Not then. Not yet.
</P>
<P>
   After shopping, Larson and Powell had dinner at Chili's, then
stopped at a convenience store around 11 p.m. so Larson could call
her mother. Their phone wasn't hooked up yet.
</P>
<P>
   Then they headed back home, intent on getting up early on
Saturday morning. They needed to find jobs and fix up the apartment
before their roommate and Powell's parents arrived on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Larson, wearing a yellow ``Atlanta'' T-shirt with a design of a
dog and the moon, went to sleep in an upstairs bedroom. Powell, in
a yellow tank top, slept downstairs on the living room couch.
</P>
<P>
   Rolling left his campsite, stole a bike and rode to the
Williamsburg apartments. An addicted window peeper, as was Ted
Bundy, Rolling was on the prowl. He stopped at the backyard deck at
apartment 113 and used a large screwdriver to pry open the unlocked
wood door swollen by humidity.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing black Isotoner gloves, Rolling took a brown ski mask out
of his hip bag and put it on. The bag also held a Mini-Mag
flashlight, gray duct tape and a 9-millimeter pistol. He crept past
Powell and went upstairs where he found Larson asleep. Rolling
covered her mouth with a 6-inch strip of duct tape as he stabbed
her in the chest near her collarbone. He kept stabbing.
</P>
<P>
   Then he went back downstairs, taped Powell's mouth, and when she
awakened, he bound her hands and told her he was going to rape and
kill her. He left the terrified woman for several minutes and went
into the kitchen, where he ate an apple and a banana. Then he raped
and stabbed Powell.
</P>
<P>
   Rolling, the son of a Shreveport, La., cop, used dish soap to
clean the bodies and remove evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in a final gruesome act that would become his signature,
he posed the bodies in lewd positions.
</P>
<P>
   Powell's parents, worried because they hadn't heard from their
daughter, arrived on Sunday from Jacksonville. When no one answered
the door, they called police.
</P>
<P>
   All neighbors would remember about No. 113 was the two pretty
brunettes carrying stuff in and hearing George Michael's ``Faith ``
blasting from the apartment early Friday.
</P>
<P>
   SPYING IN THE SHADOWS, WAITING TO STRIKE
</P>
<P>
   Flip another plastic page.
</P>
<P>
   There's a photo of Christa Hoyt's dining room table covered with
pieces of her busy life: A bookstore catalog, black binder, class
schedule, pencils and crumpled paper.
</P>
<P>
   Hoyt, 18, wanted to work at an FBI crime lab. The honors student
in chemistry was fascinated by forensic science and worked
full-time as a records clerk for the Alachua County Sheriff's
Office while she went to Santa Fe Community College.
</P>
<P>
   Hoyt lived alone in a tree-shaded duplex apartment across from a
trailer park.
</P>
<P>
   Danny Rolling had been spying on her for days, watching through
a window as she took a shower.
</P>
<P>
   On the evening of Aug. 25, as Hoyt was out playing racquetball,
Rolling broke into her apartment and hid behind a bookcase. He
surprised her with a choke hold when she returned home around 11
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   After terrorizing and raping her, Rolling forced Hoyt to lie on
her stomach. Then he stabbed her to death. He closed her eyes and
posed her body.
</P>
<P>
   Later, riding a stolen bicycle, Rolling went to a nearby
convenience store for a soda. But when he went to pay, his wallet
was missing. He rushed back to Hoyt's apartment in a panic.
</P>
<P>
   When he went to her bedroom to look for his wallet, he saw that
Hoyt's eyes were open, and he ``freaked.'' He decapitated her, then
smoothed her hair and placed her head on a bookshelf so it would be
the first thing police saw from the bedroom door.
</P>
<P>
   He never found his wallet.
</P>
<P>
   FEAR GRIPS GAINESVILLE: 'NO ONE SLEPT WELL'
</P>
<P>
   The scene of Hoyt's murder was the worst Ed Dix has ever seen.
``It was just beyond belief.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon after her body was found, and Powell's and Larson's murders
were discovered, an army of 600 TV and newspaper reporters
descended on Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   Sadie Darnell, the police spokesman, had to tell the world what
had turned Gainesville from a happy campus town to a paranoid armed
camp.
</P>
<P>
   Days before the start of a fall semester for 34,000 students,
priorities switched from bookstore runs to runs to the gun and pawn
shops. Stun guns sold out, and baseball-bat supplies ran low.
Terrified parents either retrieved their kids or retreated with
their kids to fortified Gainesville apartments.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you heard a little creak in the night or heard a little
wind blow, you were up at alert wondering if he was coming through
your window,'' recalls Dix.
</P>
<P>
   Gainesville police chief Wayland Clifton and Sheriff Lu Hindery
combined forces and created a task force that included FDLE, the
FBI and the Florida Highway Patrol.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were 100 detectives, 50 Florida Highway Troopers in
addition to what is normally here,'' recalls Dix. ``All police
agencies were working seven days a week, split shifts, every
officer was working 12 hours a day, seven days a week. The police
presence was greater than probably any city in the world for that
period of time.
</P>
<P>
   ``And no one slept well.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially after the next victims were found.
</P>
<P>
   TRACY PAULES SCREAMED: 'YOU'RE HIM, AREN'T YOU?'
</P>
<P>
   Tracy Paules, the homecoming queen, liked living with her
platonic pal, Manny Taboada, the football star.
</P>
<P>
   He was 6-feet-2 and 200 pounds, and he made his longtime friend
feel safe.
</P>
<P>
   They were both popular kids, Class of '84, Hialeah's American
High School.
</P>
<P>
   Taboada excelled both on stage, as president of the drama club,
and on the football field, where he played guard. Paules was the
all-American girl: cheerleader, softball player, newspaper editor,
senior class president.
</P>
<P>
   After high school, both worked and went to Miami Dade Community
College before deciding to move to Gainesville.
</P>
<P>
   Taboada, 23, went to Santa Fe Community College and hoped to
become an architect. Paules, also 23, enrolled at UF intending to
major in law.
</P>
<P>
   Taboada had just gotten a bartending job at Bennigan's near
their apartment. He was late coming home on Monday night, a fact
noted by Paules, who was in her bedroom on the phone, talking to a
friend about what everyone in Gainesville was talking about _ the
murders.
</P>
<P>
   When Taboada got home after 2 a.m., he was exhausted. He said
goodnight to Paules and went to bed wearing a red T-shirt and
briefs.
</P>
<P>
   What he didn't know was that Rolling was in the woods that
bordered the back of apartment 1203, peeping in their windows.
Rolling had watched Paules for three hours when Taboada came home.
</P>
<P>
   When both were asleep, Rolling used a screwdriver to pry open
the apartment's sliding glass patio doors. Once in the apartment,
he eased past Paules' bedroom, where a light was on. Taboada's room
was dark, his door opened wide enough for his gray and white
Persian cat, Sasha, to come in.
</P>
<P>
   Rolling, in the same black death costume he wore at the previous
murders, pounced on Taboada, plunging the combat knife into his
chest and striking his heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ahhhh, I've been shot,'' Taboada screamed. Although dying on
his waterbed, Taboada fought as Rolling stabbed. ``You bastard!''
Taboada cursed before trying to warn his roommate, ``Ahhhh,
Tracy!''
</P>
<P>
   Paules heard the noise and was in the hallway outside her
bedroom. When she saw Rolling, she jumped back into her room and
slammed the door, which Rolling opened with a kick.
</P>
<P>
   As Rolling wrestled Paules to the bed, she screamed: ``You're
him, aren't you?''
</P>
<P>
   Rolling answered, ``No, lady, I'm not.''
</P>
<P>
   After he terrorized and raped her, Rolling had Paules turn over
on her stomach so he wouldn't see her face as he stabbed her in the
back. He did that with each of his female victims. Then he posed
her body in the hallway.
</P>
<P>
   Police documented it on film, evidence of the most gruesome
murders in Florida's recent history.
</P>
<P>
   THE HAUNTING: FOR SOME, IT NEVER GOES AWAY
</P>
<P>
   The death toll at five, Rolling fled to Tampa and on to Ocala,
where he was arrested Sept. 7 after a botched Winn-Dixie robbery.
Suspecting Rolling of a triple homicide in Louisiana, Shreveport
police traveled to Gainesville to fill cops in on his violent past.
Physical evidence eventually linked Rolling to three of the
Gainesville murders.
</P>
<P>
   On Feb. 15, 1994, the day his trial was to begin, he pleaded
guilty to five counts of premeditated murder, three counts of
sexual battery and two counts of burglary/assault. The jury that
sentenced him to death saw just one album of photos. Some details
are too gruesome to ever repeat, even in court.
</P>
<P>
   Rolling spilled his story to his then-fiancee, Sondra London,
who co-authored his book in 1996 but was prohibited from making any
money from ``The Making of A Serial Killer.''
</P>
<P>
   Today, at the apartment complexes where the students died,
managers throw reporters off the property. The places are rented.
Life goes on.
</P>
<P>
   Most students at the University of Florida don't know anything
about the murders. They drive by the wall that lists the victims'
names, but they don't know why it's there. Or who Sonja, Christina,
Christa, Manny and Tracy were.
</P>
<P>
   But the police who worked the crime scenes, who live with the
images, know those faces. They know them well. And that's what
makes it so hard to heal.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Snook coordinates the forensics lab work for the Alachua
County Sheriff's Office. Usually, when he works a crime scene, he
doesn't go deeper than what he can see, bag, photograph and dust
for prints.
</P>
<P>
   If he lets a victim's life seep into his, it'll be there
forever. That's what happened to Snook with the student murders.
</P>
<P>
   It happened to Sadie Darnell and Ed Dix, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to analyze this one time, and I realized what made
this one different,'' Snook says. ``It's not so much the
gruesomeness of the killings, we see a lot of gruesome things, but
normally, in most cases, you don't get to know the victim as a
person. You don't get to know their family. In this case, with the
length, everything that dragged out, we got to know who these
victims were and got to know their family members, and it got you
away from being analytical. That to me was the biggest
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   On his office wall is a thank-you memorial plaque with photos of
the five students given to him by the families of the victims, who
rewarded police after Rolling's sentencing in 1994 with a luncheon
at Gainesville's upscale Sovereign restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Snook glances up at the plaque.
</P>
<P>
   He's not sure what clicks on the crime-scene replay in his mind.
But it's there, he says, and it's always the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a horrible thing those last few minutes were for each of
those victims. You think about that.''
</P>
<P>
   THE HEALING: ALWAYS, THEY 'REMEMBER'
</P>
<P>
   Sadie Darnell saw some of her colleagues leave law enforcement
because of the murders. Some journalists did, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't want to deal with the death,'' she says. ``They
didn't want to deal with that constant refrain in your mind of what
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Darnell deals with it by ``choosing to be conscious of beautiful
things. I read good books, I watch good, enriching movies. I listen
to classical music, beautiful things like that. I have to remember
there are good things in this world.''
</P>
<P>
   Sonja, Christina, Christa, Tracy and Manny were good things,
beautiful things. Darnell has become a member of their families,
and she continues to speak on their behalf.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sadie is a special kind of person, very efficient, organized,
caring, understanding and intelligent,'' says Sonja Larson's
mother, Ada, who now lives in Boca Raton. ``We have come to love
her dearly.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Darnell and the families will have a memorial service
near the ``Remember'' wall. They recently sandblasted the wall and
covered the panel with a finish that will keep anyone from painting
over it. The city planted five Sabal palms along the median in
their children's memory.
</P>
<P>
   Beautiful things. Living things. Lasting things.
</P>
<P>
   To help keep the nightmares away.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
