<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR SATURDAY, AUGUST 19 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Saturday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-KOREA-REUNIONS-NYT (moved Tuesday, August 15)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, August 15
about the reunion of relatives separated by the Korean War referred
incorrectly to the flight that took North Koreans to Seoul. The
North Korean plane was not the first to land in the South since
1950. At least one other, a warplane flown by a defector, landed
there in 1996. The article also misstated the term for traditional
Korean dresses worn by some of the North Korean women. It is han
bok, not han dok.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MCCAIN-CANCER-NYT (moved Thursday, August 17)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Thursday, August
17 about the treatment that may face Senator John McCain of Arizona
for skin cancer omitted a word in a quotation from his speech at
the Republican National Convention. He said, ``The years that
remain are not too few, I trust, but the immortality that was the
inspiration of my youth has, like all the treasures of youth,
quietly slipped away.'' He did not say, ``The years that remain are
too few.''
</P>
<P>
   BC-CIR-GUERRILLA-ART (moved Wednesday, August 16)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service Circuits article sent on
Wednesday, August 16 about RTMark, an online group that seeks to
undermine corporations, misstated the given name of a college
student who sent it money. He is Kenneth DeGraff, not Frank.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-YOUNG-NYT (moved Saturday, August 12)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service obituary sent on Saturday, August
12 of Loretta Young on Sunday misidentified ``Come to the Stable.''
It was a 1949 film starring Young, not an episode of her television
series.
</P>
</TEXT>
