u w BC-GORE-0820-COX     08-19 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE CAMPAIGNS IN MIDWEST SWING STATES BOLSTERED BY NEW POLLS
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ABOARD THE MARK TWAIN _ Al Gore's presidential campaign found
life on the Mississippi Saturday with word of a new poll suggesting
the vice president may have overtaken Republican rival George W.
Bush in a tight race for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   A Newsweek poll conducted at the end of the Democratic
convention shows the vice president with a 52 percent to 48 percent
lead over Bush in a head-to-head contest, wiping out the double
digit lead the Texas governor scored in the magazine's poll at the
end of the GOP convention two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   The poll of 806 registered voters showed Gore with a 48 percent
to 42 percent lead over Bush in a four-way contest involving Green
Party candidate and consumer activist Ralph Nader, 3 percent, and
Reform Party candidate Pat Buchanan, 1 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The poll, conducted last Thursday and Friday after Gore's
acceptance speech, had a margin of error of (+-) 4 percent, meaning
the presidential contest, in Newsweek's most recent assessment, is
virtually a tie _ a major accomplishment for Gore after badly
trailing Bush for months.
</P>
<P>
   After the GOP convention in Philadelphia, the Newsweek poll
showed Bush with a 49-38 percent lead over Gore. And a week ago,
Newsweek gave Bush a 48-38 percent lead over Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Word of the poll reached the slow-moving Mark Twain riverboat
shortly after Gore disembarked from Dubuque, Iowa, Saturday for the
second leg of a four-day, 400-mile trip down to Hannibal, Mo.,
through Midwestern states that are crucial to Gore's election
strategy.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, wearing jeans, a denim shirt and cowboy boots, paid a
brief visit to the press area on the riverboat to offer an even
briefer assessment of the Newsweek poll.
</P>
<P>
   ``My reaction to the Newsweek poll is the same as it has been to
all the polls of the past two years: I really don't think polls
matter,'' Gore said. ``People are now just beginning to pay close
attention to the election.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, with a smile: ``I must admit I'm beginning to
think that the polls have a little more relevancy as we get close
the election.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're seeing significant tightening of this race,'' Gore
spokesman Chris Lehane said. ``This is going to be a very close,
hard-fought race. And what you're seeing is Bush is trying to run,
but he can't hide from the American people on the issues.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no immediate reaction to the polls from the Bush
campaign on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   More importantly, perhaps, was the Newsweek poll's finding that
an increasing number of voters regard Gore as ``personally
likable.'' In the latest poll, 70 percent found him so, up 9
percent from a week earlier. The new poll gave him a 2 percentage
point lead over Bush in this category.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the Newsweek poll found that Gore has also wiped out
Bush's lead on such basic Democratic issues as education and Social
Security and replaced it with a commanding lead of his own. In
addition, he has widened his 1 point lead on who is best equipped
to continue the economic expansion of the Clinton years to 17
points.
</P>
<P>
   The post-GOP convention poll had Bush favored to improve
education, 48-39 percent, and saving Social Security, 45-40
percent. But the post-Democratic convention poll showed Gore now
leading 49-35 percent, on education, 51-35 percent on Social
Security.
</P>
<P>
   The latest Newsweek poll also showed Gore leading 56-30 percent
on the issue of expanding healthcare; 45-39 percent on tax cuts;
58-27 percent on Medicare coverage of prescription drugs for the
elderly; and 42-38 percent on upholding moral values.
</P>
<P>
   Lehane insisted that ``a lot has changed'' since Gore's
acceptance speech at the convention last Thursday, a speech crafted
to reintroduce the vice president as a faithful husband, loving
family man and political champion of average Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are finally starting to pay attention to the campaign,
and people are finally aware that Al Gore is someone other than
vice president,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's riverbank rallies underscore the point. The crowds at
each have grown steadily, measured in the thousands rather than in
hundreds. And the Mark Twain, a diesel-driven craft designed to
resemble old-fashioned paddle- and steamboats of the 19th century,
has been shadowed by recreational boaters at points along the
Mississippi and often photographed from the houses on the banks of
the river.
</P>
<P>
   Comments from some voters at the rallies suggest Gore was
convincing in asserting in his acceptance speech that he was his
``own man.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's getting his image out,'' said Linda Gavin, a middle-aged
high school physical education teacher from Dubuque. ``He's telling
people what he's all about, not what Clinton was all about.''
</P>
<P>
   The boat trip is taking Gore through five Midwestern states that
President Clinton carried in 1992 and again in 1996, and represent
a total of 61 electoral votes of the 270 needed to win the
presidency: Minnesota, 10; Wisconsin, 11; Illinois, 22; Iowa, 7;
and Missouri, 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``The direction the Midwest goes is the direction the country
goes,'' said Lehane.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, four of the states are among the 21 the Bush campaign
announced on Saturday would be part of a new TV ad blitz starting
Monday. It will be the campaign's biggest ad launch so far and
Bush's first for the general election.
</P>
<P>
   His aides declined to say how much Bush _ campaigning in Texas
and New Mexico on Saturday _ spent on the ads, but said they will
focus on education and Bush's leadership.
</P>
<P>
   (Scott Shepard's E-mail address is: scotts(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
