<HEADER>
A6787 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-GA-EXECUTION0820-COX     08-19 1492
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-EXECUTION0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Planned execution draws international criticism on state
 &HT;    By Rhonda Cook and Jack Warner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ An international furor is rising over the scheduled
execution Thursday of Georgia prisoner Alexander Williams, who was
17 when he raped and killed a teenage model and now, 15 years
later, is termed ``flagrantly psychotic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We seem focused on some punitive action against a man who
isn't even capable of understanding his own death,'' said Cynthia
Wayne Scott, executive director of the National Mental Health
Association of Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   In Geneva last week, the United Nations Subcommittee on Human
Rights said imposing the death penalty on a prisoner who was under
18 when the crime was committed ``is contrary to customary
international law.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott's group and Amnesty International are leading efforts to
persuade the state Board of Pardons and Paroles to commute
Williams' sentence to life in prison. The Children's Defense Fund,
the Rainbow Coalition, former first lady Rosalynn Carter and the
archbishop of Atlanta also have asked the board to spare Williams'
life.
</P>
<P>
   The board will consider these appeals Tuesday. Williams' legal
appeals have been exhausted, but his attorneys intend to file new
court actions Monday.
</P>
<P>
   The objections to Williams' execution are threefold, and by and
large have been unchallenged:
</P>
<P>
   He was a month short of adulthood when he abducted Aleta Carol
Bunch, 16, from an Augusta mall, raped her, shot her to death,
stole her car and divided up her jewelry and purchases among his
friends.
</P>
<P>
   His court-appointed attorney did not interview members of his
family, which would have revealed Williams' history of emotional
and physical abuse and mental problems. When the attorney put
Williams' mother on the stand in the sentencing phase, he asked her
merely to ``say something nice'' about her son.
</P>
<P>
   PLEA FOR COMPASSION
</P>
<P>
   Court filings contend that Williams, now 32, is insane and
delusional, and is unable to comprehend what awaits him at 7 p.m.
Thursday in the death chamber at the Diagnostic and Classification
Prison near Jackson.
</P>
<P>
   However, Williams wrote a three-page letter to the parole board
on Aug. 9, confessing his guilt for the first time and asking ``the
people of Georgia to show compassion towards me.'' Its lucidity was
clouded only by failed flights of eloquence.
</P>
<P>
   ``My eyes have adjusted from those of headstrong, willful and
wayward youth in the face of impending consequence, to those of
adulthood and the reality of a brief moments span where life was
lost andthe grief it caused,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was never my intent to kill anyone . . . My thinking
eventually was irrational and my judgement clouded. But I had since
begun walking the wrong path and so the events that led to the loss
of life unfolded.
</P>
<P>
   ``My deepest regrets and most sincere apology to Ms. Aleta
Bunch. May she rest in peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Carolyn Bunch, the victim's mother, was unimpressed. ``I know
Rosalyn Carter wrote, asking for clemency. She ought to take him
home with her,'' she said. ``I don't think a week before he's to be
executed, him saying `I'm sorry' for his arrogance cuts anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Department of Corrections policy forbids discussion of a
prisoner's mental and physical health records. But an appeal
rejected last month, and Williams' disciplinary record, indicate he
is not only deeply disturbed, but dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   He has attacked guards on several occasions, and in 1990 he was
written up for ``causing an injury to a visitor.'' According to
Corrections spokesman Mike Light, when attorney Gary Alexion came
to see Williams, Alexion demanded, over the guards' warnings, that
Williams' handcuffs be removedt. No sooner had that been done than
Williams attacked Alexion. It took four officers to subdue him.
</P>
<P>
   When an unnamed female attorney came to his cell to have him
sign some papers that same year, Williams responded by dropping his
pants and exposing himself.
</P>
<P>
   According to the court filings, which contained 22 pages of
notes Williams' attorneys said came from his prison psychological
records, initial tests when he entered prison in 1986 showed
``evidence of substantial, generalized psychotic illness, which
tends to make his behavior bizarre and inappropriate.''
</P>
<P>
   A specialist in internal medicine, called in to check Williams
when he refused to eat in 1990, reported ``he is under demonic
attack'' and apparently tried to exorcise him. Failing, he noted
that ``if the chaplain is experienced in spiritual warfare, he
should be seeing this man.''
</P>
<P>
   After the attack on his attorney, a psychologist reported that
Williams told her ``the little red man in the attorney's eye had
something to do with it . . . He claims to have started seeing the
little red man after he stopped seeing the green frogs.''
</P>
<P>
   Other notes indicate that Williams decided Sigourney Weaver was
God, believed that insects had removed his left eye and substituted
a shell, and, in June1999, remained ``psychotic and potentially
dangerous.'' In December, according to the notes, he was diagnosed
as suffering ``chronic paranoid schizophrenia.''
</P>
<P>
   The notes indicate he has been on and off medication to
stabilize his behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``What value is there to society to kill a man who has
schizophrenia and is psychotic?'' asked Scott, the mental health
advocate. ``We're going to be in the eye of the world. I hope we
can do better than this.''
</P>
<P>
   The international eye appears to be focused primarily through
the London Web site of Amnesty International, which carries a
26-page denunciation of the pending execution.
</P>
<P>
   While presenting a case for Williams on all three major points,
Amnesty appears chiefly concerned with the fact that he was a
juvenile when he killed Bunch.
</P>
<P>
   Calling the United States a ``rogue nation,'' Amnesty says ``it
is clear that outside of the USA, the practice of executing people
for crimes they committed when they were children has almost been
eradicated from the planet.''
</P>
<P>
   Amnesty argues that Williams' execution would violate
international treaties, citing the International Covenant on Civil
and Political Rights and ``customary international law.''
</P>
<P>
   The state's lawyers have argued that individuals cannot claim
they have suffered because of violations of international treaties
that are ``contracts between or among independent nations.'' They
also pointed out that the United States did not agree to the
minimum age limitation contained in the fifth paragraph of Article
Six in the ICCPR.
</P>
<P>
   Since the death penalty was reinstated in Georgia in 1973, 23
men have been executed. Of those, only one, Christopher Burger, was
under 18 at the time of his crime. Jerome Bowden was executed in
1986, despite being classified as mentally retarded, which prompted
passage of a law forbidding the execution of a retarded person.
William Henry Hance was suffering hallucinations by the time he was
executed in 1994 for a 1978 murder
</P>
<P>
   Williams' execution would be the first in Georgia in 2 1/2
years.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Supreme Court has accepted death penalty laws, such as
Georgia's, that can be applied to defendants as young as 17.
</P>
<P>
   Richmond County Marshal Steve Smith was one of the sheriff's
detectives who investigated the killing of Aleta Bunch. He said
Williams and his friends _ who later testified against Williams _
freely used the girl's parents' credit cards, taken from her,
beginning the day she died.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was street smart, `` Smith recalled. ``He was very cocky,
very arrogant. He didn't want to talk to us.'' As a result, the
sole interview with detectives ``didn't last long enough for us to
tell anything about his mental state.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidence against Williams was overwhelming, and he was swiftly
convicted.
</P>
<P>
   According to Amnesty International, defense attorney O.L.
Collins never interviewed Williams' family. ``Collins did not
request a psychiatric evaluation of his client, and did no further
investigation into his psychological history or condition. Neither
did he present any argument for leniency on the basis of Williams'
young age _ which the Supreme Court had described . . . as a
``mitigating factor of great weight.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins is dead now. Smith, who sat at the prosecution table for
the trial, said he ``did not have a high-profile reputation as a
defense attorney .''
</P>
<P>
   ``The only defense testimony at sentencing was that Alex was a
good kid who liked comic books,'' said Mark Olive, Williams'
present attorney. ``This was a beaten-up kid who was succumbing to
reality-bending schizophrenia. The jurors would not have sentenced
Alex to death if they knew the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In practice, Georgia does not even seek the death penalty on
kids anymore,'' Olive said. ``This execution would be a horrible
footnote to a foregone process.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
