<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Miller's chances for '00 not great
 &HT;    By Karen Rosen
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Shannon Miller arrived at the Olympic trials and was
surprised to find out that one of her balance beam skills had been
devalued.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the Miller,'' she said of the back handspring with a
quarter twist. ``It's no longer worth anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The 23-year-old herself isn't pulling down the high scores she
did in 1996 or 1992, when she won seven Olympic medals.
</P>
<P>
   That means national team coordinator Bela Karolyi will be
walking a fine line tonight, when he has the most say in choosing
the Olympic team. Does he go with Miller, who has the biggest name
and reputation but only the seventh-best scores Friday, or a trio
of relative unknowns?
</P>
<P>
   Without a doubt, Elise Ray, the national champion, and two-time
national champ Kristen Maloney will anchor the team. Amy Chow, a
1996 team gold medalist and silver medalist on uneven bars, has
moved up to third place and is also one of Karolyi's favorites.
</P>
<P>
   That's three.
</P>
<P>
   Jamie Dantzscher, currently in fourth place, finished third at
nationals but has to overcome a reputation for inconsistency
earlier this year. Vanessa Atler, once one of the country's
strongest gymnasts, has been struggling, but Karolyi likes her
explosiveness. Morgan White, who was seventh at nationals, is now
fifth and Karolyi always speaks highly of her, too. And two-time
Olympian Dominique Dawes is still in the mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Confidence and experience is one thing,'' said Miller, who is
working on adding difficulty to her routines, ``but you have to be
able to do the stuff, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Karolyi said he didn't expect all three remaining members of
Atlanta's Magnificent Seven to make it to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my ultimate dream,'' he said, ``to see a split
participation between the old generation and the new. But the new
generation is extremely strong.''
</P>
<P>
   In Sydney, six women will be on the team, five will compete on
each event and four scores will count.
</P>
<P>
   In Dantzscher's favor is the fact that she's good in vault,
which is expected to be the U.S. team's weakest event. Miller's
best events, uneven bars and balance beam, mirror those of Ray and
Maloney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm looking forward to the chance to be on this team,'' Miller
said, ``and then over the next four weeks really nail down all my
skills.''
</P>
<P>
   But time may be running out.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
