<SLUG> BC-GLF-BISHER0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Finding farm where career is left fallow
 &HT;    By Furman Bisher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FINCHVILLE, Ky. _ Ten years ago Jody Mudd had the world on a
string. He had mounted the crest of a career and all that he could
see around him was good. He had won The Players Championship and
the Tour Championship the same year, two biggest payoffs on the PGA
Tour (only Tom Kite has ever done that) and ranked 5th in earnings.
He was only 30 years old. There was nothing out there to stop him _
but himself.
</P>
<P>
   He developed an affection for the British Open. Links courses
aroused his competitive juices, and in 1989 he finished fifth, in
1990 fourth (at St. Andrews) and in 1991 fifth again. I remember
sitting with him in the Delta Crown Room at Gatwick after one of
those glowing finishes when he said, ``Man, I love this tournament.
I'm going to come back as long as I can.''
</P>
<P>
   On this side of the pond, though, all was not well. Rank dropped
from fifth to 105th on the American tour. Himself must have taken
charge, for before long it was as if he had vanished from the face
of the earth. By 1995 he played in only nine tournaments, and the
next year four, and never made a dime.
</P>
<P>
   The story got around that he had bought a farm near Louisville,
and was going into breeding and racing thoroughbreds. He came from
Kentucky, born and reared in Louisville, land of the Kentucky
Derby, and interest in race horses goes with the territory.
</P>
<P>
   But to give up on a career such as Jody Mudd had going? He is
said to have told friends he was ``burned out.''
</P>
<P>
   Finchville, we were told, is where he was located. It's the
address listed in the PGA Tour press guide. You see, winning The
Players Championship wins the champion 10 years exemption on the
tour, and whether you play or not, you're still listed among the
actives. Mudd's exemption runs out this year and with the PGA
Championship being played a few miles up the road, near the village
of Eastwood, it seemed fitting to check him out.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a Finchville, I never found it. At a real estate
office in Simpsonville, I got directions to Jodie Mudd's farm, down
Buckcreek Road, a blacktop lane across Interstate 64, by broad
spreads of well-tended pastures and substantial houses, coming to a
sign that read: ``For Sale _ 100 acres, Bob Dorgan, agent.''
</P>
<P>
   I'd heard that Mudd was selling the farm and moving to Florida.
This was confirmation, I supposed. The house on top of the hill
stood silent and looked uninhabited, but a ring of the doorbell and
a lady answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``We bought the house and 26 acres and just moved in last
week,'' said the lady identifying herself as Beth McConnell. ``Jody
told us he was going to Saratoga, but he was back a couple of days
later trying to round up two cows that had been running loose. I
thought he might be at the golf tournament, but he said he was
going to Saratoga.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the high racing season at Saratoga, but late for the
Saratoga sales, which require a substantial cash reserve.
Apparently, the thoroughbred business hadn't turned out well,
though you hear stories of a couple of fillies that won races for
him this summer. Nothing confirmed, but then, little can be
confirmed in Jody Mudd's recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``When did you say he last played golf?'' Mrs. McConnell asked.
</P>
<P>
   ``About four years ago, 1996.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh,'' she said, ``that was about the time of the divorce.''
</P>
<P>
   Conjecture was that isolated farm life wasn't the wife's cup of
tea and she had taken her leave and returned to Atlanta, her home.
A divorce soon followed and Mudd has lived a rather reclusive life
since, with no indication of return to the professional tour. He
has played in a rare regional tournament now and then, finished
second in the Kentucky State Open last year, but reviving a golf
game that has been mothballed for a few years isn't as simple as
pulling the clubs out of the closet and dusting them off.
</P>
<P>
   Jody Mudd comes from a golfing family. Two brothers are
professionals, Tommy and Eddie, who had serious heart surgery
recently. Jody was a star at Georgia Southern, won two U.S.
Publinks championships, and after finishing low amateur at the
Masters in 1982, almost immediately turned pro. Those who recall
the promise of the fine young player coming on the tour find it
distressing that he abandoned the game that came with so much
promise.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
