<SLUG> BC-OLY-SWM-TEXAS0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Something's in the water at Texas
 &HT;    By John Maher
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ At times during the recent U.S. Olympic swimming
trials, there were so many Longhorns in the final it was a wonder
they didn't turn the pool orange. The Three Amigos, seniors Jamie
Rauch, Scott Goldblatt and Nate Dusing, all finished in the top six
in the 200-meter freestyle and are eligible to swim on the United
States' 800 relay team in Sydney, Australia. The 100 butterfly was
another Texas affair with Longhorn recruit Ian Crocker beating
Tommy Hannan.
</P>
<P>
   If you count Gary Hall Jr., who had a cup of coffee at Texas,
eight of the 24 men selected to the team were either former,
current or incoming Longhorns. And there was a rash of Texas
swimmers who didn't make the team but still turned in impressive
performances, including incoming freshman Brendan Hansen, who
finished third in the 100 and 200 breast stroke races.
</P>
<P>
   Texas, under Coach Eddie Reese, has been a swim power. But even
by Texas' standards, something special is happening.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just time for us,'' Dusing said. ``We have all
underachieved until right now. We all came in _ me, Jamie and Scott
_ at the same time with high expectations.''
</P>
<P>
   Rauch added, ``We've been talking about this for three years.
It's been a long time coming. All of us could have gone anywhere.
But we chose a school that would prepare us for this.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the formula is that Rauch, Goldblatt and Dusing, all
good friends, are finally hitting their form. They arrived heading
one of Reese's most heralded recruiting classes ever, and they've
had a good measure of success since then. All three have been on
three straight NCAA champion 800 relay teams. But it was clear at
the trials that all three had expected more out of themselves.
</P>
<P>
   One indication that they and some other Longhorns were ready to
make a jump came in the NCAA championships this year. Although
Reese had won six previous titles at Texas, the last came in 1992.
This year the title was never in doubt. Texas scored an NCAA-record
538 points while second-place Auburn was way back at 385. The total
could rise even higher this year. Rauch, Goldblatt and Dusing will
all return, and being on the Olympic team could really raise their
performance to another level.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas exes are another factor in the equation. Texas is
fortunate to have a pair of former Longhorns, Josh Davis and Neil
Walker, who work out with the team. Although both have impressive
resumes, neither is a prima donna, a star who sets himself apart.
Reese would be hard-pressed to find a better role model to have
around his swimmers than Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, 27, is respected enough to be the leader on the men's
U.S. Olympic swim team. The easygoing Walker is a rising star in
the sport. Walker can swim three strokes, the freestyle, backstroke
and butterfly, as well as just about anyone and so can Davis. At
Texas, swimmers don't have to imagine what it takes to be the best,
they can look over in the next lane and see how that person trains,
or watch how he handles himself outside of the pool.
</P>
<P>
   As for his part, Reese always has had a reputation for being
able to spot talent, but it's frequently been for
diamond-in-the-rough swimmers. Yet the 2001 class is loaded with
talent, and Crocker and Hansen were both huge recruits. If they
were football players, the chat rooms wouldn't stop buzzing about
them.
</P>
<P>
   A final piece might be Eddie's brother, Randy. At one time, when
he was coaching a powerhouse at Florida, the Randy vs. Eddie battle
was the highlight of a swim season. Like Eddie, Randy has coached a
ton of top swimmers, but Randy was out of swimming for almost a
decade before deciding to get back in at the club level. He has set
up camp at Circle C, which continues to improve its swimming
facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Olympic trials, Eddie took his swimmers over a couple
of times a week to work with Randy. ``We like swimming outdoors.
It's better than looking at the rafters all the time,'' Walker
said.
</P>
<P>
   An outdoor facility has been planned for UT for years, but is
still on the drawing boards. Now, the UT swimmers have a de facto
outdoor facility at Circle C.
</P>
<P>
   At Florida, Randy had a reputation for being the more demanding
of the Reese brothers, not bothering to soften workouts with humor,
the way Eddie does. Some of Randy's training techniques are
legendary for their toughness. Yet, going over to Circle C helps
fights one of the biggest enemies for swimmers _ monotony. And
Eddie and Randy even do a little of their Smothers Brothers of
swimming routine to keep their athletes amused while they're
getting advice from not one, but two hugely successful coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good to see the two sides of the family. We do a lot more
work with paddles and fins with Randy. It helps you feel
stronger,'' Dusing said.
</P>
<P>
   Randy is known for developing 200-meter swimmers, and Texas
excelled at that distance during the trials. One of the methods he
uses is a pulley system, which some at Circle C consider something
of an eyesore.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got four guys going to the Olympics you can live
with it,'' Dusing said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
