<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Roller coasters serve as gauge for dizziness
 &HT;    By Michael Carvell
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BROOKLYN, Mich. _ Many NASCAR drivers talk about having a
``roller-coaster'' season, referring to the ups and downs of the
year. Terry Labonte gives the phrase a new meaning.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte, driver of the No. 5 Chevrolet, spent two days riding
roller coasters at an amusement park on the advice of his
physician. He missed the past two Winston Cup races because of
``dizziness'', which doctors originally thought was the result on a
concussion suffered during a crash at Daytona.
</P>
<P>
   After visiting a different ear specialist last week, Labonte was
diagnosed with a form of vertigo. He and Jeremy Mayfield, who also
skipped the past two events because of a head-related injury, will
return to action for today's Pepsi 400 at Michigan Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a relief,'' Labonte said. ``I guess the thing that
bothered me the most was I'd go to the neuro doctors and they'd say
nothing was wrong with me. I'd still be dizzy. I'd go to the ear
doctor and he'd say there was nothing wrong with me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I finally went to (another) ear doctor on Tuesday and he said
`Here is your problem.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Labonte was diagnosed with Benign Paroxymal Positional Vertigo
and underwent therapy during the doctor's visit. To determine
whether there was any remaining dizziness, Labonte traveled to
King's Dominion in northern Virginia on Thursday and Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to see if I could make myself dizzy again by
doing something that would be as close to driving this car as I
could get,'' Labonte said. ``I made everybody dizzy that was with
me, but I didn't have a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   During the two Winston Cup practice sessions Saturday, Labonte
climbed behind the wheel to motor around the two-mile track. Todd
Bodine, winner of Saturday's Busch race, drove the car during
Friday's time trials. He will be on stand-by today if Labonte's
dizziness returns before or during the race.
</P>
<P>
   Mayfield suffered a head injury after crashing in practice the
day before the Brickyard 400. Mayfield also was held out of Watkins
Glen last week for precautionary measures.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've really been feeling good, no headaches or dizziness,''
Mayfield said. ``My biggest fear when I got to Michigan was . . .
what's going to happen when I get in the car?
</P>
<P>
   ``I rode around (slowly) a few laps to make sure I was all
right. (Then) I went wide open and I felt real good. I can't
express how happy I am to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
