u s BC-FBO-NFL-NOTES0820-COX     08-19 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-NFL-NOTES0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Preseason injuries hitting hard
 &HT;    By Ken Seguira
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Any coach worth his whistle can tell you at least this
much about the preseason: The important thing is to try and get
through without too many injuries.
</P>
<P>
   In Preseason 2000, though, it might be difficult for any of them
to tell you that, perhaps because they're too busy lighting candles
or rubbing rabbits' feet in hopes that one more anterior cruciate
ligament won't tear or another Achilles' tendon won't snap.
</P>
<P>
   Players are dropping fast. Broncos wide receivers Chris Doering
and Muneer Moore suffered a ruptured Achilles' and a dislocated and
fractured left ankle, respectively, in the same game. The seasons
of Cam Cleeland and Steve Israel both ended in the Saints' first
game. Seattle Seahawks DeShone Myles and Rufus French both tore the
ACLs in their left knees on successive days. (Note to artificial
turf haters: Virtually all of these injuries have come on grass.)
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to take,'' Saints coach Jim Haslett said.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for the locals, the Falcons haven't suffered a
single season-ending injury. Perhaps it's karma coming around after
center Todd McClure and running back Gary Downs were lost for the
year on the second day of training camp in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The injuries have felled so many, a decent team could be found
among the ``out for the season'' gang. The wide receivers would be
the Panthers' Patrick Jeffers (ACL) and the Cardinals' Rob Moore
(ACL). On the offensive line is the Jaguars' Leon Searcy (ruptured
quadriceps).
</P>
<P>
   The quarterback is the Browns' Ty Detmer (ruptured Achilles).
There's also Panthers safety Deon Grant (broken hip), Panthers
kicker John Kasay (broken kneecap) and Jaguars safety Carnell Lake
(stress fracture in his left foot). In this group there's one Super
Bowl ring, nine Pro Bowl appearances, 10 conference championship
games, a season scoring leader, a Heisman Trophy winner, five
college all-Americans and three national championships.
</P>
<P>
   Another player for the all-injured squad. One is Packers
seventh-round pick Rondell Mealey, a running back from Louisiana
State. Mealey blew out the anterior cruciate and medial collateral
ligaments in his left knee in the team's first preseason game Aug.
4 and kept playing. After the injury, Mealey left the field under
his own power, came back, ran a pass route, gained 7 yards on a
sweep and then went around right end to score a 15-yard touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   ON LEWIS
</P>
<P>
   NFL Commissioner Paul Tagliabue's $250,000 fine of Ravens
linebacker Ray Lewis on Thursday for obstructing justice in the
Buckhead slayings investigation makes it clear that the NFL thinks
it has an image problem it wants to correct.
</P>
<P>
   But Panthers owner Jerry Richardson, in a rare interview this
past week, said he didn't think the team or league should be held
responsible for the actions of Rae Carruth, the ex-Panther charged
with murder in the shooting of his pregnant girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what we could have done. We have won the player
support program award for the NFL for two years in a row. We have a
full-time chaplain. I don't know how I could do any more of it than
I do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   PACKER PATIENCE
</P>
<P>
   The Packers, who play Miami on Monday, have not been the models
of defensive efficiency thus far. In their first two games, a 37-24
win over the Jets and a 26-20 loss to the Broncos, the Packers have
given up 58 first downs (to their opponents' 40) and are waiting
for their first sack.
</P>
<P>
   Against the Broncos, the Packers gave up 309 passing yards.
</P>
<P>
   It would seem the Packers' firing of defensive coordinator
Emmitt Thomas after last season (now with the Vikings) and hiring
of Denver secondary coach Ed Donatell as a replacement was all for
naught. Worry not, says Packers defensive end Vonnie Holliday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is our third defense in three years,'' he said. ``Like
anything, when you're trying to learn something new, it can be
frustrating. When this thing comes together, jells, gets that
chemistry, it's going to be a special defense.''
</P>
<P>
   EXTRA POINTS
</P>
<P>
   Miami coach Dave Wannstedt said the quarterback situation is not
completely resolved. If Damon Huard struggles against the Packers
on Monday, they might still consider Jay Fiedler, who injured his
hip and won't be back until the final preseason game, Aug. 24 at
New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   Denver running back and Georgia product Olandis Gary will split
carries with fellow Denver back and ex-Bulldog Terrell Davis, who
is coming back from an ACL tear, coach Mike Shanahan said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bills are happy with the progress that second-round pick
Travares Tillman, a Georgia Tech product, is making at free safety.
</P>
<P>
   The same can be said of the Jaguars and their fifth-round pick,
Kiwaukee Thomas from Georgia Southern. Despite getting burned two
Fridays ago for a touchdown by the Giants' Amani Toomer (even
worse, a photo of the play got splashed across the Associated Press
photo wire), Thomas has a good shot to be the Jaguars' nickel back.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
