<HEADLINE>
GUIDE TO AVOIDING FANTASY DRAFT PITFALLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDY CLAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a 14-year veteran of fantasy football, I've seen it all. I
hope I can help you avoid some of the draft pitfalls.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is an adequate substitution for information, so if you
haven't been watching preseason games and reading everything NFL
related that you can get you hands on, start now. The rankings on
this page will only help you so much. Plus, there is still plenty
of football to be played and analyzed before the season starts.
\Nsubheds:Root, root for ``your'' team In addition to having all of
the relevant information (who's starting where, who's hurt, etc.),
you have to check your pompons at the draft-room door.
</P>
<P>
   Root for the Cowboys if you must, but be realistic in assessing
their fantasy value. Troy Aikman is considered a great quarterback
for the Super Bowls he has won, not for his statistics. He has
never thrown for 3,500 yards and only once has thrown as many as 20
touchdown passes in a season. \Nsubheds:Injury-prone Be leery of a
big-name player with a history of injuries. Fred Taylor, Brad
Johnson, Mark Brunell and Chris Chandler are only some of the
players who can sparkle when healthy ... and there is the problem.
They tend to miss considerable playing time. If you end up with one
of those players, make sure you have a reliable backup.
\Nsubheds:Who is that guy? And beware of players coming from
nowhere to have monster seasons. Only Dan Marino has more than one
season with more than 40 touchdown passes, and for an encore to
each of his 40-plus seasons, he threw 18 fewer touchdown passes the
following season.
</P>
<P>
   Now, 30 or 26 touchdowns isn't bad, but if you were expecting 48
or 44, you were disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   The point is that Kurt Warner could have a huge dropoff this
season and still put up good numbers. Be realistic.
\Nsubheds:Bye-bye players Remember that each team will have an off
week during the season. As you draft your team, keep up with your
players' bye weeks so that you can avoid having three of your four
running backs with the same off week. \Nsubheds:We're No. 2
Everybody knows that playing time is one of the keys to a player
putting up big numbers, but that doesn't mean all backups are bad.
In fact, there are some backups I recommend, particularly at
quarterback and particularly if you can pair the backup as your No.
3 quarterback with the starter as your No. 1 or No. 2 quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   The best quarterback examples are Kurt Warner/Trent Green, Brad
Johnson/Jeff George, Rob Johnson/Doug Flutie and Brian Griese/Gus
Frerotte.
</P>
<P>
   It's a little dicey at running back because sometimes two
players end up sharing playing time, but the best one-two punches
appear to be Terrell Davis/Olandis Gary, Emmitt Smith/Chris Warren,
Mike Alstott/Warrick Dunn, Stephen Davis/Adrian Murrell and Jerome
Bettis/Richard Huntley.
</P>
<P>
   In all of these cases, if you get the first guy, try to get the
backup late. That way, if the team changes its starter or there is
an injury, you've got somebody to plug in. \Nsubheds:Point
differential Every starting quarterback in the NFL will score
fairly well in fantasy football, but how many tight ends can you
count on to score? Anywhere from two to five, which means that a
lot of teams are going to be playing a stiff at tight end.
</P>
<P>
   A tight end will almost never outscore a quarterback, but that
isn't the point. If your tight end outscore your opponent's tight
end by 50 points, and your opponent's quarterback outscores your
quarterback by 20 points, you're ahead by 30.
</P>
<P>
   Watch for the talent/production gaps, and draft accordingly.
\Ntagtop:Andy Clay, (817) 390-7760
\Ntagbottom:aclay &LR; star-telegram.com
</P>
<P>
   \Nsubheds:OVERALL \Nagatea:1. Edgerrin James, Colts 2. Marshall
Faulk, Rams 3. Eddie George, Titans 4. Marvin Harrison, Colts 5.
Peyton Manning, Colts 6. Brett Favre, Packers 7. Kurt Warner, Rams
8. Stephen Davis, Redskins 9. Emmitt Smith, Cowboys 10. Tony
Gonzalez, Chiefs 11. Randy Moss, Vikings 12. Rich Gannon, Raiders
13. Steve Beuerlein, Panthers 14. Steve McNair, Titans 15. Brad
Johnson, Redskins 16. Terrell Davis, Broncos 17. Jamal Anderson,
Falcons 18. Isaac Bruce, Rams 19. Wesley Walls, Panthers 20.
Antonio Freeman, Packers
</P>
