<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-REPORT-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TODD HELTON TAKES RACE FOR .400 IN STRIDE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one will challenge the home-run record this year. Mark
McGwire's knee injury took care of that.
</P>
<P>
   No one will win 30 games. David Wells took care of that with a
post-All-Star Game slump.
</P>
<P>
   No one will hit in 56 consecutive games. Gabe Kapler took care
of that against the Yankees the other day.
</P>
<P>
   But this season still could be one for the record books, because
it might produce the first .400 hitter since Ted Williams in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   Not Nomar Garciaparra. The tremendously talented Boston Red Sox
shortstop has fallen off the pace. He went 5-for-14 against the
Rangers last weekend, hitting the ball hard almost every time, but
that's only a .357 average. He was ``down'' to .375 after going
0-for-2 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Todd Helton, though, might reach the magical number. The
Colorado Rockies first baseman took a .399 average into yesterday's
game against the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   ``People should be excited,'' said Rockies right fielder Larry
Walker, who batted a league-leading .379 last season. ``The guy has
a chance to do something that hasn't been done in a long time _ hit
.400 and win the MVP. I'm rooting for him. Everybody's rooting for
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Helton, who's in his third full season in the majors, made the
mark if not likely then at least possible with an incredible
16-game stretch. Beginning with a game against the Phillies on Aug.
4, Helton has gone 32-for-54 (.595), raising his average 29 points
to .399 through Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm flabbergasted,'' Rockies manager Buddy Bell said. ``This
is a very hard game and he's making it look very easy.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Frye, traded from the Red Sox to the Rockies on July 27,
has played with Garciaparra and Helton this season.
</P>
<P>
   Frye said his former teammate did it with instincts and raw
ability.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not normal,'' Frye said. ``He's a freak. He does things
I've never seen. He can go up there and hit a first pitch slider,
changeup, sinker in, fastball. He doesn't look at video. He doesn't
really go over the pitchers.''
</P>
<P>
   Frye's current teammate is the antithesis. Helton keeps books on
pitchers and dissects his swings on video. But that approach also
works.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just the short time I've been here, it's got to the point
where I expect the guy to get a hit every time,'' Frye said.
</P>
<P>
   Helton's hot stretch included a remarkable road trip. He went
19-for-29 (.655) in games at Montreal and New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a guy hits like that for that long of a streak on the
road, that proves he's a big-time hitter in any ballpark,'' George
Brett told the ``Denver Post.'' ``What he's doing is incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Brett knows a little something about trying to hit .400. He
challenged the mark 20 years ago, when he got his average up to
.407, but he faded in the last couple of weeks and finished at
.390.
</P>
<P>
   That was one of four serious assaults on .400 since Williams hit
.406 in '41. Williams batted .388 in 1957, an average matched by
Rod Carew in '77. Tony Gwynn hit .394 in '94, his chances at .400
ended by the players' strike.
</P>
<P>
   But Helton has an advantage over the others. He plays his home
games in the best hitters' park in the game.
</P>
<P>
   Helton was batting .439 (93-212) in the high altitude of Coors
Field entering yesterday's game against the Marlins. The Rockies
play 24 of their final 39 games at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm never thinking about my batting average when I up there,''
Helton said. ``The media makes a bigger deal out of it. I honestly
believe it's not going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker, on the other hand, is a believer that it can.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yeah,'' Walker said. ``Yeah.''
 &LR; subheds:SPOTLIGHT
Bill Kostroun Although he has not had a glittering return, Kent
Mercker of the Angels is happy to be pitching after suffering a
hemorrhage in his brain.
Mercker makes heroic return after hemorrhage
Never has such a mediocre line in the box score looked so good.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim Angles pitcher Kent Mercker allowed three runs on five
hits in 32/3 innings against the New York Yankees last weekend, on
the surface nothing to be proud of. But considering his life was in
jeopardy the last time he was on the mound, it was a thing of
beauty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big relief when I walked out after the game,''
Mercker said. ``I picked up my girls \RMadison and Sophia\S and
hugged them. It was a big sigh of relief, like, `Whew, everything's
OK.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Mercker last pitched against the Rangers on May 11, when he
suddenly experienced a headache so painful that it dropped him to
one knee.
</P>
<P>
   He was rushed to the hospital where, after hours of tests, he
was told a blood vessel had burst in his brain. Blood was
hemorrhaging throughout his head, a life-threatening condition.
</P>
<P>
   He assumed his baseball career was finished, but he began to
think about coming back when further tests showed that a recurrence
was highly unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   Mercker and his wife, Julie, talked it over and decided he
should resume pitching.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, baseball is something I love,'' he said. ``There
are always going to be doubts with me the rest of my life regarding
my head. But you can't let it consume you to where you just sit on
the sofa all day, afraid of things.''
</P>
<P>
   When Mercker returned to Edison Field, three months after
collapsing on the same mound, he received a standing ovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never viewed pitching as a courageous or heroic thing,''
said Mercker, who pitched against the Yankees again Wednesday in
New York and allowed two runs in five innings. ``But maybe I can
help somebody who has been through the exact same thing and who has
been hesitant to do things. Maybe they'll think, `You know, he did
it, maybe I can do it.' ''
 &LR; subheds:SHORT HOPS
\Nsubheds:Strength from dad Arizona Diamondbacks pitcher Todd
Stottlemyre had a great day on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Stottlemyre, who is on the disabled list because of an elbow
injury, had a pain-free session on the mound in the visitors'
bullpen in Philadelphia. But more importantly, he began the day by
having breakfast in New York with his father, Mel, the Yankees'
pitching coach.
</P>
<P>
   Mel is battling multiple myeloma, a form of cancer that attacks
the blood. Todd spent Sunday night and all day Monday in New York
before rejoining the D'backs in Philadelphia on Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be able to talk, laugh and smile with him _ that was much
more rewarding than throwing off the mound today,'' Stottlemyre
said. ``He's doing great.''
</P>
<P>
   His father's courage in dealing with cancer makes it easier for
Stottlemyre to deal with his own problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes it, I don't want to say meaningless, because this is
what we do and there is a sense of being accountable to your
teammates, manager, owner,'' Stottlemyre said. ``But he's fighting
for his life, and I'm fighting for my next start. They don't seem
to balance out.'' \Nsubheds:Sosa happy again After ripping manager
Don Baylor for not giving him enough respect earlier this season,
Chicago Cubs outfielder Sammy Sosa said Don Baylor knew what he was
talking about when he challenged him to be a better player.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good sometimes that people say something \Rnegative\S
about me because that's good motivation,'' Sosa said. ``I work
harder and get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa has lost 15 pounds since spring training, going from 236 to
221, and is playing better in right field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's night and day,'' center fielder Damon Buford said. ``Now
he's the prototypical right fielder who makes all the plays. You
can't ask for more.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosa acknowledged that losing weight has helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I was a little bit overweight,'' he said. ``But for the
last three or four years my manager was telling me he didn't want
me to steal bases. He wanted me to drive in runs and be more
productive.''
</P>
<P>
   He has remained productive at the lower weight. He had 18 home
runs in his last 36 games through Friday, taking the major-league
lead with 39. \Nsubheds:Shift doesn't change Thome Even with a
seven-run lead and two outs in the ninth inning, the Oakland A's
still employed a radical shift against Cleveland Indians third
baseman Jim Thome. Three infielders were stationed between first
and second with the third baseman playing shortstop against the
left-handed pull hitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of teams do it and some teams overdo it like the A's,''
Thome said. ``I guess it's a sign of respect.''
</P>
<P>
   Thome's having a fine season, hitting .284 with 30 home runs and
73 runs batted in, but he figures the shift has cost him at least
20 hits this year on balls up the middle. Still, he won't change
his style.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to change the way I hit. The only way I'll hit
the ball to left field is if they pitch me away or I get beat on a
pitch and swing late. And I'm not looking to get beat.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the year he tried to bunt against the shift, and sent
a dribbler back to the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``Grady Little, our bench coach, came up to me after that game
and said, `Jimmy, there's a lot of people who drive all the way
from Sandusky to see you swing the bat. They don't come to see you
lay down a bunt,' '' Thome said. ``I remember that.''
\Nsubheds:Valentine gaining respect Even though the New York Mets
have the second-best record in baseball, are within two games of
the Atlanta Braves in the NL East and are well ahead in the
wild-card standings, manager Bobby Valentine hasn't received so
much as a vote of confidence from co-owner Fred Wilpon, let alone a
new contract to replace the one that expires at the end of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Wilpon said the decision on Valentine and GM Steve Phillips ``is
going to be easy,'' but won't do anything until after the season.''
But the players say there's no reason to wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby deserved another contract a long time ago,'' reliever
John Franco said. ``The way he's managed, the way we've won here
the last three years, are you kidding me? The longer it takes, the
harder it's going to be for \RWilpon\S to sign him.`
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Robin Ventura says he's grown to respect Valentine
for the discipline he shows in not playing Mike Piazza every game,
even though Valentine obviously needs as many victories as possible
to earn another contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby is using all different kinds of lineups, not just the
same one,'' Ventura said. ``Any manager could ride Mike's back,
want to win every single game. But we learned last year we need to
keep Mike fresh for the end of the season.'' \Nsubheds:White Sox
look over Hill The Chicago White Sox's pitching problems in the
second half should result in further employment for Ken Hill, who
was released by the Anaheim Angels earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   James Baldwin, Mike Sirotka and Jim Parque have slipped in the
second half. None of them have won back-to-back starts since
Sirotka beat the New York Yankees and Boston Red Sox on June 25 and
July 1, respectively. In their last seven starts, Baldwin is 2-1
(and is expected to miss his next start because of a tired arm),
Parque is 3-2 with an earned-run average above 5.00, and Sirotka is
2-4 with a 5.06 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Rookies Jon Garland and Rocky Biddle have been inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Hill, who threw for the White Sox twice last week and was
expected to be signed to replace one of the rookies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured some clubs would be interested, but I didn't know,''
he said. ``If not, I figured I'd just go home. But they called.''
</P>
<P>
   Hill was 5-7 with a 6.52 ERA with the Angels but worked
five-plus innings in five of his past six starts. Plus, he has
postseason experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather have him,'' DH Frank Thomas said. ``This is not
playoff baseball yet. It's a whole other level in the postseason.
It's a little tough on kids, especially when you start throwing
them into pressure situations.''
 &LR; subheds:AROUND THE NL Atlanta Braves left-hander Tom Glavine needs
five victories to join Roger Clemens as the only active pitchers
with five 20-victory seasons. ``It's important,'' Glavine said.
``It's a goal that starting pitchers have every year. You're a
20-game winner, that's a big deal. I've done it four times and five
sounds a whole lot better.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry Wood wants to pitch, but the Chicago Cubs continue to be
cautious with the prized pitcher from Grand Prairie High School who
is coming off ``Tommy John'' surgery. Wood, on the DL with a
strained oblique muscle, declared himself ready to face Randy
Johnson today after throwing in the bullpen Tuesday. But manager
Don Baylor decided to hold him back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's probably the next go-through after that,'' Baylor
said. ``With his velocity, he does generate a lot of torque.
Playing catch is one thing, but once he gets on the mound and airs
it out a couple times in the next week or 10 days, then we'll let
him pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Diamondbacks third baseman Matt Williams had 26 RBI on
May 1 last year, when he finished with 142. After missing the first
43 games of this season with a fractured second metatarsal in his
right foot, and also spending time on the DL with a strained right
quadriceps that still is not 100 percent, he got No. 26 on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Colorado Rockies' new administration went for talent over
signability with the selection of high school pitcher Matt
Harrington with the No. 7 overall pick in the June draft, but it
appears that Harrington will play his next baseball game for
Arizona State. Harrington made it known that he wanted to become
the highest-paid player in the draft, which means the Rockies would
have to pay more than the $5.3 million the Chicago White Sox gave
Stanford outfielder Joe Borchard. They have offered $3.25 million.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield (91), Eric Karros (85) and Shawn Green (81) are
driving in runs in bunches for the Los Angeles Dodgers, but the
three players have not had a RBI in the same game since a 7-6
victory over Houston on June 21 at Enron Field. The Dodgers have
played 51 games since then.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Giants left-hander Shawn Estes is thriving at
Pacific Bell Park. He is 7-1 with a 1.80 ERA in nine starts at the
new field, the lowest home ERA in the NL.
</P>
<P>
   Houston Astros shortstop Julio Lugo's two-run home run on
Wednesday was the 200th at Enron Field. There were only 110 hit at
the Astrodome last season.
</P>
<P>
   Woody Williams has the only two complete games thrown by the San
Diego Padres staff this season. Not bad, considering he missed two
months following surgery to repair an aneurysm in a blood vessel in
his right armpit.
</P>
<P>
   The Cincinnati Reds revived their playoff hopes by sweeping the
Chicago Cubs at Wrigley Field last weekend to climb to two games
over .500 and within 41/2 games of the St. Louis Cardinals in the
Central Division, but they went to Milwaukee and were swept. They
scored four runs in 19 innings, and were 1-for-26 with runners in
scoring position. ``We're not getting the job done,'' Ken Griffey
Jr. said. ``We're not getting the big hit.`
 &LR; subheds:AROUND THE AL Chicago White Sox starter Cal Eldred, who
has been on the disabled list since July 15 because of a nerve
condition in his elbow, is playing long toss and is aiming for a
return in September. The Sox hope he can make a minor-league rehab
start on Saturday, and then rejoin the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens could be echoing Joseph Lieberman's ``only in
America'' line. Clemens' contract extension with the New York
Yankees pays him $10.3 million in 2003, even if he opts out of the
deal after two years and becomes a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   The early returns on the players the Baltimore Orioles received
in their trading frenzy at the end of July aren't encouraging. Luis
Rivera, considered the most talented of the prospects, hasn't
pitched since being acquired from the Atlanta Braves because of
shoulder tendinitis. The same ailment sidelined Mark Nussbeck, who
came from the St. Louis Cardinals in the Mike Timlin deal. And the
club has discovered that pitcher Leslie Brea, the key player in the
Mike Bordick deal with the New York Mets, could be as old as 26
instead of his listed age of 21.
</P>
<P>
   The eight runs the Boston Red Sox scored against the Rangers on
Thursday lifted them out of the AL cellar in runs scored with 582,
two more than the Minnesota Twins and three more than the Tampa Bay
Devil Rays. The last time the Sox finished a season with the fewest
runs scored was 1932, when they were 43-111. This year, they have
remained contenders. ``When the ball starts rolling, I think it can
get contagious,'' first baseman Rico Brogna said. ``The fact that
we haven't hit and we're hanging right in there is a good sign
because this team has good hitters and we will hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit Tigers GM Randy Smith's wife, Erin, gave birth to the
couple's second son while Smith was traveling with the team in
Seattle. The baby didn't receive his name _ Shane _ until Smith
returned home the following day. ``That's perfect for a GM, a baby
to be named later,'' assistant GM Steve Lubratich said.
</P>
<P>
   Jorge Posada hit 21 of his first 22 home runs while playing
catcher, so he could challenge Yogi Berra's Yankees club record for
the position of 30 homers. Berra did it in 1952 and 1956. But
Posada neither knows nor wants to know the record. ``I'll look it
up when the season is over and I'll see what happens, but, right
now, I'm going to concentrate on what I have to do today,'' Posada
said. ``I'm not worrying about records.''
</P>
<P>
   The news that closer Troy Percival has inflammation of the ulnar
nerve in his pitching elbow and is expected to be out for at least
another two weeks not only is bad news for the Anaheim Angels'
wild-card chances, but it also could impact Percival's contract for
next season. He has a $3.4 million option that vests when he
finishes 40 games. He's currently stuck on 35.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Chicago White Sox had a respectable 17-16 record
in the second half and a comfortable lead over the Cleveland
Indians in the Central Division, manager Jerry Manuel called a
meeting after an 8-2 loss to Baltimore on Monday night. ``It was
just the level of intensity that I think we need to get back to,''
Manuel said. ``We have been somewhat lax and I wanted to remind
them of what's at stake. You're competing to be the best team in
the American League. You need to be at a level of consistency, a
level of expectancy.''
 &LR; subheds:THE WEEK AHEAD After being swept in Oakland last week to
fall out of first in the wild-card standings, the Cleveland Indians
play host to the A's in a three-game series beginning Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Seattle Mariners and Chicago White Sox conduct what could be
a playoff preview with three games at Seattle beginning Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the National League, the San Francisco Giants begin a
favorable stretch of games that could allow them to pad their lead
in the West. After three games against Florida beginning tomorrow,
they embark on a road trip to Philadelphia and Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   The second-place Arizona Diamondbacks play three games at New
York next weekend, games that could be important in the wild-card
race if they fall off the pace in the West.
 &LR; subheds:THE LAST WORD  &LR; quote:''It's the same thing we've gone
through the last four years. It's just different guys every year.
It's no easier the fourth time through. To go out there every day
and get your tail kicked gets old. I'm tired of losing.''  &LR; qby:_
Philadelphia Phillies third baseman Scott Rolen, who hasn't played
for a winning team in his four years in the majors.
nn
</P>
