<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-DODGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS BEAT METS, 4-1 
</HEADLINE>
   By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Gary Sheffield had an itinerant career before
going to the Los Angeles Dodgers _ against his wishes _ in 1998. He
was never a batboy in Dodger blue and was never a close family
friend of Tommy Lasorda's, and he needed a $5-million bonus to
accept being traded here from the Florida Marlins.
</P>
<P>
   His production should make him a hero at Dodger Stadium, but he
is only now reaching the numbers posted by the player he was traded
for, Mike Piazza, who was a Dodgers batboy and is a family friend
of Lasorda's.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, the Mets' catcher, was given a rest on Saturday, and he
watched as Sheffield tied Piazza's season high for home runs in a
Los Angeles uniform in the Dodgers' 4-1 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield homered in the third inning, giving the Dodgers a
lead, and again in the eighth for their final run. He knocked in
three runs, providing the margin of victory for Chan Ho Park, who
dominated the Mets with a four-hitter. Rick Reed (7-4) pitched well
for the Mets _ he threw the same number of pitches as Park, 113,
with 3 more strikes, 80 _ but he lost for the second start in a
row.
</P>
<P>
   Until Saturday, Piazza was the only Dodger to hit 40 home runs
since the franchise moved from Brooklyn to Los Angeles in 1958. But
Sheffield, who will challenge Piazza for the Most Valuable Player
award this year if his monster season lifts the Dodgers into the
pennant race, reached 40 homers Saturday to tie his record.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Sheffield traded home runs with Piazza, who had three
runs batted in as the Mets won the series opener. In Saturday's
game, Sheffield traded homers with another Met he is connected to.
Sheffield and Derek Bell were teammates on the Tampa All-Star team
that advanced to the Little League World Series final in 1980. They
remain close and chatted at length on the field before Friday's
game.
</P>
<P>
   With the bases empty in the first inning, Bell rifled a homer to
left off Park (12-8). Sheffield walked in the bottom of that
inning, then came up with one on and one out in the third. It could
have been an even more dangerous situation, but Edgardo Alfonzo
dived to snare a grounder by Mark Grudzielanek just before
Sheffield hit.
</P>
<P>
   Reed threw him a first-pitch curveball, and Sheffield timed it
perfectly, crushing it into the left-field bullpen to give the
Dodgers a 2-1 lead. He second homer came off Pat Mahomes leading
off the eighth. Sheffield should soon break Duke Snider's franchise
mark of 43, set with Brooklyn in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros, the Los Angeles career leader in homers, accounted
for the Dodgers' other run with a bases-empty homer in the third
inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets, meanwhile, were struggling against Park, who in May
allowed them two hits over seven shutout innings. Three hitters in
the lineup had never faced him before, and though Bell hits him
well (7 for 17 in his career), the rest of the order entered the
game with a .121 average against Park.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' lineup did not include outfielder Darryl Hamilton, who
has hit well against Park but has experienced soreness in his
arthritic left big toe, which sidelined him for four months.
</P>
<P>
   After Bell's homer, the Mets never advanced a runner past first.
Jay Payton singled to lead off the fifth, but aborted a stolen-base
attempt and was picked off first by catcher Chad Kreuter. Todd
Pratt then singled but was stranded when Mike Bordick fanned and
Reed flied out. Park worked five 1-2-3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets needed Reed to give them innings, and he did, working
seven strong ones and giving up seven hits and a walk. He left for
a pinch-hitter in the eighth, and Mahomes relieved him. Mahomes
started on Tuesday and had three full days of rest, but he may need
to start again on Tuesday in San Diego if Mike Hampton does not
recover in time from a stress fracture in his ribs.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets had won Reed's first five starts after he came off the
disabled list on July 17, but they have lost the last two because
of two bad innings. Reed had thrown five shutout innings against
San Francisco before allowing five runs in the sixth, and six of
his seven innings Saturday were scoreless.
</P>
</TEXT>
