<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-RED-SOX-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX THUMP RANGERS, PERISHO
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Matt Perisho called it bad luck. Manager Johnny Oates
called it an inability to throw strikes consistently.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the results just aren't there.
</P>
<P>
   Perisho gave up seven runs in 32/3 innings yesterday, which is
what Red Sox starter Pedro Martinez allows in a month. In a game
that was probably decided by the end of the first inning and over
by the fourth, Martinez and reliever Bryce Florie pitched a
five-hitter to beat the Rangers, 9-0, at Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez had come out of his previous start complaining of
shoulder stiffness, but it became apparent rather quickly that he
was fine. The defending Cy Young Award winner pitched seven
innings, gave up three hits, walked none and struck out 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``As good as he's ever been,'' Rangers first baseman Rafael
Palmeiro said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be surprised if he had to shower today,'' Oates said of
Martinez. ``If he didn't work up a sweat warming up in the bullpen,
he's probably already dressed and gone home.''
</P>
<P>
   The loss was the Rangers' third consecutive and sixth in their
past seven games. They are 13-23 since the All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be days when there is no end in sight, no
hope, no light at the end of the tunnel,'' Oates said. ``But I
guarantee you, one day we'll look up and see a light at the end of
the tunnel ... and our young pitchers are a very large part of
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Perisho, who is 2-6 with a 6.78 earned-run average, may be
included, but he's going to have to get better. Even in his mind it
can't get much worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm frustrated beyond belief,'' Perisho said. ``Everybody has
a good part of the season and everybody has a bad part of the
season. I keep wondering when this is going to stop being the bad
part. I made a lot of good pitches today and didn't get results. I
made some bad pitches and had bad results. I'm kind of baffled
right now.''
</P>
<P>
   As for yesterday, Perisho said: ``The only way I see it is bad
luck. The focus is there, the game plan is good, and I've been
working on my mechanics trying to pitch inside better. I think I'm
doing that better than I ever have in my career. But I gave up one
hard-hit ball and I ended up giving up seven runs.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates didn't quite see it that way, but the manager is still not
ready to make a judgment on Perisho or any of the young pitchers.
With the Rangers going nowhere and with no clear alternatives
available, Oates said the experiment with the young pitchers will
go to the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to sit back and watch, whether it's third base,
center field, starting pitching or reliever, for the next six
weeks,'' Oates said. ``That's what I'm going to make my evaluation
on ... who we'll take to spring training next year, who are going
to get the shots. \R Perisho\S is going to pitch. That's the only
way I can make my determination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, it may not kill us.''
</P>
<P>
   What the manager is thinking is not foremost on Perisho's mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have to show me some results,'' Perisho said.
``It's my ERA, it's my career. I'm doing the things it takes to get
here and I'm doing the things that it takes to be here. I don't
doubt my ability to pitch here. I just need to get consistent and
pitch the way I'm capable, and it will happen.''
</P>
<P>
   He has six more weeks to show the manager.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
