<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS PLAYERS SUPPORTING VALENTINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ It's amazing what winning can do for a ballclub.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Mets began the second half of the season by winning
20 of 25 games, are challenging the Atlanta Braves for the National
League West title and are almost a shoo-in for the wild-card spot.
</P>
<P>
   And because of all that, players are actually coming to the
defense of manager Bobby Valentine, who has had his share of spats
with players. Valentine, along with general manager Steve Phillips,
are in the last year of their contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Mets owner Fred Wilpon has stated it will be an easy decision
come the end of the year. But just like Dusty Baker's situation in
San Francisco, the longer Valentine remains a possible free agent
at the end of the season, the more speculation will arise as to
Valentine returning to the Los Angeles Dodgers if Davey Johnson is
replaced.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Mets entered Saturday with a 73-49 mark, 1 games
behind the Braves and 5 games ahead of Arizona in the wild-card
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby deserved another contract a long time ago,'' Mets
reliever John Franco said. ``The way he's managed, the way we've
won here the last three years. ... Are you kidding me? The longer
it takes, the harder it's going to be for (Wilpon) to sign him.''
</P>
<P>
   Mets third baseman Robin Ventura, regarded as one of the best
clubhouse influences in baseball, said Valentine's discipline in
resting catcher Mike Piazza, as he did Saturday, is one of the key
moves of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of relying on Piazza's offense every day, Valentine is
trying to keep the MVP candidate from getting worn down in
September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bobby is using all different kinds of lineups, not just the
same one,'' Ventura said. ``Any manager could ride Mike's back,
want to win every single game. But we learned last year we need to
keep Mike fresh for the end of the season.''
</P>
<P>
   Helton's quest: Colorado first baseman Todd Helton could be
playing on the moon or at Coors Field, the run he's making at .400
is impressive.
</P>
<P>
   Helton entered Saturday hitting .399, but he doesn't put much
credence in his charge to become the first player to hit .400 since
Ted Williams did it in 1941.
</P>
<P>
   ``What he's doing now is he's making a name for himself,''
Rockies hitting coach Clint Hurdle said. ``He's getting into that
group of hitters where when other teams come in, he's the first
name that comes up. He's having a signature season.''
</P>
<P>
   Helton should be helped by the schedule. The Rockies play 23 of
their final 41 games at Coors Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm never thinking about my batting average when I am up
there,'' said Helton, who keeps books on pitchers and watches video
of his at-bats endlessly.
</P>
<P>
   Jones joins Brown: When Atlanta third baseman Chipper Jones
signed a six-year, $90 million contract last week, Dodgers
right-hander Kevin Brown finally had company atop baseball's
average annual salary list.
</P>
<P>
   Jones' contract pays him $15 million per season, equaling the
average annual value of the seven-year, $105 million deal Brown
agreed to in December 1998. Since the Brown deal, the Dodgers have
been hammered mercilessly about skewing the salary structure of
baseball. But Jones' deal should ease some of that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think (signing) actually takes some of the pressure off,''
Jones said. ``So many times in the past I worried about things off
the field. Now things are really set. I think it takes all the
pressure off me, to be honest with you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expectations are always going to be high when you play for
this team and hit in the middle of the lineup. That's the way it
is. They expect me to go out and drive in 100 and score 100 and
play solid defense.''
</P>
</TEXT>
