<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Olazabal shoots 63 as course is a feast
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Maybe they won't be able to beat the leader
Tiger Woods today in the final round of the PGA Championship, but
on Saturday they could still beat up Valhalla Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   Hitting fairways with a regularity he barely remembered, Spain's
Jose Maria Olazabal made nine birdies in a sizzling 9-under-par 63
for a new course record in the PGA's third round, tying the lowest
round ever shot in a major championship.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Watson, who is 51 and mostly a Senior Tour player now,
rediscovered some putting magic for a 7-under-par 65.
</P>
<P>
   Delighting in greens still softened from rain earlier in the
week and some kinder pin placements, Peachtree City's Franklin
Langham shot another 65 later in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it has nothing to do with the golf course,'' said
Olazabal, who moved to 9-under-par despite an opening 76 Thursday.
``I think it is the way the players are playing. I don't think you
would see these kind of scores at a regular tournament in this golf
course. . . . Obviously, Tiger is making us work harder and we have
to improve our games (if) we can have a slim chance of beating
him.''
</P>
<P>
   After knocking down the flagstick all day, Olazabal missed
chances for 62 at both the 17th and 18th holes. He ran a birdie
putt under the cup at the 17th from about 15 feet, and at the par-5
18th couldn't go for the green in two ``because I'm not as long as
Tiger off the tee.''
</P>
<P>
   Elated with his round, Watson said, ``Well, my dad used to say,
`It's pretty good for old folks.' That's what it is. I've hit the
ball better, but I haven't putted much better than I did today,
except when I was 28.''
</P>
<P>
   No longer realistically thinking about a career Grand Slam with
the PGA his missing major, Watson said, ``I still feel as if I can
play with the young kids, but my days are numbered.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps if Woods were not around, Watson could at least dream a
bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Tiger changed his golf swing (in late '97), I think (it
became) the best golf swing out here,'' said Watson. Langham, who
has three second-place finishes on the PGA Tour this year, started
birdie-eagle on the way to a front-nine 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to say I'm surprised at all to be where I am,''
he said. ``I'm elated. . . . Things are cooking for me and I'm very
thankful for that.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing in the group behind Olazabal, Langham looked up on the
15th hole and noticed the two-time Masters champion at 8-under for
the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like, `Wow, I thought I was playing good,' '' Langham
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
