<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOODS REMAINS IN LEAD DESPITE A SLIGHT STUMBLE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ The field made its run at Tiger Woods on
Saturday, and for once, he did not run away.
</P>
<P>
   The course record was set, and Woods did not do it. When Woods
built a three-shot lead, he could not hold it. And as the PGA
Championship headed toward Sunday's final round, at least a dozen
players had a chance to win it.
</P>
<P>
   Shooting a two-under par 70, his worst round of the tournament,
Woods held a slim one-stroke lead at 13 under par (203) over Scott
Dunlap (12 under) and Bob May (12 under) after Saturday's
unpredictable third round at Valhalla Golf Club. J.P. Hayes, who
shot 68, was two strokes off the lead at 11 under par, while Greg
Chalmers was in fifth place at 10 under. Jose Maria Olazabal, who
set the course record with a nine-under-par 63, was tied for sixth
place at nine under par with Stuart Appleby and Thomas Bjorn.
</P>
<P>
   All of those players, and even those farther behind, will enter
Sunday with a chance to win the year's final major. And Saturday's
unexpected story was Woods' inability to take command in his quest
to become the first player since Ben Hogan in 1953 to win three
consecutive major championships.
</P>
<P>
   Valhalla was ripe for the taking, and while many players took
advantage, Woods struggled.
</P>
<P>
   He made a rare and costly double-bogey at No.12, three-putting
from 15 feet, including a missed second putt from less than 2 feet.
Suddenly, the three-shot lead that Woods took to the 12th tee was
gone, because after Woods' double-bogey dropped him to 13 under
par, Dunlap made a birdie at No.12 to tie Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap, who shot a two-under par 70 to stay one stroke behind
Woods, showed character while paired in the final group with Woods,
refusing to fold even when he fell three strokes behind. And Dunlap
ended the day with a brilliant bunker shot at 18 to within 3 feet
of the cup that led to a day-ending birdie. Not only did Dunlap
keep his composure, he kept within striking distance of Woods.
</P>
<P>
   So did May, a 31-year-old player who, like Dunlap, has never won
on the PGA Tour. Who expected Woods' closest competition at the PGA
Championship to come from three players who have never won on the
Tour _ Dunlap, May, and Chalmers, along with Hayes, who only has
one tour victory, the 1998 Buick Classic?
</P>
<P>
   You never know in golf, which is why Sunday should be so
interesting. Look at what happened Saturday: When Woods has a
three-shot lead at a major, he usually steps on the opposition's
throats. But when Woods went for the jugular Saturday, he slipped.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, all over the course, other players were having a
birdie fest. Roars rang out around the course, as one putt after
another dropped into the cup, and one approach shot after another
flirted with the flagstick. But Woods' putting was inconsistent, as
were his approach shots. And with each chance that Woods
squandered, the field drew closer to the top.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the day's most shocking moment came at No.12, when
Woods lost a three-shot lead with a double-bogey, while Dunlap made
birdie. Woods does not make many double-bogeys in majors anymore.
He never made one at the U.S. Open or at the British Open.
</P>
<P>
   But Saturday, as he reached the 12th tee at 15 under par, while
Dunlap was 12 under par, the momentum changed swiftly. Woods hit a
poor tee shot into the left rough, then his second shot landed
short of the green.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after Woods chipped to 15 feet, the gallery was shocked to
see him miss not only his first putt that slid 2 feet past the
hole, but his second putt that darted past the right edge of the
cup.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap capitalized by making an 8-foot birdie putt that pulled
him even with Woods at 12 under par. And even after Dunlap bogeyed
the par-3 No.14 to give Woods a one-stroke lead again, Woods
continued to struggle, when he bogeyed No.15 to fall into a tie at
12 under par again. Woods' approach shot at No.15 sailed over the
green into heavy rough, and though he hit a brilliant chip out of
the heavy grass to 10 feet, Woods followed by missing the putt for
par.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap made another bogey at 17, when he missed a 15-foot putt
for par after missing the green on his second shot, but both Woods
and Dunlap birdied the par-5 finishing hole, with Woods two-putting
after reaching the green in two shots, while Dunlap hit a superb
bunker shot on his third shot at 18 that stopped 2 feet from the
cup.
</P>
<P>
   So a tournament that Woods had a chance to take control of is up
for grabs. Woods looked to be in prime position midway through the
round, when Dunlap started to look shaky with his putter. Dunlap
could have tied Woods at No.8, but he missed a 3-foot putt for
birdie. At No.9, Woods made a 15-foot putt for birdie, then Dunlap
missed a 10-foot putt for birdie to fall two strokes behind. And at
No.10, Woods made a 4-footer for birdie to go three strokes ahead,
after Dunlap missed an 8-footer for birdie.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, you could hear people thinking that Woods was
pulling away, but it did not happen. The double-bogey at No.12
proved that yes, Woods is human, and yes, even for him, it is not
easy to win majors.
</P>
<P>
   So when the final round begins on Sunday, the chasers will know
that they at least have a chance to beat the world's No.1 player.
He is still the man to beat, but at least the day will start with
drama, and it could end with drama.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps someone will rise up from the pack to beat him, or
perhaps Woods will do what he usually does _ play his best when the
pressure is the highest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seventy was a good score, considering how bad I felt over
every shot today,'' Woods said. ``I didn't play well, but I manage
my game. At least I've put myself in position to win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
