<SLUG> BC-GORE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE EMBRACES POPULIST THEMES AS A MEANS OF CRITICIZING BUSH 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID BARSTOW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DUBUQUE, Iowa _ Vice President Al Gore assailed Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas on Saturday as a man who has embraced the interests
of corporations at the expense of the middle class.
</P>
<P>
   In a fiery speech he delivered here on the banks of the
Mississippi River, Gore placed Bush squarely on the side of
pharmaceutical companies that he said gouge the elderly with high
drug prices, insurance company ``bean counters'' who overrule
doctors and major polluters who cut corners on environmental
protection measures for the sake of profits.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're for the powerful, we're for the people,'' Gore said
before embarking on the second day of a journey down the
Mississippi aboard the Mark Twain riverboat.
</P>
<P>
   Positioning himself as a populist champion, Gore promised the
elderly new Medicare benefits to help pay for prescription drugs.
``My opponent won't,'' he shouted. ``They give in to the big drug
companies; I fight for families.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore promised to give doctors more authority over medical
decisions. ``My opponent won't,'' he said. ``They give in to the
big insurance companies that don't want that.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he would take on polluters who ``cut corners'' for
profits. ``My opponent does not reflect that commitment in what's
been going on in his home state,'' Gore said, a reference to Texas'
low ranking in air and water quality.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we look to the future,'' he said, ``it makes a difference
if you have someone in the Oval Office who is willing to stand up
to the oil companies and the big polluters and say the families of
this country deserve better.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign was quick to respond. ``It seems like a lot of
finger-pointing from an administration that has failed to act on
these issues,'' said Mindy Tucker, a spokeswoman for Bush. ``In
contrast, Governor Bush has signed into law a patients' bill of
rights for Texans. He has reduced toxic releases more than all
other 49 states combined and he supports reforming Medicare to
include a prescription drug benefit for seniors.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Gore delivered one of his clearest and most concise
critiques of Bush. For weeks, Gore had been somewhat circumspect in
his criticism of Bush. At an event in Cleveland before the
Democratic convention, for example, Gore passed up the invitation
to criticize Bush's record on health care. He has left it to others
to tear into Bush's record, perhaps mindful that many voters are
turned off by harsh attacks.
</P>
<P>
   But with some polls showing him at last pulling even, or nudging
ahead of Bush, Gore appeared emboldened Saturday to challenge Bush
with renewed directness and vigor. And many in Saturday's crowd of
several thousand, dominated by teachers and union workers,
delighted in the attacks, waving signs and chanting ``Go, Al, go.''
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Bush accused Gore of engaging in class warfare, and
the Bush campaign has argued that Gore _ the son of a senator, the
product of elite private schools and ferociously good at raising
money from corporations _ hardly fits the role of working-class
hero. Much of the Gore family's wealth comes from holdings in the
Occidental Petroleum Corporation, whose founder, Armand Hammer, was
a close friend of Gore's father.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's running mate, Senator Joseph Lieberman of Connecticut, is
a baker's son, but some of his most reliable contributors have
worked in the insurance and pharmaceutical industries. In this
year's Senate campaign, Lieberman, who according to Connecticut law
is allowed to campaign to keep his Senate seat while also running
as the vice presidential nominee, has collected more money from the
insurance industry _ $197,419 _ than any other senator, according
to the Center for Responsive Politics. He has raised $91,150 from
the pharmaceutical industry, second only to Sen. Orrin Hatch,
R-Utah. Lieberman's wife, Hadassah, was once director of policy
planning and communications for Pfizer Inc., one of the nation's
largest drug companies.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's press secretary, Chris Lehane, played down the importance
of those contributions and Lieberman's efforts on behalf of both
industries. ``Who's running for president?'' Lehane asked. ``Al
Gore's at the top of the ticket.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Gore and his aides have only stepped up their populist
rhetoric. ``It's really clear what's going on,'' Lehane said.
``George W. Bush is in the hip pocket of big oil, the prescription
drug companies and the big insurance companies.''
</P>
</TEXT>
