</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0820-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: New poll finds Gore leading Bush
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News ServiceAl Gore's presidential campaign appeared
<TEXT>
to be bolstered on Saturday by a new poll that found the vice
president may have overtaken Republican rival George W. Bush. The
Newsweek poll, conducted at the end of the Democratic convention,
shows Gore with a 52 percent to 48 percent lead over Bush _ wiping
out the double digit lead Bush scored in a Newsweek poll taken at
the end of the GOP convention two weeks ago. The new poll has a
margin of error of 4 percentage points, which means the
presidential contest could be a virtual tie. If so, Gore has
increased his standings from the earlier poll, which showed Bush
with a 49 to 38 percent lead.
<P>
   Told of the poll results while campaigning on the slow-moving
Mark Twain riverboat down the Mississippi River on Saturday, Gore
seemed low-key, saying ``I really don't think polls matter.'' Then
he added with a smile: ``I must admit I'm beginning to think that
the polls have a little more relevancy as we get close the
election.''
</P>
<P>
   BUSH UNVEILS PLAN TO REPAIR INDIAN SCHOOLS
</P>
<P>
   Bush unveiled a new education plan on Saturday to spend more
than $800 million to repair schools on the country's Indian
reservations. Bush proposed spending the money on 185 schools on
tribal lands, most of them managed by the Bureau of Indian Affairs,
his aides said. His proposal calls for an additional $126 million
to replace the system's worst six schools, they said. The proposed
funding is relatively little _ compared with other education
initiatives that Bush and his rival Al Gore have already made
during the campaign. But the plan allows Bush to sustain his focus
on education _ an issue perhaps more traditionally associated with
Democrats, but one that he has said will be his main topic of
discussion in the next two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH AND GORE ARGUE OVER WHO IS THE HARDEST WORKER
</P>
<P>
   While Bush talked about education and Gore discussed the
environment, their campaigns on Saturday skirmished over another
hot topic: which candidate is running harder. Bush spokesman Scott
McClellan started it after a reporter asked why Bush had only one
event Friday and none scheduled for today. McClellan quickly came
up with a list of 22 stops that Bush made in five days following
the GOP convention. That represents 138 electoral votes, McClellan
beamed. Gore's people then weighed in, saying this weekend Gore was
on a four-day 400-mile trip down the Mississippi River and will
follow that with more campaigning. Altogether there will be 20
events in six states, representing 86 electoral votes, over seven
days. ``It is Al Gore who works 24/7 and George W. Bush whose
lightweight schedule is matched only by his lightweight agenda,''
Gore spokesman Chris Lehane said.
</P>
<P>
   LIEBERMAN OBSERVES THE SABBATH
</P>
<P>
   Democratic vice presidential candidate Sen. Joseph Lieberman and
his family veered off the campaign trail Saturday to attend
services in La Crosse, Wis., at the only Jewish synagogue within 90
miles. ``After the week we've had, my family and I are thankful,
not just for spiritual reasons, but for physical and psychological
reasons, for a day of rest,'' Lieberman told about 60 worshippers
at the Congregation Sons of Abraham. Lieberman, the first Jew on a
national ticket, has openly observed the Sabbath, which lasts from
sundown Friday to sundown Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   GORE CHALLENGES BUSH TO DEBATE
</P>
<P>
   Gore on Saturday challenged Bush not to ``duck the major
debates'' scheduled by the Commission on Presidential Debates. Bush
on Saturday told The Washington Post that he would ``possibly''
consider beginning face-to-face debates with Gore earlier than the
Oct. 3 debate scheduled by the presidential debates commission, the
traditional sponsor in recent elections. However, Bush hedged on
whether he was willing to participate in that opening forum, which
is scheduled for the John F. Kennedy presidential library in
Boston, a venue Republicans regard as Democratic turf.
</P>
<P>
   NADER SUED BY MASTERCARD
</P>
<P>
   Green Party presidential candidate Ralph Nader has said he is a
corporate victim after MasterCard International Inc., filed a $5
million lawsuit accusing him of trademark infringement. MasterCard
on Wednesday claimed the Green Party's political commercials
infringed upon its $100 million ``Priceless'' ad campaign, which
has run in 48 countries. ``MasterCard should lighten up,'' Nader
said on Thursday, acknowledging the advertisement is a parody.
``They're taking their name `Master' too seriously. This is
America.''
</P>
<P>
   GORE'S SON ARRESTED FOR RECKLESS DRIVING
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore's son has a Sept. 13 court date in North Carolina to
face charges of speeding and reckless driving. Albert Gore III, 17,
was arrested and charged on Aug. 12 with driving 97 mph in a 55 mph
zone and reckless driving on a state highway in a rural, sparsely
populated area along the Outer Banks just south of Norfolk, Va.,
said 1st Sgt. A.C. Joyner of the North Carolina Highway Patrol.
Camille Johnston, a spokeswoman for Tipper Gore, said Saturday that
the teen-ager was alone at the time and was heading home to
Washington after a family vacation.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
