<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TEAMS WANT TO MAKE IT THERE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Start spreading the news, it's going to be a
Yankees-Mets subway World Series.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's what New Yorkers will have you believe.
</P>
<P>
   Last season, a subway series came dangerously close to reality,
as the Mets reached the National League Championship Series only to
lose to the Braves and failing to meet the Yankees in the Series.
But this year could be different.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the Braves win the NL East, the Mets could do what the
Marlins did in 1997 - beat the Braves in the playoffs as the wild
card and go to the Series.
</P>
<P>
   As the New York Post is quick to point out, Sportsbook.com has
the Yankees as the 8-5 favorite to represent the American League in
the Series. The Mets are the second pick in the National League,
behind the Braves, at 3-1. (The Braves are 2-1).
</P>
<P>
   Sportsbook.com has a Yankees-Mets Series handicapped at 10-1.
Place your bets.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because the New York teams have shown they want to win more
than anybody else. And we're not talking about the players, we're
talking about the front offices.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams made numerous moves before the trading deadline in an
effort to improve their chances. Sure, not all the moves are
necessarily good ones. But the intent is there. And when the
players see how badly the front office wants to win, they usually
respond favorably.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees acquired David Justice, Glenallen Hill, Luis Sojo,
Denny Neagle and Jose Vizcaino. The Mets acquired Mike Bordick,
Bubba Trammell and Rick White.
</P>
<P>
   But what will make the difference for both teams is not so much
the newcomers, but the pitchers. For the Yankees, Roger Clemens has
come on strong in the second half. The Yankees won despite him last
year, but this year they need him, both down the stretch and
especially in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question Clemens has been the difference for us in the
second half, and Andy (Pettitte) has quietly done his part too with
15 wins,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said. ``Potentially
(domination) is out there. Considering everything, we're still
sitting four games up in the loss column and I feel pretty good
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Mets, a healthy Mike Hampton is vital. Hampton might
miss a start with what he is calling a 10-year-old football injury.
He has a stress fracture to one of his ribs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to come out once from a football game (with the same
injury) in high school and they said that's what this looks like it
could be,'' Hampton said.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton hurt himself swinging the bat and said he needs to be
smarter when dealing with his aches and pains because the team
needs him.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it's going to feel like it did, I'll definitely find other
ways to do things when I'm hitting,'' Hampton said. ``I can't take
a chance of getting injured. We're getting down to September, and
this is where the team needs me. I'll do whatever it takes to be
out there every fifth day.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the intangibles. The Yankees have been knocked
around by the Mariners and White Sox this season, but come playoff
time, the Yankees will have an edge because of their experience in
big games.
</P>
<P>
   The same might be said about the Braves, only the Braves are the
biggest playoff underachievers in decades. And there is MVP
candidate Mike Piazza, who is due to place his stamp in the
baseball postseason and challenge pretty boy Derek Jeter for the
throne in New York.
</P>
<P>
   And finally, there are the baseball gods. If they have any pull
at all, they'll make sure Clemens and Piazza - who became enemies
this season when Clemens beaned Piazza - face each other again.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
