<HEADLINE>
METS' ZEILE USED TO ANONYMITY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Todd Zeile is used to being ``the other guy'' when
Mike Piazza is involved.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Dodgers traded both in 1998. Piazza, of course,
got the headlines. The two were reunited this season with the New
York Mets and, while Piazza is making a bid to become the National
League MVP, Zeile is making it difficult not to be noticed.
</P>
<P>
   He entered this weekend's series against the Dodgers batting
.295 with 17 home runs and 67 RBI for the Mets, who are leading the
wild-card race. Zeile has never finished a season with a batting
average better than last year's .293.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in a great situation,'' Zeile said. ``It's easier to
perform when you're comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Zeile is with his seventh team since the St. Louis Cardinals
traded him during the 1995 season. Rejecting an offer to stay with
Texas when he became a free agent last winter, Zeile knew he would
again be switching positions with Robin Ventura entrenched at third
for New York.
</P>
<P>
   Zeile is pleased with his progress and says change is something
he's grown to accept as part of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Moving to first base has been less of a burden than the
transition from catcher to third base, because I've had 10 years of
experience in the infield,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't a secret the Hart High and UCLA product wanted to
return to Southern California. Zeile, 34, had just bought a new
home and his son was starting Little League when the Dodgers traded
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was comfortable in Texas,'' he said. ``But I had a number of
considerations.''
</P>
<P>
   Being reunited with an old buddy was an added bonus. Piazza is
one of Zeile's closest friends on the team. The pair seek each
other out for conversation during warmups and have lockers near one
another.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was kind of a breakdown of dreams for me,'' Zeile said of
leaving the Dodgers. ``Having said that, I think I'm happy to be
back together with Mike and the fact that there have been some
people who have strong voices and are giving me the credit that was
due.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't feel forgotten by any means.''
</P>
<P>
   The lack of reaction by Dodgers fans when he returns to the town
where he hit a career-high 31 home runs in 1997 is something he
expects, though.
</P>
<P>
   Before the first game of the current series at Dodger Stadium,
Piazza drew loud reactions from the crowd each time he came to bat;
the response to Zeile wasn't much different than that for any of
the other Mets player.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't like it took time for them to forget,'' Zeile said.
``The day (the trade) happened, most people had forgotten because
it was called the Piazza trade. You know most of the people were
just thinking about what happened to Mike. But such is life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-00 2111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
