<HEADLINE>
ERSTAD SAYS SPASMS ARE NOTHING SERIOUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Anaheim Angels lost the player they can least
afford to lose for most of Saturday's game, and probably won't have
him today, either.
</P>
<P>
   Outfielder Darin Erstad left after three innings Saturday
because of muscle spasms on the left side of his rib cage. It's
something he's dealt with for the past couple of weeks, but it
reached a point Saturday where he had to come out of the game.
</P>
<P>
   He said he isn't affected throwing the ball or swinging the bat,
and Friday night's diving catch caused no pain in the area at all.
But when making a routine throw back to the infield after catching
a fly ball in the second inning Saturday, the spasms started.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just wouldn't go away,'' said Erstad, who finally admitted
to manager Mike Scioscia he wasn't feeling right. ``I tried to use
my head for the first time in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time Ersty says something to come out of a game,
usually a bone is sticking out,'' Scioscia said. ``I think Darin's
smart enough to know a half-step backwards sometimes can save three
or four weeks of playing time. Hopefully it's something we're
catching and nipping in the bud.''
</P>
<P>
   Erstad said he's certain it is nothing serious, just a feeling
of tightness in the area. He said it felt more like a cramp than
anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm moving, it doesn't hurt,'' he said. ``But tying my
shoes or lying in bed is when it's uncomfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   If Erstad is not in the starting lineup today, Scioscia said
he'd use either Orlando Palmeiro or Scott Spiezio in the leadoff
spot.
</P>
<P>
   Record setter: Tim Salmon hit his 223rd career homer Friday
night, passing Brian Downing to set the Angels' all-time home run
record. But it got lost in all the hoopla surrounding the Angels'
dramatic comeback.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the excitement in the game, I forgot about it
myself,'' Salmon said. ``So many great things happened in the game.
But I don't feel any sense of being upstaged. It was nice to get it
over with.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon said it was especially nice to hit the record-breaker off
Roger Clemens and hit it in Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about the best place you can do it other than doing it at
home,'' Salmon said. ``And Clemens, he's a Hall of Famer.''
</P>
<P>
   Salmon also hit his first career homer in Yankee Stadium, off
Scott Sanderson in 1992. And he said he doesn't want to stop at
223.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I have to add to it, make it harder for Troy (Glaus) or
whoever else might pass it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Debut: Shawn Wooten made his major-league debut Saturday,
catching the entire game and going 0 for 4 at the plate. He flied
out three times (to each outfielder) and lined out to shortstop.
</P>
<P>
   Wooten said he had a feeling he might get the start Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they like to give (backup Matt) Walbeck a start the day
after a night game to give Bengie (Molina) a day off,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought he was ready for the challenge,'' Scioscia said.
``Over the last two years, he's really turned himself into a
player.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
