u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-ANALYSIS-B     08-19 1032
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALL PIECES ARE FITTING FOR RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ANALYSIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ This keeps up, we'll all be watching the Red Sox in
October on NomarVision.
</P>
<P>
   Sean McDonough had the day off _ the Sox were on national TV _
so there was no one around to spoil a perfect picture on Yawkey Way
Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro was healthy, happy, and unhittable again. Lou Merloni, who
had three more hits Saturday, has come back from Japan, transformed
into a samurai warrior. Jason Varitek broke out of a hellacious
slump with two hits and four RBIs. Troy O'Leary was on base four
times, Bernard Gilkey three. Carl Everett had another big hit, then
broke the ice with a couple of reporters. Garciaparra walked twice,
had a hit, and scored twice.
</P>
<P>
   The concession lines were short, the bathrooms clean, and the
beer cheap.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so it wasn't quite that perfect. But after a 9-0 win over
the Texas Rangers, the Red Sox' fifth win in six games on this
homestand, a team that at times has resembled a collection of
haphazardly assembled spare parts is suddenly taking on the look of
a confident, cohesive unit.
</P>
<P>
   That's what a few wins will do for you.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winning always solves a lot of problems,'' said Sox coach
Tommy Harper. ``The new guys have gotten a chance to contribute.
Everybody knew they had played in the big leagues, we knew 'em from
their stats, but we didn't know them as people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then you start to win. Rico Brogna wins a game, Mike Lansing
wins a game, (Rolando) Arrojo pitches well, (Tomo) Ohka pitches
well, and Merloni has given us a spark. The new guys, they have to
be feeling pretty good about themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   This is what Brogna was hoping would happen after his
bottom-of-the-ninth, game-winning grand slam last Monday night.
He's played sparingly since, but the team has not counted itself
out of a game ever since he parked his slam in the visitors'
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it sparked us or not,'' Brogna said, ``but
we've been playing well. That showed me a lot of character, Lansing
hitting that ball off the Wall.''
</P>
<P>
   Brogna was referring to Lansing's game-winning double Thursday
night, when the Sox rallied from a 6-1 deficit to beat the Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, that was more significant, because we were down five,''
Brogna said. ``Monday night, the game was tied, so the worst-case
scenario if I don't get a hit is we're still playing with a chance
to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Thursday, we scored three in the eighth, three in the
ninth. You had Gilkey with his great hustle on the error (when
Royce Clayton double-clutched before Lansing's heroics). I don't
know if it was the grand slam or not, but it got us off to a good
start on this homestand like we had hoped.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett, who hit little when he first came off his suspension
but has 10 hits and five RBIs on the homestand, said he never felt
like he was in the company of strangers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always felt like a team,'' he said. ``We just didn't get
hits at the times we needed to.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these guys have a history of hitting. I've played against
them. They don't surprise me. I know what they can do for a team.''
</P>
<P>
   The win kept the Sox three games behind the Yankees in the AL
East, and they now lead Oakland by .001 in the wild-card race,
after the A's lost Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, 4-3, to the Detroit Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have a better chance this year,'' said Martinez,
who allowed just one Ranger to second base in his three-hit,
no-walk, 10-K declaration that his right shoulder was sound again
after he cut short his exercise Monday night after just four
innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can keep pitching like this,'' Martinez said, ``and then
when the rosters expand (Sept. 1), we'll have even more guys to
help us out. If one guy gets banged up, somebody else will come and
pick us up.''
</P>
<P>
   As recently as two years ago, Martinez said, he probably
wouldn't have taken himself out of Monday's game against the Devil
Rays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back then,'' he said, ``I didn't believe in pain.''
</P>
<P>
   But this time, when he came off the mound after four innings and
physical therapist Rich Zawacki detected a knot in his shoulder,
Martinez knew better.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew that by taking myself out,'' he said, ``I was helping
the team more.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have helped, of course, by playing some very bad
baseball. Monday night, Mo Vaughn and the Angels come to town, and
this is a much different Mo than the one who limped through a
dreadful homecoming a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   But this is a different Sox team than the one that was in
Anaheim a couple of weeks ago, competing against not only the
Angels but also exhaustion because of the ridiculous schedule that
required them to criss-cross the country twice in 96 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, who is 3 for 19 on this homestand, is probably
still tired, which is probably part of the reason he crankily
accused McDonough _ who has a well-earned reputation for being
scrupulously fair _ of being heavy-handed in his coverage of the
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him the other day, `You're tired,' '' Martinez said.
``I could see it, especially in Anaheim. Look at how he plays hard
every day. These guys are going to get tired.''
</P>
<P>
   The fatigue, Harper said, is more mental than physical. Manager
Jimy Williams, in addition to giving Garciaparra a blow on Friday,
asked Everett to let him know if he wanted one, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me, I never want one,'' Everett said.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox center fielder, who has been breaking his silence in
increments since all the turmoil of the last month, his suspension
and shouting match with Williams, was asked if his focus had been
disrupted.
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' he said. ``I still play ball. That's all I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Everett carried the Astros to a division title with inspired
play down the stretch last year. Is this his time now?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have any particular time,'' he said. ``I just go play.
I go through peaks and valleys, but I want those valleys to be as
small as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox are not yet at the mountaintop, and may not get there.
But on this one, even Sean and Nomar would agree: Their compass is
pointed in the right direction.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
