<HEADLINE>
USC GUARD ROBERTS EXPECTED TO MISS SEASON OPENER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVINE, Calif. _ USC is experiencing one of its healthiest
training camps in recent memory, but there has been one setback:
Senior left guard Trevor Roberts is not expected to be available
for the Trojans' season opener against Penn State next week.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts, who suffered a strained foot last week and has not
practiced in more than a week, was still walking around Saturday
with a boot on his injured foot. It would be extremely unlikely he
could recover and practice enough this week to be in game shape.
</P>
<P>
   Without Roberts, USC would start redshirt freshman Lenny
Vandermade, who has also been practicing at center. It would be the
first start of Vandermade's career.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lenny has been good. He's not Trevor,'' USC coach Paul Hackett
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another player Hackett said he is concerned about is tight end
Antoine Harris (strained calf) but Harris insists he will be ready
to play full time.
</P>
<P>
   Easing into form: Defensive end Ryan Nielsen of Simi Valley High
has missed about five practices during training camp, as he returns
from off-season shoulder surgery. But he's optimistic about this
season, especially after dropping nearly 15 pounds since last
year's training camp.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-5 Nielsen weighs 275 pounds and has noticed the
difference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a lot faster,'' Nielsen said. ``It also helps that it's a
year later and I'm recognizing things a lot faster. I'm not (100
percent) right now, but I will be for the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen figures to enjoy some freedom this season, because most
teams will try to double-cover preseason All-American Ennis Davis
of Reseda High.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd love for them to forget about me, and worry about him,''
Nielsen said. ``Ennis is a lot quicker this year, and he's got his
body back together. I'm looking forward to playing with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ahead of schedule: With two-a-day practices over, Hackett felt
the Trojans are actually doing better than he anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our conditioning is a little better than I thought, and our
young players are doing better,'' Hackett said. ``(Strong safety)
Troy Polamalu, (cornerback) Kevin Arbet, (cornerback) Darrell
Rideaux, (linebacker) Kori Dickerson, (offensive lineman) Lenny
Vandermade. Some of the younger guys are a little further ahead
than I thought.''
</P>
<P>
   Childers OK: X-rays on Friday night revealed that defensive end
Matt Childers fractured a knuckle on his left hand when it was
smashed by a helmet, but the senior said he would start against
Penn State and will not be affected.
</P>
<P>
   Mini-break: The Trojans took Saturday afternoon off and will not
practice today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to let our bodies rest up,'' Hackett said. ``We have
48 hours to get our legs back.''
</P>
<P>
   They return to practice Monday, Tuesday and Wednesday at UC
Irvine, but those sessions are closed to the public.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
