<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 22:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7004 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-GRIMES-B     08-19 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-GRIMES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNHERALDED GRIMES GROWING ON PATRIOTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ For most folks, the young-adult years are a
gradual growth process, marked by subtle changes in inseam lengths
and shoe sizes. But others virtually outpace the stock market in
their growth spurts; in a matter of months, their appearance
changes rapidly, as if their bodies are getting time-and-a-half pay
for the effort.
</P>
<P>
   When Patriots rookie defensive end Reggie Grimes was a junior at
Hunter's Lane High School in Nashville, he was 6 feet 4 inches, 220
pounds. He platooned at quarterback, fullback, and defensive end,
showing much promise at all positions.
</P>
<P>
   By his senior year, he weighed in at 245 pounds and had moved to
fullback full-time on offense. But even though he earned All-State
honors at the position (1,388 rushing yards, 23 touchdowns), he
seemed more suited for the defensive side of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   He signed with the University of Alabama to play running back.
But his body spoke up again. Grimes kept putting on weight, and
Alabama responded, moving him to defensive end before his redshirt
freshman season.
</P>
<P>
   Entering his junior year, Grimes was up to 288 pounds, yet he
hadn't lost any of his speed or athleticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played at running back at 250, and he still ran 4.65 in the
40,'' said Hunter's Lane coach Jerry Pigue. ``And he was clocked at
that time at a college camp he attended prior to his senior year.
He was redshirted as a freshman at Alabama and got up to 270 real
quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never concerned about his weight because Reggie was just
a big guy, and you just knew it was going to be hard for him to
hold 220. He tried. He would even run track just to keep his weight
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he played running back, once he broke the line of
scrimmage he just outran everybody. I used to joke that a lot of
people could have caught him but they didn't want to because he was
so big.''
</P>
<P>
   It is that size and quickness that have made Grimes a welcome
addition to the Patriots, who signed him as an undrafted free
agent. Grimes has started two exhibition games in place of Brandon
Mitchell and has nine tackles (tied for third on the team) and two
sacks.
</P>
<P>
   In a 30-20 loss to the Washington Redskins Aug. 11, Grimes had
four tackles, including a 9-yard sack.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very diligent,'' said Patriots coach Bill Belichick. ``He
takes coaching well, and you can see some improvement every day.
Those guys that improve every day _ and we have enough days here _
it's kind of hard to hold them back.''
</P>
<P>
   Grimes started every game at Alabama his sophomore season before
breaking his leg Nov. 1 against Louisiana State. He did not
participate in spring practice in 1998 while rehabilitating the
injury and never again assumed a full-time starting role.
</P>
<P>
   Still, he did more than enough to get noticed. As a senior,
Grimes had 27 tackles, 5 sacks, 2 pass breakups, 13 quarterback
hurries, and an interception return for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   Now that he's at the NFL level, Grimes said it matters not that
he didn't get drafted. He knew he would make it if he got invited
to someone's camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a lifelong dream, and I'm this close to realizing
the dream,'' said Grimes. ``I feel like if I was to get cut, it's
not going to be because I didn't do everything I could have done.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have to say determination has gotten me this far.''
</P>
<P>
   Grimes has never been short on motivation. As a senior, he won
the metro Nashville area's Hume Award, given to the high school
football player with the highest academic achievement.
</P>
<P>
   Despite making his reputation in the offensive backfield, Grimes
said he always had a taste for the trenches. In Pop Warner, he
played both sides of the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got the knack for playing quarterback when I turned 12 and I
started pitching in baseball,'' he said. ``I believe that's when I
developed my arm strength, because I would go to my grandfather's
house and play catch and all of a sudden I could throw (a football)
a lot further than I had been able to.''
</P>
<P>
   Grimes became the first freshman at Hunter's Lane to play
varsity football, and by his junior year he was starting at
quarterback. By his senior year, he was too valuable a runner to
keep at quarterback. Pigue gave the QB job to Grimes's younger
brother, Trevor.
</P>
<P>
   Grimes, who now weighs 290 pounds, was not concerned about
putting on weight so quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a pretty good amount of weight in a year, but it
really wasn't a struggle or change or anything for me,'' said
Grimes. ``It was just kind of natural.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He worked hard to keep his weight down, but he was just going
to grow,'' said Pigue. ``He understood, `I've got a chance to get
to the next level if I get to the natural size for this position.'
''
</P>
<P>
   Grimes is perhaps best noted for his interception return for a
38-yard touchdown against Florida in the Southeastern Conference
championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was as if it was hanging up there forever, and I saw it and
it was really a reaction,'' said Grimes. ``Next thing you know, I
was scoring.''
</P>
<P>
   That helped garner the interest of many who may not have noticed
Grimes because he wasn't a starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought at the end of the season he was playing as well as
any player I saw in college,'' said Pigue.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we moved him to running back full-time as a senior, he
had to take charge, and he did _ in the locker room, the huddles,
everything. That's when I knew he was going to succeed in college
and have a chance at the next level.''
</P>
<P>
   Grimes has brought that take-charge demeanor to the next level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been hard for guys to move ahead of Reggie because he's
continually taking another step up the ladder,'' said Belichick.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been real positive. But it's an unusual situation where
you look at a guy who didn't start in college and now he's in a
position where he's receiving considerable playing time.''
</P>
<P>
   Grimes said he still has a lot to work on, like footwork and
hand placement. But he is pleased merely to have the opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't expect to be playing this much this early,'' he said,
``but I did expect to come in and compete for a job. Everything is
kind of working out for my benefit right now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
