<HEADER>
A7005 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BOX-NOTEBOOK-BOS &LR;      08-19 1822
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEE DUCKS PUNCH; ARUM TAKES THE BLOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Apparently, the only thing that a jury of Bob Lee's
peers thought was unusual about the former International Boxing
Federation president accepting several thousand dollars in a
Portsmouth, Va., hotel room out of someone's sock was that the cash
didn't come with a W-2 form.
</P>
<P>
   After millions of dollars and countless hours were spent trying
to convince a jury in Newark with videotapes, audiotapes, and sworn
testimony that Lee and his son sold the IBF's ratings, the jurors
deliberated for 15 days and decided Lee wasn't guilty of accepting
a bribe at all. No, they reasoned, he was just guilty of money
laundering, tax fraud, and engaging in interstate travel to aid in
racketeering. So what money was he laundering? His allowance from
Bob Arum?
</P>
<P>
   The federal government contended that Lee had taken at least
$338,000 from various fight managers and promoters _ including some
of the biggest in the game _ in exchange for manipulating his
ratings. The unconvincing evidence of this was 22 days of testimony
by government witness Doug Beavers, the former head of the IBF
ratings committee.
</P>
<P>
   His testimony was accompanied by three video and 80 audio tapes
he helped make of Lee accepting cash for favors. That unconvincing
evidence was backed up by promoters such as Arum, Dino Duva, and
Cedric Kushner, who all testified that they had paid Lee's
organization to get their fighters rated.
</P>
<P>
   In Arum's case, he even laundered the cash through a circuitous
route involving a German fight promoter and a fight
manager-turned-bagman named Stan Hoffman, who carried $50,000 from
Arum to Germany so it eventually could end up back in New Jersey in
Lee's hands. Yet these were not bribes, the jurors concluded. What
they said, without speaking, is that they simply believed this is
how business is done in the seedy world of prizefighting, and who
cares?
</P>
<P>
   Well, Arum cares because he may end up paying the biggest
penalty, if not the only one. While the jury was still out, the
Nevada Athletic Commission used Arum's testimony about the $100,000
bribe he paid to get unranked Axel Shultz rated in 1995 to fine him
$125,000 and put him on six months probation during which he cannot
appear in the dressing rooms, at the weigh-ins, or in the ring of
any fights promoted by his company.
</P>
<P>
   While that penalty is small potatoes, somewhere Don King is
cackling. King is Arum's longtime adversary, a man Arum often has
accused of all manner of nefarious deeds. So has the federal
government on four occasions, even naming King as an unindicted
co-conspirator in the Lee case. Yet not once has it gotten a
conviction on King for anything involving boxing's shady dealings,
so Arum is now one up (or is it down?) on his rival in the matter
of boxing convictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't never admit to nothing,'' King said recently about
Arum's decision to testify. ``Imagine what would have happened to
me if I got on the witness stand and admitted to such things. I
would have been drawn and quartered. They would have run me up the
yardarm. I would have been made to walk the plank. I would be in
shackles. I didn't do anything. But I guess Bob Arum did.''
</P>
<P>
   In boxing's convoluted logic, he did. He paid bribes, according
to the Nevada Athletic Commission, to a man a federal jury said
accepted no bribes. If that's not the essence of boxing's sad state
today, nothing is.
</P>
<P>
   Arum was contrite when he was first penalized but he became
irate 24 hours later when he learned that Lee had walked.
</P>
<P>
   At the time Arum was fined, his attorney, Judd Burstein, said,
``He wears his admission as a badge of honor.'' Then Lee got off on
27 of the 33 counts against him, and that badge was sticking in
Arum's craw.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't figure out why I'm the only promoter who has gone
before the commission,'' Arum said. ``I think that's despicable
picking out the only promoter who is based in Nevada and throwing
him into this without having taken action against anybody (else). I
am chagrined.''
</P>
<P>
   He was also hot, claiming King should be dragged in on the
rejected testimony of others even though he'd had the common sense
never to admit to anything, a fact that makes one wonder which of
these two guys actually graduated from Harvard Law School in the
first place.
</P>
<P>
   What the commission did was hang Arum with his own words. What
the jury did was let Lee walk despite hearing his words and seeing
the result of his deeds, especially that damning moment when
Beavers hauled a wad of bills out of his sock and delivered it to
Lee for a supposedly arranged rating. Obviously this was a jury of
people who don't carry wallets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem is, Mr. Arum admits to wrongdoing in which a jury
found that no one was guilty,'' said new Nevada commissioner Flip
Homansky, a longtime commission doctor. ``That part of it doesn't
make sense. I don't believe this verdict will reassure the American
public that all is well in boxing.''
</P>
<P>
   Really?
</P>
<P>
   Fellow commissioner Luther Mack said he was shocked when he
heard the verdict, forgetting that America has become a country
where no one is guilty of anything regardless of his or her deeds.
It has become a place where all too often the jury system no longer
works. It has become a place where boxing's way of doing business
can thrive.
</P>
<P>
   Don King knew that all along. Apparently Bob Arum forgot it for
a moment and so was penalized for the one thing they seem to hate
in boxing these days: telling the truth.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   New Jersey's attempt to use majority rule scoring didn't take
long to explode in controversy. The idea is the three judges score
the fight but a master card is also kept in which the high and low
is thrown out and one score is kept. Last week, Vivian Harris
fought Ivan Robinson and won on the cards of all three judges, but
because he was penalized one point for too often having his
mouthpiece knocked out (honest), the master sheet had the fight a
draw. That Robinson is a Philadelphia fighter long rumored to have
friends among the judges on the New Jersey commission only served
to make the decision appear more suspect. ``That's boxing,''
Robinson said. No, that's ridiculous. It's also, in the opinion of
veteran trainer and TV fight analyst Teddy Atlas, something worse.
``It's just another way to steal a fight from a guy,'' Atlas said.
``This is a corrupt business we're in here.'' . . . Showtime has a
major show Oct. 20 in Detroit if Mike Tyson and Andrew Golota meet
as planned. If the final details are worked out, it will be the
kind of fight that creates interest, because between them Tyson and
Golota have rewritten the Marquis of Queensbury rules. Tyson twice
bit Evander Holyfield, hit Orlin Norris after the bell, tried to
break Frans Botha's arm, hit Lou Savarese when the fight already
had been stopped, and has made a living hitting after the bell.
Golota, known as the Foul Pole in boxing circles, hit Riddick Bowe
with so many low blows that he was disqualified in both of their
fights, bit Samson Po'uha in the chest, and head butted Danell
Nicholson. They won't need a referee for that fight. They'll need a
SWAT team . . . The deal has been made for Lennox Lewis to defend
his title against David Tua in November, with Tua earning a minimum
of $3.5 million plus an upside on pay-per-view sales. Tua is 37-1
with 32 KOs, and many believe he has a big puncher's chance despite
his lack of height. A lack of height is not to be confused with a
lack of size. When Tua turned pro eight years ago, he weighed 190.
Today the massive Samoan, who now lives in New Zealand, weighs 243
. . . Speaking of Tua, he had a bad time of it recently when he
took a dealer's Mercedes SUV and stopped at a convenience store in
Auckland to get a pack of gum. When he came out, the car had been
stolen. ``Give the thief credit,'' Tua said. ``He stole it faster
than it took me to knock out John Ruiz, and that was only 19
seconds.'' The car was recovered 90 minutes later . . . King was
circulating a 1983 Ring magazine article in which Arum admitted to
bribing World Boxing Association officials before a fight involving
Ray Mancini and Art Frias. Arum now says that was a
misunderstanding _ it was really a loan. Sure it was . . .
Heavyweight Michael Grant has spoken with Eddie Mustafa Muhammad,
Tommy Brooks, and Atlas about taking over his training. Atlas
already has refused, and veteran trainer Don Turner was told last
week by Jim Thomas, Grant's attorney, that he will remain as head
trainer. Turner is not so sure . . . HBO has a potentially
entertaining show Sept. 2 matching Erik Morales against former
world champion Kevin Kelley for the interim World Boxing Council
featherweight title. Originally, champion Guty Espadas was supposed
to defend his title against Morales but broke his collarbone in
training. On the same card, IBF-IBA junior lightweight champion
Diego Corrales defends his title against somewhat shopworn but
still competitive Angel Manfredy . . . Brazil's first world
champion in 24 years, World Boxing Organization junior lightweight
champion Acelino Freitas, defends his title Sept. 23 vs. an
opponent yet to be named, which is the same as saying somebody not
very formidable. Freitas is 26-0 with 26 KOs, which is why it's
difficult to get volunteers to get in with him . . . Here's Prince
Naseem Hamed's assessment of how the United States has accepted
Lewis, the WBC-IBF heavyweight champion: ``I don't think Lennox has
gotten the credit from the American press, but I think the whole
world knows Lewis is the best heavyweight on earth. He beat
Holyfield twice, the guy that beat Tyson twice. I think he's
getting his credit in America. Everyone knew in America the night
he got robbed against Holyfield when he drew.'' . . . HBO's ``KO
Nation'' series has a good card set for Sept. 9, with heavyweight
prospect Clifford Etienne (17-0, 12 KOs) testing himself for the
North American Boxing Federation title against Orlin Norris (50-6,
27 KOs). The second fight is a rematch between Bronko McKart (42-2,
29 KOs) and Winky Wright (39-3, 24 KOs). In their first meeting, in
1996, Wright won the WBO title on a split decision. McKart has won
14 straight since and wants revenge . . . Aside to the
Massachusetts Boxing Commission's incompetent commissioners: How
could you let a cop with one professional fight get in the ring
with Peter McNeeley, who had 50, and call yourselves protectors of
the public trust? If Gov. Paul Cellucci or his underlings were
paying attention _ which they're not _ they'd clean house and start
over again before there's a tragedy in the ring. When a disaster
occurs, Cellucci will call for reforms, heads will roll, and new
people will be put in charge. But it will be much too late to help
the guy who gets hurt, won't it?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
