<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-YANKEES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS' COOPER ROCKED BY YANKEES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If the New York Yankees had a hangover after watching
the Anaheim Angels rally from a five-run deficit in the ninth
inning Friday night, they didn't show it. In fact, by the time
Saturday's game was over, it was Angels pitcher Brian Cooper whose
head was spinning.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees jumped on Cooper for four runs in the first inning
and cruised to a 9-1 victory before 49,491 at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Yankees starter Andy Pettitte was the antithesis of Cooper,
throwing a complete-game five-hitter. The only run he allowed came
on Troy Glaus' eighth-inning homer, his 36th of the season.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels' 9-8, 11-inning win Friday marked only the second
time in Yankees history they lost a game at home which they led by
five runs or more in the ninth inning. The previous time happened
exactly 47 years previously - on Aug. 18, 1953, when the Yankees
took the same 8-3 lead into the ninth but lost to the Washington
Senators 10-8.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper was making his first start since a stint at Triple-A
Edmonton, where he went to correct his mechanics, but showed he
still has work to do. He gave up eight runs (six earned) and 11
hits in four innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm getting frustrated,'' Cooper admitted. ``I'm going out
there still confident I can get outs. I just can't throw the ball
where I want it to go. It's frustrating having guys set up for a
certain pitch and not being able to throw it where you want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Because the Angels have an off-day Thursday, they won't need a
fifth starter until Aug. 29. That means Cooper likely will be
headed back to Edmonton so the Angels can call up a reliever to
give the bullpen a boost.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Cooper was far from sharp, he didn't get much help
from his defense, particularly left fielder Ron Gant, who made two
errors - one physical and one mental - in the Yankees' three-run
third inning. In that inning, the Yankees tied a major-league
record with three sacrifice flies.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, three.
</P>
<P>
   With runners on second and third and nobody out, Jorge Posada
hit a slicing line drive to Gant in left. Gant got his glove on the
ball but dropped it for an error. Posada reached second and was
credited with a sacrifice fly. Tino Martinez went from second to
third.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Brosius followed with the second sacrifice fly of the
inning, hitting a fly ball to Gant in left for the first out, as
Martinez tagged from third.
</P>
<P>
   Clay Bellinger then hit yet another fly ball to left, and this
one drove Gant back to the warning track. But after making the
catch, Gant casually looked over his shoulder and slowly backed
into the wall. Meanwhile, Posada took off from second and raced
home as the relay to the plate came too late.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no excuses,'' Gant said. ``I thought there were
three outs. Even my son, who's 5 years old, he knows how many outs
there are. It's just a stupid mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   With a 7-0 lead, the game was in Pettitte's hands. He gave up
three hits through seven innings before Glaus' two-out homer to
right-center in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   The home run was the Angels' 193rd of the season, setting a
franchise record and tying Glaus with Don Baylor (1979) for the
fourth most in a single season in Angels history. Reggie Jackson
(39 in `82) holds the record and Bobby Bonds (37 in `77) and Leon
Wagner (37 in `62) are tied for second.
</P>
<P>
   It was little consolation for the Angels, who fell to 2-3 on the
current trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dug a hole for ourselves,'' Scioscia said. ``We helped them
a little bit, but they just pounded the ball. They kicked our butt.
We'll just have to crumple this one up and throw it away.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees showed the best cure for a hangover is to play well
the next day.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were fine,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said of his
players. ``When I came in this morning, Tino looked at me and said,
`How do you feel today, skip?` There was a lot of concern on
everybody's faces but you get through it. You hate to lose games
that you should win, but you're going to win some games that you
probably shouldn't. You can't dwell on it, there's too much
baseball to play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
