<HEADLINE>
WEIS OFFENSE MAY BE WORTH WAIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The Patriots are 0 for the past 41 years, so
it is understandable that there is pessimism about them, especially
their offense. Perhaps this will be a year in which the offense
struggles, but keep in mind that there's a history when it comes to
Patriots/Jets offenses that Charlie Weis has had a hand in. The
pattern is that they start slowly, then build to the point where
they can get pretty explosive.
</P>
<P>
   Example 1: The 1998 Jets. Weis, the offensive coordinator, was
in the thick of a quarterback controversy in camp. Glenn Foley was
being pushed by Vinny Testaverde, Foley got hurt, Testaverde
stepped in, and you know the rest. But the Jets started 0-2. The
offense didn't look good. In fact, Curtis Martin started his Jets
career with 116 yards in two games, and in those games, only two
receptions were made by tight ends, as 84 of 99 pass plays were
directed toward Wayne Chrebet or Keyshawn Johnson. But on Sept. 21,
the offense had a breakthrough game against Indianapolis. Weis
spread out the offense, often using three-receiver sets that Martin
ran out of, exploding for 144 yards on 23 carries. The Jets amassed
505 yards (302 rushing), their largest output in 10 years. Leon
Johnson, the third-down back, scored three touchdowns, including an
82-yard screen pass from Testaverde, who made his first start and
tossed four scoring passes. Weis had Johnson run on the Colts'
substitute packages. Martin told his offensive line before the
game, ``Get me to the line of scrimmage and I'll do the rest.'' The
Jets went on to win 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   Example 2: The 1996 Patriots. Again, the team started 0-2. Weis
was coaching receivers at the time. The Patriots didn't have
first-rounder Terry Glenn on the field for the opener, a 24-14
drubbing by the Dolphins. ``We got whipped very, very soundly,''
said then-coach Bill Parcells. ``And I know it wasn't our best. I
told the players, if it was, we're in trouble.'' Bledsoe completed
only 50 percent of his passes, Martin ran for only 23 yards, Shawn
Jefferson fumbled twice and was carried off the field with a
concussion. Bledsoe's first shotgun pass was intercepted. In Week 2
vs. Buffalo, the Patriots lost, 17-10, despite starting seven of
their first 11 possessions at their 40 or beyond, a result of
excellent play by the defense of Al Groh and Bill Belichick.
Bledsoe was 21 of 46 for 210 yards and was sacked four times. After
the game Parcells said, ``I think there's something we can build on
here.'' Sure enough, the Patriots squashed the Arizona Cardinals,
31-0, the following week, the big play an emphatic fourth-down
keeper by Bledsoe that kept a scoring drive alive with 41 seconds
remaining in the half. The Patriots went 11-3 the rest of the
season and reached the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   Example 3: The 1994 Patriots. A pitiful team and pitiful offense
finally blossomed when Bledsoe led a miraculous come-from-behind
victory over the Vikings, the start of a seven-game win streak that
led to a playoff game against Belichick's Cleveland Browns. Weis
was the tight ends coach during this offensive spurt, in which
Bledsoe first discovered that Ben Coates could get him out of a lot
of bad situations. Coates caught 96 passes that season, an NFL
record for tight ends.
</P>
<P>
   Example 4: The 1999 Jets. After going through three
quarterbacks, the Jets settled on Ray Lucas, and the result was a
6-2 second half in which the offense really found itself. Though
Weis had some play-calling duties taken away by Parcells, he was
still running the offense and made it work after a horrendous start
that was due in large part to Testaverde getting injured.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people have to be patient, because it's a new system
we're getting used to and we don't have all of our people in place
yet,'' said Glenn. ``Charlie has a great offense, and once we start
showing everything, I think people will think a little differently.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now it's preseason and we're not showing everything.
We're still trying to get our offensive line in order and trying to
see who's going to start at running back. I think we have the
people in place that could make this work. I know the players are
excited about it, and pretty soon the fans will see.''
</P>
<P>
   Glenn, of course, is one of the most vital parts of the offense.
He'll be on the field with Troy Brown a lot, the idea being that
defenses won't be able to double-team Glenn much.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, the Patriots don't have the pieces they had in '96.
Coates was in his prime, as were Martin and Bruce Armstrong, and
the younger offensive linemen such as Dave Wohlabaugh, Todd Rucci,
and Max Lane meshed well with old-timer William Roberts. Lane,
Rucci, and Armstrong often look back to those days and see no
reason why they can't be revisited. When injuries heal and everyone
is playing together again, maybe we'll see the pattern develop
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe the fans and the media aren't that confident, but the
players are,'' said Brown. ``I think we can move the ball and be
exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   Weis is also known for his trickery, something the Patriots
haven't shown in preseason, except for a perfectly executed reverse
by Brown. There appears to be time to see whether rookie J.R.
Redmond can be the next Martin.
</P>
<P>
   You've waited 41 years; what's another few weeks?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Two good Boston College stories: quarterbacks Mark Hartsell and
Matt Hasselbeck. Hartsell, who was the starter for Dan Henning for
two years at BC, never got drafted and was cut twice by the
Redskins in training camp. He hadn't played since training camp of
1997, settling in as a salesman for Astra Zenica, a pharmaceutical
firm, and living in Bridgewater with his wife, Jennifer. ``I was at
a national sales meeting,'' said Hartsell, ``and I get a call and
it's (Bears offensive coordinator) Gary Crowton, who had been my
quarterback coach at BC. I hadn't talked to Gary since 1993, though
I'd tried to contact him when he was up in New England interviewing
for the head coaching job. He wondered if I wanted to come to
Chicago for a one-day tryout. I said, `Why not?' '' The
6-foot-5-inch Hartsell weighed about 240 at the time, so Crowton
told him to get his weight down and he'd buy some time. A few weeks
later, said Hartsell, ``I had lost some weight but not all of it
and while I was running the 40-yard dash, I popped my hamstring. I
had to continue the workout with a bad hammy. My leg was dead.'' He
went home feeling he'd never get called back. But he did. He was
invited to camp, signed to a contract, and has performed well
beyond expectations. In the Bears' exhibition opener against the
New York Giants, he was 8 of 9 for 70 yards and a touchdown. ``I
want to make this team more than anything,'' said Hartsell. ``I
love it here. It's funny, it's all about being in the right place
at the right time. We have four very good quarterbacks here, so
it's going to be tough.'' He's whittled his weight to 213 and
thinks he would take a practice squad job if it came down to that.
Hartsell, 26, is trying to live out his dream and hopes to make the
six months away from his wife worth the time lost. ``I couldn't
have done this without Jennifer's support,'' he said. ``I started
doing this in March and I left her behind. And she's been so
supportive.'' The Bears will go with Cade McNown as the starter,
with Jim Miller behind him. Shane Matthews has become major trade
bait and is among the most sought-after quarterbacks in the league.
That could leave Hartsell the No. 3 job. ``I know the longer I'm
around, the better I'll get,'' he said. ``It's a great offense, and
I think I can run it well.'' . . . Story 2: Brett Favre is expected
back for the regular season _ doctors said the tendinitis in his
right elbow will subside _ and the Packers weren't worried anyway
because they feel they may have one of the league's best backups
and rising stars in Hasselbeck. The Packers have resisted trade
offers of No. 1 picks for Hasselbeck, who was the top-rated passer
in the NFL in last year's exhibition season and is on his way to
achieving that distinction again. An interesting story is the
relationship between Hasselbeck and Packers executive Andrew
Brandt. Just two years ago, Brandt was an agent representing
Hasselbeck; now Brandt is negotiating on the other side of the
table. ``It's a little different,'' said Brandt, the Packers' chief
negotiator. ``I used to see Matt about twice a year when I
represented him, and now I see him every day. He's building a house
about two doors down from me, so it's been a nice situation,
especially having the chance to watch him develop into the
quarterback he's becoming. I'm just thrilled to be witnessing that
progress.'' Brandt recalls when the Packers had a dilemma about
whether to put him on their active roster or allow another team to
take him off their practice squad. The Packers chose to activate
him. ``That proved to be quite a decision,'' said Brandt. Because
of Hasselbeck's limited service time, he fits into a certain salary
slot, so there have been no contract hassles yet, but Brandt said
of his contract, ``We sweetened it a little.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   One of the feel-good stories in NFL camps was that of
30-year-old rookie Gerald Vaughn of the New Orleans Saints. The
6-3, 207-pound safety out of Ole Miss played seven years in the
Canadian Football League before getting his NFL shot. Vaughn still
makes rookie mistakes, but he has caught coach Jim Haslett's eye
and it appears he'll make the team. Vaughn played against Emmitt
Smith when Smith was starring at Florida and against Alvin Harper,
who went to Tennessee. Harper is now out of football, Smith's
career is on the downside, and Vaughn is just beginning . . .
Patriots fifth-round pick Dave Stachelski was on the field
practicing in New Orleans at the end of the week. That's something
he barely did in New England. Stachelski denied that he was
homesick during his time in New England, saying, ``I wanted to be
there and play, but things just didn't work out.'' They sure
didn't. But Stachelski is a pretty talented player, the eighth
tight end to participate in Saints camp. With starter Cam Cleeland
out for most of the year with an injured Achilles' tendon,
Stachelski has a chance of sticking . . . As outrageous as it was
for the Redskins to charge $10 to park and $10 admission, they said
they lost $1.1 million in training camp. The team drew about 3,000
fans per day during the week and up to 7,000 on weekends. The
Redskins also sold souvenirs and food . . . The Redskins have a
plethora of running backs, and after a story surfaced that the Jets
were looking to trade for Skip Hicks to back up Martin, the
Redskins issued a statement saying that he was not available. The
Redskins also have Stephen Davis, Adrian Murrell, and a
terrific-looking runner in Chad Dukes, who at 6-3, 240 can pound
the ball. Dukes is out with a sprained ankle, but if he's let
loose, teams will line up to obtain him . . . Funny how things work
out. When Buddy Ryan was fired as Philadelphia head coach after the
1991 season, Jeff Fisher, the defensive coordinator at the time,
was overlooked because he was only 32. The Eagles instead hired
Rich Kotite . . . It would cost about $385.4 million to refurbish
the Metrodome in Minneapolis. The Vikings need to have it done,
though, if they are to remain in Minneapolis for the foreseeable
future. Gov. Jesse Ventura, the former pro wrestler, is on record
as saying he is not in favor of public money for sports stadiums .
. . There is a little bad blood between Browns teammates Errict
Rhett, the veteran running back, and safety Marquis Smith. The two
have had a few altercations in camp, and last week Smith's
helmet-first tackle opened a four-stitch cut on Rhett's face. Rhett
left his bloody jersey in Smith's locker with a note saying,
``Payback is coming.'' Rhett said, ``I hope he hits the other team
like that instead of me all the time.'' . . . Dallas will go with
kicker Tim Sedar, who as recently as last spring was teaching at
Lucas High in Mansfield, Ohio. Sedar set records at Ashland (Ohio)
University two years ago but didn't get a shot at the pro game. He
kept kicking as he coached football at Lucas High, and it became
evident that he was kicking even better than he had in college. He
got a tryout with the Cowboys and won the job . . . Arena Football
League quarterback alert: The Cowboys have signed Charlie Puleri
after veteran backup Paul Justin came up with a sore elbow . . .
Looking for a defensive end? It's easily the scarcest position out
there. Veteran Neil Smith, former Patriot Ferric Collons, and
former 49ers Roy Barker and Gabe Wilkins are the best of the
remaining lot. The Patriots have even contacted Mike Jones, who
played for them in the mid '90s . . . Look for the Vikings to cut
veteran end Fernando Smith before camp ends . . . Why is it that
kickers drafted in the first round seem to get into trouble? The
trials and tribulations of Raiders draftee Sebastian Janikowski
have been well-chronicled this year, and now we hear that the last
first-round kicker, Russell Erxleben (in 1979, to New Orleans via
Texas), was sentenced to six months in prison for bilking investors
out of $34 million. He was charged with conspiracy securities fraud
. . . Former Patriots tight end Russ Francis, who is running for
Congress in Hawaii, was fined $1,000 for campaign funding
violations . . . The 49ers don't have many veterans left, but the
ones remaining are dropping like flies. Center Chris Dalman's
career might be over because of disk problems in his neck. He may
need surgery.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Though receiver Dane Looker was having a good camp in St. Louis,
the consensus among Rams personnel was that he would have been
released, so they were thrilled when the Patriots came calling,
offering a sixth-round pick (contingent on Looker making the New
England roster). It was an odd move for the Patriots, considering
that scouts have Sean Morey with much better speed in the 40. Morey
and Looker may battle for the final receiver spot, but Morey has
the edge because of his special teams play . . . An evaluation by
NFL scouts of the last five drafts had the Patriots ranked
surprisingly high at 10th. The scouts rated Chris Canty the biggest
bust and Ted Johnson the best hit . . . In his forthcoming book,
``The Final Season,'' Parcells speaks glowingly of Martin and Mike
Holmgren. On Martin: ``He has 6,300 yards for his five-year career,
so he has averaged better than 1,200 yards per season. I'm not
saying he's the best in the league, but I mean this with all my
heart: I'll take him over any back in the league, and you can have
the rest.'' On Holmgren: ``Mike Holmgren is one of the best coaches
in the game. When you play him or one of his teams, whether it's
Green Bay or Seattle, it's a chess match. He has a great knack for
substituting his players. He loves to conceal what he's going to
do. He changes what he does game by game with his personnel
substitutions. His pattern can be erratic, and defensively you just
have to hang with him because sooner or later you will discover
just what he's trying to do. When you're coaching against him, you
hope it's sooner rather than later.'' . . . Charlie Casserly, GM of
the new Houston franchise, gave a thumbs-up to the movie ``The
Replacements,'' based on Washington's 1987 replacement team, which
went 3-0 and helped pave the way for the Redskins to win the Super
Bowl. ``I thought it was the best football movie ever,'' said
Casserly. ``In a four-star system, I'd give it five stars. A lot of
what we went through during that period was on the screen. In one
scene, a (striking) player cracks a window on a bus (carrying the
replacements). That actually happened, except one of our defensive
linemen (Darryl Grant) actually stood in front of the bus and
forced it to stop and then smashed the window.'' . . . Rob Morris
of Brigham Young is the Colts' middle linebacker of the future, but
he has struggled with early assignments and for now he's seen as
backing up veteran Dwight Hollier. ``I'm not at the point where I
want to be yet, but I'm not sure anybody else is, either,'' said
Morris. ``I've just got to keep thinking, keep reacting, keep
studying film. I think it will come.'' . . . There is still much
shock in the scouting world that Alabama defensive lineman Reggie
Grimes has fit in so well with the Patriots. Said one scout, ``Our
team didn't even have him on the board, anywhere. We saw him and
didn't think much of him. Alabama rotated their defensive front,
and there was nothing we saw. If the Patriots are getting benefits,
that's a great scouting job on their part.'' . . . Gilbert Brown,
the often-heavy defensive tackle who has been on the free agent
market, is currently in Green Bay but has not made contact with
Packer officials about playing for them. Brown spent much of the
offseason at a weight reduction clinic at Duke University, but
there is speculation he may have put some weight back on.
</P>
</TEXT>
