<SLUG> BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALLISON WILL HAVE STRONG HAND IN LEADERSHIP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The 8-inch scar that runs down his forearm is reminder
enough for Jason Allison that it's time to get back to the ice.
When he pulls on his uniform for the Bruins' first regular-season
game this October, the center will have gone nine months without
putting stick to puck in a game that counts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've thought about that,'' said Allison, sipping a cup of
coffee last week following a morning workout. ``I'm getting antsy.
I've pretty much had it with this workout stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   For those who might have nodded off while waiting outside the
emergency room during the Bruins' 1999-2000 season, Allison played
his last game Jan. 8. Four days later, he underwent surgery to
repair ligament damage in his left thumb. On Feb. 16, his season
was declared done when his right wrist had to be repaired, an
operation that required a ligament to be transplanted from under
his right forearm.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all good _ I don't foresee any problems,'' said Allison,
who is perhaps the biggest key to Boston's hopes for returning to
the playoffs after missing twice in the last four seasons. ``I'll
be ready. And if it gets sore during faceoffs, then I'll have to
make some adjustments. But I'm expecting it to be OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Without Allison in the middle, dishing the puck and scoring
goals, the Boston offense went from faltering to fatal. About 90
days after Allison's last game, Ray Bourque was dealt to Colorado,
the official end to the season and a symbolic shift in how the club
will go forward.
</P>
<P>
   Among the first orders of business when the Bruins reconvene
after Labor Day will be coach Pat Burns's selection of a captain.
Don Sweeney, recently signed to a new three-year deal, is the
likeliest candidate. The 12-year veteran is very much respected and
may be the only Bruin who played up to expectations last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The captain's important, obviously,'' said Allison, ``but
we've got the kind of team that will need five or six guys out
there leading, filling Ray's shoes. We've got to have our core guys
leading. Don Sweeney and Paul Coffey will carry some of that load.
But it's got to be a bunch of us _ me, Byron (Dafoe), Joe
(Thornton), AC (Anson Carter), Kyle (McLaren), even guys like Hal
(Gill) and P.J. (Axelsson). It's not going to be one definitive
person. It's got to be a group thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Allison likes the leadership role. His draft year, 1993, the
Capitals made him the 17th pick, but he returned to juniors
(London) and had the most prolific season of his career (55 goals,
142 points).
</P>
<P>
   Repeatedly making the point that he would never lobby for
captaincy, and responding to the issue only because he was asked,
Allison said being made a captain in juniors brought out the best
in him.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just feel better on the ice,'' he recalled. ``For me, I
don't know how to describe it, but it makes you feel important _
and it makes you feel the pressure to go out there and do well. You
want to play good every night. And I know from a couple of years
ago (a first-round playoff win over Carolina), the captain's job _
along with other guys _ will be to get the guys on the team
together more. We had a tight bunch of guys that year, and we lost
a little of that. We've got to do better.''
</P>
<P>
   From high up in the press box last season, the Black 'n' Gold
crumbling at his feet, assistant general manager Mike O'Connell
looked down at Boston's ragged, disjointed play and stated, ``We
are not a team.'' It was the most telling admission of the season
by the front office.
</P>
<P>
   The club that convenes at training camp next month will have a
great number of new faces, starting with free agent signees Coffey,
Andrei Kovalenko, and Peter Popovic. Getting back some of that good
team feeling that was a trademark of Bruins teams in the '70s and
'80s, and seemingly so essential to their success, will have to be
one of the missions of the new guy with the ``C.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Being an NHL captain is a great thing,'' said the 25-year-old
Allison, about the same age now as when Bourque took over the
captaincy. ``But regardless of who it is, I don't think it should
change the idea of leadership much. All of us have to do it.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Matt Zultek doesn't figure prominently in
Boston's plans for the upcoming season. But the 6-foot-4-inch,
225-pound left winger would like that to change, and is considering
coming to training camp even if he can't come to contract terms
with the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to have a contract, just to take some of the pressure
off,'' said Zultek, whose agent is Larry Kelly. ``But would I come
without one? Yeah, probably, because the last couple of years have
been disappointing, and I'd like to get going.''
</P>
<P>
   Zultek, once a first-round pick of the Kings, has the size and
strength to develop into a power forward. He was hoping to launch
his pro career in last year's training camp, after the Bruins
selected him 56th in the '99 draft, but a bothersome left knee kept
him out of workouts and ultimately led him to the operating room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's see . . . tendinitis, bursitis, and a cyst,'' said
Zultek, recounting what was wrong with the knee. ``The cyst was the
big thing. They didn't even know it was there until they went in,
because on the MRI it only showed up as fluid. But when they got in
there, it was the size of a golf ball _ that's what was causing me
so much pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Zultek has a strong shot and impressive speed for a big man. In
junior workouts with the Ottawa 67s, head coach Brian Kilrea would
bet him that he couldn't win footraces against the rest of the
club. Zultek never lost a bet. Over the summer, he has continued to
work diligently on his legs, hoping to improve on his speed from a
dead start.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to give him the business,'' said Bruins longtime scout
Bob Tindall, who lives near Zultek in Toronto. ``I tell him, `Hey,
Matt, you could be a millionaire.' Because the league is always
looking for that proverbial power forward, and he's got that size.
He needs to work on his meanness for that to happen. That doesn't
mean he has to be a goon out there. But look at how some of the big
guys out there (example: John LeClair) use their body to their
advantage. He's got to learn some of that.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Within hours of each other last week, Joe Sakic and LeClair
learned their salaries for 2000-01. Just prior to an arbitration
hearing, Sakic signed a one-year deal with Colorado for $7.9
million _ about a 13 percent bump from last year. In Philadelphia,
LeClair's figure was set at $7 million (up from $3.9 million) _ the
largest arbitration award in league history. Both forwards remain
on target to become unrestricted free agents next July. Scuttlebutt
around Philly is that LeClair may be dealt before the start of the
season if the sides can't agree on a long-term pact . . . Jeff
``The Not So Artful'' Odgers will be back for more this season,
filling the pugilist's position for the Minnesota Wild. Hard to
believe it was four years ago that Odgers was swapped here from San
Jose when the Bruins finally gave up on Al ``The Planet'' Iafrate .
. . Former Mount St. Charles (Woonsocket, R.I.) blue liner Mathieu
Schneider signed on with the Kings as a free agent, a deal worth $2
million for the upcoming season and perhaps the 2001-02 season.
Look for Schneider to be paired with big-hitting Rob Blake, and
Mattias Norstrom to be bumped over with Jere Karalahti . . . Bruin
short-timer Randy Robitaille, dealt in the hours following the
Atlanta expansion draft in '99, could see first-line duty in
Nashville with franchise center _ and potential superstar _ David
Legwand, perhaps with Vitali Yachmenev on the opposite wing.
Robitaille proved in Providence that he can score (102 points in
'98-99) but has yet to show any consistent touch or determination
in the NHL . . . Former Boston College Eagle Marty McInnis could be
one of the keys to the Ducks finally being more than a Paul
Kariya-Teemu Selanne sideshow act. GM Pierre Gauthier went out this
summer and added free agent German Titov and drafted 26-year-old
Jonas Ronnqvist. The 30-year-old McInnis likely will be with them
on a No. 3 line. It remains unfathomable that a team with the
firepower of Kariya and Selanne missed the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The assumption around Phoenix is that GM Bobby Smith will be out
of work immediately after Wayne Gretzky's ownership group formally
takes over the Desert Dogs, perhaps before training camp.
Meanwhile, the Great One, whose job title will be director of
hockey operations (perhaps with agent Mike Barnett hired away from
IMG to be GM), is talking openly about his intention to bring in
Claude Lemieux as a free agent _ with the likes of Detroit and
Dallas, among others, also pursuing the 35-year-old Prince of
Nastiness . . . Ex-Boston University defenseman Scott Lachance
didn't get the required $1.3 million qualifying offer from the
Canadiens to keep him in Montreal, allowing him to shop for a new
home as an unrestricted free agent at only age 27 (four years under
the standard trigger date). The 6-1 Lachance, the No. 4 pick
overall in the '91 draft (Islanders), landed last week in
Vancouver, where he'll join a blue line corps that includes Ed
Jovanovski, Mattias Ohlund, Adrian Aucoin, Murray Baron, Jason
Strudwick, and ex-Bruin Greg Hawgood . . . Columbus is the first
NHL franchise to have its practice facility adjacent to its home
rink (Nationwide Arena). The ``Wide'' still isn't complete, but is
sure to receive architectural kudos. The design includes two large
``eye'' windows that provide glimpses of the Columbus skyline . . .
Set your VCR for daytime TV Aug. 31. NHLers Scott Gomez, Jeremy
Roenick, Sheldon Souray, Chris Therien, and Kevin Weekes will be
seen that day on ``One Life to Live.'' No truth to the rumor that
referee Don Koharski declined a cameo role as the manager of a
Dunkin' Donuts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
