<HEADLINE>
HELTON WITHIN REACH OF .400 PLATEAU 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The question, until he heats up again, is no longer:
Can Nomar do it?
</P>
<P>
   Now it is: Can a football player do it?
</P>
<P>
   Colorado Rockies first baseman Todd Helton, the former
University of Tennessee quarterback who was drafted by the Rockies
in 1995 (one year after the Sox took Nomar Garciaparra), took a
.399 batting average into Saturday &UR;  &LR; night, the latest anyone has
hit that high since George Brett was batting .400 on Sept. 20 in
1980. Brett, incidentally, played in just 117 games that season and
had just 449 at-bats, a total Helton will pass by the end of the
month.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Garciaparra, Helton bats lefthanded, the same as the last
player in the American League (Ted Williams, 1941) and the last
player in the National League (Bill Terry, Giants, 1930) to hit
.400.
</P>
<P>
   And while many say Garciaparra has a home-field advantage at
Fenway Park, where he was batting .403 entering the weekend, Helton
may have the ultimate home-field advantage in mile-high Coors
Field. Helton, who turns 27 Sunday and is in his third full season
in the big leagues, was hitting .439 (93 for 212) at Coors Field
entering Saturday &UR;  &LR; night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear a lot about that from (the national media),'' Helton
told reporters last week. ``It's just something else I have to deal
with, but what am I supposed to do about it? It's a great ballpark.
We've got great fans. I'm supposed to apologize for that? A lot of
guys hit better at home than they do on the road. What about all
the hitters over the years in Boston?''
</P>
<P>
   Garciaparra, of course, is turning that argument inside out.
Fenway is supposed to be a boon to lefthanded hitters, but
Garciaparra hit .378 at home last season and has bettered that so
far this season.
</P>
<P>
   Coors Field, with its wide-open spaces and altitude
enhancements, is kind to both lefties and righties. Last season,
the Rockies hit .328 at home, .249 on the road. Their opponents hit
.329 at Coors, .271 in their home parks. Colorado's lefthanded
hitters hit .356 at Coors, righties .308.
</P>
<P>
   Here's why Helton, who was hitting .554 (36 for 65) in August to
Garciaparra's .270 (17 for 63), may live up to the ``Toddy
Ballgame'' handle given him by Denver Post columnist Woody Paige.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five of the Rockies' last 45 games are at Coors,
including 10 of their last 13. But to attribute it all to a
home-field advantage is ludicrous. Helton put himself in position
to make this bid with a phenomenal nine-game stretch in which he
went 19 for 29 on the road.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ted Williams is my all-time idol,'' said Paul Ricciarini, the
Houston coordinator of pro scouting who has seen Helton since he
played in the Cape Cod League.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't collect autographs, and the only two people I would
ask for one from are Ted Williams and Tiger Woods, so it's tough
for me to be objective.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Helton is such a marvelous talent and keeps himself under
control so well, shows such great poise at the plate _ just like
Ted. So can he do it? It's mind-boggling to imagine, but gosh darn
it, I'd have to say he has a good shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Some believe that the Rockies essentially being out of
contention will work in Helton's favor. Ricciarini believes
otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a team is playing poorly, it's easy to pitch around a guy
like Helton,'' Ricciarini said. ``And with Jeff Cirillo out of the
lineup because he's hurt, it'll be easier to pitch around him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's also some question of whether he'll put pressure on
himself. I don't see that as a factor. This is a tremendous star in
the making.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go back to the Cape with the kid. He didn't hit many home
runs, but you could see he had all the requirements of a good major
league hitter. There have been a lot of guys who didn't home runs
in the Cape but all made contact, who went on to become power
hitters: Jeff Bagwell, Mo Vaughn, Frank Thomas, Albert Belle.
</P>
<P>
   ``You could see that Todd was so athletic, a very instinctive
player, a very mature hitter, a solid guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Helton was drafted eighth overall in 1995, the same draft that a
kicker from Nebraska, Darin Erstad, went No. 1 overall to the
Angels. Erstad, of course, is taking aim at George Sisler's
all-time hit record of 257, set in 1920.
</P>
<P>
   Among the players taken ahead of Helton were Padres catcher Ben
Davis, so far a disappointment; Jose Cruz Jr., who was traded by
the Mariners to the Blue Jays; Cubs pitcher Kerry Wood, who has had
flashes of brilliance between injuries; high schooler Jaime Jones,
a bust for the Marlins; and Cuban pitcher Ariel Prieto, who has
been hurt for the A's.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had the reputation of being a tough sign, because of the
football thing and the money,'' Ricciarini said. ``But it was a
very astute draft by the Rockies.''
</P>
<P>
   It could become a historic one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The US Olympic baseball selection committee, which on Wednesday
will announce its picks to represent the country in Sydney next
month, will load its squad with mostly ``4-A'' types: experienced
minor leaguers considered not quite good enough for the big
leagues. Many top prospects won't be going to Australia because
their major league teams intend to call them up in September.
Former big leaguer Tim Raines, who is playing in the independent
Atlantic League, is a good bet to go. Slugger Ozzie Canseco, who
has 37 home runs for his independent league team, is expected to be
passed over. The committee had great interest in Morgan Burkhart _
and wouldn't NBC have loved the story of the Frontier League
legend? _ but got word from Dan Duquette that Burkhart probably
will be back on the big club when rosters expand Sept. 1. The
committee also had interest in Dernell Stenson, but he's out of the
picture for the same reason. Steve Lomasney's name came up early,
but according to one committee source, he was dropped from the list
because the Sox hedged on whether he'd be promoted. Lomasney's
ongoing hamstring problems _ he reaggravated the injury last week
but got back in action Saturday _ also would have made his
selection unlikely. Paxton Crawford was discussed, but the
pitcher's tumble from bed KO'd his chances. Still a long shot is
Pawtucket lefty reliever Tim Young, who was up with the Sox earlier
this season. Young's unusual motion may come in handy against
lefthanded hitters in international play. Former Sox farmhand
Curtis Pride, now playing for the Dodgers' Triple A team in
Albuquerque, was another possibility, but his chances faded. Mark
Texeira, the Georgia Tech star who was terrific on the touring US
national team of college players, was expected to have a great shot
at the Olympic club, but likely will be passed over. His lack of
experience with wooden bats was one concern. The Red Sox, who
drafted Texeira out of high school in 1998, are sure to rue their
inability to sign him. He is rated the best collegiate player in
the country entering his junior year . . . The Sox will send six
players to the Arizona Fall League's Phoenix Desert Dogs, a team
that will be managed by former Padres shortstop Garry Templeton:
Lomasney; pitchers Sunny Kim, Sang Lee, Chris Reitsma, and Casey
Fossum; and catcher/infielder Shea Hillenbrand. Lefthander Fossum
is the supplemental first-round pick out of the 1999 draft who
rewrote the Texas A&AMP;M record book and has 124 strikeouts in 153 1/3
innings with Single A Sarasota. Kim and Lomasney both played in the
Fall League last year . . . Pedro Martinez had a special reason to
notice when Mets outfielder Benny Agbayani caught a high fly, then
handed the baseball to a fan in Shea Stadium last Saturday, not
realizing it was only the second out. Martinez was on the mound for
the Expos a few years ago when teammate Larry Walker pulled the
same stunt in Dodger Stadium on an ESPN Sunday night game . . . You
understand, don't you, that Roger Clemens collects $10.3 million
for 2003 whether or not he pitches that season for the Yankees?
Under the terms of his deal, Clemens will receive a $5 million
signing bonus, paid out over the next two years, and salaries of
$7.8 million for 2001 and 2002. By throwing in the third-year
option, the Yanks can say Clemens's deal averages $10.3 million,
well below the $15 million a year the Dodgers gave Kevin Brown.
Clemens, who is 44 wins short of 300, could decline the option,
still collect the dough, and seek a new contract, with the Yankees
or another club. Remember: It's not about the money . . . Big
league clubs would be wise to make copies of the comments Chipper
Jones made after agreeing to his six-year, $90 million deal with
the Braves, as an example of how to become filthy rich and stay
gracious about it. Said Chipper, ``This kind of money is really
unheard of and it's almost embarrassing to talk about. It's not
where I came from. I came from middle class. We had to work hard
for what we got. To have this given to me is a little
overwhelming.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Giants are a season-high 18 games over .500, which has
reinforced Dusty Baker's status as one of the game's most highly
regarded managers. But don't overlook the talent Baker has at his
disposal. ``J.T. Snow is hitting over .300, is going to knock in
100 runs, and is the best-fielding first baseman in the league,''
one executive said. ``Jeff Kent, the second baseman, is doing
things only Rogers Hornsby has ever done. He's knocked in over 100
runs in each of the last four years. Rich Aurilia, the shortstop,
led the league's shortstops in home runs and RBIs last season and
will come close to that this season. Barry Bonds is the player of
the '90s. Dusty calls the center fielder, Marvin Benard, the
second- or third-best leadoff hitter in the league. Ellis Burks,
you know all about him in Boston. A stud. They have two kids
catching (Bobby Estalella, Doug Mirabelli) who aren't costing them
anything and are going to combine for around 25 home runs and 75
RBIs. Then, look at the pitching. Livan Hernandez, former World
Series MVP. Shawn Estes, 19-game winner in 1997. Russ Ortiz,
18-game winner in '99. Kirk Rueter, 32 games over .500. And the
closer, Robb Nen, who in the last three years has more saves than
anybody except Trevor Hoffman. It ain't all magic there. They've
got some talent.'' . . . The White Sox' Big Three of James Baldwin,
Mike Sirotka, and Jim Parque were 27-12 with a 3.95 ERA before the
All-Star break. They were 6-7, 4.99 after the break, entering the
weekend . . . Former Sox outfielder Damon Buford, who went to the
Cubs for Manny Alexander, has made just two errors in center field,
a typical Gold Glove-caliber performance. But Buford, an everyday
player for the first time in his career, is already expected to be
no better than a backup next season, when the Cubs are planning on
an outfield of Rondell White, top prospect Corey Patterson, and
Sammy Sosa. Buford has a career-high 14 home runs, but he also has
97 whiffs and just 36 RBIs. Sosa, incidentally, now says manager
Don Baylor's criticism of his fielding and base-running actually
helped him, a turnabout from the days when Sluggin' Sammy acted
highly offended by Baylor's remarks. Sosa has slimmed down from 236
pounds in spring training to his current 221. ``It's good sometimes
that people say something (negative) about me because that's good
motivation,'' Sosa said. ``I work harder and get better. Maybe I
was a little bit overweight.'' Said Buford: ``It's night and day.
Now he's the prototypical right fielder who makes all the plays.''
. . . Belle, who has a no-trade clause through the 2001 season and
is owed $30 million by Baltimore for the next three seasons, heard
the loudest booing he's heard all season last Wednesday after he
did not run out a double-play grounder and misplayed a ball off the
right-field fence. As Kenny Rosenthal, who just has left the
Baltimore Sun for The Sporting News, reminds us: ``When Cal
(Ripken) retires, the Orioles become Albert's team. How'd you like
to be in charge of that marketing campaign?'' . . . Not to be
missed: ``Summer of Love,'' Jim Callis's terrific piece on the Cape
Cod League in Baseball America, and also on the publication's Web
site (www.baseballamerica.com). BA is an absolute must-read for the
hard-core fan . . . One major league executive said there have been
more waiver claims than ever this season. Yankees GM Brian Cashman
made 48 claims in one day, according to the executive. Many
baseball people still believe that the Yankees really didn't want
Jose Canseco but claimed him so that neither the Mariners nor White
Sox could take him. Canseco already had gone unclaimed by everybody
else. The danger in claiming players is that if the waiving team
doesn't withdraw waivers, you could get stuck with a player you
really don't want. Two years ago, the Padres claimed lefty Randy
Myers so he wouldn't wind up in Atlanta. Myers pitched 14 1/3
innings for the Padres, got hurt, and hasn't thrown a pitch in the
last two years, while collecting $12.25 million . . . Tampa Bay
rookie Aubrey Huff, who two years ago was still at the University
of Miami but Monday night played in Fenway Park against Martinez:
``That felt really good to get a hit against Pedro, and then I'm
there at second base and behind me is Nomar Garciaparra. I'm
looking around and I'm like, `God, this is really happening.' '' .
. . Two of Massachusetts's top high school prospects recently
returned from Long Beach and the Area Code games, a heavily scouted
competition of the nation's best prep talent. Mike Conroy, a
lefthanded-hitting outfielder from BC High, and John Toffey, a
shortstop and righthanded pitcher from St. Sebastian's, were picked
for the team that represented the Eastern seaboard. Toffey is the
son of Boston sports agent Jack Toffey . . . Bob Kurtz, who served
with distinction for eight years in the Red Sox TV booth, is now in
Minneapolis prepping for the first year of a new NHL franchise, the
Wild. But old habits die hard, and you can bet that Kurtz is
keeping up with the Sox on Sportspages.com . . . Matt Kinney lost
his big-league debut to the Blue Jays, 3-2, Friday night, but the
Twins are high on the 23-year-old righthander from Bangor, Maine,
who went from the Sox to the Twinkies in the deal that brought
Boston Orlando Merced and Greg Swindell. Merced was released
without getting a hit for the Sox, while Swindell left after the
'98 season as a free agent. Kinney, meanwhile, had surgery a year
ago for bone chips in his elbow, but went 6-1 with a 2.71 ERA at
Double A New Britain, then was promoted to Triple A Salt Lake,
where he was 5-2 with a 4.25 ERA. Kinney has been working on a
changeup to go with an above-average slider and a 90-94 m.p.h.
fastball. The Twins think they may have a front-line pitcher in the
making . . . Glenallen Hill had seven home runs in his first 38
at-bats with the Yankees, then hit two more Friday night. Yankee
newcomers David Justice, Hill, and Canseco hit 22 home runs in
their first 216 at-bats. The Bombers hit just 100 home runs in
their first 83 games, but had 55 in their first 35 after the break.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
