<HEADLINE>
MERLONI SEES, HITS ALL
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-MERLONI-BOS  (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Psychic friends of the world, Lou Merloni has no use
for you. Palm readers and astrologists, go enlighten someone else.
</P>
<P>
   What can you possibly tell the Red Sox utilityman that he
doesn't already know?
</P>
<P>
   That he is currently in a hitting zone, the kind in which a
check swing turns into an RBI bloop double? That happened in the
third inning of a 9-0 shellacking of the Texas Rangers Saturday.
Merloni's popup just over the head of first baseman Rafael Palmeiro
landed in fair territory, scoring Nomar Garciaparra and sending
Troy O'Leary to third.
</P>
<P>
   He also knows that his current stint in Boston is a stroke of
good fortune. One month ago, Merloni was sitting on bench for the
Yokohama BayStars of the Central League in Japan. He was a pinch
hitter, batting .213 in 42 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not a good time,'' said Merloni, the Framingham
resident who was released by Yokohama and signed by the Red Sox to
a minor league contract July 31.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got my release to get back to America, I just enjoyed
being back in Pawtucket playing again,'' said Merloni, who was
called up to Boston last Monday. ``It gave me a lot of life, just
to have fun playing and trying to contribute.
</P>
<P>
   ``This callup was real unexpected, but I'm just happy to be
playing baseball. It's a change of scenery for me up here in
Boston, but I'm just starting with the same attitude, not trying to
do too much.''
</P>
<P>
   No one even needs to tell Merloni to be superstitious.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came in the clubhouse today and they moved my locker,'' said
Merloni. ``All my stuff was moved, so I came in and I decided it
wasn't time to change anything. So I moved to my other locker and
moved my stuff back.''
</P>
<P>
   Did that have anything to do with the fact that he went 3 for 5
with 3 RBIs and 2 runs Saturday? Merloni's not taking any chances.
Since his callup, he is hitting .560, with three three-hit games;
before this season, he had four three-hit games in 82 career games.
</P>
<P>
   ``His Japanese is probably a little better than what it used to
be, that's for sure,'' said Red Sox manager Jimy Williams. ``But
he's really contributed a lot offensively.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been here before, so we all know how he is _ he's a heck
of a teammate. He plays hard. He's a winner. He gives you
everything he's got. And, to say the least, he's really swinging
that bat.''
</P>
<P>
   With Saturday's output, Merloni extended his career-high hitting
streak to six games, including five straight multihit games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got lucky today,'' said Merloni. ``I got the check-swing
double and kind of changed up and took a lazy swing up there. I'm
just trying to see the ball, same as before.''
</P>
<P>
   How long this will last is anyone's guess _ psychics included.
Right now, Merloni is merely thrilled that he isn't riding a bench
in Japan.
</P>
<P>
   He's also pleased that a good hitting stretch isn't going to
waste.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been good aim, that's about it,'' said Merloni. ``I'm
hitting balls and you look up and it's finding the hole somewhere.
Rather than just trying to place anything, I'm just swinging the
bat, looking up, and seeing where it goes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
