<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARTINEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARTINEZ WARMS TO THE TASK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL VEGA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ He felt pretty good warming up before Saturday's outing
against the Texas Rangers. But, as Pedro Martinez said, ``The
bullpen is not the game. You have to go out and face a few batters
and do it from one inning to the other and, pretty much, get to the
spot where you left the game before.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the Red Sox ace couldn't wait to start again, to get back
on the mound at Fenway Park, and, most important, to work out the
stiffness in his right shoulder that had plagued him in his
previous start, last Monday against Tampa Bay, causing him to ask
out after four innings.
</P>
<P>
   While all of Red Sox Nation worried about whether Martinez would
go back on the disabled list, he assured manager Jimy Williams,
pitching coach Joe Kerrigan, and team doctor Bill Morgan he was not
likely to miss a start.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, before a sellout crowd of 33,222, Martinez put
everyone's fears to rest _ including his own. He went seven innings
in a dominant 9-0 victory over the Rangers, ringing up 10
strikeouts to tie Jim Lonborg (784) for ninth place on the club's
all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could tell the people were really worried, even myself, I
was concerned, because I threw on the side and this thing happened
from one day to the other,'' said Martinez, who said the stiffness
stemmed from jet lag and dehydration on a long flight home from
Texas. ``To me it's not something I'm used to seeing. It was weird,
and I was concerned, so the first two innings of the game I just
tried to do things perfectly, mechanically, with my arm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of testing myself out there in the first three
innings to see how it would go. After I got all that run support, I
figured I didn't have to do any more than what I was doing and just
tried to keep it simple.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, who had averaged an anemic 0.8 runs in Martinez's
four losses this season, came through with four in the first three
innings, then added five more in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   That enabled Martinez, who improved to 14-4 while lowering his
league-leading ERA to 1.53, to focus on the task at hand _
establish his fastball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had pitched the first inning, pretty much, just by throwing
fastballs,'' said Martinez. ``That was also one more test for
myself. I just wanted to make it simple and keep throwing the
fastball and see how good I felt.
</P>
<P>
   ``After that, I just started mixing my pitches,'' added
Martinez, who struck out the side in the second on a steady diet of
changeups. ``They were geared for the fastball after the first
inning, so it was a good idea to change things up.''
</P>
<P>
   But if there was one pitch that signaled everything was all
right, it was Martinez's money pitch. ``The outside fastball,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got on top of the fastball right away,'' Martinez said.
``When I started the game, I kept hitting the outside corner
against the lefties and I never let it go, so it was key pitch on
the (day) for me. I ended my outing by throwing the same pitch: the
outside fastball.''
</P>
<P>
   While it appeared Martinez was back to his dominating self, he
was not quite ready to give himself a clean bill of health.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, not yet,'' he said. ``I have to keep working. (The arm)
got heavy on me in the innings that were a little longer than
normal, so I'm going to have to keep working and doing the therapy
that I'm doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope the fans know that I'm in a state where I know my
body, and I was good enough to go out there and keep doing what I'm
doing. Hopefully, I'll be fine by the end of the season.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
