<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-WATSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER 65, IT'S NO TIME TO RETIRE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM MCCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ His chase for this elusive major championship
goes back to those days when a golden bear provided his fiercest
competition. Now that a young tiger is the game's best, well . . .
maybe it's a stretch to say Tom Watson still is in quest of the PGA
Championship, but he is making his presence felt.
</P>
<P>
   Just a few weeks shy of his 51st birthday, Watson needed just 22
putts in a brilliant 7-under-par 65 Saturday in the third round of
the 82d PGA Championship at Valhalla GC. It didn't quite throw him
into the mix of things (he's at 5-under 211 overall, eight shots
behind), but it rekindled some magic and reminded him why this
championship is so special.
</P>
<P>
   ``The PGA was certainly my No. 1 goal for many, many years,''
said Watson, who earned victories in the other three legs of the
Grand Slam.
</P>
<P>
   For an hour or so, Watson had a share of the competitive course
record, but by the time he left the interview area, Jose Maria
Olazabal had shattered it with a 63. No surprise, said Watson.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a forgiving golf course,'' he said. ``The fairways are
soft, and on the greens, the ball stops dead.''
</P>
<P>
   There were questions about his past failures at the PGA,
particularly the 1978 edition at Oakmont CC when he squandered a
five-shot lead through 54 holes and lost in a playoff to John
Mahaffey. But Watson shrugged them off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't dwell on it,'' he said. ``I don't play `What if.' I
don't look back.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, there was a vintage 65 to talk of.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't real pretty to look at from a ball-striking
standpoint,'' he said, ``but from the putting standpoint, it was
beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   There were a pair of bogeys on the par-3s going out, but a
handful of birdies offset that. Of particular delight, said Watson,
was a 12-footer that he converted on the par-4 sixth hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the stroke of the day,'' he said. ``I have been
having trouble with my left-to-right putts and I made an
adjustment.''
</P>
<P>
   Which proves that even old golfers can learn knew tricks.
Especially if you remember how to learn, said Watson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I watch Tiger,'' he said. ``I always watch the best players,
and he is by far the best player.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Woods had to be impressed with some of the skill displayed
by Watson. On top of that birdie at the sixth, Watson rolled in a
15-footer at the seventh, then shook off a bogey at the par-3
eighth with a sizzling 7-iron at the par-4 ninth that came to rest
inches from the cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can make those,'' said Watson, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   He went through seasons of misery on the putting green, but has
played his way through the troubles.
</P>
<P>
   After making the turn in 2-under 34, Watson turned up the heat
with an incoming 31 that included a near hole-out on the par-4 14th
(he could have kicked in the birdie putt), a 35-footer at the 15th,
and a textbook birdie at the par-5 18th: driver, 4-iron lay-up,
sand wedge to 12 feet.
</P>
<P>
   All of which makes him long for weekly battles with guys half
his age, right? At that suggestion, Watson broke into a big a smile
and laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still feel as if I can play with the young kids,'' he said.
``But, you know, my days are numbered.''
</P>
<P>
   Then he glanced down at his scorecard, shook his head
approvingly, and said: ``But I still like to compete against
them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
