<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITERIA FOR INCLUSION HAS SOME ON THE OUTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ When he saw the list, Greg Kraft couldn't
believe it. He wasn't in the field for the 82d PGA Championship.
Granted, he's not Tiger Woods, and he has no delusions about being
a marquee name. But certainly, he thought, being 72d on the money
list and the winner of some $600,000 this year was good enough to
get into the season's final major championship.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. The PGA of America instead turned this major championship
into an invitational.
</P>
<P>
   ``They reserve the right to exempt whomever they like,'' said
Kraft. ``Category 11. But it's hard when they give out exemptions
to guys I've been beating all year.''
</P>
<P>
   Kraft and many other players were taken by surprise when they
saw the final list during last week's Buick Open. In past years,
the PGA of America has gone fairly deep into the money list, which
this time included the period from August 1999 to August of this
year. Last year, the 86th name on the list made it, and in 1998 the
picks went into the low 100s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt it was enough,'' said Kraft. ``It always had been in
the past.''
</P>
<P>
   But, for some reason, PGA of America officials stopped the list
at 70, then filled out the rest of the 150-player field with
special exemptions. That total was a staggering 37. Throw in the 25
club pros who are given spots and you have 62 berths that are out
of the players' control.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft said he wasn't the only player taken by surprise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was probably the most talk I've heard (in a locker room),''
he said. ``It was the only thing they talked about, was who got
into the PGA.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he has never won on the PGA Tour, the 36-year-old Kraft
is a consistent performer. Few players work as hard on their game,
and last year that paid off with a 52d-place finish on the money
list ($810,777). He doesn't begrudge the exemptions offered to
players such as Greg Norman (``He'd probably have made it had he
not been injured, and he deserves it'') or Tom Watson, nor would he
quibble with international names such as Bernhard Langer, Padraig
Harrington, or Lee Westwood. But some exemptions baffle him. He's
too respectful to name names, but Kraft is of the opinion that the
PGA of America did an injustice to many middle-of-the-pack PGA Tour
players.
</P>
<P>
   He's not alone in that thought.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no opinion,'' said Hal Sutton, shaking his head. ``But
they gave (an exemption) to everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a sensitive issue when players of past glory such as Ben
Crenshaw and Sam Torrance are given spots because they have links
to the PGA of America's crown jewel _ the Ryder Cup _ and then they
shoot high numbers (Crenshaw opened with an 83, Torrance an 82).
Also bothersome is the PGA of America's fascination with world
rankings. Seemingly every half-hour there would be a release saying
that so many of the world's Top 100 players were in the field. Good
gracious, who cares? When Kraft sees players below him on the PGA
money list _ Bill Glasson, Billy Mayfair, and Bob May, for example
_ get in because they have slightly higher world rankings, then
something is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Good sense, not computers, should dictate who gets in.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft said he talked to officials of the PGA of America and the
PGA Tour. He did get into the field as an alternate, for which he
was grateful, though the entire matter ruined his tournament at the
Buick Open last week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was hitting the ball perfect up there, and when I got the
news I wasn't in, I was so irritated it affected my game and I
didn't play well,'' he said. ``Every little thing bothered me, so I
wasn't going to coe here (Louisville, Ky.) and play the waiting
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he went home to Clearwater, Fla., and simmered. He got
a call Tuesday morning and was told that Bobby Nichols had
withdrawn and that he was in. Kraft played nine holes late Tuesday
afternoon, nine more Wednesday, then shot 1-under 71 Thursday. Had
he gotten the call from the PGA of America on Wednesday, he said,
``I wouldn't have come. I was that upset.''
</P>
<P>
   What he would like, he said, is a set of rules that is concise
and easy to understand.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like the Masters,'' said Kraft. ``It's very hard to get into
it, but you know what you have to do to get into that tournament.
In the future, the PGA of America should have some set of
guidelines. There's too much gray area here for them to play with
the rules. Last year it was 86 (on the money list), two years ago
something like 104. This year 70?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Norman will carry the Olympic torch across Sydney Harbor Bridge
on the morning of the opening ceremonies. It's a nice honor for
him, and he's justified in taking a lot of pride in it, but
unfortunately he's a bit too enamored with this Olympic concept,
lobbying for the inclusion of golf. ``Everybody should be working
to get golf in the Olympics,'' said Norman, who hopefully speaks
for himself. There is already a significant amount of international
golf events _ from the Dunhill Cup, to four World Golf
Championships, to the Ryder Cup, to the Presidents Cup, to the
Walker Cup, to the Solheim Cup, to the PGA Cup, to the World Cup.
Just carry the torch, pass it on, and shush. Let the Olympics be
about synchronized swimming and not golf. Right, Tiger? ``To be
honest with you, I don't think (the Olympics) would be a big
priority in our game,'' said Woods . . . Then again, the Olympics
are about politics, if nothing else, and politics helped ruin this
week's NEC Invitational at Firestone in Akron, Ohio. Somewhat
contrived to begin with, this World Golf Championship event was
made even more so by mindless European Tour officials who changed
the rules in the middle of the game. Originally, 1999 Ryder Cup
members were going to be exempted into the field, along with
Presidents Cup members, but European leaders chose to make examples
of some of their leading talents. Thus, Jesper Parnevik, Sergio
Garcia, Paul Lawrie, and Jean Van de Velde won't be in Akron, even
though they were on last September's Ryder Cup team. European
leaders chose instead to send the top money winners, for all
intents and purposes punishing those aforementioned players because
they play primarily in the US and don't support the European Tour .
. . Lanny Wadkins, when asked if he had time for a question after
Thursday's marathon round in oppressive humidity at the PGA
Championship: ``Man, I don't have time for anything. It's 7:15. On
the Senior Tour we play in four hours, drive a cart, then have a
beer.'' It took Wadkins six hours to complete his first round at
Valhalla. Normally, he could play 36 in that time.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Things have not been going particularly well for John Daly on
the golf course, so perhaps he'll find success in the recording
studio. That's right, Daly recorded a country song with his two
daughters. The title? ``You Can Lean On Me.'' It is scheduled to be
released later this month, when Daly hosts a fund-raiser in
Toronto. He told reporters, ``My singing's terrible, but it's been
better than my golf game lately.'' . . . Enough of the criticism of
Valhalla. OK, it is not in the same league as the other venues for
this year's majors (Augusta National, Pebble Beach, St. Andrews),
but it's not exactly a cow pasture. Frankly, this nonsense about
making things very, very special simply because it's the year 2000
is quite tiring. Who cares? It's not like the PGA of America has a
habit of playing lousy golf courses. Quite the contrary; its site
list is impressive: Winged Foot, Riviera, Southern Hills,
Inverness, Cherry Hills, Pebble Beach, Oakmont, Oakland Hills. The
problem with Valhalla in 2000 is that it's too soon a return (the
PGA Championship was here in 1996), and the fact that the club is
owned by the PGA of America bothers people greatly. But whether you
like it or not, doing things for the money is not a criticism that
should be directed solely at the PGA of America. ``Everyone wants
to see Winged Foot,'' said Lee Janzen, ``a traditional course with
trees everywhere. But I think this is a fantastic golf course and a
beautiful setting.'' . . . So, if Woods wins the PGA Championship,
what does the PGA of America do with its annual nonsense called the
PGA Grand Slam of Golf? It's supposed to pit the four major winners
against each other, but in this case it would mean Woods (three
wins) vs. Vijay Singh (the Masters). There is an alternate's list
that currently has Ernie Els and Tom Lehman next in line, but
here's my suggestion: Let Woods hit three balls off the tee. Singh,
of course, would hit one. Woods would play all three balls all the
way; it would require him to take roughly 210 swings, but he's
young. And imagine the ratings. Not just one round of Woods, but
three . . . Woods recently had to shoot down the rumor that he was
engaged to his girlfriend, Joanna Jagoda. Last week, a story in a
local newspaper indicated that Woods may have purchased a home in a
swanky neighborhood up the street from Valhalla. ``No, no,'' said
Woods before the reporter could finish his question. ``I heard that
the minute I got off a plane here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-00 2244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
