<SLUG> BC-VFW-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VFW MOBILIZES TO REVERSE DECLINE IN POLITICAL INFLUENCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By OSCAR AVILA  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   About a thousand World War II veterans
die every day. The Kansas City-based Veterans of Foreign Wars wants
to make sure its political clout doesn't disappear with them.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush and Vice President Al Gore will
address the group's national convention in Milwaukee this week, a
ritual for political candidates. But the VFW is finding it harder
to stay relevant after the conventions.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the nation's oldest veterans group is launching an
ambitious effort to reach elected officials and encourage members
to vote.
</P>
<P>
   ``Veterans issues used to be a sacred cow. Now we're relegated
to a position of just another special-interest group,'' said Steve
Van Buskirk, VFW spokesman. ``We're going to have to learn to play
the game better.''
</P>
<P>
   This year, the VFW for the first time is hiring a public
relations firm to organize its annual voter drive. Fleishman
Hillard is dutifully faxing press releases and organizing media
interviews.
</P>
<P>
   Van Buskirk said the group plans to spend more money on voter
turnout this year than it has in decades. He said surveys show that
veterans do not vote at a significantly higher rate than the
general public.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're appalled by that,'' he said. ``Veterans should realize
that they need to lead the charge to the polls.''
</P>
<P>
   Another first: The VFW sent a delegation to the Republican and
Democratic conventions. Officials met with party leaders and such
congressional heavyweights as Senate Majority Leader Trent Lott.
</P>
<P>
   This comes eight months after the VFW fell out of the top 25 of
Fortune magazine's annual poll of the most influential lobbying
groups. The VFW is ``no longer in the top echelon,'' the magazine
said.
</P>
<P>
   Another group, the nonpartisan American Legion, has testified at
convention platform committees for years. Bush and Gore both are
scheduled to address the American Legion's convention next month.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Thomas of the American Legion's legislative office said
veterans groups can't assume that politicians will take notice of
their issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to work a little harder these days,'' Thomas said.
``There might be fewer veterans, but we can still be persuasive.
Our successes haven't come in a vacuum. They happen as a result of
advocacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Although this year's platforms were essentially written before
the conventions, the VFW and American Legion helped tweak the
documents on issues such as health care for veterans, military
benefits and national security.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of whom VFW members support, Van Buskirk thinks
turnout will improve this year because Sen. John McCain's
presidential candidacy energized many veterans. Hundreds of
veterans flocked to the former POW's rallies, often waving copies
of his biography.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain's valor in combat is becoming an anachronism.
</P>
<P>
   Fewer politicians have fought in wars or even served in the
military. Bill Clinton was the first president without military
service since Franklin Roosevelt.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts say politicians still stand to gain points by
embracing veterans groups. Gore, who served in Vietnam, has been
known to wear his Legion cap at veterans events. Bush served in the
Texas Air National Guard.
</P>
<P>
   Van Buskirk said veterans aren't a unified voting bloc, making
it difficult for them to exert influence like the elderly or other
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Although many veterans criticized Clinton for avoiding the
draft, he handily defeated decorated World War II veterans in 1992
and 1996. And the groundswell from veterans wasn't enough to carry
McCain past Bush.
</P>
<P>
   As a nonprofit group, the VFW cannot endorse candidates. Van
Buskirk said both Bush and Gore had been attentive to its issues.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Calore, commander of VFW Post No. 846 in Overland Park said
veterans need to become more sophisticated voters by focusing on
the candidates' political records, not their military backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   Calore said he doesn't care if candidates received a draft
deferment or won a chestful of medals, as long as they ``did the
honorable thing.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As the saying goes: What have you done for me lately? It's
more important that we know what they will do to stand by us in the
future,'' Calore said. ``We need to support someone who is right on
the issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
