<SLUG> BC-OLY-NOTEBOOK-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUPPLEMENT STRATEGY? THEY'RE EATING IT UP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ `Nutritional supplements,'' everything from creatine to
multivitamins, are the latest craze among Olympic athletes who want
to jack up performance without falling afoul of the doping lab. Top
swimmers such as Jenny Thompson and Dara Torres take two dozen
supplements a day. Their teammates, Gary Hall and Anthony Ervin,
eat supplements meant for horses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our guys are on the stuff that (Kentucky Derby winner)
Fusaichi Pegasus uses,'' bragged coach Mike Bottom.
</P>
<P>
   The idea, Thompson said, is ``to beat the cheaters without
cheating.''
</P>
<P>
   The question, though, is what ``cheating'' means these days.
Though testosterone, erythropoietin (EPO), and human growth
hormones all are created naturally by the body, their synthetic
versions are banned at the Olympics. So why should creatine, which
helps increase strength, be any different? The purpose behind using
any synthetic substance is the same: to get ``faster, higher,
stronger'' by artificial means. So why is EPO banned and creatine
OK?
</P>
<P>
   It may just be that the International Olympic Committee, usually
a quadrennium behind on the doping front, hasn't gotten around to
creatine yet. And though the US Olympic Committee frowns on
supplements generally, it hasn't banned them. Meanwhile, athletes
and their coaches are cleaning out the shelves at GNC. And the
Sydney organizers are thinking about opening a perfecta window at
the natatorium for the men's 50.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   After all the hoopla over the prospect of former major leaguers
playing on the US Olympic baseball team, only one _ 40-year-old Tim
Raines _ has a chance of being on the roster when it's announced
Wednesday. And the selectors are finding that many of the minor
leaguers they want are likely to be called up next month when major
league clubs expand their rosters to 40. The Yanks will need at
least a dozen phenoms in Sydney if they expect to contend for a
medal. The Japanese, whom the US faces in its opener, are bringing
eight pros, including ace Daisuke Matsuzaka. And the South Koreans
are shutting down their pro league to make players available. Not
to mention the Cubans, whose ``amateurs'' have never lost the gold
medal . . . Thorny issue in US Greco-Roman wrestling, where an
arbitrator stepped in to play referee and ultimately created a
reversal that put Matt Lindland on the team instead of Keith
Sieracki. After Sieracki defeated Lindland at the June trials,
Lindland claimed that Sieracki had used an illegal leg move. Though
Lindland lost two appeals, an arbitrator ordered a rematch, which
Lindland won, 8-0. ``We're going to the lawyers with this,'' vowed
Sieracki, who'd been competing in Russia and had only four days'
notice of the rematch. Siding with Sieracki is the USOC, which
argues that field-of-play decisions shouldn't be subject to
arbitration . . . The Romanian women's gymnastics team for Sydney
is much the same as the one that won last year's world
championships: all-around champ Maria Olaru, Simona Amanar, Andreea
Raducan, Andreea Isarescu, and Loredana Boboc, plus Claudia
Presacan. Unlike the Americans, who hold nationals and trials
before picking the team in a back room, the Romanians still use the
old Bela Karolyi pointing method (``You, you, you, you, you, and
you.'').
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The US women's swimming team is its oldest ever. Four
competitors (Torres, Thompson, Amy Van Dyken, and B.J. Bedford) are
27 or older and Torres, at 33, is the oldest ever by five years.
What accounts for the graying of the roster? Money _ and changing
attitudes about how long women can compete. ``It's being accepted
by society and by athletes that your career is not over in high
school,'' said US women's coach Richard Quick. ``Thirty years ago,
your career was over at 16 or 17. Then it was over at the end of
college. Now, women can make a decent living swimming. As long as
the flame of desire burns as brightly in her mid-30s, a woman can
continue to improve.'' The US men's team, youngest since 1988, has
eight teenagers and most are medal contenders. Ian Crocker (17) of
Portland, Maine, has a shot at gold in the 400 medley relay. Erik
Vendt (19) of North Easton figures to win silver in the 400 IM and
has a shot at bronze in the 1,500. Aaron Peirsol (17) is favored
for silver in the 200 backstroke, Pat Calhoun (19) for silver in
the 100 breaststroke, and Ervin (19) for bronze in the 50 freestyle
. . . Why won't Thompson swim the 50 free at the Olympics? ``Jenny
doesn't like the 50,'' said Quick. ``She never has liked it. It's
not her best event.'' And since Thompson is already swimming the
100 free and 100 butterfly and probably all three relays, she has
plenty on her plate. If she wins medals in each, which she should,
Thompson will end her career with 11. If one is gold, she'll break
the record for most by a US woman (5), held by speedskater Bonnie
Blair. Thompson, by the way, is the latest Olympic athlete to bare
some or all for the camera. Her topless pose (with fists artfully
arranged) in the recent Sports Illustrated caused a stir among
moralists who thought it was the wrong message from a role model.
Thompson's reply: I'm proud of my body . . . Now that Vendt is the
first US swimmer to break 15 minutes for the mile, several others
are likely to follow. ``This puts our country at a whole different
psychological level,'' said US men's coach Mark Schubert, who
coaches Vendt at Southern Cal. Most likely to be next is Chris
Thompson, who has gone 15:04 . . . Look for lots of mixing and
matching and subbing on the US relays in Sydney. Thompson, Torres,
and Cristina Teuscher probably will swim in the 800 freestyle medal
race, even though none of them swam in the final of the 200
freestyle at the trials. The reason: all of them are faster than
the 2-3-4 finishers in Indianapolis. That means Samantha Arsenault
of Peabody could end up swimming in the prelims (which still would
get her a medal). Odds are, too, that Hall will swim anchor on the
men's 400 freestyle even though Neil Walker won the 100 at the
trials. Since Hall anchored both 400 relays to gold at both the
Olympics and world meet, he's the obvious choice . . . So, what's
the verdict on bodysuits? ``The jury's still out,'' said Schubert.
Since USA Swimming lifted its ban so close to trials, most swimmers
didn't have enough time to get comfortable in the sharkskin-like
suits and weren't sure which of the multiple versions they should
use. By Sydney, that will change. Said Schubert: ``We'll be a lot
more specific about which suit for which stroke and which suit for
which body type.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Nice showing by the US rowing team at the recent world
championships for non-Olympic events in Croatia. The men's
lightweight eight retained its gold medal (with seven new people in
the boat) as did the coxed pair. The men's coxed four and women's
lightweight pair (with Cambridge's Catherine Humblet) won silvers .
. . Sure these aren't the Winter Games? There was a dusting of snow
recently in the Sydney suburbs, and the temperature was so low last
week (a windy 51) that only a few thousand parka-clad spectators
showed up for the Australian track and field trials. No worries,
insist local meteorologists, who predict that the thermometer will
be in the more seasonable 60s during the Games . . . Less than half
of the US men's indoor volleyball team that sagged to ninth in
Atlanta will be back in Sydney. Returning are Lloy Ball, John
Hyden, Mike Lambert, Dan Landry, and Jeff Nygaard. The Americans
are up against the iron: both No. 1 Italy and No. 2 Russia are in
their prelim pool . . . Which airline is bringing the US Olympic
team to Sydney? United, whose ongoing dispute with its pilots has
created scheduling nightmares for weeks. The real problem isn't
getting the 600-plus athletes Down Under. It's getting them to San
Diego, where the processing began last week . . . Who are James
Morrison, Human Nature, Julie Anthony, John Farnham, Olivia
Newton-John, Vanessa Amorosi, and Tina Arena? They'll be the star
entertainers at the opening ceremonies in Sydney. All of them are
Aussies and all except Newton-John are strangers to most of the
planet. The organizers could have gone international but decided to
stick with homegrown products of Oz.
</P>
</TEXT>
