<HEADLINE>
FISH HATCHERY CAB PRODUCE UP TO 20 MILLION SPORT FISH ANNUALLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By Bill Graham  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star   WARSAW, Mo. - Sport fish bound for
Missouri's lakes and ponds now have an $18.6 million computerized
birthplace.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Bass, catfish, walleye, muskies and hybrid stripers by the
millions will be produced at the Lost Valley Fish Hatchery by the
Missouri Department of Conservation.
</P>
<P>
   The 78 outdoor raising ponds and several indoor holding tanks
comprise the largest fish hatchery in the state, capable of
producing up to 20 million sport fish a year.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, says manager Dave Waller, it is one of the largest
public hatcheries in the nation -- even the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is going to greatly increase our capability for sport
fish restoration,'' Waller said. ``We will be shipping fish all
over the state.''
</P>
<P>
   There also will be laboratory services for private
aquaculturists and a visitor center with a 12,000-gallon aquarium.
The hatchery also may be used for research on endangered species,
such freshwater mussels.
</P>
<P>
   Lost Valley, which opened in March, has replaced two small and
outdated hatcheries -- Lewis and Clark at Sugar Lake in southern
Buchanan County and Indian Trail in Dent County. To pay for it, the
Department of Conservation used about $12 million in federal money
from a sport fish restoration fund and $6.6 million from department
funds, Waller said.
</P>
<P>
   The fish will stock new ponds and lakes. Plus, some fish like
walleye and muskie need to be stocked in large reservoirs to ensure
quality fishing, a cornerstone of the state's tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
   People like to look at fish as well as catch them. So the
Department of Conservation expects to dedicate the hatchery and
open public educational exhibits in October.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're expecting 75,000 visitors a year here,'' Waller said.
``This is a well-thought-out and functional place.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the size and the technology, however, that make Lost
Valley unique.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Waller's home telephone woke him Tuesday night. It
was the Lost Valley computer system calling, informing him that a
level in a water supply tank was incorrect. Waller called the main
computer back with his laptop computer and then tapped in a command
that fixed the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh well water flows constantly through the indoor tanks, and
much of it is recycled back through the system from an outdoor
holding pond. Thousands -- and at times millions -- of young fish
depend on clean water with a steady temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Computers keep the water flowing with programming by Micro-Comm,
a digital control technology company.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's amazing is that this has worked pretty well,'' Waller
said. ``We haven't lost a fish because of it, and it's saved fish
several times.''
</P>
<P>
   Once young walleye are turned loose in places like Longview
Lake, they are on their own to eat or be eaten.
</P>
<P>
   But concentrated in a hatchery, they are pampered. Technicians
have laboratories to monitor water quality and watch for disease
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``A fish hatchery is essentially a wet feedlot, an underwater
feedlot,'' Waller said.
</P>
<P>
   The ``production room,'' where fish are hatched, looks like a
large factory with multicolored pipes, tanks, control knobs and
gauges.
</P>
<P>
   Gurgling water makes the room sound like a mountain stream.
</P>
<P>
   Fresh water drops from pipes into fish tanks, while old water
drains from the bottom into concrete floor channels covered by
grates.
</P>
<P>
   Peek into one tank, and you see thousands of blackish flathead
catfish fry that were hatched in July in a small egg jar suspended
in a circular aquarium. Now, they are 2 inches long and crowding
the corner of a 150-gallon rectangular tank. Their pellet food is
dropped from an overhead trough at intervals controlled by an
electronic timer.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby, several thousand 6-inch muskie swim gently against the
current in a circular tank. Keeping them in a circular pattern
helps keep the sharp-toothed predators from hurting one another as
they feed.
</P>
<P>
   Hybrid striped bass that will eventually be stocked at the James
A. Reed Memorial Wildlife Area swim madly back and forth in a
10-foot-wide circular tank, like 12,000 underwater rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``These hybrids never rest,'' Waller said. ``They swim
constantly. I don't know how they grow.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside, rectangular rearing ponds cover much of the Sterett
Creek valley, along with two wastewater control ponds and a 10-acre
lake to hold recirculated water.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone is thrilled with the hatchery's size and the fact
that 900,000 gallons of water a day, on average, are pumped from
seven deep wells in the valley just north of Warsaw.
</P>
<P>
   Water levels in some shallow wells serving nearby rural homes
became low in July. One well went dry.
</P>
<P>
   Ron and Delma Roellig lowered their well pump, and they worry
about having to drill a new well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Myself, I think it's a combination of things,'' said Delma
Roellig. ``We've got about 15 more houses out here, there's a
drought, and then they start drawing 650 gallons a minute.''
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Conservation conducted well tests before
beginning to pump water in March, said mechanical engineer Greg
Mihalevich. Also, the wells were drilled deep to reach a lower
water table than those feeding domestic wells.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Conservation now is monitoring three test
wells, with assistance from the Missouri Department of Natural
Resources, to see whether the hatchery is affecting water levels.
Test results so far are inconclusive, Waller said.
</P>
<P>
   Truman Lake is nearby, as the hatchery lies in what once was the
Osage River bed. But the well water is much cleaner and healthier
for the fish than surface water, Waller said.
</P>
<P>
   The raising ponds are far cleaner than the wild waters where the
fish will be stocked.
</P>
<P>
   Polypropylene liners make the ponds more like 1/2-acre to 1-acre
tanks. When they are drained, the fish collect in a concrete basin.
Instead of wading in knee-deep mud to collect fish, as they do at
old hatcheries, crews simply walk down concrete steps to the basins
and net the fish.
</P>
<P>
   ``This beats the old days of sloshing around in the mud,''
Mihalevich said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-00 2257EDT &QL; 
