<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRUINS EXPECT TO BE MUCH-IMPROVED IN THE SECONDARY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When Jason Bell was a senior at Long Beach
Millikan High, his team lost every game. Little did he know that
when he walked into the UCLA secondary he'd be going from one
no-win situation to another.
</P>
<P>
   No, the Bruins haven't lost every game in the four years Bell
has been a Bruin - far from it. In fact, Bell started at cornerback
during most of their school-record 20-game winning streak. But the
perception is that when the Bruins won it was in spite of their
defense, not because of it.
</P>
<P>
   And last season, when they slumped to 4-7 in a season mired by
suspensions, injuries and inexperience, the secondary was a primary
problem.
</P>
<P>
   In the conference opener, Stanford backup quarterback Joe
Borchard torched the Bruins for five touchdowns and most of the
Cardinal's 442 yards passing.
</P>
<P>
   That was their most-embarrassing moment - for a week. That's
when Arizona State's Delvon Flowers, in the final minute, took a
slip-screen pass from third-string quarterback Griffin Goodman and
wove his way 49 yards for the winning touchdown without a Bruin
laying a hand on him.
</P>
<P>
   When the year was done, the Bruins allowed more than 2,700
passing yards for the fifth year in a row and tied a school record
by surrendering 22 touchdown passes.
</P>
<P>
   The inevitable optimism of a new season has the Bruins believing
they'll be much better everywhere on defense - even the secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've played some young guys, I think that's the biggest
thing,'' UCLA coach Bob Toledo said. ``When you play young,
inexperienced guys they have a tendency to get you beat. I think
we're better back there this year.''
</P>
<P>
   There are three reasons they think so:
</P>
<P>
   --The return of Bell (heel) and Marques Anderson (suspension
from school), who were the starting cornerbacks two years ago.
Anderson, who gained nearly 15 pounds, has moved to strong safety.
</P>
<P>
   --Ricky Manning, who will start opposite Bell, and Joe Hunter
had 13 starts between them as freshmen last season and will be
better off for the experience.
</P>
<P>
   --The return of defensive coordinator Bob Field. It is the first
time since 1997 that the Bruins aren't implementing a new defensive
system. ``That's very significant,'' Field said. ``It's like
learning a new language - everything's different. It takes time to
get it down. Three years in a row, we were speaking a different
language.''
</P>
<P>
   The one open position is at free safety, where Jason Zdenek, a
seldom-used fifth-year senior from Chaminade High, leads a field of
candidates including track hurdler John Hall; Audie Attar and Jason
Stephens, who have failed auditions in the past; and talented true
freshman Ben Emanuel, whose progress has been slowed by headaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand (the skepticism) because of the past,'' Bell
said. ``But we've got a lot of talent and we're taking the right
approach with our confidence and our attitude. I'm surrounded by a
defense now that respects winning. We're practicing like we're
going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, no group was more, ahem, confident in the first week of
two-a- day practices than the secondary. It wasn't hard to hear
Bell, Hunter and Manning trash-talking when they worked against the
receivers in drills. In a blocking drill, Bell made it a point to
line up against the Bruins' two best receivers, Brian Poli-Dixon
and Freddie Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   What's remarkable is that this confidence hasn't been beaten out
of them by now.
</P>
<P>
   Bell has started 17 games and has yet to intercept a pass.
Anderson's biggest play came two years ago when he stripped Jeff
Allen a yard short of the goal line to save UCLA's win over
Stanford; of course, Anderson had been badly beaten on the play.
</P>
<P>
   Hunter and Manning, meanwhile, always have Borchard.
</P>
<P>
   It all made them easy fodder for handicapped-parking jokes.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this position, you're always going to be criticized - even
Deion Sanders,'' Hunter said of the cornerback position. ``If we
make a mistake, every man, woman and child is going to see it. You
know from day one you're on the hot seat so you just accept it.
You've got to have a certain swagger.''
</P>
<P>
   Manning says he uses the torchings - on the field and off - to
motivate himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when your body's telling you to stop, I use it to
keep me going,'' he said. ``As a unit, it's one of the best things
that could happen for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Bell and Anderson also say they're motivated by last season.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was forced to watch from the Rose Bowl stands,
something he hadn't done since high school. Bell's view was from
the sidelines but no less painful.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was especially tough watching the defensive backs,'' Bell
said. ``There wasn't a lot of leadership at the position and Coach
Field is so intense. To see it fall apart like that was tough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned a lot about patience. I also learned to love and
respect the game. Every time I step on the field now I know how
much I miss it, how much it means and what a privilege it is to
play.''
</P>
<P>
   And who knows? If the secondary really is better, Bell could
finally be walking into a no-lose situation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
