<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-LEDE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEARCHING FOR TRIPLE CROWN, WOODS CAN'T PULL AWAY FROM FIELD AT
PGA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Tiger Woods, the Secretariat of the PGA Tour,
remains in position to clinch golf's version of the Triple Crown
today in a city that helped coin the phase.
</P>
<P>
   But like the red colt known for distancing itself from pursuers,
Woods is discovering that Kentucky is a tough place to bury the
competition on the path to history.
</P>
<P>
   Secretariat squeezed out a two-length victory in the 1973
Kentucky Derby, a narrow escape by his lofty standards. Woods, in
turn, finds himself holding a one-stroke lead over two challengers
heading into today's final round of the PGA Championship at
Valhalla Golf Club.
</P>
<P>
   For a player who has won the past two major championships by a
combined 23 strokes, that hardly qualifies as breathing room.
</P>
<P>
   But Woods, who squeezed out a 70 in yesterday's third round to
move to 13 under par for the tournament, said he considers himself
fortunate to remain in control of the leader board after struggling
with his swing on a day when 24 players posted better scores than
he did during a record-setting, birdiefest at Valhalla.
</P>
<P>
   ``To shoot 70, as poorly as I struck the golf ball, I thought
that was pretty good,'' said Woods, who leads Scott Dunlap and Bob
May by one shot and has seven players within four strokes heading
into the final round. ``To go into \Rtoday\S with the lead, it was
an added bonus. I hit a couple of shots where I almost hit my right
foot on the way down. That's not good.
</P>
<P>
   ``At every major championship, you always have one day where you
are not going to hit the ball well. If you can get it around with a
decent score that day, you are going to keep yourself in the
tournament. And that's what I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Specifically, Woods remained on pace to join Fort Worth legend
Ben Hogan as the only golfers in history to win three major
championships in a season by withstanding his worst nine-hole
stretch in a major (back-nine 37) since the Masters. Woods
rebounded from his first double bogey of the tournament at No. 12,
as well as a bogey at No. 15, to post a closing birdie that pushed
him a stroke ahead of Dunlap and May.
</P>
<P>
   But he yielded ground to several pursuers on a day when Valhalla
played to a scoring average of 71, the lowest ever for a PGA held
at a par-72 venue. Fifty-three players broke par, a third-round
record for the tournament. Included was Jose Maria Olazabal, whose
63 tied the lowest score ever posted in a major championship.
</P>
<P>
   Woods, however, said he kept ``getting stuck'' at the top of his
backswing, causing him to push shots off-line. He declared himself
lucky that Dunlap, his playing partner, missed two short birdie
putts during a round of 70 that could have given him the outright
lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``He played the better of the two guys in our group, that's for
sure,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   Dunlap, who has never won on the PGA Tour, said matching scores
with the world's top-ranked player gave him a ``pretty big'' boost
in confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like the rest of the golfing world, I was wondering how I'd
do,'' said Dunlap, 37. ``I passed the test. If my chances \Rof
winning\S were 1-in-20, I'd say they've gone down to 1-in-10.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob May, a former Oklahoma State player, saw his stock rise with
a second consecutive 66. May collected seven birdies and one bogey,
moving to 12 under and earning the right to be paired with Woods in
the final round.
</P>
<P>
   May, like Dunlap, is winless on the PGA Tour. In fact, the only
player within three strokes of Woods who has won a tour event is El
Paso resident J.P. Hayes (10 under), winner of the 1998 Buick
Classic. May, 31, said his dubious golfing pedigree is no concern
heading into a matchup with Woods.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not a lot of pressure on me. I am not supposed to
win,'' May said. ``People don't know me. Hopefully, I will have a
good round, and they'll know me a little better.''
</P>
<P>
   For Woods, the stretch run beckons in his quest for a ``Triple
Crown.'' Instead of another Sunday coronation march, as Woods
enjoyed by building 54-hole leads of 10 strokes (U.S. Open) and six
strokes (British Open) in the past two majors, he'll have people
nipping at his heels today.
</P>
<P>
   Will that create a greater mental challenge?
</P>
<P>
   ``Not at all,'' Woods said. ``Hopefully, it will make me better.
I have a good chance to win, and I plan to finish on top.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if he has to nose out his pursuers in the final furlong,
just like Secretariat.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
