<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCAIN-CANCER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO COMPLICATIONS IN MCCAIN CANCER SURGERY 
</HEADLINE>
   By LAWRENCE K. ALTMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX _ Sen. John McCain of Arizona sailed through five and a
half hours of surgery for two malignant melanomas on Saturday
without complications and with no immediate indication that the
cancer had spread, his doctors said.
</P>
<P>
   The operation involved removal of two malignant melanomas from
his left temple and left upper arm along with lymph nodes from his
neck and a portion of his salivary gland.
</P>
<P>
   But only after pathologists look at the lymph node through a
microscope next week can a determination be made about whether it
contains cancerous melanoma cells, Dr. John D. Eckstein, McCain's
personal physician at the Mayo Clinic Hospital, said at a news
conference here.
</P>
<P>
   ``My husband is in wonderful shape and we have a wonderful
report,'' Cindy McCain told reporters. Her husband was cracking
jokes in his hospital room after he awoke from anesthesia, she
said, and ``all my prayers have been answered.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain's doctors, though expressing optimism, introduced a note
of caution. Eckstein, a specialist in internal medicine, and the
team of surgeons said it was premature to speculate on future
medical plans.
</P>
<P>
   The pathology tests that will be performed early next week are
crucial because if the cancer is confined to the skin, as
preliminary tests earlier in the week and on Saturday indicated,
McCain's prognosis will be as favorable as it was after the
malignant melanoma was removed from his left shoulder in 1993.
McCain received no therapy beyond surgical removal of the shoulder
melanoma, and doctors have pronounced him cured of it.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary pathological tests indicate a good outlook. Dr.
Michael L. Hinni, a head and neck cancer surgeon who led the team,
said quick tests known as frozen sections showed that ``all
melanoma was removed during the surgery.'' But experts not
connected with McCain's case said that frozen sections can be
unreliable for melanoma.
</P>
<P>
   If pathology tests show that the new melanoma has spread to a
lymph node, McCain will need further treatment such as
chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two new melanomas, the one from the left upper arm was
least troublesome because it was caught at cancer's earliest stage,
a type known as ``in situ.'' It can be considered ``a precursor to
a real melanoma'' that rarely if ever, spreads, or metastasizes,
said Dr. Lynn M. Schuchter, a melanoma expert at the University of
Pennsylvania and a member of the American Society of Clinical
Oncology's communications committee.
</P>
<P>
   The temple melanoma obviously was more worrisome because the
surgeons took the extra steps of performing many magnetic resonance
imaging and CAT scans, a specialized type of X-rays, earlier in the
week and removing lymph nodes Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The temple melanoma was at least 2.2 millimeters deep as
measured in a biopsy that was performed at the Bethesda Naval
Medical Center on Aug. 4. Such depth is a critical factor in
determining a melanoma patient's prognosis. McCain's temple
melanoma would be classified as type 2 for which textbooks cite
10-year survival figures of about 60 percent to 70 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's surgery involved injecting a blue dye and radioactive
tracer into the melanoma on the temple in a procedure known as a
sentinel lymphoscintigraphy. Later in the operation, the doctors
used a gamma counter to locate the tracer in the first node
draining lymph fluid from the temple, an indication of the path by
which the cancerous melanoma cells would most likely spread. The
doctors also removed a number of additional lymph nodes.
</P>
<P>
   A sentinel node procedure allows pathologists to slice the node
like a loaf of bread in the laboratory and then use chemical stains
to provide a more comprehensive analysis than can often be
accomplished by examining sections of a dozen or so lymph nodes.
</P>
<P>
   Surgical removal of melanomas is standard therapy, and in the
next phase of McCain's surgery, the doctors took the precaution of
removing a wide area of skin surrounding the melanoma.
</P>
<P>
   In the final step of the operation, the doctors reconstructed
the skin and soft tissue overlying the temple, face and neck.
</P>
<P>
   It will take several days for the swelling and bruising of
McCain's face and neck to subside. He is expected to remain in the
hospital for two or three days.
</P>
</TEXT>
