<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-PGA-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WATSON PUTTS FOR SUCCESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIMMY BURCH 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Tom Watson experienced a flashback yesterday
at the PGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Watson, 50, buried birdie putts in bunches at Valhalla Golf
Club. He shot a 65 and grabbed a short-lived share of the course
record. Watson's mark lasted for exactly 1 hour, 41 minutes ....
the amount of time needed for Jose Maria Olazabal, playing 11
groups behind, to post a 63 that matched the lowest score ever
recorded in a major championship.
</P>
<P>
   Watson, however, offered no complaints about being bumped from
the Valhalla record book. He was too busy reveling in the type of
putting performance he has only dreamed about in recent years: 22
putts in 18 holes, with six birdie putts ranging between 10 and 35
feet. Watson also holed a 15-footer to save par at No. 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't putted much better than I did \Ryesterday\S, except
when I was 28,'' said Watson, who moved to 5-under par for the
tournament. ``My round wasn't much from a ball-striking standpoint.
But from a putting standpoint, it was beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Watson said a mid-round decision to take the putter on a
straighter plane in his backswing led to a dramatic turnaround.
Over the final 13 holes, Watson one-putted 11 times.
</P>
<P>
   Although out of the running at the PGA (eight strokes back),
Watson said the confidence he gained yesterday should serve him
well when he defends his title Sept. 22-24 at the Bank One event at
Bent Tree Country Club in Dallas.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is pretty good for old folks,'' Watson said. ``It'll give
me something to draw on when I get back out on the Senior Tour.''
\Nsubheds:Record-setting rounds
</P>
<P>
   Tom Watson and Jose Maria Olazabal were among 53 players who
broke par yesterday, a third-round record for the PGA Championship.
The previous mark was 38, established during the 1995 event.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Valhalla played to a scoring average of 71, a full-stroke
below par. That marked the lowest scoring average in any round for
a PGA held at a par-72 course. The previous mark was 71.9, set at
the 1989 tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Why the sudden run on low numbers?
</P>
<P>
   ``The pins were a lot more accessible than during the first two
rounds,'' Tiger Woods said. ``But I've seen where the pins will be
\Rtomorrow\S. That won't be the case again.'' \Nsubheds:Nicklaus'
historic first
</P>
<P>
   One day after the words were uttered, Jack Nicklaus' comments
about Tiger Woods still strike a chord with Kaye Kessler, a retired
reporter who has known the Golden Bear for 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler, 76, was a columnist for the now-defunct ``Columbus
Citizen-Journal'' when he published the first account of a
10-year-old phenom in his town: a youngster named Nicklaus, who had
just posted a 51 for nine holes at a Columbus, Ohio course.
</P>
<P>
   A half-century and 18 major championships later, Kessler
listened with slack jaw as Nicklaus, 60, heaped praise on Woods,
24, after playing with him during the first two rounds of the PGA
Championship. Woods, who has won golf's last two major
championships by a combined 23 strokes, can join Fort Worth legend
Ben Hogan as the only professionals to win three major
championships in one season with a victory today at the PGA.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point, with what he's doing, I think he's a better
player than I ever was,'' Nicklaus said of Woods.
</P>
<P>
   Kessler put that sentiment into perspective yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the first time I've ever heard Jack say anybody was
better than he was,'' Kessler said.
</P>
<P>
   Woods' response?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's awfully nice of Jack to say that,'' Woods said. ``But I
think his statement might have been a little different if he was
closer to his prime.'' \Nsubheds:Major factor
</P>
<P>
   Franklin Langham, who has three runner-up finishes on the PGA
Tour this season, posted an impressive round yesterday in his first
appearance at a major championship. Langham shot a 65, climbing to
8 under.
</P>
<P>
   Langham said he has not been intimidated by the trappings in his
first major.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not going to say I'm surprised to be where I am. But I am
elated,'' said Langham, a native of Augusta, Ga. who manned the
scoreboard at the 16th hole at the Masters Tournament during his
days as a junior golfer. ``I came in here hitting the ball well and
expected to play well, major or otherwise.'' \Nsubheds:Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Scott Dunlap, on the crowd support he received while matching
70s with Woods in the third round: ``I heard my name called as much
as Tiger's, which was a neat experience. Not everyone wants the
favorite.''
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Els, runner-up in the season's first three majors, has
been added to the field for the PGA Grand Slam of Golf, Nov. 21-22
in Kauai, Hawaii. The four-player event usually is limited to the
reigning major champions but a vacancy is available because Woods
has won multiple majors in 2000. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
