<HEADER>
A7046 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-FBC-UCLA-SCRIMMAGE-LA     08-19 0305
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-SCRIMMAGE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONSISENT PAUS SHARP IN SCRIMMAGE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILLY WITZ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA's first scrimmage of fall camp didn't match
the first-team offense against the first-team defense, didn't offer
any revelations, and didn't give coach Bob Toledo much to talk
about. He'll have to look at the film.
</P>
<P>
   But the nearly two-hour scrimmage, open to about 2,000 donors
Saturday afternoon at Drake Stadium, also did nothing to dispel the
notion that Cory Paus will open the season as the Bruins' starting
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   Paus completed 7 of 10 passes for 184 yards and one touchdown, a
well-placed ball on a seam route that tight end Gabe Crecion turned
into a 65-yard score. Ryan McCann, who'd hoped to wrest the job
from Paus, wasn't bad either _ completing 6 of 9 for 155 yards, two
touchdowns and one interception. Included was a crisply thrown
18-yard scoring pass to Drew Bennett.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo, who said he would give McCann and Paus seven to 10 days
to compete for the job, could name a starter as early as Monday.
Thus far, Paus has been the more consistent quarterback and Toledo
emphasized Saturday that was what he was looking for.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing to say is everything is not depending on
what they did today,'' the coach said. ``It's not just throwing
passes, it's operating the offense.''
</P>
<P>
   The first-team defense was impressive, forcing the second-team
offense to go three plays and out on its first three series. Also
distinguishing himself were freshman punter Chris Kluwe, whose
booming punts were noticeably higher than those by incumbent Nate
Fikse; reserve defensive tackle Stephen Sua, who had two sacks; and
true freshman Manuel White (Valencia High), who carried six times
for 38 yards.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-00 2345EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000819.0270 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 23:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7047 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-METS-LADN     08-19 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-METS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PERPLEXING DODGERS BEAT METS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ When the Los Angeles Dodgers make it look this
easy, their season becomes that much harder to understand.
</P>
<P>
   Two homers by Gary Sheffield and a complete game by Chan Ho Park
was the way the Dodgers drew it up in spring training. When they
did it Saturday afternoon in a crisp 4-1 victory over the white-hot
New York Mets, it begged the question, ``Why is this team eight
games out with 41 to play.''
</P>
<P>
   The answer is long and complicated, but for one day in front of
a sellout crowd of 53,051 and a national TV audience, the Dodgers
fired on all cylinders. Headed by their front man, Sheffield, whose
39th and 40th homers tied Mike Piazza's L.A.-franchise record, they
had the rare look of a contender.
</P>
<P>
   Park, forced to skip his last start with the flu, came back with
an overpowering fastball and struck out 10. More importantly, he
never lost focus in tight situations and had his most-overpowering
performance since May 13, when he struck out 12 in a 3-1 victory at
St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Throw in Eric Karros' first home run in three weeks and an
errorless game from the league's second-worst defensive team and
the Dodgers breezed to just their fourth win in 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there is any doubt that we're capable of games
like this,'' said Sheffield, who is on a pace to hit 54 homers this
season. ``We just have never had the intensity to play this way all
the time. It's frustrating when you're reminded how good we can be
because we've never been able to keep it up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets came in with 14 victories in their past 18 games and
led 1-0 just two batters into the game - on a home run by Derek
Bell.
</P>
<P>
   But New York was playing without Piazza, who caught the night
before and hit a home run in the Mets' 5-3 win. Park allowed a
season-low four hits in his second complete game of the year. He
retired 10 consecutive batters early in the game and 11 of 12 to
close it out.
</P>
<P>
   There was a downside for L.A., however. The National League
West- leading San Francisco Giants defeated Atlanta for the second
straight day to remain eight games ahead of the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   With a victory, the Mets could have moved within a half-game of
the Braves in the East.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really doesn't matter what other teams do,'' said Karros,
who has 28 homers. ``The only thing that matters is winning. There
have been times this year when we have looked as good as any team.
And there have been times when we've looked as bad as any team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Was this a big game? Check back in 10 games to see if we've
kept it up.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers close out the series today with their hottest
pitcher Darren Dreifort, who is going for his seventh consecutive
victory. After that is a three-game series with the slumping
Montreal Expos to close out the homestand.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the only Dodger who has shown up every day is Sheffield,
whose MVP-type season has been buried under the team's
disappointing performance.
</P>
<P>
   He gave the Dodgers the lead for good in the second when he
drove Rick Reed's first-pitch fastball into the stands in left for
a two-run homer. Two batters later, Karros hit a 2-2 pitch off Reed
(7-4) into the packed left-field stands to make it 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield greeted new pitcher Pat Mahomes in the eighth with his
second homer. As he reached the dugout, the cheers swelled until he
came out for a curtain call. Not only was it his 40th, but he tied
Piazza's club record with his 22nd at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I had seen it all with the season Mike had in `97,''
Karros said. ``Sheff is blowing right by him and it's only
August.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-00 2347EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
