<DOCNO> NYT20000819.0271 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 23:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7048 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-TIRE-RECALL-NYT &LR;      08-19 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TIRE-RECALL-NYT </SLUG>
  
 FORD CHOSE TIRES NOW BEING RECALLED TO REDUCE RISK OF ROLLOVERS,
DOCUMENT SHOWS   By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ An internal Ford Motor Co. document obtained by
lawyers suing the automaker and Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. shows
that the company considered using tires with higher pressure than
the Firestone tires now subject to a recall, but decided against
them because they increased the risk that Explorer sport utility
vehicles using them would tip over.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgestone is recalling 6.5 million tires mounted mainly on
Explorers because they are prone to losing their treads at high
speeds. Federal regulators say that they have received more than
750 complaints about the tires involving at least 62 deaths. Almost
all of the deaths occurred in sport utility vehicles that rolled
over, mostly Explorers.
</P>
<P>
   Since the recall began, Bridgestone has urged consumers to fill
15-inch tires on Explorers to 30 pounds per square inch. Ford has
recommended since the Explorer went on sale that the 15-inch tires
be filled to 26 pounds per square inch, but has said over the last
week that a range of 26 to 30 pounds was acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   The difference has caught the attention of lawyers who sue
tiremakers because tires are more likely to fail if they are used
at lower pressures. The lower the pressure, the softer the tire,
which means that more of its sidewall is in contact with the road.
This increases the heat of the tire, and can cause the tread to
peel off, particularly if the tire is poorly made.
</P>
<P>
   C. Tab Turner, a lawyer in Little Rock, Ark., who is suing Ford
and Bridgetone/Firestone on behalf of people injured in
tire-related crashes, said in an interview on Monday that the
document showed that the Explorer was an inherently flawed vehicle
that was prone to tipping over.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tire pressure is directly related to the handling and
stability issue,'' Turner said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford officials strongly defend the stability of the Explorer.
Even with the deaths attributed to the tires, the occupants of
Explorers have a 22 percent lower death rate in rollover crashes
than occupants of other mid-sized sport utility vehicles, said
Ernie Grush, Ford's manager of safety data analysis. The overall
death rate for Explorer occupants in all types of crashes is 24
percent lower than the overall rate for other mid-sized sport
utilities, and is comparable to death rates for cars because
Explorer occupants fare well in collisions with other vehicles,
Grush said.
</P>
<P>
   Ford officials have said that they selected the tire pressure
for the Explorer so as to give it a smooth ride, and have insisted
that a tire pressure of 26 pounds per square inch provided an ample
safety margin against slow leaks that a consumer might not notice.
Tire damage, and ultimately tire failures, are rare unless a tire
is operated at less than 20 pounds per square inch, and become a
significant possibility only in the low or mid-teens of pressure,
said Tom Baughman, Ford's engineering director for North American
trucks.
</P>
<P>
   While hard tires are less likely to fail, they also allow a
motorist to turn more sharply than soft tires do, even at high
speeds. Automakers try to limit how sharply a vehicle can turn,
particularly if it has a high center of gravity as most sport
utility vehicles do, so as to limit the risk that it will roll
over. If a motorist turns sharply any vehicle while traveling very
fast, the vehicle may roll, but the risk is increased for taller
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The internal Ford document says that the company decided against
the use of higher-pressure tires so as to limit so-called cornering
forces, a measure of how hard the front end of the vehicle can be
turned. Ford officials have said that they did not choose a low
tire pressure because of rollover concerns. Brook Lindbert, the
tire and wheel engineering director at General Motors, said that
automakers tried to limit cornering forces mainly through
suspension designs, not tire pressure.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-19-00 2353EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000819.0272 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-19 23:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7050 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     08-19 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV27-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 27)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; CLOSE TO THE WIND &LR; , by Pete Goss. (Carroll &AMP; Graf, $15.95.)
Competing in a round-the-world single-handed yacht race, the author
ended up rescuing a fellow sailor and battling six-story waves.
Writing in The New York Times Book Review last year, Barbara Lloyd
said, ``You are immersed in his passion.''
</P>
<P>
   Another disastrous ocean race, off Australia, is recounted in
 &UR; KNOCKDOWN: The Harrowing True Account of a Yacht Race Turned
Deadly &LR; , by Martin Dugard (Pocket Books, $13.95). This is ``a
melodramatic but nonetheless riveting chronicle,'' Elizabeth
Hightower wrote in 1999, ``a story that simply won't let go.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A CERTAIN AGE &LR; , by Tama Janowitz. (Anchor, $13.) The Hamptons,
in New York, are the setting for the tragicomic story of a young
woman of diminished prospects who sees marriage to a wealthy man as
the only thing that can save her. The novel ``offers nimble
commentary on the mating scene and upmarket beach house
architecture,'' Henry Alford wrote last summer.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A SEASON IN THE SUN &LR; , by Roger Kahn. (University of Nebraska,
$12.95.) The author of ``The Boys of Summer'' traveled the nation
in mid-1976, talking baseball with players at various levels, from
small-college teams to World Series champions. ``My only complaint
against `A Season in the Sun' is its length _ there isn't enough of
it,'' Donald Hall said in The New York Times Book Review in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   The University of Nebraska Press has also reissued Kahn's  &UR; GOOD
ENOUGH TO DREAM &LR;  ($15.95), about his year as president and part
owner of the low-minor-league Utica Blue Sox. This ``incongruous
owner'' is ``a skilled storyteller who was presented with a
lifetime's supply of colorful characters,'' Bob Ryan wrote in 1985.
Both books have new afterwords by the author.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A RAGE TO LIVE: A Biography of Richard and Isabel Burton &LR; , by
Mary S. Lovell. (Norton, $19.95.) An eminent, or perhaps notorious,
Victorian, Sir Richard Burton was an explorer, scholar and linguist
who translated the ``Kama Sutra'' and slipped into the forbidden
city of Mecca, in Arab disguise. This is ``an extraordinary
biography,'' James R. Kincaid wrote in The New York Times Book
Review in 1999. The author shows Isabel Burton to be ``as
resolutely tactless as her husband but also as courageous, defiant
and smart.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CHARLOTTE GRAY &LR; , by Sebastian Faulks. (Vintage International,
$14.) This novel follows a Scottish woman's journey into
Nazi-occupied France during World War II to find a missing RAF
pilot. ``What is essentially a love story turns into a sensitive,
powerful reflection on moral anguish in Vichy France,'' Anita Gates
wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PARADISE, NEW YORK &LR; , by Eileen Pollack. (Temple University,
$17.95.) In a coming-of-age story, a young white woman tries to
save her family's crumbling Catskills resort and falls in love with
the reclusive handyman, who is black. ``Pollack's first novel
succeeds, sometimes too didactically, in taking on such large
themes as racism and bigotry, love and loyalty,'' Ruth Coughlin
wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MURDER DUET: A Musical Case &LR; , by Batya Gur, translated by Dalya
Bilu. (Harper Perennial, $14.) The cerebral Israeli policeman
Michael Ohayon returns in the fourth in a series of mysteries, this
time investigating the murders of classical musicians. ``Gur's
introspective detective unravels her complicated plot with his
usual intelligence,'' Marilyn Stasio said in The New York Times
Book Review last year. ``But for pure reading pleasure, nothing
touches the smart discussions on music and art.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A THIRST FOR RAIN &LR; , by Roslyn Carrington. (Kensington, $12.)
The lives of neighbors who share a cramped communal yard intersect
and collide in this first novel, set in the hills of Trinidad
during a four-month drought. ``The stage will be washed clean but
the strains of Carrington's powerful redemption song will linger,''
Anderson Tepper wrote in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BOMBSHELL: The Life and Death of Jean Harlow &LR; , by David Stenn.
(Lightning Bug Press, $24.95.) The brief career of a Hollywood
legend who was both sex symbol and comedian is recounted in a
well-documented biography, with a new section of previously
unpublished movie stills. ``Without judgment and without smacking
his lips ... Stenn tells how Harlow's life had run amok even before
she became a star,'' Jeanine Basinger said in The New York Times
Book Review in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Another Hollywood biography by the same author is  &UR; CLARA BOW:
Runnin' Wild &LR;  (Cooper Square, $21.95), which contains a new
filmography. Bow's sex appeal brought her the title of the ``It''
girl, but she was a has-been by the age of 25. ``This is a touching
portrait of a sad and turbulent life,'' Sharon Shervington wrote in
1988.
</P>
</TEXT>
